<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Clemens may yet become an Astro
<TEXT>
<P>
   To paraphrase Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr., a line in the
sand has been drawn regarding the once-and-future Roger Clemens
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Get it done, or get on with life as the Astros know it, McLane
has said.
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker, the
Clemens trade negotiations might not be hot and heavy, but they are
ongoing with Clemens' current team, the Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase Clemens' agents, Alan and Randy Hendricks, it has
become a game of wait-and-see. No longer are the superagents
actively involved in contract renegotiations in the midst of trade
talks. It simply will be a deal or no deal that they offer to their
client after the particulars are ironed out.
</P>
<P>
   After all the confusion _ the testy volleys between the sides,
the talk of handshake deals between the Jays and Clemens, the
clandestine phone conversations between McLane and the Hendrickses
_ some of us are wondering how this deal possibly could get done
now.
</P>
<P>
   But really, we should be wondering how it possibly could not get
done. As with Joe DiMaggio, news of this deal's death was greatly
exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   It was bitter and seemingly crippling when Clemens held his
memorable December news conference, pulling out of the bartering
business and pulling no punches when it came to Hunsicker and
Astros president Tal Smith.
</P>
<P>
   But in the strangest twist yet, it appears Clemens' biting
declaration might become the biggest reason the Astros can have
their cherished fireballer _ and on terms more to their liking.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, it has come down to three factors. McLane has refused
to give up on the deal, even after his top two baseball hands were
verbally chopped down by Clemens. The Jays have realized they might
be better off in the clubhouse without Clemens, no matter his
talent. And much of the baseball world realizes it might be wasting
its breath talking trade with Toronto, because Clemens wants to
play in Houston and for a title contender, probably in that order.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know they have to deal him,'' one Toronto source said
Friday of the Blue Jays. ``They know some of their players probably
won't be comfortable with him there this season.''
</P>
<P>
   They know what you should know. Clemens could be an Astro by the
opening of spring training Feb. 17.
</P>
<P>
   From the Astros' perspective, some sort of deal must happen
soon, so the likes of Derek Bell, Scott Elarton and Richard Hidalgo
do not spend the spring wondering about their status with the team.
Chemistry is a fragile thing.
</P>
<P>
   For Toronto, the deal must be made because the disappointment
Clemens has voiced regarding having a championship-caliber
supporting cast has hurt his relationship with the club and the
city. As talented as he is, the Jays are ready for a new direction.
</P>
<P>
   The only question is whether Clemens will go the Astros,
Rangers, Indians or Yankees. When he mentioned recently that St.
Louis was in the mix, it likely only was a calculated way of
tweaking the Astros a bit more, hoping McLane would step up in fear
of a division rival's landing the ace.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a tricky trade for sure, as much after it happens as
during the deal-making. The Astros do not want to mortgage their
future and will work hard toward keeping at least one of Bell,
Elarton and Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   McLane also does not want to stab Hunsicker and Smith in their
backs, which is why Hunsicker is the point man in negotiations with
the Blue Jays. In a straight player-for-players deal, Hunsicker
does not have to deal with the Hendrickses and new contracts. He
isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the Astros suddenly are in a preferred position.
When Clemens took his renegotiation card off the table, he made it
a more cut-and-dried negotiation. He made it Hunsicker's
negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   If Clemens does come to Houston, there is no reason for the
Astros to add huge numbers to his contract until after the 1999
season or later (his current deal runs through 2000) _ and even
then more on their terms.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has made his arrival into camp a stickier proposition if
it happens, but that, too, can be dealt with.
</P>
<P>
   We are reminded of a recent conversation with Rockets star
Scottie Pippen and the issue of Dennis Rodman. Pippen talked of
loving Rodman on the floor, loving his contribution and his
commitment _ on the floor. But he also said he had a business-only
relationship with the Neoned One. Away from the floor, they did not
converse, socialize or exchange much more than a few pleasantries.
And together they won an NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   That's how this deal can work for Hunsicker, Smith and Clemens.
Damage has been done, but it would seem impossible for one side not
to respect what the other can offer.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens and Hunsicker might only exchange a few pleasantries,
but together they can win a World Series championship. And that's
what both sides want more than anything.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
