<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS OR COPS? ELITE STREET CRIMES UNIT HAS MIXED REPUTATION 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also NY-SUSPECT-SHOT, NY-SUSPECT-WESTAFRICANS) 
(DW) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For nearly three decades, members of the New York
City Police Department's street crimes unit have patrolled the city
at night in search of crimes about to occur, sometimes making their
appearance scruffy to blend in and driving battered cars as
camouflage.
</P>
<P>
   It has been known as an elite force, and became even more so two
years ago when Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and Police Commissioner
William Safir announced that the city would nearly quadruple the
force and expand its focus from taking illegal guns off the street
to fighting a number of crimes, from rape to thefts.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the unit has become a hallmark of the aggressive
policing championed by the Giuliani administration and has offered
one avenue for active beat officers to advance through the ranks
and gain a detective shield. But its tactics also have been
criticized by community leaders and other police officers who say
the department should rein in the unit's members, who like to say
they ``own the night.''
</P>
<P>
   The shooting on Thursday of Amadou Diallo, an apparently unarmed
Bronx peddler, by four officers in the unit who were looking for a
rape suspect brought harsh complaints not only from Amnesty
International but also from associations of minority officers in
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dealing with a critical issue of race in the United
States,'' said a retired police detective, Graham Weatherspoon, who
spoke at a news conference Friday held by a local officers' group,
100 Blacks in Law Enforcement Who Care. ``Three years ago, a man
with a rifle was arrested in midtown Manhattan without a shot being
fired. The man arrested was a male white.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the same news conference, Sidique Abubacarr Wai, the
president of a national advocacy group for members of minorities,
the United African Congress, added: ``Africans are murdered in this
town every month and we are sick and tired of burying our own.''
</P>
<P>
   The street crimes unit has been called upon through the years to
pinpoint and tackle many problems. They have saturated midtown
Manhattan to quell crimes of opportunity during New Year's Eve
celebrations and have been sent to precincts troubled by rashes of
murders, rapes or assaults.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when the unit had only about 100 officers, it was
responsible for 20 percent of all arrests of people carrying
illegal guns in the city, according to police statistics. Since
1997, when the mayor increased its ranks to more than 400 _ still
less than 2 percent of the entire police force _ the unit has been
responsible for nearly 40 percent of all gun arrests annually.
</P>
<P>
   Last Year, Safir singled out the work of the unit, saying that
it had been instrumental in reducing the number of reported
shootings to fewer than 1,000 during the first half of 1998,
compared with 2,500 in the first half of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors, speaking on the condition of anonymity, have
noted that the unit's mission of searching out crimes instead of
responding to them had left some of their arrests vulnerable to
complaints of unlawful search and seizure. Cases have been thrown
out because officers chased suspects without probable cause, only
then finding a gun or other illegal item. ``They have a reputation
as cowboys,'' one prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   Two days ago, a Brooklyn grand jury declined to indict the
rapper Russel Jones, known as Ol' Dirty Bastard in the rap group
Wu-Tang Clan, on charges that he attempted to murder street crime
officers who had stopped his car last month. The officers, who
fired on Jones and another passenger, claimed that the rap
performer had fired first, according to the police. But Jones said
that the officers had been frightened by a cell phone he was
holding when he was stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury found no evidence that Jones had fired at the
police, and he said on Thursday that he planned to file a lawsuit
against the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
