<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAME FOR GIRL'S DEATH OVERSHADOWS SCHOOL CONSTRUCTION SAFETY
HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Haunted by the death of a 16-year-old girl who was
struck by a brick that fell from one of its construction sites last
year, the leaders of the New York City School Construction
Authority Friday outlined the steps they were taking to prevent
such accidents.
</P>
<P>
   They include replacing all but two of the agency's 30 project
managers and requiring four references from each prospective
contractor.
</P>
<P>
   But their testimony, at a state Assembly hearing in lower
Manhattan, was overshadowed by sparring between the chairman of the
Assembly Education Committee, Steven Sanders, and the governor's
former representative at the authority, Paul Atanasio.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' insisted that Atanasio take some responsibility for the
events leading to the girl's death.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, a Democrat from the Manhattan's Lower East Side, called
the hearing to address a report by city and authority investigators
in December that found fault at every stage of the renovation of
the school, P.S. 131 in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   They range from the approval of an inexperienced contractor to
the hiring of an unqualified project manager to the failure to
install a protective sidewalk shed that might have saved Yan Zhen
Zhao's life.
</P>
<P>
   The report suggested that Atanasio had persuaded authority
executives to hire his assistant's husband, Gary Marrone, to
oversee the renovation of several schools even though he had little
experience.
</P>
<P>
   One of Marrone's assignments was P.S. 131. Though he was
transferred 82 days before the accident, the report said that the
lax safety he had fostered for more than a year had been a factor
in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   His face red and his hands shaking as he read a statement,
Atanasio took aim at Sanders, who had called the chain of events
leading to the girl's death an outrage that could be traced to
Atanasio.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, Sanders, it is your comments about me that are the
outrage,'' Atanasio said. ``To be sure, there are those who bear
responsibility for the child's death, but to suggest that I am
responsible because the husband of my assistant worked as a project
officer on P.S. 131 is patently untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Atanasio's anger only rose as Sanders twice addressed him,
apparently inadvertently, as `` Marrone.''
</P>
<P>
   `` Who?'' Atanasio interrupted each time.
</P>
<P>
   Though Atanasio, who resigned after the report's release,
refused to accept blame for the accident, he said that he might
have had more to do with Marrone's hiring than he originally
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   At first he told investigators he had no knowledge of Marrone's
hiring. But Friday he said he could not dispute the claims of four
authority officials that he had intervened on Marrone's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that Marrone should not have been hired by the
authority, though he wondered aloud why the authority had been
unable to secure the site in the nearly three months between
Marrone's removal and the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Before Atanasio's testimony, the authority's president, Milo E.
Riverso, spoke about the many cracks in management the accident had
exposed and the ways the agency had tried to patch them.
</P>
<P>
   He described a new corps of project managers, who function as
the authority's eyes and ears at each job site who are going
through a new course on site safety.
</P>
<P>
   And he said the contractor at P.S. 131, Espo Construction of the
Bronx, which has since pleaded guilty to manslaughter in the girl's
death, would not have made it through the authority's new screening
process since it had supplied no references suggesting it had done
general contracting work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire corporate culture of the SCA has changed,'' Riverso
said.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Albert Vann of Brooklyn was one of several committee
members who praised the changes, but said he doubted that a
nine-year-old agency with such flaws could remake itself in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to be on your guard,'' Vann said to Riverso.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
