<SLUG> BC-NY-PA-TRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SPEECH IN PENNSYLVANIA DRAWS TRASH PROTESTERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Va., N.J.)  By   JEANNETTE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISBURG, Pa. _ Environmental advocates, angered that trash
from New York is being dumped in Pennsylvania landfills, protested
a visit here Friday night by Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen demonstrators, including a man dressed as Benjamin
Franklin, waited outside the the Harrisburg Hilton and Towers,
where Giuliani gave the keynote speech at the Pennsylvania
Republican Committee's annual Lincoln Day Dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayor Giuliani should stop exporting his problems to other
states,'' said Jeff Schmidt, spokesman for the Pennsylvania chapter
of the Sierra Club. ``When this mayor decided to close New York's
landfill, he bowed to local political pressure. His answer has been
to dump on his neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, state Rep. Todd Eachus, a Democrat, led a
demonstration at the state Capitol in which 50 pounds of office
trash was collected for shipment to Giuliani's office in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania takes in more out-of-state trash than any other
state. Nearly 3.3 million tons of that waste came from New York in
1997, according to the most recent figures from the Pennsylvania
Department of Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the mayor has angered residents of New Jersey
and Virginia and their Republican governors over the issue of New
York City trash that is sent to landfills in those states.
</P>
<P>
   The dozen sign-waving demonstrators never saw the mayor, but he
mentioned them during his remarks to the 700 Republican supporters
who paid $50 each to hear him speak at the dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to see a few protesters out here,'' he said. ``I
felt at home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 0015EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
