<HEADLINE>
BRUINS MIGHT HAVE HIDDEN GEMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
Leftovers from the recruiting trail and other places ....
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wake them up: Westlake's Mike Seidman, Newhall's Jerry Owens and
Venice's J.P. Losman were familiar names when they signed letters
of intent Wednesday morning. But which lesser-known players may
emerge as contributors, either next season or in the years to come?
</P>
<P>
   Four names to remember:
</P>
<P>
   _Asi Faoa, a linebacker from Magnolia High in Anaheim who did
not register with the ubiquitous recruiting services until
recently. One of his coaches, Richard Penn, played for Bob Toledo
at Pacific and tipped off the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Faoa is 6-foot-4 and 240 pounds, with a wide base and frame that
can hold more weight. The Bruins believe he'll be an impact player,
if not in 1999 then soon thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   _Ryan Wikert, a safety from Temecula Valley High. At least one
recruiting service, Student Sports, believes he's the sleeper in
UCLA's highly ranked class. He is 6-2, 175 pounds and ran a
4.5-second 40-yard dash for the coaches. One other thing: He's a
hitter, and the Bruins need all the physicality they can find.
</P>
<P>
   _Mat and David Ball, twin defensive ends from Dixon, Calif.
Mention the word ``twins'' around Westwood, and the nice, polite
Webb brothers, Josh and Micah, come to mind. But the Balls, 6-5 and
235 pounds, are fearless and athletic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're excellent basketball players,'' Toledo said. ``And
they have a mean streak in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Close second: UCLA strengthened its position as a national
recruiting power by finishing second on four elite out-of-state
players:
</P>
<P>
   T.J. Duckett, a linebacker from Kalamazoo, Mich., who is
considered the nation's No. 1 overall player and signed with
Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Breedlove, perhaps the nation's No. 1 offensive lineman,
from Central, S.C., who signed with Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Milligan, another top offensive lineman from Norcross, Ga.,
who signed with Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Arnold, the Seattle tailback who signed with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Time to mature: Don't expect Owens, the Hart High receiver, to
play immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions on redshirts are made once training camp begins, but
Owens has a slew of experienced players to overtake: Danny Farmer,
Brian Poli-Dixon, Freddie Mitchell, Brad Melsby, Jon Dubravac and
redshirt Paul Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We targeted (Owens) a long time ago,'' Toledo said. ``We knew
he was outstanding. He's a great student and a great person. He
fits the mold of our program. But he needs to get bigger and
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying put?: It appears offensive coordinator Al Borges will
return for the 1999 season. He was a candidate for the same post
with San Diego, but a source said Borges and Chargers coach Mike
Riley had a philosophical difference: They both wanted to call the
plays.
</P>
<P>
   Borges' challenge from spring practice to training camp and
through the season is hefty: identify and develop a starting
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Five players will compete for Cade McNown's job when spring
practice begins April 6: junior-to-be Drew Bennett, sophomore Scott
McEwan, redshirt freshmen Ryan McCann and Cory Paus, and Losman,
the incoming freshman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
