<HEADLINE>
BASKETBALL COLUMN: SAME OLD QUESTIONS FOR NEW OLD KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ How do you win a National Basketball Association
championship with Patrick Ewing?
</P>
<P>
   This has been the New York Knicks' million-dollar question for
14 seasons. The attempts to answer it, which have cost the
organization millions as well, have been slow in coming. With Ewing
as the dominant force and focal point, the Man, the Knicks have
come close a couple of times and have generally been entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   But the championship that Knicks fans crave has been beyond
their grasp. And Friday night's 93-85 loss to the Orlando Magic
seemed to push it even further away.
</P>
<P>
   This season marks the Knicks' most dramatic, most desperate step
in years to find the answer. They have reconfigured the team, cast
out the bruising, staccato halfcourt pounding in favor of a
smaller, quicker, guerrilla-warfare-type attack.
</P>
<P>
   But the question remains: How do you win an NBA championship
with Patrick Ewing? Because whatever the Knicks do must pass
through Ewing. The paradox of the Knicks' situation is that while
they have not been able to win a championship with Ewing, they will
never win one without him.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks opened a new season Friday night. For the 36-year-old
Ewing, who scored 17 points on 7-of-13 shooting, the season begins
much as it ended, with renewed clarion calls for him to step back,
accept a reduced role on the so-called New Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has a laundry list of what Ewing needs to do: take
fewer shots, play better defense, grab more rebounds, abdicate the
scorer's role. That's fine, as far as it goes, and that's precisely
the problem: We don't know how far it will go.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk about the new Knicks' firepower, all the Knicks
have at this juncture is theoretic firepower. Latrell Sprewell, who
scored 24 Friday night, hadn't played NBA competition since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston (12 points) is just coming into his own as a
confident, forceful front-line player. Larry Johnson (10 points) is
an undersized power forward. Marcus Camby, the third prong to the
New Knick attack, has been dismal and didn't even play Friday
night. Houston, Sprewell and Johnson shot a combined 18-43 for 46
points.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing has begun to accept a new role with the Knicks, though if
he has a few more nights like this, he may go back to his old self,
with the fans' blessing. Much of it has been forced on him by age,
aching knees and a weakened wrist.
</P>
<P>
   But he has also begun to listen to his teammates. ``His role is
changing and the players want his role to change,'' Orlando's Penny
Hardaway said Friday. ``I hear their interviews, and if you read
between the lines, his teammates are saying it very subtly. Now
it's 15 players to one, not like it's 50-50. Everybody is saying,
`Pat, you have to change.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Hardaway also said that without Ewing, the Knicks are a ship
adrift. Whatever misery fans think they have endured is nothing
compared with what they will be left with when there is no Ewing.
Just a few years ago Hardaway was throwing lob passes to Shaquille
O'Neal. The Magic beat the Bulls in the Eastern Conference Finals
and played for the NBA championship. Then the organization allowed
Shaq to leave, and everyone's life has been miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a player like Shaq or Patrick or Kareem, you go
into every game knowing you can win,'' Hardaway said. ``We knew
Shaq was going to give us 30, that meant all we had to do was do
our jobs. That gives you a whole lot of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Magic, like the Knicks, is being reconfigured. While the
Magic is grooming Ike Austin as its center of the future, the
Knicks, who do not have a center of the future, are watching Ewing
play off into the sunset. As long as Ewing is in the lineup _
rebounding, trailing, scoring _ the Knicks know they have a chance
to win.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the focus on Ewing, this is perhaps an even more
defining season for Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy. This is a new
Knicks team, nothing like the Pat Riley-bred grind 'em up Knicks.
The 37-year-old Van Gundy _ stripped of his training wheels, John
Starks and Charles Oakley _ has formulated a bold new style of play
for the Knicks, a style based on speed, quickness, aggressiveness
and scoring.
</P>
<P>
   The new scheme needs a safety net, a rebounder, a defensive
presence. That is what Ewing will provide. That is what Ewing has
always provided. Friday night, Ewing led the team nine rebounds.
``I felt pretty good,'' Ewing said after the game. ``I got a little
winded, but over all I felt pretty good. We just got our butts
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be the foundation of the team as long as he's here,''
Van Gundy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players have come and gone,'' he added. ``Coaches have come
and gone, management has come and gone. That's why he's still here
_ because he's the cornerstone.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all well and good. But there is still that million-dollar
question: How do you win an NBA championship with Patrick Ewing?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
