<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-CHELSEA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CHELSEA CLINTON'S PRIVACY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS grafs 2 &AMP; 4 for editorial refinements. No other changes.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Feb. 6:
</P>
<P>
   It was Teddy Roosevelt, that exuberant personality, who first
threw open the door to life at the White House. His children all
became celebrities of the age. It was Woodrow Wilson who slammed
the door, threatening to shun any reporter who wrote about his
daughters. The door stayed shut, guarded by fathers like Harry
Truman, until the Kennedy children became symbols of a youthful
presidency, objects of public adoration, and then of heartbreak.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson daughters, the Nixon daughters, Amy Carter all had
painful public moments. But no one knows the pain of life in the
White House better than Chelsea Clinton, and few first families
have been more protective than her parents. For six years,
reporters have largely honored their request to respect Ms.
Clinton's privacy. In that time, she has matured into a poised
young woman.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, as well, the White House has put her on
display at politically opportune moments and in structured
situations. She has traveled with the first lady, sat with her at
the Democratic National Convention in 1996 and attended church at
awkward moments with her father, and was the physical link between
her parents, holding their hands as they left for Martha's Vineyard
after his admission of a relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   This brief review of the coverage of Chelsea Clinton is useful
in assessing the flap over a People magazine cover article on her.
Her parents' reaction of ``profound sadness'' seems overwrought
when compared with the respectful, almost puffy tone of the piece.
</P>
<P>
   Their fear, no doubt, is that the floodgates will be opened now.
We doubt that the mainstream press will abandon the current policy
of restraint. That policy has produced generally appropriate
reporting of Ms. Clinton's public activities and allows for
journalistic interest in the personal and family dynamics of a
White House gripped by crisis.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case during Watergate and, perhaps to a lesser
extent, in the current scandal. The People story, like much of the
magazine's fare, was opportunistic but soft. It will not cause
responsible newspapers and broadcasters to start snooping into
Chelsea Clinton's private life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
