</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BUSS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSS WOULD LOVE IT IF RODMAN JOINED IN FUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Del Harris is staying (for now), Dennis
Rodman isn't coming (probably) and Jerry Buss has no intention of
selling the Los Angeles Lakers (not yet, anyway).
</P>
<P>
   So said Buss himself, when the Lakers' majority owner sat down
for a wide-ranging, half-hour interview with reporters prior to
Friday's NBA season opener at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   The pursuit of Rodman, the colorful and controversial rebounding
whiz, has been a personal mission for Buss, who has befriended the
former Chicago Bulls star. But with the Lakers able to offer only
the $1 million veteran's minimum salary _ prorated to $610,000 for
the short season _ Buss figures Rodman will choose retirement and
an acting career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's looking doubtful,'' said Buss, sitting at his desk, with
the Lakers' five NBA championship trophies behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``How interested was I? I was very interested. Dennis is someone
who could give us rebounding like we have never had at that
position. He's a true talent. And I was just hoping somehow that if
he chose a team, it would be us. I know he wants to play here, but
everybody always gets caught in the (salary) cap problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``A player of his talent, it would be tough for him to play for
that kind of money. If he plays and plays for that kind of money, I
just hope it's here. ... He would have to do it strictly for the
idea of winning a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Rodman's talents are always accompanied by distractions _
his flamboyant lifestyle, his penchant for skipping practices, the
occasional profane outburst _ he also was viewed as the possible
missing piece to the Lakers' championship hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Buss realizes not everyone wants Rodman in a Lakers uniform, but
said: ``You can't please everybody. Some people don't even like the
Laker Girls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I can read he public, they want to win (the
championship) badly, and I want to win it,'' he said. ``Los Angeles
is very hungry for a championship. It's been a while. We had such a
glorious run back in the Kareem-Magic days that people are hungry.
They miss that.''
</P>
<P>
   If Rodman does become a Laker, it will be with no strings
attached to his personality or lifestyle, said Buss, who knows
Rodman ``because we tend to habit the same places.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis is Dennis,'' he said. ``You're not about to tell Dennis
how to be someone else. You take him the way he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's talent agency, International Creative Management, could
not be reached for comment Friday evening but earlier said he
continues to weigh his options. No other NBA teams have outwardly
expressed interest in Rodman, and several have turned him down.
</P>
<P>
   ICM is attempting to make the Lakers deal work by obtaining
entertainment work for Rodman, which would make up for the
relatively low NBA salary he'd earn. And his value as a movie star
is higher if he maintains a high profile through basketball, Buss
noted.
</P>
<P>
   So he holds out some hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over until the fat lady sings,'' Buss said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Harris, entering his fifth season as coach and the
last year of his contract, will work the entire season without an
extension. Buss praised Harris' work but said he did not consider
giving Harris a new deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't come up,'' he said of an extension. ``It just
doesn't come up in discussion, so there is no decision. Overall, I
think Del's done a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Buss has sold shares of the Lakers to a number of
parties, including media mogul and Dodgers owner Rupert Murdoch, he
said he has no intention of giving up ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see selling the Lakers. I'm afraid of my children,''
he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   When he does decide to step away from day-to-day operations,
Buss' plan will be to turn over business operations to daughter
Jeanie Buss, now president of the Forum, and basketball operations
to son Jim Buss, now an assistant general manager.
</P>
<P>
   But sell the team? Only if the offer is right.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did that guy (Murdoch) pay for that soccer club in
England?'' Buss said.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch paid $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the Lakers are twice as valuable as that,'' Buss said
with a smile, then joked, ``Hear me, Mr. Murdoch? ... It would take
about a billion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
