<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR OLOWOKANDI, IT COULDN'T BE ANY WORSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hey, Michael Olowokandi .... You decided
basketball looked like a good time, so you left England about four
years ago and enrolled at the University of the Pacific. Three
years later, you were chosen by the Los Angeles Clippers with the
first pick in the 1998 NBA draft, you learned low-post secrets from
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar during the lockout, then you bolted for Italy
when the NBA season appeared doomed. Now you're back in the United
States, preparing for your very first NBA game. Any concerns?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it won't be as bad,'' said the 7-foot rookie an hour
before his first NBA tipoff, ``as that first game at Pacific. I
think that one was an exhibition game.''
</P>
<P>
   How'd it turn out?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say it was an experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Still looking out for No. 1: The Clippers also had the first
pick in the 1988 draft, selecting Kansas All-American and current
Phoenix super-sub Danny Manning. Manning, beginning his fifth
season with the Suns, spent 5{ seasons with the Clippers before
getting shipped to Atlanta for Dominique Wilkins in 1994. The NBA's
reigning Sixth Man of the Year, Manning has recovered from a third
major knee surgery and scored 30 points last week in two exhibition
victories over Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Local favorite Suns: Friday's Sports Arena visit also was a
homecoming for the Suns' two rookie guards, Toby Bailey and Gerald
Brown. Bailey, a 6-foot-5 off-guard from UCLA, was chosen in the
second round (45th overall) of last year's NBA draft. A lingering
hamstring injury to Rex Chapman means Bailey will be tossed into
the fire early. Bailey scored 15 points and had 12 rebounds in two
exhibition games against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, an undrafted free agent from Pepperdine, will begin the
season backing up Jason Kidd at point guard. Brown scored 21 points
in the two Dallas games.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Rebel with a cause: When training camp opened two weeks ago,
the only person on the Clippers payroll who expected Tyrone Nesby
to be at the Sports Arena and in uniform for the opener was ...
Tyrone Nesby.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth,'' said the undrafted rookie forward
from Nevada-Las Vegas, ``I always thought I could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   When he wasn't picked in last year's NBA draft, Nesby went to
the Continental Basketball Association, playing 25 games with the
Sioux Falls Skyforce before getting invited to a Clippers tryout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably been the biggest surprise in camp,'' coach Chris
Ford said. ``Nez backs down to no one. He goes out there and makes
things happen. I wouldn't hesitate to use him early.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second of the Clippers' exhibition games with the Lakers,
Nesby scored 11 points in just 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I deserve to be here,'' he said. ``There were a lot of
guys who were drafted when I thought I should be, so that's what
motivates me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
