<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALL-TOGETHER-NOW-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO: TRUCE OR CONSEQUENCES  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 850-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 6 February 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``i''
international news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time since the dispute over Kosovo turned bloody a
year ago, it is possible to imagine _ though not, with any
confidence, to predict _ a turn for the better.
</P>
<P>
   So long as the West is firm enough in its brandishing of sticks
and carrots, Serbs and Kosovars may soon be browbeaten into a
compromise that neither side much likes.
</P>
<P>
   Under a deal now in prospect, the province's Albanian-speaking
majority would be freed from the harsh grip of the Serbs, but not,
at least for three years, allowed to secede.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign mediators would be given wide-ranging powers as they
prepared Kosovo for elections. And, just possibly, Europe might
feel a bit better about its capacity to cool the Balkan cauldron.
</P>
<P>
   Not that any cooling will be all Europe's doing. If agreement is
reached at talks near Paris next week, it will be the result,
largely, of unity of purpose among America and its main European
allies.
</P>
<P>
   And if the peace-broking effort fails, it will probably be
because the Serbs, Kosovars or both have spotted differences of
emphasis between the western powers that they can use to wriggle
off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   Already a modicum of transatlantic consensus has moved
deliberations over Kosovo's future into much higher gear. Almost
certainly, the province would still be cascading towards war if the
United States had not decided, last month, to harness its European
partners' support while promising to share, in a reasonable way,
the responsibility for enforcing any agreement.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's experience since the collapse of the Soviet Union has
driven home some important truths, painfully learned in Bosnia,
about the sort of cooperation needed to fight regional fires in the
alliance's backyard.
</P>
<P>
   First, America's preponderance in the use of air power is so
huge that a serious show of willingness to use it can concentrate
the mind of almost any local bully. At a stroke, the threatened or
actual use of precision bombing can sharply tilt the balance of
power in any regional conflict, without much risk for the user.
</P>
<P>
   But the second axiom that NATO has rediscovered is that bombs
alone cannot build multi-ethnic societies, soothe intercommunal
hatred or even protect people from its effects.
</P>
<P>
   Whether in Bosnia or Kosovo, these complex tasks require ground
troops _ not to arbitrate in a full-scale war, as the U.N. tried to
do in Sarajevo, but to shore up cease-fires, decommission weapons,
nip provocations in the bud and rebuild confidence in small, subtle
ways.
</P>
<P>
   European soldiers tend to be better for these purposes than
Americans, not least because American voters have become so
reluctant to see their compatriots die in far-off places where they
see no vital interest.
</P>
<P>
   A third axiom, less often articulated, is that in many such
places the only alternative to deploying peacekeepers in decent
numbers is a brutally enforced exchange of population _ another way
of saying ethnic cleansing. This flies in the face of all the
principles that western governments proclaim.
</P>
<P>
   Togetherness has a price In an ideal world, peacemaking by
American aircraft and peacekeeping by European troops would
complement one another neatly. But things have never been that
simple, and they will not be in Kosovo either.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, threats by NATO to use air power carry much
greater weight if they involve a genuine coalition _ led, perhaps,
by the United States but with more than a token European
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   That, incidentally, is why European governments should spend
money on improving their own ability to use air power efficiently,
with or without American support.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should Europe be left entirely alone to face the risks of
deploying troops in Kosovo's harsh terrain. At the very least, a
peacekeeping force in Kosovo will need American logistics, American
intelligence and an American guarantee of extraction from danger.
</P>
<P>
   American help could, however, be even more valuable: a small
contribution to any ground force would send a clear signal to local
warriors that the force could not be harmed with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration will have difficulty getting Congress
to agree to send even a limited number of ground troops: skeptical
congressmen are keen to drop bombs but hate putting soldiers in
harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the administration can win the day, especially if it
does not present the proposal in a partisan manner; at least some
Republicans are sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, Europe should get the help it needs to
stabilize Kosovo, this time. But Europeans should not be fooled by
the news this week that America proposes to spend an extra $112
billion on defense over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Among the various claims on that money _ pay rises, anti-missile
defenses, cyber-warfare _ European peacekeeping ranks low.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO's 50th anniversary summit will doubtless declare in
April, burden-sharing in the alliance is more important than ever.
But its survival, in Kosovo and elsewhere, may depend on Europe's
willingness to pay a bigger share of the bill. &QL; 
