<HEADER>
A4306 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-MAGIC-NYT &LR;      02-06 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-MAGIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS OPEN A NEW SEASON WITH SAME OLD LIABILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ With his team getting run off the Orlando Arena
floor Friday night, Jeff Van Gundy called a timeout in the opening
moments of the fourth quarter. Disgusted, he scolded the Knicks as
if they were misbehaving school children.
</P>
<P>
   Amid great expectations in their season opener, this new class
was that bad.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing all their old liabilities to bear _ hot heads, cold
shooting hands and a sloppy offense _ the Knicks fell apart in the
second half and were blown out by the Magic, 93-85.
</P>
<P>
   Down by 21 points midway through the fourth period, they gnawed
and clawed to get within 9 points in the final minutes. Latrell
Sprewell's 3-pointer with 2 minutes, 52 seconds remaining and
Charlie Ward's layup moments later capped an 11-0 run and brought
New York to within 82-75.
</P>
<P>
   But the game of catch-up was too huge after the Knicks had dug
themselves a huge hole in third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Some debut. Sprewell finished with 18 points on 8-of-16
shooting, and Patrick Ewing ended with 15 points on 7-for-13
shooting. But Allan Houston's misfires hurt. He hit only 5 of 17
shots, and, like the Knicks, looked out of rhythm each time he rose
and released the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Anderson finished with 19 points for Orlando, which simply
played smarter and stronger than the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Outlaw made the defining play of the night, sending a lean-in
Sprewell shot with fewer than 9 minutes remaining straight to the
floor. The block sent the crowd into a tizzy. It had booed Sprewell
from the start of the game, and felt a great satisfaction to see
perhaps the league's most unpopular player rejected. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks fell apart at the end of the third quarter, scoring
just 3 points in five minutes and looking completely out of sync.
They were down by 14 points heading into the final period.
</P>
<P>
   Horace Grant gave Orlando a 68-58 lead with 1:17 remaining in
the period, and then one of the Knicks' old liabilities came back
to haunt them: their point guard lost his head.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Childs gave the rookie Matt Harpring a shove into the
backboard support after Grant's basket, a heated moment that cost
him a technical foul and the Knicks another point. Then Sprewell
missed two free throws and it just kept getting worse for the
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 6:13 of the quarter, the Knicks were 1 for 7 from
the floor, 1 for 5 from the line and had 3 turnovers in 11
possessions.
</P>
<P>
   At times, there were flashes of greatness, like Ward finding
Houston gliding to the basket in midair for a layup in the first
half, or the way the Knicks whipped the ball around the perimeter
looking for the open man in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell threw down his first dunk as a Knick with 11:18 left in
the third quarter, a vicious two-handed breakaway jam that left him
sneering with delight. It seemed to be his way of telling the
Orlando crowd to get off his back.
</P>
<P>
   On the night he officially returned to the NBA _ 14 months after
choking P. J. Carlesimo and establishing himself as the league's
primary headache _ Sprewell was booed lustily.
</P>
<P>
   During player introductions. When he went to the free-throw
line. And almost every time he checked out of the game and returned
to the bench. One young fan held up a sign that read, ``Choke,
Spree.''
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to fit into a new offense and blend in with
Ewing and Houston. It is completely another to absorb the wrath of
almost every NBA road fan in America.
</P>
<P>
   If the Pat Riley-coached Knicks were reviled for most of the
1990s as hooligans in gym shorts, Sprewell's arrival begins a new
villainous chapter for the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only took seven minutes into the third quarter of a
preseason game for them to embrace him in New York,'' said Knicks
Coach Jeff Van Gundy, alluding to the standing ovation Sprewell
received in a preseason game. ``Road fans? I don't know if road
fans will ever warm up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's first day back on the road in the NBA began
encouragingly. He took extra shots after the morning shootaround at
the Orlando Arena, answered a few questions as he walked back to
the team hotel and, once there, was greeted by a few more fans
welcoming him back to the league.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived at the arena more than two hours before the game, and
began working on his 3-point shot. Knicks fans who had filed into
the arena early shouted words of encouragement to him.
</P>
<P>
   The onslaught began soon after. He knew it was coming. Yet
still, the reaction seemed to make him apprehensive in the game's
first few minutes. Horace Grant went over Sprewell's back and
tipped in two rebounds, he missed his first shot and checked out of
the game to a chorus of jeers with 5:58 left in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Friday morning what he expected, he said, ``A lot of
booing. A lot of heckling.''
</P>
<P>
   He had not played in a game since Nov. 29, 1997, two days before
the practice in which he attacked and threatened to kill Carlesimo
during a wild altercation. Suspended for a year by Commissioner
David Stern, he had his contract terminated by the Golden State
Warriors
</P>
<P>
   Though the arbitrator John Feerick sharply reduced the penalty,
Sprewell ended up missing 68 games that cost him $6.4 million in
salary _ the longest and costliest non-drug related suspension in
league history.
</P>
<P>
   He returned Friday night to an unfriendly crowd that scrutinized
his every move and waited anxiously for him to play poorly.
</P>
<P>
   As a team, the Knicks gave Magic fans their wish in the first 24
minutes. About the only thing the Knicks could be encouraged about
after the first half was that their three best players _ Houston,
Ewing and Sprewell _ had not played well together. And yet, they
were only trailing by 46-44. Ward had four turnovers early on. He
made some poor decisions by penetrating too far under the basket as
the defense collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson and the free-agent acquisition Kurt Thomas
compensated for everyone else's deficiencies. They combined to grab
10 rebounds and score 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   Until that awful third quarter, the Knicks had a shot. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
