<HEADER>
A4309 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAVE-THE-EVERGLADES-E     02-06 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAVE-THE-EVERGLADES-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN TO SAVE FLORIDA EVERGLADES IS ON TAP  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Florida)   (This excellent 750-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 6 February 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD AND HOMESTEAD, FLA. _ Cutting through the condominium
complexes and strip malls that dominate the landscape north of
Miami, hundreds of miles of canals make their way to the Atlantic.
Once there, they disgorge into the ocean 1.7 billion gallons (6.4
billion liters) of fresh water a day.
</P>
<P>
   A hundred miles to the south, the parched Everglades National
Park struggles to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Water levels in the park are half what they were 50 years ago.
As if coming from a cheap tap, the water flow in south Florida is
never right.
</P>
<P>
   Long before New Yorkers discovered Florida, the south of the
state was a marshy haven for alligators and exotic birds. Each year
the summer rains that flooded Lake Okeechobee created natural
rivers running southward, ensuring a steady flow of fresh water for
the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   As Florida's population expanded, however, developers and
farmers saw little profit in swamps. They began pushing for an
intricate system of drainage canals leading to the ocean to dry out
the land, protect it against future flooding and provide drinking
water for new residents.
</P>
<P>
   The Army Corps of Engineers undertook such a project in 1947,
and south Florida's population and land prices have been rising
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, like a tourniquet, the new water-control system shut off
the natural flow of fresh water to the Everglades, and development
has since cut the region almost in half.
</P>
<P>
   A series of dykes now regulate the amount of water that enters
the Everglades National Park, drying up large tracts of marshland.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the water that does run into the park is contaminated by
chemicals sent downstream from farms; park officials estimate that
there has been a 93 percent decline in the bird population since
the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the water-management system has signally
failed to keep pace with south Florida's growth. Created to provide
drinking water for 2 million people, it must now must serve 6
million, with as many as 15 million expected by 2050.
</P>
<P>
   As if to redress its mistakes, the Army Corps of Engineers is
now back in the picture. A 20-year, $7.8 billion plan (the largest
environmental restoration proposal in American history), introduced
by Vice-President Al Gore last October, proposes that the engineers
should destroy several of the dykes that keep water from reaching
the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, thousands of acres of land in the region would be
bought by the government to act as reservoirs for the increased
water flow.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also calls for drilling hundreds of wells 1,000 feet
deep to store excess rainwater for the dry months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   To appease the state's powerful agricultural interests,
extensive flood-control measures are proposed to ensure that the
redirected water does not spill over on to farmland.
</P>
<P>
   The plan (to be paid for with both state and federal money) will
not be voted on by Congress until July. It must first withstand all
kinds of challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club, an environmental group, objects to the proposed
use of underground storage wells, arguing that by building a
drinking water infrastructure to accommodate 15 million people
Florida is only encouraging further urban sprawl during the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the group advocates increasing the amount of land to be
bought for reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Florida's powerful
construction-and-land-development lobby argues that the proposed
land purchase is too large, and that the cost of the project will
require an exorbitant increase in property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Another blow to the proposal came in a recent letter to the
secretary of the interior, Bruce Babbitt. The letter, signed by six
eminent ecologists, argued that there were ``deep, systematic
problems'' with the plan, and that it needed further review by an
independent group of scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush, Florida's new governor, used to be a land developer,
and environmentalists were doubtful of his support. Yet Bush has
pledged that he will endorse the Everglades work so long as it is
based on sound science and fiscal accountability; he recently
appointed an ``Everglades czar'' in his administration.
</P>
<P>
   All sides agree that the state's water-management system has to
be changed, the sooner the better. But, with Florida's demographics
and ecosystems continually subject to change, water management _ as
one Miami lawyer explains it _ is much like Rubik's cube: solve one
bit of the puzzle, and you create several more. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 750-word article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 0057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
