reduce ``unnecessary'' procedures; mandatory authorization before
patients are sent on to further treatment; and swift ending of
contracts if doctors fail to live up to the mark.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, doctors dislike this close accounting, saying
that it lowers the quality of their work.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 survey by the Commonwealth Fund and Louis Harris and
Associates found that roughly 40 percent of doctors complained they
had less control in medical decision-making and less time to spend
with patients than three years earlier, in part because of the
administrative load.
</P>
<P>
   Only a quarter were fully satisfied with practicing medicine, a
disturbing statistic for patients.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some American doctors actually envy their colleagues in
Britain who, although enrolled in the National Health Service, are
not (yet) micro-managed to anything like the same degree.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors also complain that their wallets are stretched. It is
hard to shed tears, when their average annual income has increased
by roughly 5 percent a year to $166,000 today; but, according to
Wendy Everett of the Institute for the Future, a health-care
consultancy in Menlo Park, Calif., some specialists have seen their
earnings more than halved over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Although general practitioners are in shorter supply than
specialists, and more keenly sought by HMOs, they too are trying to
shy away from managed care.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jose Escarce of RAND in Santa Monica, cities with
plenty of HMO coverage are half as likely to attract new doctors
into practice as areas, such as parts of the Midwest, that remain
relatively HMO-free.
</P>
<P>
   But America's doctors can run only so far: over 90 percent of
them have some dealings with managed-care companies, since over
two-thirds of their patients are enrolled in them. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 600. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Medicine is a complex business in America, and doctors are not
the only, or indeed the most important, players. Once medical
professionals directed health-care policy; now there are employers,
managers, money men and increasingly vocal patients.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Schroeder, president of the Robert Wood Johnson
Foundation in Princeton, N.J., reckons that doctors have lost their
central role in the health-care debate largely because they spent
their time on the wrong issue.
</P>
<P>
   Since Medicare was introduced in the 1960s, the AMA and its
doctors have been fighting government involvement in medical
practice for fear it would undermine their autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   What they did not appreciate until recently, Dr. Schroeder says,
is that corporate managed care would prove far more effective at
putting them in their place.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, doctors are trying to adapt. Although two-thirds of
them still work alone or with a single partner, Arnold Relman,
former editor of the New England Journal of Medicine, predicts that
American doctors will increasingly gather into large group
practices and integrated medical centers like the Mayo Clinic,
where they can pool their resources more effectively to fight the
HMOs and run their own affairs.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems that new graduates, trained in the shadow of modern
managed care, are better equipped to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly medicine remains a popular profession in America:
there are almost three applicants for every medical-school place,
up by two-thirds from a decade ago. And, since in the end almost
everybody needs them, doctors have a special hold over people.
</P>
<P>
   One prominent health-care consultant has lamented that doctors
are the biggest single obstacle to reforming American medicine. But
he prefers not to be named, for fear of offending his doctor. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
