<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPINNING-TIRE-BIZ-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON-THE-SKIDS TIRE MAKERS TREAD CAREFULLY TOWARD MERGERS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)   (This excellent 700-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 6 February) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``f'' financial news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK AND TOKYO _ How fortunes change. A decade ago the
takeover of Firestone by Bridgestone, an ambitious Japanese
imitator, seemed to symbolize the decline of America's
manufacturing industry. Today it is the Japanese who seem
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Although the deal announced on Feb. 3 between America's Goodyear
and Japan's Sumitomo Rubber Industries was tactfully described as
an ``alliance,'' nobody is in any doubt over who will be in charge
_ or that other tire mergers are now likely.
</P>
<P>
   Before the deal, Bridgestone, Goodyear and France's Michelin
dominated the industry, with more than half of a world market now
worth an estimated $75 billion.
</P>
<P>
   This merger will reshuffle the rankings, catapulting Goodyear
into the number-one spot, with $15.1 billion in sales and 22.6
percent of the global market.
</P>
<P>
   Sumitomo will receive a shade over YEN 100 billion ($930
million) from Goodyear in exchange for handing over control of its
operations in America, Britain, Germany and France.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest, in Western Europe, will have sales of $4 billion,
almost a third of Goodyear's $13 billion total revenues last year.
Sumitomo will be left with its home market and a business that
makes golf balls.
</P>
<P>
   But Sumitomo was hardly negotiating from strength. Japan's
second-largest tire maker is only a quarter the size of its
arch-rival, Bridgestone, which sold YEN 2.35 trillion-worth of
tires and industrial products around the world in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, Bridgestone has overhauled its pension
scheme (a nightmare for most Japanese companies), written off the
goodwill associated with buying Firestone, replaced equipment and
rationalized its American operations.
</P>
<P>
   Sumitomo, on the other hand, has struggled. Without
Bridgestone's scale, it has had to rely on its depressed domestic
market. Its operating margin for the year to December 1998 was 3.3
percent, compared with Bridgestone's 9.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that the largest tire makers have found life
much easier. In a separate announcement this week, Goodyear
reported falling annual sales last year and announced 2,800 layoffs
as part of a cost-cutting program.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Colas, an analyst at CSFB, reckons that the industry has at
least 15 percent overcapacity. As car makers are squeezing
suppliers on costs, they are expecting better and safer tires.
</P>
<P>
   They are also thwarting tire makers' attempts to reduce the
range of tires on offer, a measure designed to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   Sumitomo, for instance, had been hoping to slim its range by
almost half to 3,000 in the next two years. But, as car makers
themselves are trying to save money by using fewer platforms, they
want to have more varieties of tire to help differentiate their
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear is forecasting $300 million-360 million in cost savings
in three years from this week's deal, a relatively easy target.
There are bound to be further job cuts among the new group's
109,000 employees. There will also be savings from purchasing
efficiencies _ raw materials represent half of the industry's
costs.
</P>
<P>
   And in Europe, the combination of Goodyear and Sumitomo, with
its powerful, but neglected, Dunlop brand, could mount a serious
challenge to Michelin.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the feeling that this deal will lead to others. In Japan,
Michelin has been sniffing around Yokohama Rubber, the
third-largest tire maker, with consolidated sales last year of YEN
415 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Sumitomo, which was linked with Goodyear even before its
recent deal, Yokohama fancies itself as the Pirelli of Asia _ a
go-it-alone maker of high-performance tires, much like the Italian
company.
</P>
<P>
   But such a strategy no longer makes sense, says Kunihiko
Shiohara of ING Barings. Sumitomo's sellout means that Yokohama is
now, in effect, on the block.
</P>
<P>
   In other markets there are regulatory worries. A merger between
Germany's Continental and Michelin would be ``an antitrust
nightmare,'' says Colas.
</P>
<P>
   Pirelli would fit with Goodyear, but their 90 percent or so
share of the Brazilian market would complicate a linkup. So
Bridgestone might pounce on Pirelli, even though it would do better
to buy a low-cost tire maker in Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Tire makers everywhere will be looking anxiously over their
shoulders. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 700-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
