<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-SONICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS DROP OPENER TO SONICS IN OVERTIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Mavericks blew a great chance to get the season
off to a great start last night.
</P>
<P>
   With two opportunities to defeat Seattle in regulation, the
Mavericks missed both chances and wound up dropping a 92-86
decision to the SuperSonics in overtime at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle outscored Dallas, 8-2 in overtime, as the season finally
got started after a 191-day old lockout.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks will complete a two-game road trip tomorrow night
in Oakland against the Golden State Warriors. The Mavericks' home
opener is scheduled for Tuesday against the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Steve Nash could have won the game for Dallas in
regulation, but he missed a 20-foot jumper with six seconds left.
A.C. Green rebounded with 4.9 seconds left, and the Mavs called
timeout to work for the possible winning basket.
</P>
<P>
   Cedric Ceballos got the ball on the play after the timeout, but
lost it on a drive to the basket, and the game went into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Sonics guard Gary Payton took over from there, scoring the first
six points of the extra session as Seattle opened the era of new
coach Paul Westphal on a winning note.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks won their second game of the season here last
season, and seem to always play well in this building. But this
time they couldn't close the deal when they were sitting right in
the cat bird's seat.
</P>
<P>
   With four new players on their roster, the Mavericks were
looking to see where they stood against one of the conference's
elite teams. What they found is that they're not far from being
where they want to be.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs stayed close most of the game, and led by eight points
early in the second period. But costly turnovers, combined with
failing to prevent the Sonics from getting second shots, wound up
costing the Mavs.
</P>
<P>
   Green tied the game at 84-84 when he took a feed from Nash and
drilled an 18-footer from the left side. Then came those frantic
two shots in the waning seconds that couldn't find the mark.
</P>
<P>
   Green scored four points and grabbed six rebounds as the Mavs
shot .579 from the field and led after the first period, 27-21
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs padded the lead to as much as eight points early in the
second period. But the Sonics took a 46-42 lead at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Payton scored 10 of his points in the first half, and center
Olden Polynice had nine points and seven rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Mavs coach Don Nelson used his bench judiciously, playing 13
players in the first half. All scored except Hubert Davis and Chris
Anstey.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Dirk Nowitzki was starting his first pro game, and it was
obvious he had butterflies. Nowitzki missed all three of his shots
in the first half and was scoreless at intermission, including two
long-range shots that went over the backboard.
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki wound up with two points _ both on free throws _ and
was 0-of-5 from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   A jumper by Vin Baker pushed the Sonics ahead 52-46 three
minutes into the third quarter. But a running jumper by Ceballos,
who scored a team-high 16 points, and an offensive rebound by Gary
Trent off a missed free throw bolted the Mavs ahead, 67-64, going
into the final period.
</P>
<P>
   Nash, who had nine points, buried a 3-point field goal as the
Mavs closed to within 78-77 with 5:02 left.
</P>
<P>
   Erick Strickland had 10 points and Michael Finley added 9 points
for the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mavs are kicking themselves for blowing two chances down
the stretch, when they could have won the game before it went into
overtime. /
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
