<SLUG> BC-TV-XFILES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUTH REVEALED ...WELL, SOME OF IT, BY `X' STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone else out there get the feeling that, soon after the
season opener, ``The X-Files'' crossed the center line and drove
off the cliff in pursuit of Thelma and Louise?
</P>
<P>
   If so, I have good news. ``The X-Files'' that you know and love
_ the one about Fox Mulder's quest to expose the conspiracy between
the shadowy Syndicate and the alien invaders _ is back, at least
for the next two episodes. And just in time. Another goofball
stand-alone episode like the Christmas one with Ed Asner and Lily
Tomlin as holey ghosts might have made me an ex-phile. Even the
``Dreamland'' two-parter, in which Mulder (David Duchovny) assumed
another man's identity, drove me to paying bills and doing the
laundry. On a critic's scale of disapproval, you can't sink much
lower without striking oil.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, viewers will find out in the February-sweeps
two-parter airing Sunday and Feb. 14 that the black oil that wreaks
havoc on the human condition is called ``purity,'' and it's the
lifeblood of the alien invaders.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the mischievous style of Chris Carter, the
self-described paranoiac responsible for ``The X-Files.'' It is
also like Carter to open up a new can of worms as he puts the old
ones on the compost pile.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a lot of stuff explained,'' Carter
promised, ``... (but) that doesn't necessarily mean everything's
wrapped up and finished. In fact, there's a lot to do.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. We'll learn a great deal about the conspiracy and
the Cigarette Smoking Man (William B. Davis) in these two episodes,
both written by Carter and Frank Spotnitz. But there's plenty of
truth still out there (see box).
</P>
<P>
   Carter assumes the series will run at least one more season _
its seventh _ and then he wants to build on the movie franchise
begun last summer. (He thinks the next film could be out in 2001.)
</P>
<P>
   ``An eighth season could happen,'' he said, ``but the plans are
to culminate at the end of season seven. I don't think you
necessarily have to have a movie in the theaters right after that.
Maybe a year is a good amount of time before the next movie.''
</P>
<P>
   As to how it all ends, even Carter isn't entirely certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you try to define it too early and too well,'' he said,
``you lose some of the fun of discovering it along the way. I use
the Lewis and Clark analogy all the time: They knew which direction
they were headed, (but) didn't know what they were going to find.
That's kind of the way we've been proceeding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
