<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-LIMITS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION SEEKS TO END LANDING LIMITS AT SOME AIRPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS grafs 3 &AMP; 4 to move up info explaining the purpose of landing
limits and to explain the term `incumbent carriers';   graf 12 to
move up info on `ripple effect' of too many planes
landing;editorial refinements throughout.) 
(ATTN: Ill., N.Y., Neb.)  (lb) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD and JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration wants to end limits on
how many planes can land in an hour at New York's Kennedy
International and La Guardia airports and Chicago's O'Hare,
according to people who have been briefed on the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The change would make it easier for start-up airlines to
challenge established carriers, at a time when transportation
officials have been taking steps to increase capacity and are
looking for other ways to promote airline competition.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of limits is not one of safety, Federal Aviation
Administration officials said. If planes are joining an approach
queue faster than they are landing, air traffic controllers simply
tell them to fly slower, or not to take off.
</P>
<P>
   But in establishing who can fly into the four airports, the
Transportation Department has handed a huge advantage to
``incumbent'' carriers, which were allotted most of the landing
``slots'' decades ago and have relinquished few of them. Slots are
now bought and sold for prices up to $3 million each, aviation
executives say.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department, in a request to Congress on
Monday, will ask for legislation phasing out the rule that limits
flights at the three airports, officials said. While the department
could act itself, congressional action provides political cover and
would be less subject to court challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Political brawls over similar proposals have broken out between
lawmakers barraged by noise complaints and others lobbying for more
air service. It is a particularly emotional, and local, issue.
</P>
<P>
   In his only major interview since becoming House speaker, Dennis
Hastert, whose Illinois district is near enough to O'Hare to
benefit from more service but far enough to escape most noise
problems, told The Chicago Sun-Times that he was open to adding
flights there.
</P>
<P>
   The rule limiting flights ``is a major impediment to better air
service for communities all over the country,'' said Jeffrey Shane,
an aviation lawyer who represents Access Air, a new carrier, based
in Omaha, Neb., that wants to fly its three Boeing 737s to La
Guardia. Access leases two slots from Northwest Airlines but fears
that Northwest will soon take them back for its own use.
</P>
<P>
   Others said the effect of a change would be hard to predict. At
the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, Allen Morrison, a
spokesman, said that the limits have forced various airlines to be
turned away but that the agency did not know how many.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Air Traffic Controllers Association, the union's
executive vice president, James Randall Schwitz Jr., said, ``It's
basically going to have no effect on the system.''
</P>
<P>
   The airports are near saturation levels now, he said, and ``you
can only put a certain number of airplanes in a given amount of air
space at a certain time.''
</P>
<P>
   If more planes try to land and all are delayed as a result,
experts said, that would ripple through the system, as airplanes
land late, take off late for their next flights and continue to be
late all day, with passengers missing connections.
</P>
<P>
   But other aviation experts emphasized that the government was
bringing in new landing systems and other technology to increase
capacity, and that the limits on flights were too constricting.
</P>
<P>
   And Shane said that some airlines did not use all their slots
every day, or flew small planes just to maintain the slots and keep
others from getting them.
</P>
<P>
   How elimination of the rule would affect the balance and
competition among airlines is hard to predict, experts said. Samuel
Buttrick, an airline analyst at Paine Webber, said, ``Open access
to slot-controlled airports will offer entry to discount carriers,
but at the same time allow dominant carriers to expand.''
</P>
<P>
   If not for slot controls at O'Hare, Buttrick said, United
Airlines might have squeezed out the other hub carrier, American.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the congressional delegations from the New York
metropolitan region are expected to join House members from near
O'Hare, including Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., to fight the plan in the
House. Last year, a similar coalition succeeded in killing a bill
that would have allowed more departures and arrivals at the
restricted airports.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   New York City leaders were lining up to oppose the proposal.
``They are crazy,'' said Claire Shulman, the Queens borough
president. ``Maybe it would lower fares a little bit. But on
balance, this will be a disaster for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan is likely to win strong support from other regions,
where officials complain that high air fares are hurting the
economies of smaller cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think my colleagues downstate would want Syracuse,
Binghamton, Rochester and Buffalo to die because they couldn't
stand 10 more flights a day,'' said Rep. Louise Slaughter,
D-Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The policy, formally called the high-density rule, was
established 30 years ago but the numbers have been gradually
increased since then. The proposal to phase out the rule over five
years will be part of the administration's bill to reauthorize the
Federal Aviation Administration; the last reauthorization was for
just six months, in part because of a dispute over limits on
airport operations, and it expires on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   National Airport, across the Potomac River from Washington, is
the only other airport with such limitations; it would not be
affected by the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   At O'Hare, existing rules limit arrivals to 80 in any half-hour
and 155 an hour. At La Guardia, the limit is 68 an hour; at
Kennedy, the rules are in effect from 3 p.m. until 8 p.m., and the
hourly limits vary from 75 to 95. At all three airports, there are
subquotas for big airliners, commuter flights and general-aviation
planes.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Transportation Department refused to comment in
advance of the Monday announcement. But the transportation
secretary, Rodney Slater, said in a speech in New York on
Wednesday, ``In the past year, the high-density rule has come under
increasing scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be an issue on which all of us must engage in the
coming legislative year,'' he said in the speech, to the Wings
Club, an aviation group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 0131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
