<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4332 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI &LR;      02-06 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON STAFF HAD IMPROPER CONTACT WITH AN EIGHTH RECRUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The University of Washington acknowledged Friday that
five UW signees to football letters of intent were visited
improperly by Husky coaches, not four, and that coaches visited a
total of eight recruits Sunday outside NCAA regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In another twist to the UW's admitted violation of two NCAA
rules this week, the discrepancy came to light Friday when Oregon
coach Mike Bellotti alleged that the Huskies also talked Sunday to
defensive lineman Kevin Mack of Oxnard, Calif., a recruit who
signed with the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, UW assistant coach Randy Hart acknowledged that the
conversation with Mack came in the home of Husky recruit Jerome
Stevens, a linebacker at Rio Mesa High in Oxnard and a close friend
of Mack.
</P>
<P>
   Until that disclosure, the Huskies had said four of their signed
recruits had been visited Sunday by their coaches. Washington had
not mentioned Stevens in its list of the four visited.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Daves, the UW sports information director, ascribed the
discrepancy to a mistake by Rick Neuheisel, the new head coach, who
in a press conference Wednesday had listed only four Husky recruits
as having been a part of the improper visits.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, UW compliance director Ralph Bayard said Friday there
were three other recruits contacted who didn't sign with the UW:
Mack; Adam Wade of Moreno Valley, Calif., who signed Friday with
Colorado State; and Daniel Waldrop, a lineman from Los Angeles who
wavered among Washington State, Colorado and Nebraska down the
stretch before choosing Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Daves said the confusion arose during Neuheisel's hurried
explanation Wednesday during what was originally scheduled to be a
briefing of the media on letters of intent signed that day.
</P>
<P>
   After Neuheisel arrived 50 minutes late for the meeting, he went
over recruiting in detail. He then spent seven minutes addressing
the NCAA violations before Daves indicated he needed to leave for a
player meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at one point how many of the signed Huskies had been
visited illegally Sunday, Neuheisel said, ``Five. No, wait a
minute.'' Then he read the names of John Anderson, Chris Massey,
Domynic Shaw and Clayton Hathorne, leaving out Jerome Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Bayard said Friday he felt it was an oversight by Neuheisel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that five had signed with us in my own mind,'' Bayard
said.
</P>
<P>
   The improper visits are part of a two-pronged bugaboo this week
for Neuheisel, who admitted having made calls to enrolled Colorado
players in apparent violation of an NCAA rule. But he emphatically
denied trying to recruit those players, as CU has alleged, and no
player called by Neuheisel has pointed to that train of
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Bellotti, one of four coaches who has publicly taken the Huskies
to task for the visitation violation, said he was alerted by an
assistant coach to the Hart visit to the two recruits, Stevens and
Mack.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd been recruiting him (Mack) the whole time,'' Bellotti
said, referring to the recruiting season.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, indeed, apparently was impressionable. SuperPrep Magazine
said in mid-January he had committed to San Diego State and quoted
Mack as saying, ``I remain open, even though I am committed.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had requested that Mack come to Stevens' home, Hart
said, ``When I got there, they said, `Kevin's coming over.' I said,
`Great.' He said he wasn't going to change. He had already
committed to Oregon a week ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellotti maintains Oregon still had a shot at Massey before
Washington's visit to him Sunday, although Massey and his father
had indicated a lean toward Washington down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Bellotti said, referring to Oregon's chances at
Massey. ``My conversation with the dad on Monday led me to believe
that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Gueringer, who coached both Massey and Wade, said Friday,
``The Washington guy (defensive coordinator Tim Hundley) had no
influence on the decision those kids made. Chris was always a
Washington guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade, meanwhile, wanted to sign with Colorado State earlier this
week, but his father wouldn't validate his son's letter of intent,
preferring he go to Washington. Finally, the father relented and
Wade signed Friday with CSU.
</P>
<P>
   The twin flaps have made for a rocky welcome for Neuheisel,
whose arrival at Washington already had been greeted with some
controversy because of his $1-million-per-year contract, apparently
one of the five highest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel, who coached four years at Colorado, knew some
similarly tough times in Boulder despite a 33-14 record. In 1997,
the Buffaloes forfeited all their victories in a 5-6 season for the
use of an ineligible player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed that Neuheisel could have any staff members in
prospects' homes during the quiet period,'' said Wayne Drumm of
Anchorage, father of Colorado player Brandon Drumm. ``Even parents
of recruits know those rules. I can't see any way coaches wouldn't
know. It blows my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   As is routine in matters involving NCAA irregularities,
Washington declared ineligible the five who signed with the Huskies
and is expecting to see them reinstated soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 Conference will investigate the two violations and
decide in June whether to reprimand or penalize the Huskies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
