<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4350 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     02-06 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS WARM UP TO RETURN OF NBA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ They love it. They know it. And on Friday
they weren't afraid to show it.
</P>
<P>
   The fans at the Los Angeles Lakers' season opener against
Houston were in midseason form even if the Lakers and Rockets were
not. The sellout crowd of 17,505 came late and left early, before
Eddie Jones put the finishing polish on the Lakers' 99-91 win.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA may have shown a reckless disregard for its fans by
staging a four-month lockout, but on this night all seemed
forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, taking the temperature of fans outside the Forum to
gauge NBA fever was like collecting opinions about the pope's
recent trip to the United States from people on their way into a
Roman Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the faithful were flush with excitement. They had
braved the worst traffic conditions imaginable _ getaway Friday,
rush hour, rain _ and temperatures almost as cold as Jones'
first-quarter shooting to be there, hadn't they? If that's not
commitment, it's sufficient grounds to be committed.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say that Dale Madison and his three buddies who were
having a good ol' time tailgating in the reserved parking lot at
the Forum three hours before the start of the game were not among
the 53percent who responded to a recent national survey by saying
they had missed pro basketball ``only a little'' or ``not at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were dying,'' Madison said as he poked at a piece of
poultry on his handy hibachi. And what did he call this First
Supper?
</P>
<P>
   ``Chick-en Hearn,'' Madison said, grinning.
</P>
<P>
   But of course.
</P>
<P>
   You could say Madison and his friends Tim Arebalo, Ben Correa
and Jason Jimenez are sick, and you'd be technically correct. They
all came down with the flu sometime after noon and left their jobs
early. That was the only way they could beat the traffic into L.A.
from their hometown of Chino.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we do for the Lakers,'' Madison said between gulps
of rum and Coke.
</P>
<P>
   If their tortillas were getting soggy because of the rain,
Madison and his buddies didn't seem to notice.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a zealot to find satisfaction in soggy chicken and
sloppy basketball. And it takes some kind of devoutness to gather
outside the players' tunnel a couple of hours before the opening
tip and just stand there and be spit on by clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Smith, Jo Santos and Albert Bungay let their smiles be
their umbrella. After four months of sitting around and waiting for
the NBA season to begin, nothing could dampen their spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were missing the players,'' Smith said as her friends
nodded.
</P>
<P>
   And if none of the players rolled down their windows to sign an
autograph or 20 before their cars disappeared down the tunnel,
well, at least most of them smiled and waved as they coasted by.
</P>
<P>
   That may have been enough to mollify the likes of Smith, Santos
and Bungay, but frankly, Arlene Herrera had been hoping for a
little more love. Two hours before the opening tip she also was
standing near the tunnel, hugging a hodgepodge of pictures that she
wanted the players to sign.
</P>
<P>
   She figured they'd be a bit more accommodating, after what the
league put its fans through these past few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't they owe us at least a smile or an autograph?'' Herrera
wondered aloud.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ebdane could have told her she was all wet if she thought
she'd be rewarded for standing out in the rain.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lakers were in Santa Barbara for training camp, Ebdane
and his buddies drove from their homes in Oxnard to UCSB to obtain
the players' autographs.
</P>
<P>
   They said they were roundly ignored by everybody except Kobe
Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't make so much money, but we always support the
Lakers,'' Ebdane said. ``At least they can give us autographs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebdane was standing outside the Forum Club with a camcorder
cradled in one hand, killing time and chilling out after making the
two-hour drive from Oxnard. Having given up on getting the
attention of the players, he had shifted his focus to other
celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   He already had recorded the entrances of Lakers Executive Vice
President Jerry West and former USC star-turned-commentator Cheryl
Miller and was hopeful of catching Jack Nicholson, or perhaps Dyan
Cannon and other female cast members of ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ebdane stared entranced at the Forum Club entrance, his
friend Jesse Dumava looked at him and laughed. ``This guy was so
excited last night,'' Dumava said, ``he couldn't sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   If you were sleepwalking toward the Forum doors some 90 minutes
before the game, you were in danger of being wiped out by a
green-and-yellow wave that rolled in like high tide from the
parking lot at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   A large group of rowdy college exchange students from San Diego
spilled out toward the arena. The way they were chanting, you would
have thought they were on their way to a soccer friendly.
</P>
<P>
   What in the world were they saying?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain it,'' said Rafael Zarvos. ``This is my first
time at an NBA game.''
</P>
<P>
   Once inside the building, he would say, his voice filled with
wonderment, ``I don't believe I can see Shaquille O'Neal.''
</P>
<P>
   How hard was it going four months without watching O'Neal brick
a free throw? Joseph Nelson of Westchester said he gave up beef
awhile back, and not having the NBA on his plate was a lot harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be wanting that roundball,'' Nelson said, ``just like I'd
be wanting that steak.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the sirloin _ for one night, at least, the sizzle was
enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 0207EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4351 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      02-06 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS A TOUGH READ AMID NBA'S `MIDSEASON' PARITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As is customary at this early February juncture of the
NBA season, it's time for the midseason report card.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most remarkable thing about the season so far is the
parity. Who could have imagined last summer that by the All-Star
Game break every team in the league would be either tied for the
divisional lead or no more than one game back?
</P>
<P>
   For years, the NFL has worked actively toward this kind of
balance. But as the sports fan has come to learn this decade, the
NBA always seems to be a step quicker than every other sport.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA puts to shame major league baseball, where more than
half the teams will enter spring training with no hope of a
championship, thanks to huge, unchecked revenue disparities between
franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here is pro hoops, almost at Valentine's Day, and no team,
thanks to the NBA's enlightened, creative labor policies, is
anywhere close to elimination (with the possible exception of the
Clippers, who have an automatic entry into the NIT).
</P>
<P>
   And since every game at KeyArena has gone into overtime,
including Friday night's 92-86 win over the Dallas Mavericks, the
promise of excitement is almost unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   There is a problem, however. Such evenness makes it difficult to
distinguish the trends that will be difference-makers in the
season's second half. Other than the dominance of the Mavericks,
who have never beaten the Sonics this year, it is hard to make
sweeping assessments about the Seattle club.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, some Sonic and league developments are clear at
the mid-winter break:
</P>
<P>
   --Despite a change in management, Gary Payton still owns this
team. His season averages of 28 points, 7 rebounds and 6 assists
are testaments to the best guard in the game, now that
what's-his-name is back to selling phone service.
</P>
<P>
   --Soon-to-be-Thin Vin Baker is almost playing as well as he did
during the last regular season. But his season doesn't start until
he makes everyone forget last year's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   --Given George Karl's magnificent regular-season record, Sonic
fans were naturally concerned that the transition to new coach Paul
Westphal would be filled with problems. While Westphal is indeed a
thousand words behind Karl in the quote standings, the undefeated
record speaks eloquently to his basketball genius. Club president
Wally Walker has never made a more inspired coaching hire.
</P>
<P>
   --The shift of Hersey Hawkins from starting guard to reserve, to
accommodate the main offseason acquisition, Belly, er, Billy Owens,
is a bust. The controversial move so far has Owens averaging just 5
points in 22 minutes, while Hawkins, who gets the, ahem, bulk of
the minutes, has scored just two points all season.
</P>
<P>
   There is hope, however, as soon as the Sonics figure whether
Owens on defense has his feet nailed to the floor or merely glued.
</P>
<P>
   --The many scattered patches of empty seats at Key Arena,
particularly in the rich-people regions, is an ominous sign.
Although the building is said to be sold out regularly, it's plain
at least some fans this season prefer to stay at home with Jerry
Springer's TV show if they need to see chunky people pointing and
pushing.
</P>
<P>
   --The league's newest feature, a requirement that each player
shoot at least one airball a game, is taken far too seriously by
the Sonics. Just Friday night the Sonics shot 40 percent, and the
Mavericks missed 10 of 11 field goal attempts in overtime.
Nevertheless, fans of tradition can savor the 5-foot jump-hook
airball from Olden Polynice, who despite his seven-year absence
from Seattle is still packing his trademark.
</P>
<P>
   --Averaging a double-double (11 points, 13 rebounds), Polynice
should be considered just behind Shaquille O'Neal and David
Robinson in the voting for Western Conference All-Star center,
presuming voters in KeyArena are not injured by shrapnel from his
free throws.
</P>
<P>
   --Despite his 36 years, Detlef Schrempf hasn't lost so much as a
single adjective when it comes to complaining to the officials. The
ravages of age often cause many players to moderate, but Schrempf
has shown no loss of victimhood.
</P>
<P>
   --The Mavericks' Cedric Ceballos might be the greatest fat
player since Billy ``The Whopper'' Paultz. In the most recent game
Friday, the semi-cherubic forward had 16 points, including multiple
drives past Sonic defenders, who reinforced the long-ago conclusion
of third-grade spelling class that there is no D in Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   --In the Mavericks' starting frontline tandem of 7-foot-6 center
Shawn Bradley and 7-0 rookie forward Dirk Nowitzki, Northwest
residents have not seen so much slow whiteness since the Nisqually
Glacier.
</P>
<P>
   --In Moochie Norris, the Sonics have the greatest first name in
NBA back-up point guard history. But you knew that right from the
beginning of the season.
</P>
<P>
   So for the second half of the NBA season, the Sonics find
themselves well positioned _ closing in on the lead, backing away
from the buffet table and owning the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   How could Jordan walk away from this?
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
