<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-PRINCE (Amman, Jordan) _ Jordan's next government will
remain committed to peace in the Middle East and close relations
with Washington but wary of both Iran and Iraq, Crown Prince
Abdullah said this week in his first interview since he was
designated successor to his father, King Hussein. By William A.
Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-HUSSEIN (Amman, Jordan) _ King Hussein, ruler of Jordan
for 47 years and the 43rd in his family line of declared direct
descendants of the prophet Muhammed, lay in his deathbed at a
military hospital here Friday, the end of an era for his small
desert kingdom almost at hand. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Paris) _ On the eve of the Kosovo peace
conference, the Serbian government used an early round of
obstructionist tactics and refused to give travel documents to
three military members of the ethnic Albanian delegation who were
due to fly today to the talks. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-MANDELA (Johannesburg) _ President Nelson Mandela gave
his last state of the nation speech to Parliament Friday,
highlighting the successes of South Africa's first post-apartheid
government and calling for the nation's blacks and whites to stop
``slaughtering'' each other with their ``words'' and ``attitudes.''
By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   ISTANBUL-BRIDGE (Istanbul, Turkey) _ Many people here believe
that Istanbul urgently needs at least one more Bosporus crossing.
But reported plans for a new bridge have set off an outpouring of
civic protest that mirrors the battles over urban renewal and
highway construction which broke out in many American cities in the
1960s and '70s. By Stephen Kinzer. With photos and map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-SUSPECT-SHOT (New York) _ Federal officials joined a widening
city investigation on Friday into the killing of an unarmed West
African immigrant by four police officers who fired 41 shots in a
ferocious barrage that remained officially unexplained even as
controversy over the case spread from City Hall to the streets of
the Bronx. By Robert D. McFadden and Kit R. Roane. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   SUBURBAN-SPRAWL (Los Angeles) _ The word ``sprawl'' does not
even appear in the index of ``Earth in the Balance,'' Vice
President Al Gore's earnest 1992 treatise on the environment. But
these days that word and the set of creeping suburban problems it
embraces, from traffic congestion to loss of open space, has
emerged as one of the reigning buzzwords in the political lexicon.
By Todd S. Purdum. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GATES-GIFT (Undated) _ Bill and Melinda Gates have increased the
amount they are giving to their two foundations this year, bringing
the total assets of the two foundations to about $5 billion. By
Katie Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   PATAKI-POLITICS (Undated) _ Taking his bid for national
recognition to the Midwest, New York Gov. George Pataki repeatedly
invoked the politics and philosophy of Ronald Reagan on Friday,
seeking to portray himself as a populist Republican whose ideas
would, like Reagan's, unify his splintered party. By Clifford Levy.
With photo.
</P>
<P>
   DEATHROW-RELEASE (Chicago) _ Anthony Porter, a Chicago man on
death row for 16 years for a 1982 double murder, who came within
two days of being executed, was freed on bond after journalism
students tracked down a man who confessed to the crime. By Pam
Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-WITNESSES (Washington) _ The three witnesses called by
House managers to resuscitate the Senate's impeachment trial gave
little ground under questioning and offered no new evidence to
buttress the perjury and obstruction of justice case against
President Clinton. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-MONICA (Washington) _ Monica Lewinsky was stung enough
to object to the prosecutor's use of the word ``salacious'' in her
deposition for President Clinton's impeachment trial. But otherwise
she showed the bravura demeanor that comes of being one of the most
practiced criminal investigation witnesses in the annals of
presidential history. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ A draft Democratic censure of President
Clinton assails his misconduct as ``shameless, reckless and
indefensible'' and concludes that the president ``gave false or
misleading testimony and impeded discovery of evidence in judicial
proceedings.'' By Eric Schmitt. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-LIMITS (Washington) _ FAA has decided to get out of the
business of limiting landing and takeoff slots at the nation's most
crowded airports: O'Hare, Reagan National, Kennedy and La Guardia.
This will be a great boon to new airlines or existing airlines that
have tried to break in to these markets. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Washington) _ The economy added more jobs than
expected in January, and the unemployment rate remained at a
28-year low of 4.3 percent. The nation's payrolls grew by 245,000
jobs last month, well above forecasts of a gain of 138,000 jobs.
Workers' average hourly earnings, a gauge of business costs, rose
half a percent, or 6 cents, in January, faster than December's
increase of 0.3 percent. By Sylvia Nasar. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BMW-ROVER (Frankfurt, Germany) _ After a boardroom battle that
lasted more than seven hours, the chief executive of BMW AG
resigned Friday and the board announced a broad overhaul of top
management. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   HUMOR-CONSULTANTS (Rochester, N.Y.) _ Companies are hiring humor
consultants to help devise strategies to offset the shell shock of
layoffs and rapidly changing technology. By Michael Brick. With
photos.
</P>
<P>
   TOY-FAIR (New York) _ As the 96th annual American International
Toy Fair gets under way on Monday, toy makers are showing off the
products that will hit store shelves later this year and, they
hope, ultimately land in millions of toy chests. Many are line
extensions of last year's best sellers and others reflect the
growing importance of technology on child's play. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   HEDGE-FUNDS (Undated) _ Though predictions of heavy withdrawals
were rampant, investors are believed to have removed about 5
percent of their assets from hedge funds in a roller-coaster 1998,
according to several companies that track the industry. By
Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Reasonable boomers can always disagree
on exactly when the '60s died _ was it the day the Beatles'
``Revolution'' popped up in a Nike TV ad? _ but there will be no
dispute about when the '60s were embalmed. It's happening this
weekend on NBC, which has turned the decade into a sweeps-month
mini-series that, however earnest, suggests what ``Hair'' might
look like as a Disney theme-park attraction. By Frank Rich.
</P>
