new stamp on Feb. 18 celebrating Jackson Pollock's contribution to
Abstract Expressionism. The stamp is based on a 1949 Life magazine
photograph showing the artist, a chain smoker, in his studio
pouring paint onto canvas, a cigarette hanging precariously from
his mouth. But in an artist's rendering of the photograph on the
stamp, the cigarette has vanished. By Rebecca M. Knight.
</P>
