<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4354 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-SUNS-LAD     02-06 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-SUNS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS BEAT CLIPPERS IN SEASON OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On a Friday night crowded with first impressions,
the Phoenix Suns left the outline of a dreaded and familiar `L'
pushed into the Clippers logo.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Clippers _ who displayed enough pluck and
determination to take a shot at sabotaging their own annual
draft-lottery run _ lost to the Suns 101-92 after being the victims
of a 17-0 Phoenix run in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In front of 7,689 post-lockout witnesses at the lame-duck Sports
Arena, new coach Chris Ford boldly went where every Clippers coach
has gone before. Top draft pick Michael Olowokandi met his first
matchup in the NBA low post _ and he just happened to be Suns
veteran Danny Manning, the league and Clippers' No.1 pick in 1988.
As rumored since the labor tussle ended, All-Star forward Tom
Gugliotta began the season in Southern California _ but as a member
of the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there were a lot of good things out there,'' said
Ford, who thought right. ``I hope the fans see that.''
</P>
<P>
   In their first application of Ford's player-friendly,
run-and-shoot offense, the Clippers made 11 of 23 field-goal
attempts in a 25-point first quarter. Point guard Darrick Martin _
who in theory is keeping the position warm until newcomer Sherman
Douglas takes over _ handed out six assists. He finished the game
with six. Backcourt partner Eric Piatkowski made two 3-pointers
during that stretch, and scored 11 points. He finished with a
team-high 16.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clippers still trailed by three.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi joined the league and the battle with 1:44 left in
the quarter, and promptly missed a seven-foot one-hander. Jason
Kidd (18 points, 10 assists), the Suns' Energizer-bunny point
guard, converted a three-point play at 1:14 to give the Suns their
28-25 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   So the Clippers countered by going out and putting up 31 points
in the second quarter. The Suns _ behind 11 points from Gugliotta,
who had been a betting favorite to suit up for the Lakers _ kept
their hosts at arm's length for most of the period. Gugliotta
finished the half with 16 points and 10 rebounds. He finished the
game with game-highs of 24 and 17.
</P>
<P>
   But with Martin translating from Ford's equal-opportunity
playbook, the Clippers refused to wilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we played well in the first half,'' Ford said. ``We
only had five turnovers; a lot of good things were happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's one: With 35 seconds left before intermission, Olowokandi
took a pass on the left block, executed a frighteningly quick
baseline spin and dunked over Suns center Luc Longley, treating the
former Chicago Bull like he was, well, Luc Longley. That cut the
Phoenix lead to 53-50. Olowokandi, who finished with 14 points and
six rebounds in his NBA debut, had picked up a few clues while
watching from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while, I got a feel for what they (Suns) do on
defense,'' he said. ``I saw my openings and tried to take
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   After a free throw by Martin, the next Clippers hero was rookie
free-agent forward Tyrone Nesby, who dribbled and danced past
Gugliotta for a layup that tied the score at 53.
</P>
<P>
   The half concluded with Lamond Murray _ who made just 6 of 19
shots and finished with 14 points _ nailing a buzzer-beating runner
from midcourt that gave the Clippers a 56-53 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The 56 didn't seem so gaudy when the Clippers found themselves
stuck there until 6:07 of the third quarter. That's when Maurice
Taylor followed a miss with a five-foot baby hook for the Clippers'
first points of the half. Meanwhile, back in the NBA, the Suns were
making it ugly, running off 17 unanswered, undisturbed points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our defense broke down,'' Ford said. ``We quit
talking out there.''
</P>
<P>
   To impress loyal Clippers critics enough to generate any
positive chatter, the new coach will have to replicate and sustain
that first-half performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let these guys get beaten down,'' Ford said. ``We've
got to build them up and get ready for the Bulls on Sunday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
