<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4355 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-WR     02-06 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING NIGHT ISN'T WORTH LONG WAIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds details) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ So there's your answer, loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of educated guesses about what post-apocalypse pro
basketball would look and sound like, the Los Angeles Lakers and
Houston Rockets rang in the new year Friday night with a clank.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers won 99-91, and it wasn't quite pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Jones of the Lakers was way short on his first jump shot,
way long on his second, and nowhere close on his third on his way
to 2 for 12, the !ital!thunks!off! enhanced by technology, the
microphones bolted to the backboard and wired to the PA system.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley of the Rockets went to the trouble of posting up
emergency Lakers starter Corey Blount only to get more backboard
than rim on his first try.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three-year-old Scottie Pippen, nervous or just sloppy in
a 4-for-18 Rockets debut, thought about schooling 20-year-old Laker
Kobe Bryant and wound up with a running jump shot blocked back in
his face.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were shooting 40 percent at the half. Even in the
'90s, that's bad. The Lakers got better as the night wore on, and
at this rate, they'll be in midseason form by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll still be watchable, decent basketball,'' Lakers
coach Del Harris had said before the game, not wanting to be
accused of overhyping the product. ``I don't think it'll be totally
sweeps (quality television).''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it didn't help the general quality that the Lakers
played without their scheduled starting forwards, Rick Fox (foot)
and Robert Horry (baby).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, maybe the messy parts would have been messy even if
this was game 33 of a normal season instead of game 1 of the
post-lockout season.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it also could get worse, after the enormity of the
50-games, 90-nights schedule sinks in, before marches like Denver's
eight games in 10 days and Minnesota's three West Coast trips in 16
days leave healthy young men feeling like Bob Dole on his last
ditch, 72-sleepless-hours campaign trek.
</P>
<P>
   The question then will be who's up to the unusual challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom cuts both ways, with either young teams like
the Lakers holding the edge on fitness or veteran teams like the
Rockets better off because they ``know how to take care of
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Do the old guys really have a secret?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Bryant, the Lakers' very young
guard/forward/tycoon, said, shrugging. ``I'm waiting to find that
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' inexperience has been a burden for two years but
could be a help this year, when they're not only still young and
basically healthy but also deep, with the prospect of a nine- or
10-man rotation to keep legs fresh.
</P>
<P>
   Against arthritic teams like Houston and Utah, two of their
Western rivals, and Indiana, the Eastern power of the post-Jordan
age, maybe they'd be advised to turn up the tempo and try to tire
the old men out.
</P>
<P>
   Houston has six guys over 30, four over 33, including Pippen
(coming off back surgery), Barkley (bad back) and Hakeem Olajuwon
(bum knee). Utah has four over 34, including its big two. Indiana's
lineup averages 32.9 years of age.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have !ital!one!off! man, Derek Harper, older than 30,
and should be able to run all night.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, nothing will win back shaken fans like a good fast
break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully (they'll run) not just (against) the veteran
teams,'' said Derek Fisher, who as the starting point guard
controls the ball and the tempo as much as anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like over the past couple of years we've cheated
ourselves a little bit by playing too conservatively. We've got
players who are more suited to running.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like a call to abandon the thus-far futile quest for
a mature half-court attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Bryant said, ``a team like Houston, those veteran guys,
they know how to conserve their bodies. They're not going to let
you run them off the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   A return to Showtime seems a remote possibility, and, in fact,
the Rockets outscored the Lakers 17-9 on ``fast break points,''
however the official scorer defines them.
</P>
<P>
   Harris isn't exactly a running coach. And in the '97-98 season _
back when NBA seasons came with hyphens _ when Nick Van Exel was
sidelined the Lakers became more deliberate than usual. And now Van
Exel is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in here is the rationale for signing Dennis Rodman,
who would get the rebounds and turnovers off of which a fast break
feeds.
</P>
<P>
   Or somewhere in here is a plea for the Lakers to push the
fast-forward button on that offense.
</P>
<P>
   This game got better and ultimately might even be termed
intense. But based on first post-lockout impressions, watching the
Lakers run would be more fun than watching them shoot. &QL; 
!hair!!ital!Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three
days a week. He can be reached at (818) 713-3616.!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
