<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4357 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      02-06 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYTON RULES IN OT AS SONICS WIN OPENER UNDER WESTPHAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ No one knows exactly what to expect during this
abbreviated NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Sonics' 92-86 overtime win Friday against the Dallas
Mavericks proved anything, it is that there will be at least four
strong denominators in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The fans.
</P>
<P>
   Defense.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   And the fans.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dallas Mavericks, those Western Conference beasts,
giving the Sonics fits, Payton threw an overtime tantrum of his
own, scoring six of the team's eight points in the extra period.
And the Sonics, who figured to rely on offensive outbursts,
benefited most from their defensive pressure to hold off the Mavs.
</P>
<P>
   All that, of course, with the encouragement of a raucous and
sold out KeyArena. It was an impressive start to what promises to
be an intense 50-game regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The game also begged the question: What lockout?
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans did a good job,'' Payton said. ``They came back.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sonics forward Vin Baker: ``The fans were incredible. If
anybody from the NBA came into KeyArena last night, you'd think we
never left.''
</P>
<P>
   Some things just never change.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas pushed the Sonics for the second straight home opener. A
year ago, the Mavs spoiled the Sonics' home debut with a 89-81
victory. But Payton put the Sonics on his back in typical fashion.
</P>
<P>
   He scored a game-high 28 points, 14 in the fourth quarter and
overtime, and played 44 minutes. The effort preserved coach Paul
Westphal's first Sonic victory after replacing George Karl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean to take him for granted and I'm taking him for
granted already,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   When the game entered overtime, Westphal told Payton to take
over.
</P>
<P>
   He was getting to the basket relatively easy against a much
smaller Steve Nash.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs were debating whether to double team Payton. When they
did, he found the open man for a jump shot. When they didn't,
Payton beat one-on-one coverage with hard drives toward the rim.
</P>
<P>
   While Dallas missed its first eight shots in the extra period,
Payton owned the baseline, where he converted short-range baskets.
His last field goal gave the Sonics a 90-84 lead with 2:15 left.
Detlef Schrempf's two free throws with 10.7 seconds left ice it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play the way we was supposed to. We still have a few
kinks to get out,'' Payton said. ``But it was good to win this way.
... Coach put it on my back. He told me to keep the ball in my
hands. Either I'm going to be the hero or the goat. I'll take
either one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics missed their chance to win in regulation when Baker's
hook shot bounced off with 32 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs then squandered two chances to end the game. Steve Nash
misfired on a 3-pointer. A.C. Green gathered the rebound with 4.9
ticks left, but Cedric Ceballos lost the ball as he drove the
baseline and the game went into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos and Michael Finley struggled against the Sonics'
defense. Dale Ellis and Billy Owens held them to a combined 25
points.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, who started at shooting guard in place of Hersey Hawkins,
held his own even with a broken left pinky finger. He suffered the
injury during his third practice with the Sonics, but kept it a
secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had great contributions defensively from Olden
(Polynice),'' Wesphal said, ``and Billy came in and really did a
great job on Finley. ... But it was really everybody _ we won the
game with defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics flashed their best defensive effort after they fell
behind 70-64 early in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   After Moochie Norris buried a wide-open 3-pointer, Hawkins
parlayed a steal into an easy layup that pulled the Sonics within
70-69.
</P>
<P>
   Erick Strickland answered for Dallas with a layup. But Baker
swatted away Strickland's very next layup attempt, and ignited a
fastbreak. Hawkins sprinted up court and found Ellis, who quickly
canned a wide-open 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   Payton then forced Strickland to lose the ball and converted an
uncontested layup. The Sonics eventually went ahead 76-72 on Ellis'
putback with 6:41 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The sequence wasn't enough to put the Mavs away.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas responded with a 10-4 run. Nash and Finley ignited the
spurt with a pair of 3-pointers. Ceballos' two free throws later
tied the score at 82-82 with 2:50 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sonics owned the boards, 52-42, behind Polynice's 13
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be booed,'' Polynice said. ``I know I can
rebound with anybody in this league. I didn't do anything
spectacular. I just did what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, both teams accounted for just 16 turnovers. The
Sonics and Mavs both played up-tempo styles and both teams shot
just 40 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bet you in a lot of arenas, teams that are playing sloppy
are getting booed,'' Owens said. ``We didn't hear any boos. All we
heard was encouragement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
