<P>
   OLY-SAMARANCH (Barcelona) _ Special Report: In the past two
months, with the Olympic movement battered by allegations of
corruption at Salt Lake City and elsewhere, Juan Antonio Samaranch
has sought to bridge the gap between his retiring personality and
insistent images of uncontrolled indulgence. For his supporters, he
remains a servant of sport who transformed the Olympics from
financial ruin to unimagined prosperity. But an examination of
Samaranch's life, based on interviews in Europe, Asia and North
America, suggests that at the least he had no enthusiasm for
uncovering wrongdoing in the Olympic movement and may have
encouraged it through his own example as he pursued his consuming
goal of broadening and enriching the Olympics. By Roger Cohen with
Jere Longman.
