<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4364 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-06 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE DOGS SHOW UP THE CATS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The canine super bowl opens Monday and these tradition-bound
pages, as usual, will roll over for it. After all, the Westminster
Kennel Club show at Madison Square Garden is a ``major fixture''
with rich, ancient franchises, paeans to fine breeding, breathless
television analyses of poise and conformation, maybe even a betting
line. There will be rookies, veterans, passionate fans. It has
everything a big-league spectacular needs and little to fear; no
tall dog is expected to slip out on his handler tonight looking for
action on Eighth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, on its little paws, the Cat Show will pad
into town. A feline super bowl it is not. No one from this
department will be sent to interview the top tabby, to decipher
millennial attitudes from the popularity of specific breeds. As far
as we're concerned, the dog show is an athletic competition, the
cat show is a fur exhibition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How come?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much sporting about cats,'' said Roger Caras,
whose books and broadcasts have made him a leading animal expert.
``Cats don't perform. They just sit there. You feed them. They are
the most economically insignificant of all domestic animals. They
have this reputation of being independent, but they are animals who
have given up their independence so they can be taken care of. Cats
and dogs should not be compared.''
</P>
<P>
   Caras' voice, crisp and authoritative, softened: ``The first
time I saw a Border Collie at work, tears came to my eyes. It was
astounding. The ballet of that incredible work, the intelligence,
the energy.''
</P>
<P>
   I told him a friend of mine thinks cats are self-starters who
will go after mice without being asked, while dogs, often lazy and
stupid, will watch mice play.
</P>
<P>
   Caras snorted. ``Dogs are far better mousers than cats. I've got
a Jack Russell terrier, one of the 27 animals including cats in my
house right now, who is incredible at hunting vermin. Cats are
important if you are lonely; they are for loving, and that's real.
But their only function is companionship.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a slight gasp when I recounted this to Christine
MacMurray, the medical editor of the Animal Medical Center in New
York. ``Roger Caras said that?'' she said. ``Why would you even
compare dogs and cats? They are as different as elephants and
tigers. Oh, you asked the question.''
</P>
<P>
   When I asked MacMurray if she thought it was fair that we
covered the dog show and not the cat show, she made a sound like a
yawn. ``I won't be reading about either one, much less going to
them,'' she said. ``I'm sure there is some value in celebrating the
best, but most of this is about advertising for breeders. Those of
us in the animal advocacy world are more interested in controlling
the populations so that millions of cats and dogs _ including
purebreds _ are not killed every year.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not exactly where I wanted to go. The question on my
mind had been simple: Why do we give so much more attention to a
show featuring dogs than to a show featuring cats? Could it be that
the patriarchal media have made a connection with the perceived
masculinity of The Dog (top dog, big dog, dawg)?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' said Caras. ``There is nothing more masculine than an
old tom cat. A very rough animal. And they don't call a female dog
a bitch for no reason.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't many pet owners see a powerful dog as an affirmation
of their own masculinity?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me quote some friends,'' said Caras. ``Joe Garagiola loves
little fluffy dogs, like Yorkies, and he's very secure in his
masculinity. Gretchen Wyler, that wonderful performer, told me that
a dog is her child that will never grow up, and a horse is her
dancing partner.''
</P>
<P>
   MacMurray said she was glad I had brought horses into the
conversation. Besides being treasurer of Pets Alive, a group that
rescues animals, including horses, she has very strong feelings
about best friends and dancing partners in the sports world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see horse racing and dog racing made illegal,''
she said. ``It's a form of abuse. Greyhounds live terrible lives. I
don't know much about race horses.'' I told her that it was the
human grooms who lived badly at the race track, but that few horses
had golden feed bags. Rendering trucks cruise the race tracks for
horses that break down or don't win enough. Losers become glue or
food for dogs and Frenchmen.
</P>
<P>
   MacMurray shuddered. ``Thanks for calling, Bob,'' she said.
``But back to your original question. These extravagant shows about
cats and dogs don't help the problem. The audience doesn't see the
irresponsible breeders, the puppy mills, the dogs discarded after
summer vacations, the cats prowling the alleys of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   But isn't that about bad human breeding? These shows are about
good animal genes. Caras said, ``We want to pick out those who best
represent the breed, and make sure their genetic material is
preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
