</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHANAHAN FOCUS: BE PREPARED  
 DRAFT CHALLENGES THE BROWNS  
 MARINO SEEKS 3 OR 4 MORE SEASONS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Denver Broncos running back Derek Loville put it the best: there
is no better coach in professional football at preparing for the
big game than Mike Shanahan. And Shanahan showed it in Super Bowl
XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were going to win the Super Bowl even before we got
to Miami,'' Loville said. ``Only I didn't shoot my mouth off like
Atlanta did. But we put in our game plan before we came to Miami;
so all we had to do was refine things once we got to the Super
Bowl. I remember thinking, `There is no way Atlanta is preparing as
hard as we are. No way.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike went over every little thing, down to the smallest
wrinkle in the game plan. That is his personality, getting involved
in everything and not leaving anything to chance. We did everything
right. We were calm, professional, we were in bed early, we were
well-coached. It's all because of Mike. He was organized down to
the letter. I don't think the Falcons had a real shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan's techniques during the intense time that is Super Bowl
week could serve as a blueprint for all coaches, young and old, in
the National Football League. The Broncos were well-rested,
prepared for everything Atlanta tried and, over all, more mentally
ready. That is all Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word Mike always used was focus,'' Broncos quarterback
John Elway said. ``Focus, focus, focus.'' And unlike some coaches,
Shanahan practices what he preaches.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Illustrated reported that six hours before kickoff,
Shanahan was watching the movie ``A Night at the Roxbury'' with his
son, Kyle, in the hotel room. Suddenly Shanahan darted out,
carrying his cue card with all the Bronco plays, and went to
Elway's room to go over the offense. In fact, that card rarely left
Shanahan's hands all week. That's focus.
</P>
<P>
   To win, Shanahan used his Super Bowl formula. It includes:
</P>
<P>
   USE TIME WISELY &UR;  &LR; _ If there is a week break before the big week,
as there was before Super Bowl XXXIII, put in the game plan before
arriving in the host city. That's what the Broncos did, and it made
their practices in Miami go more smoothly. The Falcons put in their
game plan the week of the game, and at times Falcons looked lost,
such as when safety Eugene Robinson gave up an 80-yard pass play
for a touchdown to Rod Smith because of blown coverage, or the
numerous blown blocking assignments.
</P>
<P>
   STICK TO ROUTINES _ From the time Atlanta's plane landed in
Miami, the Falcons were disoriented. Coach Dan Reeves changed the
order in which players got off the plane, and some complained.
Shanahan changed nothing, meaning players were never surprised.
That can be a major comfort in what is a turbulent week.
</P>
<P>
   KEEP FAMILIES OFF THE PLANE _ It sounds cruel, but football is a
cruel sport. Robinson admitted that having families travel with the
team, and in some cases stay with them in the team hotel, was a
distraction for both him and some teammates. Families of Denver
players were not allowed to travel with the team, and Shanahan kept
the players so busy that they rarely had time to spend with their
families once they got to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   WATCH YOUR MOUTH _ Reeves made a number of mistakes during the
week and in the game itself, but the biggest was taking shots at
Shanahan, basically calling him a traitor from the days when they
were in Denver. Bronco players said Reeves' comments only
intensified Shanahan's legendary competitiveness. Elway said the
game became personal for Shanahan. Then came Ray Buchanan, the
Falcon cornerback who guaranteed a victory. Atlanta players had to
answer questions about Buchanan's guarantee all week, as well as
about Reeves' comments regarding Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   ENFORCE STRICT RULES _ Call this the Eugene Robinson Act. The
Falcons enjoyed the night life all week, which would account for
why many of them were constantly late to sessions with the news
media. The night Robinson was arrested and charged with soliciting
prostitution, the Falcons had no team dinner or team meetings and
had no restrictions except a midnight curfew. The Broncos? They had
a team dinner around 7 p.m. and meetings from 8 to about 9:15,
followed by a mandatory light meal and an 11 p.m. curfew. Quite
simply, if Robinson had played for the Broncos, it is unlikely he
would have been arrested, because he would have been occupied.
</P>
<P>
   ADD SOME WRINKLES _ Finally, make sure there are a few surprises
in the game plan for your opponent. Denver's defense allowed only
one touchdown because it surprised the Falcons with a variety of
new blitzes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every way, Mike had us more prepared than the Falcons
were,'' said running back Terrell Davis. ``It's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Draft Challenges the Browns
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Browns are going into the off season with two
goals: draft a quarterback, probably Kentucky's Tim Couch or
Oregon's Akili Smith, and avoid selecting too many stiffs or
outcasts on the list for Tuesday's expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 30 existing teams had to put five players on the
list and expect to lose no more than two. If the Browns were to
select a team's player, the team could pull two players back.
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League wanted to make sure the Browns did
not spend all or most of their salary cap money plucking talented
veteran free agents from other teams. If the Browns had no
restraints, and they wanted Giant defensive end Michael Strahan _
an unrestricted free agent and perhaps one of the top five young
players in the game _ the Giants would have no chance at keeping
him because the Browns would easily be able to outbid them. So the
league mandated that Cleveland use at least 38 percent of its cap
on the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the Browns is walking the minefield of the
draft list. For every decent player, there are 10 with high
salaries and bad attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Marino Seeks 3 or 4 More Seasons
</P>
<P>
   Dan Marino is talking about playing three or four more seasons
and could sign an extension with the Miami Dolphins in the coming
weeks ... Some teams are taking a hard look at Jeff Lewis, a free
agent who was the Broncos' third-string quarterback. There is
speculation that the Giants are one of those teams. Meanwhile, the
Giants have made no official decision on who their quarterback will
be next season, and probably will not until after the college draft
... The Minnesota Vikings continue to listen to offers for
quarterback Brad Johnson, and their asking price is high. They
wanted a No. 1 pick and defensive end Michael Sinclair from
Seattle. The Seahawks said no thanks; Sinclair led the league in
sacks last year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
