<HEADLINE>
FAT CAT, AS DEFINED BY THE NBA  
 OLDIES BUT GOODIES  
 MAKING PEACE WITH NBC  
 REJECTING RODMAN  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a term for enjoying life as a wealthy and carefree
National Basketball Association player. It is called living large.
You can afford to drive expensive cars, wear the best fabrics and
eat at the finest and, well, fattiest restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   It is that last pleasure Shawn Kemp, Bryant Reeves and several
other players took to the extreme. They not only lived large during
the six-month lockout, they showed up large to training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really shocking,'' said the Hall of Fame guard Walt
Frazier. ``I'm surprised, because sooner or later they had to know
that they were going to have to go back to work. They should be
embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, eight months off, and you're still out of shape?'' he
added. ``The league should be worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves ate so much over the extended break, he lost his starting
job with the Vancouver Grizzlies to the journeyman forward Tony
Massenburg. Arriving 40 pounds heavier than last season, Reeves has
shed about 15 pounds in two weeks. But he still needs to drop
another 25 pounds to return to his playing weight. Currently,
Reeves tips the scales at about 315.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be a point of embarrassment,'' said Reeves when asked
whether he was worried about his weight gain having a lasting
impact on his career. ``I don't know, I haven't been faced with
that yet. We'll wait until that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Kemp, who says he was only a few pounds overweight, showed up in
Cleveland with a waistline that resembled his nearly 40-inch,
vertical leap. He, too, has shed pounds in the past few weeks. But
Kemp's getting into shape during the season may take a toll on his
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think Shawn would be the first to admit that he came
in with a couple of extra pounds as did other players in other
situations,'' said Cleveland Coach Mike Fratello. ``I would like to
see the players come back and understand, you know, nine months is
different than coming back two or three weeks late.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I think happened to some of the guys who may have put
some extra pounds on is that they, one, may have bought into the
idea that this thing honestly wasn't going to get back together
again,'' Fratello said. ``Two, they got away from their workout
regime for the first month or two of the off season. Some of us
have that great ability to put pounds on more quickly than
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Kemp and Reeves were not alone. If it was not Dennis Scott and
Patrick Ewing in New York, it was Scott Burrell in New Jersey or
Oliver Miller in Toronto saying he needed to drop 10 to 15 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, when I see a player have an outstanding season, 9 out
of 10 times his contract is up,'' Frazier said. ``They get up for
the contract. After that, they don't seem to care.''
</P>
<P>
   Kemp signed a deal worth more than $100 million with the
Cavaliers in the summer of 1997 and Reeves' six-year, $66 million
extension kicks in with the Grizzlies this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Greg Ostertag, it was the same thing,'' Frazier said. ``A
lot of people were afraid to sign Ike Austin for the same reasons.
I look at Kemp, and he is so out of shape, he's obviously not ready
to carry the load for them. You're going to see a lot of hamstring
pulls early.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Oldies But Goodies &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Glenn (Doc) Rivers, who retired from the NBA two seasons ago
with a chronic back condition, keeps watching the daily
transactions and shakes his head in disbelief. Players older than
his 37 years keep re-appearing on rosters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the Jazz pick up Thurl Bailey, and I said to myself,
`Huh?,''' said Rivers, now a TNT basketball analyst. ``I thought it
was a misprint. I figured they had gone and got Pearl Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Might as well.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Dominique Wilkins, 39, signed on in Orlando for two
seasons. Also off the Magic bench: the 39-year-old Danny Schayes.
Herb Williams, who turns 41 on Feb. 16, still has a year left with
the Knicks. The 37-year-old Antoine Carr got a one-year deal in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   As the proliferation of teen-agers in the NBA grows, more and
more teams are also going to the NBA attic to dust off relics and
give them uniforms, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's desperation, but 10 years ago a
22-year-old was a rookie in the league,'' said Rivers. ``That guy,
in some cases, is now a four-year veteran. Experience means so
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, a lot of guys are in much better condition because of
strength coaches and dieting. It used to be a when a guy reached 30
or 31, you worried about him going downhill. Twenty-eight was your
prime. Now, guys are playing well at 36 and 37.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the average age of Karl Malone, John Stockton and Jeff
Hornacek is 36.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to do with athleticism and everything to do
with knowing the game,'' Rivers added. ``For a lot guys, though,
once you finally get that experience, you're too old to do anything
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Making Peace With NBC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing, who said during the lockout that NBC's role in
the labor dispute would not be forgotten, appears to have mended
fences with the network.
</P>
<P>
   The union president and several players had threatened to
boycott interviews with NBC, blaming the network for agreeing to a
deal with the NBA that ensured that the owners would receive their
rights fees for telecasts _ even if games were not played.
</P>
<P>
   But in a conversation with Dick Ebersol, the NBC Sports
president, the strained relations were put to rest. On the night
the deal was agreed to in principle, Commissioner David Stern and
Billy Hunter, the union executive director, also agreed that the
players would cooperate with the networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBC thing ended with the lockout,'' Ewing said. ``That's
all over with. We're moving on now.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rejecting Rodman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman has still not made a decision, fueling speculation
that the irascible rebounder will not choose a team until the
season is at least a few weeks old. Potential suitors like Miami
and Orlando have been backing out over the past week, especially
given Rodman's requests for preferred treatment (i.e. he does not
want to practice). Pat Riley seemed keen on taking in the wayward,
37-year-old forward, but backed off after Rodman was quoted as
saying, ``Not even Riles can deal with my demons.'' ... The present
and future of German basketball met Friday night in Dallas when
Detlef Schrempf's SuperSonics outlasted Dirk Nowitzki and the
Mavericks. Actually, Nowitzki, the 6-9 rookie, scored only two
points in 16 minutes of a 92-86 overtime loss. Schrempf scored
nine. The game was attended by a phalanx of German basketball
officials, who are trying to repair a strained relationship with
Schrempf. Nowitzki is seen as a key to the country's Olympic hopes
over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4367 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-FISHING-NYT &LR;      02-06 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-FISHING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCENTIVES HELP BASS IN TOP MEXICAN LAKE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By KEN SCHULTZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINALOA, Mexico _ The rising sun was a welcome sight for Katie
Watson and me. We were sitting on our cold and nearly numb hands as
our guide, Tony Balboa, slowed his boat and shut off the motor. We
had already been fishing for largemouth bass for an hour on this
unusually cool morning and I was about to dip my fingers into El
Salto Lake to warm them up. The water on this 15-year-old Mexican
impoundment was warmer than the air, and the thick mist rising off
the surface was beginning to thin here in a back channel.
</P>
<P>
   A frequent visitor to this mountain-fringed lake in western
Mexico, Katie said there was a cemetery up ahead, inundated when
the lake was flooded. Shortly, we pulled within casting range of a
tombstone and Tony motioned us to cast our surface plugs toward it.
The upper 10 inches of a lone tombstone were above the surface, and
I must have looked a little wide-eyed at it because the
English-speaking Mexican guide laughed and said, ``Try to catch a
live one.''
</P>
<P>
   Katie cast a silver-and-black popper to the right side of the
stone, let it lie still for a moment, then softly twitched it. Both
the calm water and the morning quiet were shattered when a big bass
attacked it, leaving a bathtub-sized swirl where Katie's popper had
been. She let out a yell, but had no chance to set the hook; the
bass bolted forward and expelled the hard-plastic lure. Perhaps it
was a coincidence that the sun crested the treetops at that moment
and the mist disappeared, but we were both instantly warmed up.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of big ``live ones'' here currently has anglers'
blood and the adrenaline flowing. Katie's fish could well have been
a kin to the 11-pound bass that a Dallas fisherman caught on the
same lure at dusk the previous evening. And that topped off a day
in which he had also caught and released a 10-pounder and his wife
an 8-pounder.
</P>
<P>
   This is down-and-dirty bass-fishing, however, and catching
largemouths of such enviable sizes is commendable since the lake is
full of flooded timber, and the bass _ as fast and broad-shouldered
as National Football League linebackers _ are virtually guaranteed
to streak into a submerged cactus or mesquite tree as soon as they
are hooked. Many anglers have lost the biggest bass of their lives
at El Salto when their line proved no match for jalapeno-hot fish
and wooden underwater booby traps.
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't just big bass that are drawing anglers from the
United States, Canada, Europe and Japan. Nestled in the mountains
about an hour-and-a half drive from Mazatlan, this 24,000-acre lake
is being fished by one of the top outfitters in the adventure
fishing travel business, Billy Chapman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   A former New Jerseyan whose customers have followed him to the
best waters of several countries, Chapman is putting roots down
here. He has already constructed the deluxe Angler's Inn fishing
lodge (www.AnglersInn.com) and is starting a small retirement
community, a coastal roosterfish and snook-angling business, a
dove-hunting operation, bird-watching tours.
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps most importantly, Chapman is expanding a
humanitarian program for the people living in the mountain villages
who were displaced by the creation of the lake.
</P>
<P>
   That program, Clothes for Bass, is only two years old, but in
1998 it dispensed 16,000 pounds of clothing to more than 300 people
here. Formerly farmers, the residents are now commercial fishermen,
netting El Salto for tilapia, a food fish transplanted to Mexico
from its native Africa many decades ago. Tilapia repopulate quickly
and need to be harvested at El Salto, but the temptation exists to
also take the bass, which fetch a good price on the underground
market. Commercial netting and selling of bass is illegal, but
continues at other lakes, adversely affecting bass populations.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman's program for recreational anglers will help sustain the
bass, which attract dozens of anglers weekly; all of the bass they
catch are released alive. It also gives something tangible back to
the local people. ``One 10-pound bass will bring $3,'' said
Chapman, ``but a full complement of clothes for a family are worth
$1,500. So if they sign an agreement with me not to take the bass,
and stick to the tilapia, we'll give them plenty of clothes, plus
medical supplies, toys and other things they can't afford.'' The
average commercial tilapia fisherman earns $6,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman has mostly relied on a large client list to donate the
clothes and supplies (Clothes for Bass, 14842 Maple Drive,
Kellyville, Okla. 74039). Last year nearly 400 people contributed
more than 25 pounds of clothes apiece. He put the contributors'
names into a drawing and picked one for a free four-day
bass-fishing trip to El Salto.
</P>
<P>
   Bass are present in El Salto only because the lake was stocked
with 200,000 Florida-strain bass in 1985, when it was filling.
These fish, which have formed the cornerstone of much-heralded
trophy bass-stocking programs in California and Texas, are noted
for growing fast and achieving huge (10-to 20-pound) size. In
December, El Salto produced a lake-record 14-pound-3-ounce bass for
one of Chapman's customers, and 20-pounders may be possible. If so,
that would put El Salto on a short list of the world's best
big-bass lakes. In 1994, a 16-pound-3-ounce bass was found dead in
El Salto; it had choked to death with a tilapia wedged in its
throat.
</P>
<P>
   Katie and I caught no huge bass, but there will be more days to
come, as well as warmer temperatures. Perhaps we spent too much
time gawking at a potpourri of bird life, including the first
falcon I have ever seen in the wild. The waterfowl is especially
abundant at El Salto, particularly ospreys, herons, ibises and
egrets, which obviously find the fishing to their liking as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
