<P>
   IMPEACH
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ Senators on Saturday watched
excerpts from the videotaped depositions of Monica Lewinsky, Vernon
Jordan and Sidney Blumenthal, in the final session of the
evidentiary stage of the trial of the president. Closing arguments
are expected this week, and both sides agree that acquittal is a
foregone conclusion. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LEADERS (Washington) _ Amid the partisan fires of the
impeachment and trial of President Clinton, the Senate majority
leader, Trent Lott of Mississippi, and the minority leader, Tom
Daschle of South Dakota, managed to forge a better relationship
than they had ever had before. ``Both senators like each other,''
one of their colleagues said, citing that as one reason that ``the
Senate didn't spin out of control.'' By Frank Bruni. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ROGAN (Washington) _ As one of the 13 House prosecutors,
James E. Rogan, 41, has greater name recognition in his second term
than many of his colleagues do after decades in office. But it is
this starring role that has put Mr. Rogan on the Democratic Party's
short list of Republicans from moderate districts who are most
likely to suffer a voter backlash in 2000. By Evelyn Nieves. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SKETCH (Washington) _ The scene as the Senate views the
videotape of Monica Lewinsky's deposition. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CAMPAIGN (Boston) _ The reluctance of Republican
presidential prospects to weigh in enthusiastically _ or at all _
on the president's impeachment trial underscores their party's
ambivalence about how impeachment is playing politically. By
Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KING HUSSEIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Pending official notification of the king's death, the News
Service on Friday filed a HOLD FOR ORDERS obituary of 4700 words
and a shorter version at 2150 words. The obituary carried an ``a''
general news category code; other stories will use an ``i''
international category code. At the appropriate time, we will
re-top the obituary and release it. Until official notification is
released, these are the stories planned for Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-HUSSEIN (Amman, Jordan) _ With King Hussein unconscious
and near death, Jordan's government transferred full powers
Saturday to Crown Prince Abdullah, making the 37-year-old heir to
the throne king in all but name and effectively ending Hussein's
rule after 47 years. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-PRINCE (Amman, Jordan) _ As Crown Prince Abdullah
formally took charge of Jordan's government Saturday, experienced
observers here said that internal political challenges _ rather
than foreign affairs crises _ are likely to present the new king
with his first leadership tests. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-CANCER (Undated) _ The type of cancer the King had was
unpredictable, thus his sudden turn for the worse. By Lawrence K.
Altman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SAMARANCH (Barcelona) _ Special Report: For his supporters,
Juan Antonio Samaranch remains a servant of sport who transformed
the Olympics from financial ruin to unimagined prosperity. But an
examination of Samaranch's life, based on interviews in Europe,
Asia and North America, suggests that at the least he had no
enthusiasm for uncovering wrongdoing in the Olympic movement and
may have encouraged it through his own example as he pursued his
consuming goal of broadening and enriching the Olympics. By Roger
Cohen with Jere Longman. Eds: Will also moved `s' category.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Rambouillet, France) _ The Kosovo peace
conference, ini- tially designed as an elaborate set piece of
diplomacy, stumbled toward a chaotic opening Saturday. Ethnic
Albanian delegates were finally allowed to fly out of Serbia and
join foreign ministers who had been left cooling their heels in the
gardens of the chateau where the negotiations will take place. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-ELECTIONS (Kano, Nigeria) _ As Nigeria prepares to hold
presidential elections on Feb. 27 and usher in a civilian
government in May, no single leader seems capable of healing the
gash on the nation's political soul that was inflicted on June 12,
1993. On that date, Moshood K.O. Abiola, a billionaire businessman,
appeared to win Nigeria's presidential elections, only to see them
annulled by the military. By Norimitsu Onishi. With map.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-WORK-RULES (Gummersbach, Germany) _ Germany's strict
work rules have helped give it one of the best-paid and most
productive work forces in the world, but it has also fueled a
stubbornly high rate of unemployment. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM-CRASH-INQUIRY (Amsterdam, Netherlands) _ More than six
years after an El Al plane crashed into a low-income housing
complex in Amsterdam and killed 43 people, emotions run high over
speculation that the cargo held nerve gas agents for use by
Israel's military. By Marlise Simons. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-TREES (New York) _ With many families of the 1990s no
longer fitting the nuclear family model of the 1950s, teachers are
rearranging lesson plans and redrawing assignments long regarded as
staples of the classroom. The most entrenched and problematic of
these assignments, teachers, school administrators and
psychologists said, is the classic family tree, which is causing
anxiety among parents and students from nontraditional backgrounds.
By Lynette Holloway. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PRESERVING-DOCUMENTS (Washington) _ This week, the National
Archives and Records Administration is expected to unveil the
design of the new enclosures for the Declaration of Independence,
Constitution and Bill of Rights. The enclosures are airtight cells
of titanium and aluminum that will hold the documents behind
tempered glass in an atmosphere of inert argon gas. The
encasements, resembling large, deep picture frames, will replace
similar enclosures that were made almost 50 years ago and appear to
be prematurely deteriorating. By Warren E. Leary. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-DEBATE (Atlanta) _ For their parents, who watched stocks
crash and banks fail, the government was considered the salvation
of a generation that had been betrayed by the financial markets.
But for today's aging baby boomers, who face increasing concerns
about the solvency of Social Security and other federal retirement
programs, it is now the government that cannot be trusted and a
bullish Wall Street that provides some hope. That dynamic, detected
in public opinion polls and a score of recent interviews with baby
boomers on Atlanta's streets, may become a critical component of
the debate over the future of Social Security. By Kevin Sack. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-CHECKS (Washington) _ President Clinton said Saturday that
he would ask Congress to require background checks on all people
who bought firearms at gun shows and flea markets, regardless of
whether the sellers were commercial gun dealers. Clinton summarized
his proposal this way: ``No background check, no gun, no
exceptions.'' By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SNOWMOBILE-BAN (Grand Lake, Colo.) _ An arctic gale was blowing
in Squeak Creek as Ken Todd roared down from the Continental
Divide, bucking his powerful snowmobile through drifts on a road in
Rocky Mountain National Park. It was a motorized tableau that a
coalition of environmental groups would like to erase from the
National Park System. In a midwinter attack, the coalition, called
the Bluewater Network, has petitioned Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt to ban snowmobiles from the 28 places among the National
Park System's 378 that allow them. By James Brooke. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE-LAWYER (Houston) _ It may look like a computer disk,
but in the eyes of a federal judge in Texas it behaves too much
like a lawyer. In a ruling last month thought to be the first of
its type in the country, Judge Barefoot Sanders of Federal District
Court in Dallas found that Parsons Technology Inc., which publishes
Quicken Family Lawyer and Quicken Family Lawyer '99, goes too far
in the assistance it provides consumers, resulting in an
unauthorized practice of law in the state. By Barbara Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ ``Our little girl has grown up.''
Maureen Dowd on Monica Lewinsky's deposition.
</P>
