<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4373 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-950(4TA     02-06 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-950(4TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL REPORT: THE MANY SHADES OF SAMARANCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: A 1,600-wd version of this story will move as
OLY-SAMARANCH-SHORT-VERSION) 
(JT) 
 By ROGER COHEN with JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARCELONA, Spain _ The man who steered the Olympic Games from
financial ruin to huge prosperity over the past 18 years is a
mild-mannered Spaniard whose unchanging attire _ blue suit, blue
shirt, blue tie _ amounts to the uniform of somebody who prefers to
pass unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   But here in his hometown, Juan Antonio Samaranch keeps a
basement office that tells of a man welcomed with deferential
tribute. The octagonal room has the untouched air of a mausoleum
filled with offerings: a silver cup with chrysanthemum crest
presented by the emperor of Japan, an oil painting of Samaranch
from Russia, and, in the entrance, a woven tapestry-portrait
presented by a Kuwaiti sheik.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch earns no salary in his job as president of the
International Olympic Committee, but travels the world like a head
of state. All of his expenses outside Spain _ a modest suite at the
Palace hotel in Lausanne, Switzerland; food, first-class air travel
and so on _ are paid by the Olympic movement or countries hoping to
become host to the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept suites,'' he said of the lavish accommodations
offered by Olympic hopefuls. ``I need a living room.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how much his lifestyle costs the IOC annually, Samaranch
said in an interview: ``I don't know. Hundreds of thousands of
dollars, maybe, millions no. I fly first-class. It's normal. I am
78 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two months, with the Olympic movement battered by
allegations of corruption at Salt Lake City and elsewhere,
Samaranch has sought to bridge the gap between his retiring
personality and insistent images of uncontrolled indulgence. For
his supporters, he remains a servant of sport who transformed the
Olympics from financial ruin to unimagined prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   But an examination of Samaranch's life, based on interviews in
Europe, Asia and North America, suggests that at the least he had
no enthusiasm for uncovering wrongdoing in the Olympic movement and
may have encouraged it through his own example as he pursued his
consuming goal of broadening and enriching the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Samaranch was not without sufficient information from us and
others to conduct a serious investigation a long time ago,'' said
Norm Seagram, an organizer of the failed Toronto bid for the 1996
Olympics and co-author of a 1991 report to the IOC suggesting that
abuses by IOC members cost the city up to $800,0000. ``But his
response was superficial.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Samaranch dismissed such charges. ``I am
wounded because it is disagreeable to be accused of false things,''
he said. ``We always tried to look into rumors of bad conduct _ but
they were just that, rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   His lips trembled slightly. A proud man, an embattled man, he
was seated in a second Barcelona office, this one on the 23rd floor
of ``La Caixa,'' Spain's biggest savings bank, of which he is
honorary chairman. A room with a sweeping view of the hometown he
transformed by steering the 1992 Olympics here. The bank pays his
expenses when he is here.
</P>
<P>
   Those Summer Games in Barcelona were widely regarded as a
triumph, a reflection of Samaranch's extraordinary transformation
of the Olympics from an event that scarcely anyone wanted to a
coveted money spinner.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that Samaranch ever sought personal
enrichment from this booming Olympics-related business. But more
money slowly brought demands _ for controls and transparency _ that
were unfamiliar to him. IOC members appear to have felt little or
no pressure from their president to resist seductive blandishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mistakes? I don't know about mistakes,'' Samaranch said. ``We
explained clearly what the rules were, we heard some rumors, we
tried to reduce the number of people in the selection process for
Olympic cities, but we could not. Naturally members are attached to
their privileges.''
</P>
<P>
   He has his defenders. Marc Hodler, the veteran Swiss IOC member
and lawyer whose public comments on corruption helped ignite the
current scandal, called Samaranch a ``great president'' who
``achieved unique things by understanding the commercial potential
of the Games.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe so much to him,'' said Anita DeFrantz, the American
vice president of the IOC. ``Women are now members of the IOC. More
women compete in the Olympics. He should be allowed to complete his
job by cleaning things up.''
</P>
<P>
   But a cleanup under public scrutiny is a new notion for
Samaranch. As a government functionary in the the Spain of General
Francisco Franco and as president of the IOC, the Lausanne-based
society that is the ``supreme authority'' of the Olympic Games,
Samaranch has had scant exposure to the strictures of public
accountability. It appears now that this career path may have left
him out of phase with his times.
</P>
<P>
   This was strikingly underscored at an international doping
conference in Lausanne last week, when Samaranch proposed that he
should lead a new global effort to combat athlete drug use. The
suggestion was soundly rejected by European and American
representatives, who seemed stunned that Samaranch had failed to
grasp the precipitous drop in the IOC's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a failure of leadership, unquestionably,'' said
Gen. Barry McCaffrey, the White House drug czar, who attended the
conference. ``The IOC members are merely trustees of the world's
athletes. We want to see democracy, open votes, open meetings, open
books.''
</P>
<P>
   Otto Schily, the German interior minister, was blunter: ``One
should know when to retire from an office,'' he said of Samaranch.
``If one reigns like a constitutional monarch, that is not helpful
for sport.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tact and Tenacity, With Calculation
</P>
<P>
   But Samaranch said he is determined to fight back. Although
several IOC colleagues have speculated that he might step down
later this year, Samaranch said that his plan is clear: Use an
Olympic committee session next month to shore up his position with
a vote of confidence, reform the organization, and retire in 2001
with his record salvaged.
</P>
<P>
   It is a bold strategy, but Samaranch has been underestimated
before.
</P>
<P>
   Of middling build and modest manner, courteous, attentive to
detail, fanatical about physical fitness, Samaranch quietly builds
bridges and loyalty, edging toward well-defined ambitions with a
mixture of tact and tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Samaranch has achieved what he sets out to do. Jose
Maria Sumpsi, a longtime friend of the IOC president, showed a
design conceived by Samaranch in the 1960s that featured the shield
of the provincial government of Barcelona above the five-ringed
Olympic symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was done years before Samaranch was president of either
body,'' Sumpsi said, ``but he already knew clearly what he wanted;
then he went for it. In 1973, he became the president of the
Barcelona provincial government. Seven years later, he was
president of the IOC. The vision on this design came true.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for nothing, it seems. Consider Samaranch on the subject of
diplomacy, an art he formally practiced for just three years, as
Spain's ambassador to Moscow between 1977 and 1980:
</P>
<P>
   Know how to listen. Never speak in a language not your own (an
interpreter provides time to think). Convey credibility. Have a
clear objective. Understand that you may not reach your aim in a
straight line. So be ready, when necessary, ``to employ a few
curves.''
</P>
<P>
   These ``curves'' _ roundabout routes to a given target _ have
been a consistent feature of Samaranch's life.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a self-made Barcelona textile baron and a one-time
sportswriter who used the pen name Stick, Samaranch was born to
considerable wealth in 1920. He emerged in the late 1940s as a
passionate sportsman with a particular interest in roller-hockey (a
sort of poor man's ice hockey), and an eye for political
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Dapper, gallant, he earned a reputation as a lady's man of
unfailing solicitude (birthdays duly noted, bouquets always on
time). His wealth was cemented and standing enhanced with his
marriage in 1955 to a Barcelona society beauty, Maria Teresa
Salisachs, whose family money was older than his own.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time he rose steadily in the ranks of Gen. Franco's
Fascist administration, becoming the rough equivalent of a junior
under-secretary of sport and gaining the prestige that allowed him
to join the IOC in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not ashamed of what I did in Spain,'' Samaranch said.
``Franco did good things for my country. He kept us out of World
War II. He created a middle class. He chose a good successor, the
king.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch smoothly navigated Spain's transition from autocratic
to democratic rule after Franco's death in 1975. ``He adapts to
everything,'' said Ernest Lluch, a former Spanish health minister
who knows Samaranch. ``In fact, he is one of the great
chameleons.''
</P>
<P>
   Just two years after Franco's death, Samaranch was named Spain's
first ambassador to Moscow. Already a vice president of the IOC,
Samaranch had a clear aim in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years after joining the IOC in 1966, I had started
thinking about being president,'' he recalled. ``Moscow was
preparing the Olympics of 1980, and I knew that going there would
be a good move for my ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   As it was. When Lord Killanin of Ireland stepped down in 1980,
Samaranch was elected with an absolute majority of 47 votes in the
first round. Hispanic and Soviet-bloc votes helped do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Many, however, saw the presidency as a poisoned chalice.
``Everybody was writing the Olympic obituary,'' said Michael Payne,
a British IOC member who oversees marketing. ``We were politically
and financially bankrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   After the African boycott of the 1976 Summer Games in Montreal,
60 Western nations, led by the United States, boycotted the 1980
Moscow Games over the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan. Sport seemed
a Cold War victim. The IOC had less than $500,000 in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Art Of Mollification
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch responded with an extraordinary energy, apparently
driven by his abhorrence of conflict, his Spanish experience of
political reconciliation and his vision of an all-embracing
Olympics. Wherever he could, and by whatever means, he reached out
to extend the Olympic family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has always known how to soften people and he impregnated
the Olympics with this art,'' said Jaume Boix Angelats, the author
of a critical biography of Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   When Angelats was working on his book, the IOC president would
constantly invite him and his co-author on far-flung, expenses-paid
trips to meet him. They declined. ``He wanted us in his debt,''
Angelats said.
</P>
<P>
   Lluch, the former Spanish health minister, produced a Longines
watch given to him by the IOC president after a presentation in
Lausanne of the hospital facilities for Barcelona. ``He just came
up to me and said, `Have a little souvenir.' Funny.''
</P>
<P>
   But whatever its quirks, Samaranch's diplomacy, based on endless
travel, worked. After the Soviet boycott of the Los Angeles Games,
he coaxed 160 of 167 countries then in the Olympic movement to
attend the 1988 Olympics in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first years of his reign, he made more positive,
uplifting changes than all the other IOC presidents put together,''
said John Lucas, an Olympic historian. Among them were rescuing the
Games financially, opening opportunities for women, enabling more
developing nations to compete and bringing professional athletes
into the Games.
</P>
<P>
   But the restless expansion had a price. Olympic awards were
showered on the likes of the East German dictator Erich Honecker
with a view to luring his country to the 1988 Seoul Olympics after
the 1984 boycott, even though he was widely rumored _ and later
discovered _ to be running a state-sponsored doping system.
</P>
<P>
   New IOC members poured in _ more than 80 percent of the current
membership joined under Samaranch. Their credentials were not
always spotless. Maj. Gen. Francis Nyangweso of Uganda became a
member in 1988. He was a former Olympic boxer; he was also an army
commander during Idi Amin's campaign of torture and terror.
</P>
<P>
   An Australian Olympic official has said he paid Nyangweso
$35,000 the night before Sydney won the 2000 Summer Games, beating
Beijing by two votes. The general has denied using the money for
personal use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who do you find in Uganda?'' asked Franklin Servan-Schreiber,
an IOC spokesman. ``Do you want to push for human rights around the
world? That's Amnesty International. Or do you want African
athletes at the Olympic Games?''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch wanted African athletes. In 1986, he brought in
Jean-Paul Ganga of the Congo Republic, a leader of the 1976 African
boycott of the Montreal Games and a strong anti-apartheid
campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   The move was prescient: when apartheid collapsed, Ganga helped
steer South Africa back to the 1992 Olympics. But Ganga has since
been accused by the IOC of taking more than $216,000 in illicit
benefits from Salt Lake City. He has denied that his vote on the
2002 site selection was for sale and has said he will protest his
expulsion from the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Samaranch wants to sacrifice his friends,'' Ganga said in an
interview. ``That is dangerous for him. It is war now.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Samaranch appears to have failed is in not perceiving that
making the Olympics bigger _ his unswerving goal _ required
balancing with tighter controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cost-effectiveness and Internet-style openness are concepts
foreign to him,'' said Alberto Montagut, an editor of the Catalan
edition of the newspaper El Mundo. ``Resignation does not exist in
his culture, because it is the act of an accountable type of
management.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pools of Money, Yet No Reckoning
</P>
<P>
   For years, management was not much of an issue for the Olympic
movement: there was almost no money to manage.
</P>
<P>
   When Hodler, the Swiss IOC member, joined in the early 1960s, he
recalled that the only revenue was the 40 Swiss francs ($29) paid
each year by members _ providing overall annual revenue of about
$300.
</P>
<P>
   Under Samaranch, however, the quaint poverty of aristocrats and
gentlemen gave way to the rigorously commercialized wealth of
managers of the lucrative five-ringed Olympic brand.
</P>
<P>
   After Peter Ueberroth demonstrated at Los Angeles in 1984 that
clever marketing could make the Olympics profitable, IOC income
from sales of television rights, exclusive corporate sponsorships,
licensing agreements and tickets soared. Worldwide television and
sponsorship rights are now worth $3.5 billion for the 1997-2000
period alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We changed the Olympic movement,'' Samaranch said. ``We made
it universal. We gave it the means to help people. We held one
Olympics after another that was a triumph.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, a lot of people _ many of them poor _ benefited. The
IOC set up a program called Olympic Solidarity in 1961 to promote
the movement by building sports facilities and providing athletic
scholarships around the world. For a long time it had little money.
Now, for the 1997-2000 period, it has $122 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the pools of money created an anachronism at IOC
headquarters in Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly a nongovernmental, nonprofit, private association of
unsalaried men and women _ voting in secret, choosing new members
by co-option, publishing no overall accounts _ was responsible for
hundreds of millions of dollars in annual revenue and for choosing
the site of Olympic Games worth fortunes to the cities elected.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Charter states: ``The Olympic Games are the
exclusive property of the IOC which owns all rights relating
thereto.'' These rights were a gold mine in a world where sport
bred passions once reserved for religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not a corporation,'' Hodler argued. ``We are a club of
friends. And we never had the two-thirds majority necessary to
change the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Pound, an IOC vice president from Montreal and the
lawyer who handles television rights sales in the Americas,
conceded that there was still ``very little financial
transparency'' and ``we could do a better job.''
</P>
<P>
   It is by no means clear, however, that Samaranch ever had any
real enthusiasm for steps that might bring that transparency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world of sport changed a lot in recent years,'' he
acknowledged. ``Maybe our mistake was not to change the IOC
statutes. I tried.''
</P>
<P>
   The Samaranch Limited: $7,000 Per Trip
</P>
<P>
   Although he does not vote on the selection of Olympic cities,
contestants for the bids clearly thought it was worthwhile to court
Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   The Nagano Olympic committee laid on a private three-car train
for him in 1991 with a view to winning _ as it did _ the 1998
Winter Games. The train, run by JR East, Japan's largest railroad
company, cost about $7,000 to hire for the trip from a site near
Tokyo to Nagano, a spokesman for JR said.
</P>
<P>
   When in Nagano for the Games, Samaranch was put up at the
Imperial suite of the Kokusai 21 Hotel from Jan 28, 1998 to
February 23, 1998, at a cost of close to $3,000 per night _ or over
$75,0000, a Nagano committee official said. He also received a
Japanese sword and a painting, each valued at about $16,000, Nagano
city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch took the occasion to decorate Yoshiaki Tsutsumi, a
secretive billionaire Japanese businessman with whom he enjoys what
the Tokyo Shimbun describes as a ``honeymoon relationship,'' with
the ``gold Olympic order.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsutsumi had led the battle to bring the Olympics to Nagano _ a
multimillion-dollar campaign whose details have been hidden by the
burning of Nagano's Olympic accounts. He also contributed
substantially to one of Samaranch's pet projects _ the Olympic
museum in Lausanne, opened in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In South Korea, which he has visited more than 25 times since
becoming president, Samaranch has enjoyed another intimate
relationship with a millionaire businessman, Kim Un Yong.
</P>
<P>
   A former bodyguard of the late dictator Park Chung Hee, Kim made
a fortune on land deals south of Seoul's Han river. He went on to
found the World Federation of Tae Kwon Do (Korean karate), before
being elected to the IOC in 1988, the year of the Seoul Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Kim was on the executive committee that chose
the first recipient of the Seoul international peace prize, worth
$300,000. The prize went to Samaranch. Subsequent winners got less:
the prize is worth $20,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   When in Seoul, Samaranch has regularly been housed in the
Presidential suite of the Shilla Hotel (current rate: about $1,700
a night), owned by the Samsung group, whose chairman, Lee Kun Hee,
was elected to the IOC in 1996 after making contributions to the
Olympic movement, Korean officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about these activities, Samaranch said he did not ask for
the train in Japan. And he said he immediately donated all gifts to
the IOC Samaranch did not specifically address the question of the
Samurai sword from Nagano. But an IOC statement said: ``The IOC has
absolutely no record and no recollection of the Samurai sword.''
</P>
<P>
   The $300,000 Seoul prize was given to the Olympic museum,
Samaranch said. He said the generous Asian treatment of him was
acceptable because he does not vote in the selection of Olympic
cities.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems clear that Samaranch's lifestyle provided little
incentive to restraint during the many years that he and other IOC
members say they were trying to instill a new cost-conscious
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never any serious attempt at control, because this
amounts to a secret society where all members pledge to support
each other.'' said Robert Helmick, an American former IOC member
who resigned in 1991 amid allegations of conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch dismissed such allegations, saying ``nothing that
comes from Helmick has any value, because he had to resign.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Members' Hands Were `Not in Their Pockets'
</P>
<P>
   It is Hodler of Switzerland who, for over a decade, has led the
IOC's attempts to reform the bidding process and so curtail Olympic
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   On June 16, 1987, backed by Samaranch, he sent out a letter to
members of the IOC, to national Olympic committees and to candidate
cities, stating that ``gifts of value are not permitted'' and
admonishing IOC members to stay no more than three days in any city
bidding for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But the letter was clearly ignored.
</P>
<P>
   When Toronto mounted its bid for the 1996 Summer Games in the
late 1980s, it found that ``26 members broke established rules
either by coming with more than one guest, arriving more than once,
or staying more than the allotted time.''
</P>
<P>
   It further found, in a report submitted in January 1991 to
Samaranch and Pound, the IOC vice president, that there was
``blatant abuse'' in travel expenses. IOC members, the report said,
were cashing in first-class tickets and failing to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   These and other practices helped inflate the cost of Toronto's
bid to $14 million. ``The attitude of the IOC members was like the
doorman with his hand half out. You can't quite say the hand is
out, but it's certainly not in his pocket,'' said Seagram.
</P>
<P>
   And what was the response from Samaranch and the IOC? Pound said
that the committee tried to take over co-ordination of travel, and
asked _ orally but not in writing _ for details on the names of
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to react,'' he said, ``But you can't just pick 26
IOC members at random and shoot them.''
</P>
<P>
   Seagram, however, said there was ``no urgency and basically no
further communication'' after the submission of the report.
Samaranch, he said, did mention over dinner the need for names, but
never followed up on this. ``We were surprised and disappointed,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC did little to enforce its rules against gifts. Samaranch
appeared concerned ``not to rock the boat,'' said Sam Ramsamy, the
IOC member from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of IOC action, things evidently went from bad to
worse. When Berlin bid for the 2000 Summer Games, it found 20 IOC
members descending on the city for stays of five or six days and
accepting gifts ranging from porcelain to gold medals at a total
cost _ for the presents alone _ of about $85,000.
</P>
<P>
   A report by Germany's Green Party on the Berlin bid, which was
based on examination of city records, found that travel
arrangements were often exorbitant. One IOC member spent over
$12,000 on his air ticket, stopping in Los Angeles, Madrid,
Tenerife and London, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Isao Ichimura, the secretary general of the Nagano bid
committee, observed how, after a helicopter flight over Nagano
sites, committee members simply walked off with the binoculars they
had been given. ``We couldn't very well say no, although we
expected them back,'' Ichimura said.
</P>
<P>
   In Spain, Leopoldo Rodes, a banker and promoter of Barcelona's
bid for the Games, invited German Rieckehoff, the IOC member from
Puerto Rico, for dinner. A collector of walking sticks, Rieckehoff,
who has since died, stopped on his way out to admire a
silver-topped stick that Rodes kept by his front door.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stick belonged to my grandfather,'' Rodes said, ``but it
was obvious he wanted it, so I gave it to him. That seemed
normal.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Salt Lake City bidding for the 2002 Games began,
the offering of gifts and outright payments _ as well as the use of
agents offering to sell blocs of votes _ had become so entrenched
as to be part of the process.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC estimates that Salt Lake spent $800,000 on 14 IOC
members, including scholarships for children, medical care and cash
payments _ acts under investigation by the United States Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not surprised _ in fact I was relieved _ when the
revelations came out,'' Hodler said. ``There had been smoke around
for years. But the fire was difficult to find.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flame and the Lucre, Side by Side
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch has now become a vociferous advocate of reform. At the
president's insistence, the Olympics acted quickly to sanction
members accused at Salt Lake City, and is pushing for a radical
change in its own structures.
</P>
<P>
   But the IOC president's most cherished project _ the Olympic
museum in Lausanne _ captures the contradictions that may make such
reform difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the museum, which is approached through a faux Greek
colonnade, a flame burns with the inscription ``The Olympic flame
brightens the world.'' Beside it is a sign pointing to the museum's
nearby ``SWATCH'' store. Even here, idealism and commercialism
nestle side by side.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, a movie on Olympic history plays all day. ``In 1980,'' a
voice says, ``Juan Antonio Samaranch was elected. This was a
turning point in Olympic history.'' This is true, of course. But
the statement squares uneasily with Samaranch's professed humility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had a fairly full life,'' he said. ``I look back and
think maybe I made a few mistakes. But I got a few things right. I
tried to be loyal to my friends and I have helped a lot of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   He took out his wallet and extracted some membership cards of
Barcelona clubs. ``I am a man of habits, you see,'' he said.
``Look, I am the third member of the Barcelona tennis club, which
now has thousands of members. I am No. 7 at the Barcelona opera
house club. And No. 88 at the Spanish automobile club.''
</P>
<P>
   So, he was asked, are you an institution? ``No,'' he said, ``I
am an old man. In general people respect me. But there are always a
few exceptions.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
