<HEADER>
A4379 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     02-06 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SPECTATOR SPORT: LABOR CHIEFS AEROBICS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Cesar Chavez was leading the farm workers in the lush
valleys of California, he surely had little time to work out on the
treadmill.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true for Patrick Ewing, who gave himself to his
union during the time of the troubles. However, now that there is
certified contractual peace in the National Basketball Association,
Ewing, more than anybody else, may be paying the price for his
dedication to the cause.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the association looked as if he was carrying a
few file folders and cellular phones under his uniform Friday night
as the Knicks were wiped out in Orlando, 93-85. He will have plentyof chance to play himself into shape because there are more games
where that one came from - 49 more in the next three months,
including Sunday's matinee against the Man With the Mousse.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Matt Winick, that droll schedule-maker with the
NBA, had the delightful touch to sent Pat (Hit Me With Your Best
Shot) Riley back into the belly of the beast on the very first
Sunday afternoon of this short and furious season.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks take on the Miami Heat in the Garden opener at 1 p.m.
before the New Jersey Nets take on Orlando in the Meadowlands at 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   While Ewing was diligently attending negotiations and generally
exasperating everybody (including most of his union mates) with his
insensitive comments about life-and-death struggles, many other
players were keeping their profiles down as well as their weight.
The standup comedian, Jayson Williams of the Nets, seems to be in
great shape, which only reinforces the old remedy that laughter is
the best medicine.
</P>
<P>
   When A. Philip Randolph was organizing the Brotherhood of
Sleeping Car Porters, he also had little time to get to the gym.
During the long evening in Orlando, Ewing seemed continually off
balance. Well, who wouldn't be, carrying an attache case strapped
to his waist? In the fourth quarter, with the Knicks down by 7,
Patrick had a chance for an offensive rebound and a monster dunk,
if only he could have gotten off his feet. He attempted to tip the
ball with his wrist, basically flatfooted, and the ball skittered
away harmlessly, and so did the game.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever it is that owns the Knicks as of this edition would
surely be justified in wondering whether this club will be the
ultimate victim of the strike. Not always the most cognizant
person, Ewing says he will play himself into shape. He has never
been 36 years old before, nor has he ever tried playing 50 games in
90 days.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Knicks just might evolve into a more
mobile offensive force. The noted pacifist Latrell Sprewell is a
lithe full-court presence not quite like anybody the Knicks have
ever had. So maybe the Knicks are a work-in-progress. Besides, they
were not going to win anything with Good Old Oak and Good Old John
and Good Old Patrick playing the same weary game. The Knicks are
going to be different, but the Bulls have no relationship to
anything that happened in the past. If the NBA played under the
same format as European soccer leagues, then the Bulls would be in
dire danger of finishing dead last and being relegated to the
Continental Basketball Association. Or maybe Jerry Reinsdorf would
not have torched his team if there were a penalty for being
dreadful.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I think about it, considering the frantic scrambling
for free agents in the wake of the settlement, the bulk of the NBA
has a relatively settled feel to it _ at least in the first wave of
box scores.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie and Mark in Indiana. Mutombo and Smith in Atlanta. Duncan
and Robinson in San Antonio. Sloan and Malone and Stockton in Utah.
Hill and Dumars in Detroit. And a nation of strangers in
Sacramento. Sounds like normal for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets used to have the feel of Sacramento East, a turnpike
team where players stopped on their way from somewhere to anywhere.
But now they've got a nice little team in the swamp.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets may be more than tantalizing with added maturity from
Jayson Williams and Keith Van Horn and maybe even Sam Cassell to
say nothing of John Calipari, the coach himself, whose energy and
ego were often a distraction in his first two years.
</P>
<P>
   Will anybody care? There were first-night indications that fans
are not filling up the arenas. The league had better look exciting
in a hurry because spring is not all that far away in the northern
tier, and people could be into gardening and exercise and baseball
and going out for dimsum on peaceful Sunday afternoons instead of
watching the tall blokes on the tube. The first robin and Bernie
Williams and Mike Piazza are coming soon. There will not be much
patience for a ragged product.
</P>
<P>
   And that brings us back to the Knicks. When Samuel Gompers was
organizing the cigar workers, he probably could not afford a
personal trainer. Patrick Ewing could have.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1140EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
