<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4391 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TYSON-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      02-06 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON, SENT BACK TO PRISON, WAS NOT SEEN AS SERIOUS CONTENDER FOR A
TITLE   
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Mike Tyson was led away to the Montgomery County Maryland
jail in handcuffs on Friday afternoon to serve a one-year sentence
on two counts of second degree assault, he left behind a trail of
broken financial commitments, which will cast a huge cloud over his
future in boxing. However, his departure barely left a ripple in
the heavyweight pool, because he wasn't a serious contender for a
world championship.
</P>
<P>
   After he regained his boxing license from the Nevada State
Athletic Commission on Oct. 19, Tyson, and his new team of
advisors, were able to cash in on his still immense, though fading,
popularity. In light of his lackluster performance against Francois
Botha (he was trailing on all cards before he knocked out Botha in
the fifth round) and Friday's jail sentence for assaulting a
50-year-old man and a 62-year-old man following a minor traffic
accident last Aug. 31, Tyson becomes an even more difficult sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people around Tyson look at him as a money tree,'' said
Promoter Bob Arum, president of Top Rank Boxing. ``They couldn't
wait until it blossomed to bear fruit. Wouldn't it have been better
to get this situation in Maryland handled properly before putting
him back in the ring? The people around Tyson have to take stock of
what's important now. His family should use this time to get him
the extensive psychological help that he needs.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of their defense to keep Tyson out of jail, Tyson's
lawyers painted a bleak future if the former heavyweight champion
was sentenced to jail time on the assault charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he gets jail time for one day, he's done, finished,
according to the Nevada Commission,'' said Paul Kemp, Tyson's
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Kizer, a Nevada assistant attorney general, said Tyson
can't be barred from fighting this year, because his license is
good through the end of 1999. But he must go before the commission
to get a license for 2000. Whether he gets one for 2000 is
completely at the discretion of the five commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   With Tyson going to jail, and possibly returning to prison in
Indiana for violating the conditions of his probation, Showtime
Cable network, the MGM Grand, which had signed Tyson to a
four-fight deal for an undisclosed amount, and Tyson's former
trainer, Kevin Rooney, who recently reached an $8.6 million
settlement over a breach of contract lawsuit, are big losers.
Rooney received $2.5 million following the Botha fight and was to
receive the balance over Tyson's next two fights. Showtime signed
Tyson to a four-fight, $33 million deal. They also took over all
the liens that the Internal Revenue Service had placed on Tyson's
homes in Las Vegas and Connecticut by paying off his $14 million
tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Larkin, Showtime senior vice president of sports and event
programming, was at the Montgomery County District Court on Friday
during Tyson's sentencing hearing. He had no comment. The
Tyson-Botha pay per view did 600,000 buys, which was well short of
the record 1.9 million buys that Tyson did in his rematch against
Evander Holyfield on June 28, 1997. That was the fight that set
Tyson on his current downward spiral. He became upset at Holyfield
during the bout, because he said that Holyfield was head butting
him and he wasn't getting any protection from referee Mills Lane.
So, Tyson bit both of Holyfield's ears and was disqualified.
Subsequently, the Nevada commission revoked Tyson's license and he
was out of boxing for 19 months. During that time, he had three
hearings to regain his boxing license (one in New Jersey and two in
Las Vegas), and had his run in with the two Maryland motorists,
Abimelec Saucedo, 62, and Richard Hardick, 50. Tyson also battled
depression and took Zoloft, an anti-depressant, off and on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started getting letters from the IRS saying they were going
to take the house and all our stuff,'' said Monica Tyson, Tyson's
wife. ``He was depressed a lot about that.'' Tyson had stopped
taking the drugs when he assaulted Saucedo and Hardick.
</P>
<P>
   The Nevada commission gave him his license back after he passed
a grueling battery of psychological examines by a group of
psychologists and psychiatrists at Massachusetts General Hospital
in Boston. Though Tyson was determined mentally fit to return to
the ring, the psychologists said there was no way to guarantee that
Tyson would not react violently inside or outside of the ring
again.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Stephen P. Johnson thought that Tyson, despite his weekly
sessions with a psychologist, still hadn't learned how to
effectively managed his anger. If he had, Johnson believes, Tyson
never would have gone after two elderly men that he didn't know
after a minor fender bender.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tyson never said a word during the sentencing hearing on Friday,
dismissively waving off Johnson when he asked if he had anything he
wanted to say before he imposed the sentence. For most of the four
hours he sat dispassionately at a table before Johnson as a parade
of defense character witnesses attested to his fine character.
There wasn't even a reaction when he was sentenced.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Paul Kemp, and Carol Crawford, an assistant
prosecutor, painted conflicting pictures of Tyson. Kemp said that
Crawford's argument that Tyson should be given jail time because of
his propensity toward violence was nothing more than ``a shrill,
sensational call for vegeance.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford didn't put on one witness to counter what Kemp said
about Tyson. Instead she relied on an 11-page memo Douglas Gansler,
the Montgomery County prosecutor who took office in January, sent
to Johnson on Jan. 4 and 126 pages of documents that included news
articles and transcripts from television interviews that depicted
Tyson as violence-prone. Kemp said those items were merely
pre-fight hype and bravado that Tyson used to promote his bout with
Botha and were not based in reality.
</P>
<P>
   But Crawford said what happened to Saucedo and Hardick was very
real and it was made even worst by the fact that the accident was
``at best a minor inconvenience and at worst a petty annoyance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine what it must feel like to have an agitated Mike Tyson
headed toward you?'' Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Mike Tyson's anger and rage served him
well. It fueled his rise from a Brownsville juvenile delinquent to
the youngest heavyweight champion ever at age 20. Inside and
outside the ring it went unchallenged, except for civil lawsuits,
until he was convicted of raping Desiree Washington, a beauty
pageant contestant, in 1992. That rape conviction made it difficult
for Johnson to let Tyson go with just a slap on the wrist in this
case. His free rides are over.
</P>
<P>
   The heavyweight division moved forward while Tyson was out for
19 months. And his return bout against Botha was nothing more than
a blip on the screen. With Holyfield and Lewis set to meet in a
heavyweight unification bout on March 13 in Madison Square Garden,
Tyson's absence won't make a difference in the overall scene. The
boxers that Tyson was considering as opponents _ Axel Schulz and
Brian Nielsen _ don't figure prominently in anyone's heavyweight
championship scenerio.
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Finkel, Tyson's advisor, said he had anticipated the
boxer fighting four times this year. But his April 24th fight isn't
going to happen. Gansler said Tyson could be released after six
months, with time off for good behavior. If Judge Patricia Gifford,
the Indiana judge who presided over Tyson's rape trial in
Indianapolis, doesn't decide to revoke his probation, then he would
be back for a fight in the fall. But will his act continue to play
with the public?
</P>
<P>
   ''Tyson is no longer a fighter,'' Arum said. ``He's a curiosity.
People who want to see him fight and bought the pay per view for
his last fight weren't interested in boxing. They were watching on
the chance that something bizarre would happen.'' Arum added:
``You're not going to see the end of him until he winds up dead.
Unless he gets the help he needs, you haven't seen the worst of him
yet, either.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
