<P>
   Here are the top Times Express stories planned for Saturday,
Feb. 6, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service Night Supervisor is Ned
kilkelly; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail: nekilk(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-JORDAN-HUSSEIN (Amman, Jordan) _ With King Hussein
unconscious and near death, Jordan's government transferred full
powers Saturday to Crown Prince Abdullah, making the 37-year-old
heir to the throne king in all but name and effectively ending
Hussein's rule after 47 years. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-JORDAN-PRINCE (Amman, Jordan) _ As Crown Prince Abdullah
formally took charge of Jordan's government Saturday, experienced
observers here said that internal political challenges _ rather
than foreign affairs crises _ are likely to present the new king
with his first leadership tests. By William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-KOSOVO-TALKS (Rambouillet, France) _ The Kosovo peace
conference, ini- tially designed as an elaborate set piece of
diplomacy, stumbled toward a chaotic opening Saturday. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-NIGERIA-ELECTIONS (Kano, Nigeria) _ As Nigeria prepares to
hold presidential elections on Feb. 27 and usher in a civilian
government in May, no single leader seems capable of healing the
nation's political soul. By Norimitsu Onishi. With map.
</P>
<P>
   EXP-GERMANY-WORK-RULES (Gummersbach, Germany) _ Germany's strict
work rules have helped give it one of the best-paid and most
productive work forces in the world, but it has also fueled a
stubbornly high rate of unemployment. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
