</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EX-SPIES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENT-A-SPY: COLD WAR FOES JOIN AS CAPITALIST TOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
 (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl)  
By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If anyone had suggested during the Cold War that former CIA and
KGB agents would one day be working together as business partners
to provide sensitive information to U.S. corporations, the idea
would have seemed too far-fetched to be believed.
</P>
<P>
   But that is exactly what is happening today as hundreds of
out-of-work spies from the United States and Russia are joining
hands in the pursuit of capitalism, providing protection,
intelligence and political risk assessments to U.S. companies
extending their reach to emerging markets and other global hot
spots.
</P>
<P>
   They include men like Gen. Victor Budanov, a former chief of
counterintelligence for the KGB, who formed a joint venture with
Gerard Burke, who was once assistant director of the National
Security Agency. Budanov heads the Moscow office of Parvus
International, a business intelligence firm in Silver Spring, Md.,
founded by Burke that employs former CIA, KGB and Soviet-bloc
agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not talk about our former jobs,'' Budanov said. ``We are
in a new life and we are now partners in the same boat of helping
our American clents.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the American Society for Industrial Security, a trade group
with 35,000 members representing private security companies, has a
Moscow chapter with about 35 ex-employees of the Soviet
intelligence agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows the territory there better than former KGB
officers?'' said Joseph Ricci, a spokesman for the group. ``Some of
our members at first had a hard time with having a Russian chapter
_ but then most of our members started out working for the U.S.
government. But these KGB guys are not employed by their government
anymore and they have to make a living. Their loyalty is to who is
putting food on their table.''
</P>
<P>
   Business intelligence firms provide U.S. corporations operating
overseas with information about local politics and pitfalls,
protection for executives and background data on local business
partners.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Parvus keep American businesses from stumbling
into bad business arrangements in far-flung places like Kazakhstan,
Russia and the Ukraine and bail them out when they do _ helping
them deal with kidnappings, fraud, theft and extortion.
</P>
<P>
   For many of these firms, it makes perfect sense to employ former
spies, many of whom have spent their lives studying other cultures,
speak many languages and can often surreptitiously ferret out
information through networks of local contacts _ both among local
government officials and shadier types.
</P>
<P>
   ``Former KGB officers, like our CIA, are the best and the
brightest,'' said Frederick Rustmann, a retired CIA officer who is
head of CTC International (named after the CIA's Counter-Terrorism
Center), a firm in West Palm Beach, Fla., with six former CIA
agents and one ex-KGB officer on staff and scores of former
Soviet-bloc spies on retainer abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all in the same trade and we all learned the same
techniques,'' Rustmann said. ``KGB officers are naturals. We use
them to collect information for us and for security. You can rent a
former KGB agent with four languages, a gun and a car for 50 bucks
a day. And he'll interpret for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Many former Russian spies are available because the KGB was
broken up into several agencies and scaled back after 1991, and the
financial rewards are far greater on the outside. And the recent
political and economic turmoil in Russia has only increased the
demand for their services, with Western companies scrambling for
more intelligence and protection than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   But don't the spies feel a little weird about working side by
side with their former adversaries? Apparently not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, our countries were enemies, but many of us were
friends,'' Rustmann said. ``The fact is, when I was in Libya I had
lots of KGB friends. Our backgrounds are similar, our psychology
and training are similar. We used to go on picnics together and our
families were friends. I was always trying to recruit Boris and he
was trying to recruit me.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke said in the six years that Parvus has been doing business
in Moscow, only once did a client _ a Fortune 100 company _ raise
questions about whether former KGB agents were trustworthy. Burke
dealt with this concern by slowly introducing his KGB staffers to
the American client and then increasing their level of
responsibility and accessibility to corporate secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in this business for many years and I'm able to vet
these people carefully,'' Burke said. ``From time to time in the
back alleys of the world, you are confronted with a lot of
inducements and you see a very, very dark side. There are some
former spies I wouldn't touch with a 10-foot pole.''
</P>
<P>
   Many former Soviet-bloc spies say they are still serving their
countries, only in a new way, by making sure that American
businesses keep capital invested in their homelands. ``Instead of
doing stupid Cold War stuff, we have finally found some useful
purpose in life,'' said one former spy who asked not to be named.
``We want to make sure that American investors don't get burned
here so that capital keeps flowing in. What used to be a lethal
weapon has now become very peaceable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
