<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4399 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-ELECTIONS-ART     02-06 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-ELECTIONS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIA SEEKS A CANDIDATE FOR PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANO, Nigeria _ Go past the men guarding the walled compounds of
the most powerful politicians here in Nigeria's quintessential
northern city, past the satellite dishes planted in their
courtyards, past the waiting rooms where hangers-on elbow one
another for an audience with the men of influence.
</P>
<P>
   Enter their innermost conference rooms, where the northerners
are making deals and planning strategies _ and agreeing, most of
them say, to hand over the biggest prize of all, the presidency of
Africa's most populous nation, to the south.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time we give the south the chance to produce a president
because there is so much clamor and because of Abiola,'' said
Kabiru Gaya, a prominent member of the All People's Party, one of
the country's three parties and the one most clearly identified
with the north.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like someone being wounded,'' continued Gaya, 46, a
former governor of Kano State, as the movie-screen-size television
in his conference room was switched on to CNN. ``And this is the
only way to treat the wound.''
</P>
<P>
   The wound stems from what is called the ``June 12 issue.'' On
that date in 1993, Moshood K.O. Abiola, a billionaire businessman
from the Yoruba southwest, appeared to win Nigeria's presidential
elections, only to see them annulled by the northern-dominated
military.
</P>
<P>
   As Nigeria prepares to hold presidential elections on Feb. 27,
no single leader seems capable of healing this gash. The wound
threatens to deepen the disunity in a country of 108 million people
riven along ethnic, religious and geographic lines, even as the
price of the one product that makes Nigeria matter to the United
States and the West _ oil _ has plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nigerian electorate has lost faith in the entire political
system,'' said Sule Lamido, 50, a prominent member of the People's
Democratic Party. ``We need someone to give all Nigeria a sense of
belonging, but there is no one who can do that now.''
</P>
<P>
   So, to keep Nigeria together, a consensus has emerged among
politicians in the north _ whose generals have ruled Nigeria for
all but 10 years since independence from Britain in 1960 _ that the
next president should come from the south. The slogan for this is
the ``power shift.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether this power shift gives real power to the winner, who
will emerge from elections that are being financed and influenced
by the military, is uncertain. Whether it yields national unity is
equally uncertain, and it carries, many believe, as many seeds of
divisiveness. If the north, dominated by the largely Muslim Hausa
and Fulani peoples, concedes the next president to the south, will
he be a Yoruba Christian from the southwest or an Ibo Christian
from the southeast?
</P>
<P>
   Some even see in the north's concession a Trojan horse, a
maneuver by the north to rule by pitting the two southern groups
against each other. ``Let the south produce the next president,''
said Ahmed Jalingo, a northerner and a professor of political
science at Bayero University here. ``When they fight and fail, we
will take over. I think the military will take over temporarily,
and the south will have to accept a northern compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   There is disagreement over who should be the presidential
candidate for the People's Democratic Party, the party favored by
retired generals and the only one of the three with national
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the party's presidential aspirants are southerners,
including the two best known, Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo, a former
president, and Alex Ekwueme, a former vice president. But a
national convention to choose the candidate, scheduled for this
weekend , has been postponed by three days, because of
disagreements. Gen. Obasanjo, as a career soldier, is considered
acceptable by the party's retired generals; but his own people, the
Yoruba, distrust his ties to the northern military.
</P>
<P>
   His selection as presidential candidate would alienate the Ibo,
who are backing one of their own, Ekwueme, briefly civilian vice
president two decades ago. The Ibo have supported the People's
Democratic Party, unlike the Yoruba, who essentially have formed
their own party, the Alliance for Democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance for Democracy Party and the All People's Party of
the north have agreed to present a common slate. The likely
scenario is for the Alliance for Democracy to present the
presidential candidate _ from the south _ and the All People's
Party to produce the vice president _ even though the All People's
Party won more seats nationally in the municipal and governorship
elections.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not yet clear whether the commission overseeing
Nigeria's elections will let the two parties present a joint
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The election follows one of the darkest periods in Nigeria's
history. After a northern military ruler, Gen. Ibrahim Babangida,
annulled Abiola's election, another northerner, Gen. Sani Abacha,
imprisoned Abiola in 1994, as part of a widespread crackdown on
human rights that turned Nigeria into an international pariah.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, weeks after a third northerner, Gen. Abdulsalami
Abubakar, took over after Abacha's sudden death and announced the
end of military rule, Abiola died _ still in custody.
</P>
<P>
   But the south's resentment of the north feeds on deeper wells.
Nigeria, like much of Africa, was put together haphazardly as a
nation by colonial powers. Tensions have erupted often since
independence, most violently during the Biafran civil war of the
1960s, when a million people died in an attempt by the Ibo to
secede. Most recently, scores belonging to smaller ethnic groups in
the Niger Delta region in the south have been killed, protesting
the fact that the north has monopolized oil profits and left the
oil-producing Delta without paved roads, sewers, running water or
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The north has dominated us for decades,'' said Kofoworola
Bucknor-Akerele, who was elected deputy governor of Lagos state in
January as a candidate for the Alliance for Democracy. ``Democracy
is very much part of the south. We want to restore it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alhaji Abubakar Rimi disagrees. Rimi, like Gaya a former
governor of Kano state and Communications Minister under Abacha,
said all Nigerians had been dominated by military rulers who have
enriched themselves. ``What people in the south have not been able
to do is separate the military institution from the geographic
north of Nigeria,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few and most prominent northern politicians to reject
the concept of power shift, Rimi, 58, has declared his candidacy in
the presidential primaries for the People's Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is power shift, the situation can only get worse for
the north,'' Rimi said in his private conference room. ``I know
anybody from the south who comes to power will neglect the north.
That will be dangerous for him and for Nigeria.''
</P>
<P>
   Umar Othman Tofa, who lost in the gubernatorial primaries in
Kano State in the All People's Party, said he supported the idea of
the power shift, until a candidate capable of uniting all Nigerians
emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should not be a permanent solution,'' Tofa said of the
power shift. ``But because we are in a crisis, we need power shift.
Desperate situations require desperate solutions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
