<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3620 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBAL-LENDING-REVIEW     02-06 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-LENDING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO CURB BORROWING: MAKE LENDING RISKIER 
</HEADLINE>
 (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl)  
By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since the global financial crisis began in East Asia 19
months ago, public debate has focused on the mistake made by the
damaged countries: too much borrowing. Now the flip side of that
problem is coming into focus: too much lending.
</P>
<P>
   The latest thinking about how to stop new outbreaks of global
financial distress features proposals to slow down lending by
making it riskier and more expensive. The plans, coming from
academics and public officials, would rein in the banks, mutual
funds, hedge funds, pension funds and wealthy individuals in
industrial countries who in the 1990s poured tens of billions of
dollars in short-term loans into East Asia's booming economies.
</P>
<P>
   These loans played a huge part in precipitating bankruptcies,
bank failures, plunging currencies and recessions, first in Asia,
then in Russia and now in Brazil. When trouble came, the lenders
canceled the loans, withdrawing their money and leaving whole
countries in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that in this particular crisis, private sector
lenders have not emerged well,'' Stanley Fischer, first deputy
managing director of the International Monetary Fund, said a week
ago at the World Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland, an annual
gathering of world leaders, corporate executives, economists and
other movers and shakers.
</P>
<P>
   The lenders, naturally enough, aren't happy about the attempts
to alter their behavior. Rising from his seat in the audience,
Citigroup vice chairman Deryck Maughan responded to Fischer by
noting that lenders had already lost considerable sums in the
current crisis _ a curb in itself on overly risky lending in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, William Cline, chief economist at the Institute
for International Finance, which represents lenders, said new rules
that make lending riskier would only inhibit the flow of capital
that emerging countries will need to expand their economies once
the current global crisis ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take some time for a really strong, resurgent lending
market to revive,'' Cline said. ``It is asking for trouble to put
up impediments now to this future lending.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is the very goal of the new proposals. They seek to
avoid flooding a country with too much short-term lending that can
be quickly withdrawn. Already some nations are restricting such
lending by taxing short-term loans as they enter the country, thus
making them more expensive for the borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   The new approaches would strike at the lenders, preventing them,
for example, from pulling out their money in the event of crisis
conditions _ a weakening currency, shrinking economic growth _ that
threaten to devastate an economy. Other proposals would give debtor
countries the legal right to reschedule and postpone payments owed
to foreign banks and bondholders.
</P>
<P>
   Restricting lenders would solve another problem. It would
deflect criticism that the Clinton administration and the IMF, in
pushing through huge bailout loans for countries in crisis, are
using public money to repay lenders for risky credits they should
not have extended in the first place, or at least not in such
quantities. Such bailouts will only encourage excessive lending in
the future, this argument goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If lenders don't take a hit, they won't price their loans
correctly,'' said Robert Litan, a senior fellow at the Brookings
Institution. ``They will set interest rates too low, and they will
shovel too much money into questionable markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposals to curb lending are coming increasingly from
international organizations, most of which bring together
representatives from industrial countries where the lenders are
located. One proposal, for example, would require or encourage
lenders to put aside, say, 9 cents or 10 cents for every dollar
lent to banks and businesses in high-risk countries. These are
amounts larger than the sums that are required to be put aside
today. With that extra money sitting idle, lenders would have to
increase their interest rates to earn as much as before _ and the
higher rates would inhibit lending.
</P>
<P>
   Another change would make it easier to renegotiate debt, much of
which is in the form of bonds sold to mutual funds, hedge funds,
wealthy investors and the like. Through a majority vote, for
example, these bondholders could agree to stretch out payments from
hard-pressed debtors in emerging countries. Currently, most bonds
agreements require a unanimous vote to do this.
</P>
<P>
   Still other proposals would put ceilings on short-term lending
in risky markets, or require lenders to take a loss on their loans
in the event of a crisis _ a ``haircut'' that Litan is pushing.
</P>
<P>
   Are any of these changes likely to be adopted and enforced?
Probably not, if the global crisis ends soon. Besides, there are
few mechanisms to enforce these rules across borders.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the global crisis endures, overcoming the resistance of
lenders will not be easy. Borrowers may also object, given the
likelihood that the various restrictions will require them to pay
higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is,'' Litan said, ``that no one wants to be the
first to make the necessary commitment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
