<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4404 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCSEC-STOCKS-REVIEW-     02-06 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-STOCKS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIAL SECURITY ON WALL ST. : A BUY ORDER FOR $1 TRILLION
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl)  
By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What would happen if the government were investing
hundreds of billions of dollars of Social Security reserves in the
stock market, and the anti-abortion forces in Congress decided that
none of it should be put into companies that make or import pills
that induce abortion?
</P>
<P>
   Playing politics with the Social Security reserves would be
quite unpopular. But companies that might want to put abortion
pills on the market could hardly afford the risk that their stocks
would be off limits to maybe the biggest single investor in the
world. So it's a safe bet that any plans to put the pills on sale
would be shelved.
</P>
<P>
   That is the kind of nightmare foreseen by the economists and
politicians who oppose President Clinton's plan to beef up Social
Security reserves by investing some of the money in stocks.
Political tampering, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan warned
Congress in January, could ``put at risk the efficiency of our
capital markets and thus our economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and conservative economists oppose the Clinton plan
because they fear government intrusion in the markets. But most of
them would also divert Social Security money into stocks. Under
various proposals, all workers would be allowed to take some of the
money they would otherwise pay in taxes and invest it in stocks
that would go into their own private investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But these plans are fraught with potential problems, too, the
most serious being the possibility that workers could lose some of
their retirement savings through bad investments or a drop in the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are trying to take advantage of a simple fact of
economic history: Over a long period of time, private stocks have
earned much more money for investors than the government bonds
where by law the Social Security reserves are now held. Economists
project the average annual return on stocks over the next 75 years
to be 6 percent to 7 percent more than the rate of inflation,
compared with an average of less than 3 percent above inflation for
government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   This is important because every additional dollar investments
earn for retirement is one less dollar the government will have to
raise for Social Security through higher taxes or reduced benefits
when the baby boomers begin to retire early in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue is more a matter of politics and ideology than of
economics. Most of the advocates on both sides _ those who want the
government to control the investments and those who want workers to
invest the money themselves _ would rather leave the Social
Security system as it is now with its lower return on investments
than take what they see as the unacceptable risks of the other
side's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Under President Clinton's plan, nearly $600 billion, or 15
percent of the Social Security trust fund, would be invested in
stocks between now and 2015. Counting dividends and inflation, the
government would then own about $1 trillion in stock, nearly 4
percent of all the outstanding public stock in the country.
</P>
<P>
   A strict firewall would be built to protect this investment from
political meddling. Management would be placed in the hands of an
independent board whose members would serve long, staggered terms
and not be subject to removal for political reasons. Investments
could be made only in broad index funds, not in individual stocks.
The government's voting rights on its shares would be restricted,
and the managers would be required to vote shares solely according
to the economic interest of the beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The president and his economic advisers argue that the
management board would be every bit as insulated from politics as
the Federal Reserve Board. And they say the experience of state
pension funds and the Thrift Savings Plan for federal workers shows
that public pension money can be invested in the stock market
without political interference.
</P>
<P>
   But critics point out that over the years, the Federal Reserve
has often been subjected to political arm twisting. (The Nixon
White House, for example, leaned heavily on Fed Chairman Arthur
Burns to see that the economy was especially strong in 1972 when
Nixon ran for re-election. Burns denied it, but many historians are
now convinced that he manipulated monetary policy to that effect.)
</P>
<P>
   Any firewall that Congress builds, the critics note, Congress
can also tear down with one vote.
</P>
<P>
   As for state and local pension funds, they have generally
avoided political tampering, but there are countless exceptions.
Pension funds in California and Illinois have been required to
contribute money to offset state budget deficits. Funds in
Pennsylvania and Connecticut recently lost millions of dollars
because politicians insisted they make investments to keep or
attract job-producing businesses in those states. In the 1970s and
1980s, more than half the state legislatures prohibited their
retirement funds from being invested in companies that did business
in South Africa. Pension funds in four states _ Florida,
Massachusetts, Minnesota and Vermont _ have been required to sell
their stock in tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrift Savings Plan has indeed been free of politics. But
with assets of about $70 billion, its portfolio is much smaller
than Social Security's would be. In addition, unlike Social
Security, participation is voluntary for Federal workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pension fund money is lusted after by politicians of both
parties,'' said Richard Koppes, former general counsel of the
California Public Employees' Retirement System. ``They can't resist
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Allowing workers to invest part of their retirement money
themselves, as most Republicans want to do, avoids most of the
political problems, but it raises others. Most Americans are not
sophisticated about finance and could be victimized by unscrupulous
sales pitches. In 1988, when Britain allowed workers to opt out of
the public pension system and invest in private accounts, many
people lost billions of dollars to scam artists in what was called
the ``mis-selling'' scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that markets are not always strong. The
decade of the 1970s, for example, was not good for stocks. Adjusted
for inflation, the average portfolio did not reach its 1969 level,
even with dividends reinvested, until 1983. A huge government
portfolio could smooth the peaks and valleys, but private investors
could lose a large part of their retirement savings in a bear
market.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, small accounts would be expensive to administer, and a
sizable chunk of workers' savings could go to administrative fees.
According to Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman Arthur
Levitt Jr., a 1 percent annual fee, for instance, reduces an
account's balance by 17 percent after 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, since almost everyone in politics wants to put some of
the money in the stock market one way or another, perhaps the
president and Congress will decide that the reward is worth the
risks. The division between the two sides over how to invest the
Social Security money is so sharp, though, that a compromise will
be difficult. But the attraction of finding a way to minimize tax
increases and benefit cuts is mighty strong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1229EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0098 </DOCNO>
