<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4405 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-ART-     02-06 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-ART-words(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR BETWEEN THE STATES FOR NOMINATING GLORY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Del., Iowa, N.H., Ohio, Ariz., Ark., Ore.)  ARIZONA: McCAIN RETHINKS HOME STATE PRIMARY 
ARKANSAS: THIS TIME AROUND, OUTRAGE DIDN'T MATTER 
OREGON: PACKWOOD SPEAKS TO PAPER, KIND OF  
(jw) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to nominating presidential candidates, Louisiana
and Delaware don't like to play by the rules that have
traditionally governed this quadrennial rite. Of all the states
that in recent years have tried to gain nominating clout by moving
up the dates of their caucuses and primaries, these two have been
the boldest and most aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, Iowa claimed the right to hold the nation's
first caucuses, usually scheduling them in late February or early
March. But in 1996, Louisiana Republicans ignored that claim and
scheduled their caucuses first. Party leaders said a few days ago
that come Election 2000, Louisiana plans to be out front again.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, for many years New Hampshire claimed the right to hold
the nation's first primary, always scheduling it just after Iowa's
caucuses and a full week before primary voting in any other state.
But in 1996, Delaware horned in and grabbed some of the early
nominating glory by holding its primary just four days after New
Hampshire had voted. And come Election 2000, Delaware has plans to
once again vote right on New Hampshire's heels.
</P>
<P>
   But Iowa and New Hampshire are fighting back in this new War
Between the States.
</P>
<P>
   As they did in 1996, election officials in both states vow they
will move up their voting dates as often as necessary to preserve
their first-in-the-nation status, though they acknowledge that such
action could set off a mad rescheduling competition and might
violate some national party regulations. These officials are also
demanding, as they did in 1996, that announced and prospective
candidates pledge to ignore Louisiana and Delaware. Further, they
warn that candidates who refuse to take the pledge might be
punished by slighted voters in Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   That threat scared many candidates away from Louisiana and
Delaware in 1996 and sharply reduced the impact of their
beat-you-to-the-polls votes. And this time around the threat is
again bringing in some pledges.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, a probable candidate, sent pledge
letters last week to party officials in both Iowa and New
Hampshire, saying that those states must be allowed to go first in
the presidential nominating process because they are small and
manageable enough to afford ``every campaign a fair hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The grand tradition of American politics, where every
candidate is given the same chance, must be preserved,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Another aspirant, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., also has made a
pledge, telling New Hampshire officials last weekend that he was
committed to preserving the state's first-in-the-nation primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do everything in my power,'' he said. ``I will not
campaign in Delaware.''
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN RETHINKS THE ARIZONA PRIMARY
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to when his own state should hold its primary in
2000, McCain has recently had some second thoughts _ curious second
thoughts, his critics say.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he supported a decision by the Arizona Legislature to
leapfrog the primary date several months ahead, to mid-February,
apparently calculating that the shift not only would give the state
more influence in the nominating process but would also provide his
favorite candidate, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, with an early
opportunity to build momentum (a moot calculation as things turned
out, because Gramm was out of the race by the time Arizonans went
to the polls).
</P>
<P>
   Now, for Election 2000, in which he must think of his own
candidacy, McCain favors moving back the date of the primary, to
March 14.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that many of the state's cities and towns have scheduled
local elections for that day, he argues that holding a primary in
mid-February and local elections a month later would be a costly
inconvenience for voters. Better to consolidate the elections on
March 14, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of two other White House aspirants, former Vice
President Dan Quayle and Steve Forbes, the publisher, question that
reasoning. Pointing out that Quayle now lives in Arizona and that
Forbes won the primary there in 1996, they contend that McCain
faces the possibility of serious political trouble, maybe even
defeat, in the 2000 Arizona primary and wants to postpone it until
after March 7.
</P>
<P>
   That day will be the biggest of the year for primaries, the
Super Tuesday of Super Tuesdays, with about a dozen states
scheduled to vote, including California and New York. No candidate
wants to go into it burdened with the embarrassment of a bad
performance in an earlier home state primary.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, most of Arizona's Republican leaders, including those
in the Republican-dominated Legislature, have refused to go along
with McCain on moving the primary back to March 14.
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough, McCain said the other day, adding, ``Early, later
or medium, I can beat anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   THIS TIME AROUND, OUTRAGE DIDN'T MATTER
</P>
<P>
   Remember Dr. Fay Boozman, the ophthalmologist who was the
unsuccessful Republican candidate in last year's U.S. Senate race
in Arkansas?
</P>
<P>
   In one campaign appearance, he said he was a strong opponent of
abortion, except in cases of rape, incest and when the life of the
mother was threatened. But he argued that abortion was mostly a
moot issue insofar as rape was concerned because, he said, the
stress of the assault triggered a biochemical reaction in the
victim that made conception unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Women's groups were outraged and many medical authorities shook
their heads in wonderment. And after the election, when Arkansas
Gov. Mike Huckabee, a conservative Republican, said he planned to
appoint Boozman as director of the state's Department of Health,
there was a firestorm of protest, with 11 women in the Legislature
declaring him unqualified for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the governor made the appointment. It is not subject
to legislative approval.
</P>
<P>
   PACKWOOD SPEAKS TO PAPER, KIND OF
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Bob Packwood, the former Republican senator from
Oregon, has had his differences with that state's leading
newspaper, The Oregonian of Portland. In fact, in the four years
since he resigned from the Senate after its Ethics Committee found
him guilty of sexual harassment, a story given heavy play by the
paper, Packwood has refused all requests by its reporters for an
interview _ until the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Then, according to Wednesday's Oregonian, he left the following
voice mail for Jim Barnett, a reporter:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Bob Packwood. I got your call yesterday. It's
Thursday, 7 o'clock. As you're aware, Jim, my policy hasn't
changed. But if you would like a quote, it's the same one I gave
you the other day, and I'm curious to see if The Oregonian will use
it. Quote: Since I quit talking to The Oregonian, my business has
prospered beyond all measure. I assume my business has prospered
because I don't talk to The Oregonian. Therefore I will continue
that policy. Unquote. Thanks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1231EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 12:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CAMPAIGN-910&AMP;     02-06 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CAMPAIGN-910&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H.)  
 POLITICAL MEMO: CANDIDATES SAY LITTLE ABOUT IMPEACHMENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Ohio, Texas, Arizona, N.Y., Tenn., Miss., Kan., N.J., (Eds: See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-LEADERS, IMPEACH-ROGAN,
IMPEACH-SKETCH) 
(jw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Ask Republican presidential prospects about the biggest
issue facing their party _ whether President Clinton should be
convicted by the Senate _ and you'll probably get something short
of a direct answer.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich of Ohio: ``I don't want to get into dictating
to the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Bush of Texas: ``This person has embarrassed us and
the Senate needs to do what it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona: ``I hold the quaint notion that I'm
a juror _ and jurors wait until after the trial to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee: ``Let the senators
decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone has ducked the question. Some contenders, including
Steve Forbes, the publishing magnate, and former Vice President Dan
Quayle, have called for Clinton to be convicted. But in their
barnstorming tours through early primary states like New Hampshire,
even those candidates have been careful, especially recently, not
to make the subject a centerpiece of their speeches. Mostly, they
discuss the matter only when quizzed by reporters.
</P>
<P>
   This reluctance to weigh in enthusiastically _ or at all _ on an
issue that has so dominated American politics and consumed
Republicans in Congress underscores their party's ambivalence about
how impeachment is playing politically.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, it would be understandable for candidates to
condemn Clinton and press for his ouster because many conservatives
who are influential in the primaries favor that position. On the
other hand, polls show that Republicans, even conservatives,
increasingly worry that impeachment may hover over their party like
a mushroom cloud that could damage them in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, most Republican prospects for president expressed
their deep disapproval, even disgust, with Clinton. But they also
made clear that they were wrestling with how to handle what hardly
seemed a winning issue. Clearly, they do not want impeachment to
define their candidacies _ or risk being identified as prime movers
behind what some voters already claim is a partisan witch hunt.
</P>
<P>
   If voters in 2000 are still critical of the Republican Party's
handling of impeachment, candidates who are now outspoken on the
matter could be particularly vulnerable. Those who are keeping a
low profile may be tempted to campaign next year against what they
could describe as an impeachment-obsessed Congress, even one now
controlled by their own party.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I ducked the issue, there might be a temporary political
advantage because even among a lot of Republicans this is not very
popular,'' said Forbes, who sought the nomination in 1996. ``But I
feel you've got to put it on the table. You've got to explain the
way you feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes usually condemns Clinton's behavior in his speeches but
lately he has dwelled more on the Republicans' failure to respond
with a full agenda of issues. Asked what the Senate should do, he
said: ``Given the man's abuses of office _ which go far beyond the
Monica business _ they have a duty to go through with the trial.
And if I were a senator, I would vote to convict.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle also declares forcefully that the Senate should remove
Clinton from office. In a speech in Indianapolis this week, he
repeated what had become a stock anecdote. ``Think of this,'' he
said. ``The day Bill Clinton was impeached by the House of
Representatives, Al Gore, in the Rose Garden of the White House,
stands before the world and says, `Bill Clinton is one of America's
greatest presidents.' We have a different interpretation of what
integrity is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle explained that he, too, thought the Senate should convict
Clinton, saying, ``I think perjury is clearly in the category of
high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, a prominent religious conservative, also hammers
away at Clinton and asserts that he should be forced from office.
``He could salvage his place in history by turning the presidency
over to Al Gore,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   But even those remarks are not nearly as harsh as the scathing
attacks on Clinton after the Monica Lewinsky scandal broke.
</P>
<P>
   At a Republican gathering in Biloxi, Miss., a year ago, Forbes
described the ``shadiness and sordidness that we have in the White
House today.'' At the same event, Quayle called the scandal a
``disgusting situation'' and mockingly put forward an anti-crime
proposal that he described as ``three interns _ and you're out!''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander was one of the first contenders to call for Clinton to
resign _ and said he would vote for impeachment in the House _ but
has been mum on what the Senate should do.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Reed, who ran Bob Dole's presidential campaign in 1996,
said, ``In the beginning, everyone thought this guy was going to be
gone in 72 hours.'' But the president's approval rating has
remained strong. ``That says something to these candidates and
their campaigns,'' Reed said. ``It says that they ought to leave
this alone.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why Kasich, when asked how often in his political
speeches he brought up his House vote to impeach Clinton, said:
``Virtually, not at all. I do talk about the notion that our
big-time leaders have to be more selfless. But renewing the spirit
of America is not about what the president did. It's about what a
president could do in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Kasich would not take a stand on what the Senate should
do, he said, ``I believe these are impeachable and removable
offenses.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, who is considering a run for the nomination,
said through a spokeswoman that she would have no comment about
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican candidates, declared or undeclared, were willing
to go as far as others in their party and predict that impeachment
could damage their party's prospects in 2000. Bush, for one, said
he expected that people would be no more interested in the matter
than they are now. ``I don't think the attitudes of the American
people and the political landscape and environment is going to be
much different than it is today,'' he said. ``People want to look
forward, not backward.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Republicans should worry about the political
fallout, Alexander said: ``We should be concerned about that, but
that shouldn't affect how senators vote. Senators should vote their
conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an idea that once this is all over, the country will
render a verdict,'' he added. ``And I think it will be a verdict
against Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Gore, of course, has stood loyally in
defense of the president. Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey,
who is also seeking the nomination, has not been reluctant to
criticize Clinton. But, like many Republicans, he has not made the
issue a central theme. And unlike most Republicans, he asserts that
the president should not be thrown out of office.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the president did is wrong, and anytime a president lies
it erodes his credibility and the authority of the office,''
Bradley said. ``However, I don't believe that what President
Clinton is accused of rises to the level of high crimes and
misdemeanors, and therefore don't believe he should be convicted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
