u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ROGAN-ART-NYT     02-06 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ROGAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RISING STAR FINDS HIMSELF A TARGET OF ANGER AND SUPPORT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (Eds: See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-LEADERS, IMPEACH-SKETCH,
IMPEACH-CAMPAIGN) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Almost from the moment he was elected to the
House of Representatives, James Rogan was singled out by fellow
Republicans as the freshman most likely to become a star.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan had become California's youngest judge at age 33 in 1990,
majority leader in the State Assembly in his first term, in 1996,
and a congressman in 1997. He so impressed Republican House leaders
that they waived their seniority rules and appointed him to two
high-profile committees: Commerce and Judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as one of the 13 House prosecutors trying to persuade the
Senate to remove President Clinton from office, Rogan, 41, has
greater name recognition in his second term than many of his
colleagues do after decades in office. But it is this starring role
in the president's impeachment trial that has put Rogan on the
Democratic Party's short list of Republicans from moderate
districts who are most likely to suffer a voter backlash in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Rogan is done,'' said Art Torres, chairman of the
California Democratic Party. ``People didn't really know him until
this impeachment issue. He had painted himself as a moderate. Now,
he has been exposed as the far-right zealot he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans counter that the impeachment issue will be dead by
2000, when the president will not be eligible to run again anyway.
Michael Schroeder, chairman of the California Republican Party,
dismisses the Democrats' predictions of a backlash as ``wishful
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years is an eternity in politics,'' Schroeder said. ``To
assume that the voters are going to take revenge when the president
will be out of office is just not reasonable.'' Besides, he added,
the Democrats could not beat Rogan in November, in the best
election year they have had in California since 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the impeachment issue, Rogan's district would have
been a battleground in 2000. The 27th Congressional District, which
runs along the San Gabriel Mountains from Burbank and Glendale
through Pasadena and San Marino, is in transition. Registered
Democrats now hold the majority over Republicans in these Los
Angeles suburbs by 44 to 39 percent. In November, Rogan was barely
re-elected, with 50.8 percent of the vote, over an unknown whom he
outspent two-to-one.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats assert that polls they have conducted show that a
substantial number of voters in Rogan's district are less likely to
vote for him again because of his stance on impeachment. Later this
month the Democrats plan a voter registration drive in a handful of
swing districts where disenchantment with impeachment is at a
crest, and Rogan's is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan, who has been inundated with calls, e-mail and letters,
the majority of them anti-impeachment, is well aware of the
ramifications of his position, said his press secretary, Jeffrey
Solsby. ``It's one thing to lose an election,'' Solsby said. ``It's
another thing to compromise your conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Zarian, a city councilman in Rogan's home base of Glendale
who hosts a nightly conservative talk show, argued that support for
him was overwhelming, ``and not just from conservatives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven out of 10 people I talk to on the street believe that
the president should be thrown out,'' he said. ``I don't know about
those polls, but I've seen the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveys of public opinion show that most people want the
impeachment trial to end soon, and with the president's acquittal.
That sentiment seemed to prevail with some people who took time
from shopping here to speak with a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I see Rogan on TV, I want to scream,'' said Kathy
Murphy, 28, a registered independent who did not vote in the last
election but said she planned to next time. ``I thought by not
voting, it would show how turned off I am to the whole political
process. Now I think that throwing the rascal out is a better
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, John Mack, 46, a Republican, said he was glad
that Rogan had ``stuck to his conservative guns.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is a moral disgrace to the entire world,'' Mack said.
</P>
<P>
   Cara Weinstein, a 36-year-old Democrat, said she had friends who
were already planning to contribute to whoever Rogan's next
opponent might be.
</P>
<P>
   She and her friends are not alone. The likely Democratic
contenders for the seat, state Sen. Adam Schiff of Burbank and
state Assemblyman Jack Scott of Pasadena, both say they have
received a barrage of calls and letters from voters and party
leaders asking them to run.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan's appearance in the spotlight has had its benefits, his
press secretary said, including an instance the other day when the
White House sought advance notice of the House prosecutors'
strategy. Rogan, quoting a former California judge, responded,
``It's none of your damn business what the other side is going to
put on.''
</P>
<P>
   The telephone rang off the hook in his office. By 10-to-one,
Solsby said, ``The callers said they were proud.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
