<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3628 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNS-REVIEW-NYT     02-06 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WORKPLACE OFTEN TAKES AN INTERN FOR THE WORSE 
</HEADLINE>
 (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl)  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monica Lewinsky, America's most famous intern, has certainly
learned many tough lessons in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, she's not the only bright-eyed intern dealt a
rude awakening by the realities of office sex, intrigue, power
politics or just plain bad workplace behavior. Consider what
happens to young pups in, say, the world of journalism, the
profession chronicling the Lewinsky saga.
</P>
<P>
   I know, because as a New York University journalism professor I
regularly sent my students out on newspaper, TV and radio
internships, and they reported back to me. Below are selected
entries from the weekly internship logs kept by my students over
the last few years. Taken together, their experiences could be a
syllabus for a course in the school of hard knocks.
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD PETROW
</P>
<P>
   INTERN ASSIGNMENT: Production assistant for national TV talk
show originating in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   RUDE AWAKENING: The intern is sexually harassed by a producer,
but gets a new internship after a complaint is lodged against the
offender.
</P>
<P>
   Log entry No. 1: J., the producer, kept telling me how great I
looked, and asked me out for a drink, and kept calling me ``Babe.''
I guess I know what interns are thought to be in that office. I'm
not interested in sleeping my way up the journalistic ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Log entry No. 2: J., the producer, cornered me in the lobby of
the building and kissed me on the mouth and called me ``a sweet
mushroom.'' Professor, is this sexual harassment?
</P>
<P>
   Log entry No. 3: J., the producer, asked if I dyed my pubic
hair, and when I said, ``Pardon me?!'' he unzipped his fly and
threatened to show me his.
</P>
<P>
   INTERN ASSIGNMENT: Production assistant for a network TV news
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   RUDE AWAKENING: Not only was the intern just a go-fer, but she
had to pay out of her own pocket for what she went for.
</P>
<P>
   Log entry: One of the producers asked me to buy him candy. Not
only does he take advantage of me, but also he doesn't pay me back.
What makes it worse, he always asks: ``You don't mind, do you,
honey? You know you're one of my favorite interns and I'll give you
a great recommendation when you leave.'' He also talks to me in a
condescending way, telling me to ``come here.'' Like I'm some kind
of dog.
</P>
<P>
   INTERN ASSIGNMENT: Research assistant at a weekly TV news
program.
</P>
<P>
   RUDE AWAKENING: It's who you know.
</P>
<P>
   Log entry: Favoritism plays a strong role here. Men interns who
are later hired for full-time jobs become researchers or tape
editors, while females are forced into receptionist slots. One
intern is a 17-year-old boy who is IGNORANT, LAZY and frankly
INCOMPETENT. He constantly wanders off and gives other interns
tasks he doesn't want to do, but he is the son of a friend of the
producer. It makes me SICK.
</P>
<P>
   INTERN ASSIGNMENT: Work at an upscale arts magazine in New York.
</P>
<P>
   RUDE AWAKENING: So-called creative types can be pretentious
windbags.
</P>
<P>
   Log entry: I have a problem dealing with art and artistic
people. Why do they say such things as, ``an idea expressed by this
form of multicultural contemporary art . . . is primordial in
essence''? I don't understand what the hell they are talking about.
</P>
<P>
   INTERN ASSIGNMENT: News assistant at a New York radio station.
</P>
<P>
   RUDE AWAKENING: You've got the job: Hip, hip, hooray.
</P>
<P>
   Log entry: My last day at the radio station. My boss asks me to
come into the newsroom. The next thing I know I'm being serenaded
to a chorus of ``For He's a Jolly Good Fellow.'' They swamped me
with gifts _ a hat, gingerbread cookies, Chinese food. My boss said
I was one of the top five interns of all time. Later I was informed
that I could continue on as a volunteer, but that there aren't any
paid positions available.
</P>
<P>
   INTERN ASSIGNMENT: Editorial assistant for an alternative
entertainment weekly.
</P>
<P>
   RUDE AWAKENING: The intern equivalent of learning you're not in
Kansas anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Log entry: We get freaky stuff in the mail, like the press
release from Mon Cherie's the Chamber, which is this
dance/bondage/sexual fetish club in Atlanta. It had just celebrated
its first anniversary, which was OK by me except that they felt
compelled to send us pictures of half-dressed people wearing dog
collars having chocolate sauce licked off their bodies by people in
leather. We sent them back a note saying, ``Unfortunately, we do
not have an editorial need for this type of material.''
</P>
<P>
   INTERN ASSIGNMENT: Production assistant for a local TV news
operation.
</P>
<P>
   RUDE AWAKENING: Sometimes your heroes have feet of clay.
</P>
<P>
   Log entry: The correspondent and producer were several hours
late because the correspondent hadn't finished the script. I was
stunned. At NYU, when a script is due at a certain time, it is due
then! When the correspondent finally arrived, he fixed his makeup
and complained about his red eyes. He had problems delivering his
standups and decided he would become a spoiled brat. I was in
disbelief as I watched his childlike bickering, unrealistic demands
and temper tantrums. Never had I seen someone act so
unprofessional. I then realized that this man, whom I had thought
to be one of the greatest reporters on television, was an
incompetent journalist with no talent.
</P>
<P>
   INTERN ASSIGNMENT: Reporter at the New York bureau of a major
Japanese daily.
</P>
<P>
   RUDE AWAKENING: Superiors can be imperious jerks.
</P>
<P>
   Log entry: As I have already been offered a job with a newspaper
in Tokyo after my graduation, I thought it might be wise for me to
intern at the paper's New York bureau. I telephoned the New York
bureau chief and told him of my situation. I asked if he could see
me.
</P>
<P>
   He asked, ``When?''
</P>
<P>
   I said, ``Today, tomorrow, anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he gave me a scolding. ``You are being very selfish. Today?
Tomorrow. Don't you have any decency to consider our schedule?'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   I apologized most profusely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about it for a while, then call me back later,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   I thought about what to say to him, then called him back. I told
him that I was really sorry about imposing my timetable on him, but
that I would appreciate if he could decide what to do with me as
his circumstances allow.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' he said, ``are you available tomorrow?''
</P>
<P>
   INTERN ASSIGNMENT: Editorial assistant at The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   RUDE AWAKENING: The workplace can be a cold place.
</P>
<P>
   Log entry: I have just completed my first week of work at The
New York Times, the newspaper of record. . . . I enter in the
mornings without anyone saying hello and exit in the evenings
without anyone waving goodbye. At least three people in the office
pass my desk without so much as a nod or grunt in my direction. By
the way, I did mention to two others that the Times Square
neighborhood was lively. They looked at me as if I were a
two-headed dog.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
