<HEADER>
A4410 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIGER-TROUBLE-REVIEW-     02-06 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIGER-TROUBLE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UP NEXT: WHEN GIANT PETS RUN TOO WILD 
</HEADLINE>
 (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl)  
By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's the high-concept MOVIE PITCH: Escaped Man-Eating Tiger
Terrorizes Smalltown U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   Drama abounds in heart-pounding tale of a suburb suddenly forced
to resolve cultural conflicts in face of primordial threat: a
marauding (actually, it was wandering, but let's invoke dramatic
license) tiger. Characters include TOM BROWN JR., wily
wilderness-skills instructor, environmental writer and backwoods
tracker, and JOAN BYRON-MARASEK, cat-lover extraordinaire known to
older locals as ``the Tiger Lady.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a true story, one that began spinning out late last month
amid the dizzying glare of the New York City media. It features
television HELICOPTERS clattering over the treetops; TERRIFIED
NEIGHBORS herding CHILDREN indoors; CLAMORING REPORTERS, COPS,
BACKWOODS SURVIVALISTS, and, naturally, LAWYERS. Not to mention the
symbolic center of the tale: BENGAL TIGER, hunted down on Jan. 27
after appearing near some new homes, shot by police as darkness
fell, limping into the woods to die.
</P>
<P>
   The SCENE: picturesque, woodsy Jackson Township, N.J., a rapidly
suburbanizing municipality 40 miles from New York in the northern
periphery of the state's vast Pine Barrens forest. The town is in
the throes of a culture clash, with new residents tucking $250,000
houses deep into the woods, imposing suburbia on crusty Pineys (as
some locals call themselves) who are struggling to maintain an
individualistic way of life that, for example, allowed MS.
BYRON-MARASEK to keep about two-dozen full-grown tigers and 40 dogs
on her 12 fenced acres without attracting a lot of commotion.
</P>
<P>
   The STORY THUS FAR: After the tiger was killed, trackers
followed the beast's path to collect prints and forensic evidence,
as Brown described it, to determine where it came from. ``The poor
thing did not act as a tiger; it acted like a lost beagle,'' said
Brown, who operates Tracker Inc., a company that conducts
wilderness and survival training courses.
</P>
<P>
   Officials believe the tiger escaped from Ms. Byron-Marasek's
place, which is registered as a charity called Tigers Only
Preservation Society. She isn't talking, but through her lawyer has
denied that the tiger was hers, casting herself as a dedicated
animal-welfare activist. Various state and federal agencies
regulate the private keeping of exotic animals like tigers and
lions, but wildlife experts say monitoring is haphazard.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the state had issued Ms. Byron-Marasek permits
to operate a haven where she cared for 23 tigers acquired from
unknown sources. Late last week, saying the site had deteriorated
significantly since it was last inspected 13 years ago, the state
ordered her to make immediate improvements in safety fencing and
other conditions or lose her tiger permits.
</P>
<P>
   (In a SUBPLOT, astonished Jackson Township residents learned
after the shooting that their 100-square-mile municipality was
actually home to as many as 30 tigers, giving it the distinction of
having one of the greatest concentrations of tigers on Earth _
higher even than the most dense tiger populations in their natural
habitats in Asia. For besides the 23 registered to Ms.
Byron-Marasek, another 9 tigers reside at the nearby Six Flags
Great Adventure amusement park, which insists that all of its
tigers are accounted for.)
</P>
<P>
   The town is torn. A roadside memorial to the slain tiger has
been erected. Yellow ribbons flutter from pine trees. Animal rights
activists have set up a defense fund for Ms. Byron-Marasek.
</P>
<P>
   THE MORAL: ``Basically, tigers are huge predators,'' said David
Phemister, the conservation programs coordinator for the National
Fish and Wildlife Foundation, which manages the international Save
the Tiger Fund. ``Keeping them as pets, even in a situation where
you're performing an animal welfare or rescue operation, is
something that almost inevitably doesn't work out. And it seems to
me personally that an escaped tiger roaming through suburban New
Jersey is the epitome of things not working out.''
</P>
<P>
   About 8,000 tigers now live in the wild, down from over 100,000
at the start of this century, according to Save the Tiger Fund.
Another 1,000 tigers are held worldwide in zoos, conservation
parks, circuses and the like, according to the American Zoo and
Aquarium Association.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Jackson Township tiger hunt showed, no one really can
say how many tigers are living where you'd least expect to find
them. A 1997 National Geographic article pictured an Arkansas woman
who keeps 52 of the big cats at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be more tigers in private hands in the United
States than there are wild tigers in India,'' said Phemister.
``How's that for a depressing thought?''
</P>
<P>
   FADE OUT.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
