<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-965(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAYED IN SERBIA, REBELS' DELEGATES LEAVE FOR TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMBOUILLET, France _ The Kosovo peace conference, initially
designed as an elaborate set piece of diplomacy, stumbled toward a
chaotic opening on Saturday. Ethnic Albanian delegates were finally
allowed to fly out of Serbia and join foreign ministers who had
been left cooling their heels in the gardens of the chateau where
the negotiations will take place.
</P>
<P>
   The three delegates, guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army,
were refused travel documents by the Serbian authorities whom they
are fighting. But after intense Western pressure _ and after having
made the point that they could cause a ruckus at this conference
any time they wanted _ the Serbs relented early Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The three men, Jakup Krasniqi, Ram Buja and Zem Syla, who
changed their mud-caked boots and crumpled camouflage uniforms of
the Kosovo Liberation Army for suits, ties and topcoats, were
picked up at their rural headquarters and driven to the airport in
Pristina, Kosovo's capital, by Western diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   The full 16-member ethnic Albanian delegation, which includes
the Albanians' political leader Ibrahim Rugova, was expected to
join the 13-member Serbian delegation at the chateau, where
President Jacques Chirac of France, Foreign Secretary Robin Cook of
Britain and Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine of France were waiting
to open the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The bumpy start to the conference was a fitting prelude to what
could be a two-week standoff between the two sides, who seek widely
differing solutions to the crisis in Kosovo, a province of southern
Serbia that was stripped of its autonomy in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the Serbian delegation, Deputy Prime Minister
Ratko Markovic, set the tone for his side on the eve of the
conference, saying he would not speak _ even through intermediaries
_ to the Albanian ``terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs insist that Kosovo, the heart of Serbia's medieval
empire, must remain a part of Serbia, while the ethnic Albanians _
who make up 90 percent of the 2 million people estimated to live in
Kosovo _ want independence.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats from the United States, the European Union and Russia
who will run the day-to-day negotiations here are seeking an
in-between autonomous status.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration pushed hard the week before last to
persuade NATO to agree to air strikes against Serbia if President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia refuses to agree to a political
settlement at the end of two weeks of talks here.
</P>
<P>
   But it still seemed unclear whether NATO would actually go ahead
with air strikes or try to find a face-saving way out.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said on Thursday that he was ``seriously
considering'' sending U.S. ground troops to Kosovo as part of a
NATO-led force. He emphasized that he would do so only if a
political settlement was reached _ and Clinton said that was a
``big `if.'''
</P>
<P>
   A fairly big stumbling block to productive talks here appeared
obvious from the outset. The Serbian delegation includes Nikola
Sainovic and Vladen Kutlesic, both Yugoslav deputy prime ministers.
But like Markovic, they have little power. They are essentially
factotums of Milosevic, who according to Western diplomats will
have to be consulted by his three men at every step of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the talks were to start, NATO's European commander,
Gen. Wesley Clark, sounded a note of caution, suggesting that
neither the Serbs nor the Albanians _ whose delegation represents
the very disparate views of Kosovo's majority population _ really
have their minds fixed on success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned that the conflict parties are prepared
for a failure of the peace talks,'' he told Deutschland Radio
Berlin in Germany. ``With every battle the conflict becomes more
and more difficult to handle. Therefore we hope and will do all we
can to ensure the conflict parties reach a successful agreement,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore the gravity and ferocity of the Kosovo conflict,
Human Rights Watch, a New York-based group, released a report here
Saturday, detailing some of the main atrocities in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The report, based heavily on witness accounts, focuses on a
massacre in Obrinje on Sept. 26, when 21 members of the Delijaj
family were killed by Serb forces. It also gives details of a
summary execution on the same day of 13 ethnic Albanian men and of
a massacre last month of 45 civilians in the village of Racak.
</P>
<P>
   The conference comes almost a year since the outbreak of
fighting between the Kosovo Liberation Army and the much stronger
forces of the Serbian police and the Yugoslav army.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting has been marked by guerrilla tactics of ambush by
the ethnic Albanians and by tank and artillery attacks by the Serbs
against village farmers, whose compounds the Serbs see as potential
guerrilla bases.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre in Racak last month convinced the Clinton
administration that the Kosovo conflict was not likely to go away
and had the potential of marring the 50th anniversary celebration
of NATO in Washington in April.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire arranged last October by the U.S. envoy, Richard
Holbrooke, evaporated last month as more Serbian troops returned to
Kosovo to confront resolute, better-armed guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 unarmed international monitors, working under
the auspices of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe, were unable to stop the fighting, and in the case of the
Racak massacre were prevented from entering the village when the
killings were under way.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing that NATO's credibility was on the line, the Clinton
administration decided to push for a negotiated settlement that
would have as its basis the same sort of autonomy that Milosevic
stripped from Kosovo 10 years ago. He has ruled the region with
heavy police repression ever since.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The plan under discussion at Rambouillet has been drafted in the
last three months in separate, and largely fruitless, talks with
the Serbs and the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Hill, the main U.S. envoy to the talks, told
reporters on Friday that neither side likes the plan. It denies the
Albanians the independence they crave, while for the Serbs it gives
away too much _ in particular by requiring them to withdraw almost
all security forces.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States, the four European countries and Russia _
which make up the so-called Contact Group formed to solve the
problems arising from the breakup of former Yugoslavia _ have made
clear that this is largely a non-negotiable plan.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials openly talk of imposing a settlement
on the two sides, an unusual negotiating tactic in the world of
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sign on the dotted line'' is the message, a U.S. official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially the plan makes Kosovo, a pocket of European
countryside about the size of Connecticut with steep mountains and
fertile land, an international protectorate for three years. During
that time, elections and the makings of self-government are
envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Kosovo would be called on to form their own
police, courts and other institutions so that the ethnic Albanians
can take control of those spheres. Serbian authorities would retain
the power to make foreign, economic and defense policies.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign negotiators are likely to oppose an Albanian desire
to hold a referendum on independence at the end of those three
years. An independent Kosovo would challenge the sanctity of
borders in the Balkans _ in particular complicating the situation
in Bosnia, whose Serbs control almost half the country and still
seek union with neighboring Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators' plan implies that the Serbs would use the
three-year interim period to show that political and economic
reform in Serbia, one of two remaining republics in Yugoslavia
along with Montenegro, was sufficiently advanced to make it
feasible for Kosovo to remain within Yugoslavia. This proposition,
Western diplomats acknowledge, is difficult to imagine if Milosevic
remains in power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
