<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
 
 (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl)  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Budget Fight Opens in Washington
</P>
<P>
   The scramble has begun for trillions of dollars in surplus
federal revenues. President Clinton proposed a $1.77 trillion
budget for the year 2000 jammed full of tax breaks and new spending
_ for families with children and for schools, the elderly and
disabled, the environment and scientific research.
</P>
<P>
   But he warned Congress again not to lay a finger on the $117
billion budget surplus for that year and the more than $2.4
trillion in surpluses he projects for the next 10 years. Clinton
insists the money should be held in reserve until a plan is
completed to insure the long-term solvency of Social Security and
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress have other plans _ a big
across-the-board tax cut. But they can't agree on the structure and
size of the cut.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN M. BRODER
</P>
<P>
   Admirers of a Pristine Past Score Twice in the Rockies
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration proposed to put 429,000 acres of
Montana off limits to mining in an effort to protect the
spectacular vistas that first greeted Lewis and Clark as they
approached the Rocky Mountains .
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., approved, but his colleague, Sen.
Conrad Burns, R-Mont., said the administration was showing ``a
Washington-knows-best attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the land is in the Lewis and Clark National Forest, near
Glacier National Park and the Bob Marshall Wilderness. It is the
only place where grizzly bears frequently roam down from the
mountains and out onto the prairie, and it's prime habitat for elk
and other species.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the Rockies, Colorado wildlife managers released
the first of several dozen lynxes into the snowy wilderness. The
restocking program is meant to prevent their complete disappearance
from the region.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.
</P>
<P>
   In a Word, Return
</P>
<P>
   The District of Columbia's latest incident of racial tension
ended quietly when Mayor Anthony Williams asked a white aide who
had used the word ``niggardly'' in talking with a black co-worker
to return to his job.
</P>
<P>
   The aide, David Howard, resigned after reports that the
co-worker thought he had used a racial epithet, rather than a word
that is a synonym for miserly and does not derive from the slur.
After investigating, Williams found that Howard did not utter the
slur that the co-worker thought he heard. The mayor also told
Howard he had acted ``too hastily'' in accepting his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, head of the city's Office of The Public Advocate,
accepted the offer to return to city government, but said he would
prefer a new assignment. _ MICHAEL JANOFSKY
</P>
<P>
   One Less Hat for the Ring
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt surprised almost no one when
he announced he would not run for president in 2000 but would
oversee the Democrats' drive to retake the House. Friends said the
Missouri Democrat realized he had a better chance of becoming
speaker of the House than of becoming president, what with Vice
President Al Gore's grip on much of the party apparatus.
</P>
<P>
   One thing was missing from the announcement _ an endorsement of
Gore. ``I'm not there yet,'' Gephardt said later. ``These are long
and difficult contests.''
</P>
<P>
   _ KATHARINE Q. SEELYE
</P>
<P>
   A Dad Gets Equality On Diaper-Changing Rights
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton's book, ``It Takes a Village,'' described
the plight of Kevin Knussman, a Maryland state trooper who, because
he was a male, was denied paternity leave to care for his newborn
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes, what it takes is a lawsuit: On Tuesday, in the
first sex-discrimination case under the federal Family and Medical
Leave Act, a federal jury in Baltimore awarded Knussman $375,000 in
emotional damages. The American Civil Liberties Union, which
represented the trooper Knussman, said the case established that
fathers have the same right to care for babies as mothers.
</P>
<P>
   _ TAMAR LEWIN
</P>
<P>
   A Rare Liver Disease Hits a Football Icon
</P>
<P>
   Walter Payton played 13 years for the Chicago Bears, leading
them to the 1986 Super Bowl championship and breaking Jim Brown's
record for rushing yardage; his career mark of 16,726 yards gained
still stands.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. Now, at 44, Payton finds himself struck by a rare
liver disease that requires a transplant within two years. Payton,
thin and appearing tired, made his condition known at an emotional
news conference at which he asked friends and fans to pray for him.
</P>
<P>
   He also declared, ``I survived a lot of hits playing football,
and this is just something else that I'm going to have to
overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   AIDS Virus Traced to Chimps
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the AIDS epidemic was discovered in 1981, many have
wondered: Where did the AIDS virus come from? Virus detectives say
they have an answer: an endangered subspecies of chimpanzees. Using
genetic and molecular tests, an international team of scientists
said they had traced the origin of HIV-1, the virus that has caused
most of the 30 million AIDS infections in the world, to Pan
troglodytes troglodytes, chimpanzees that live in west and central
Africa. Because these chimpanzees apparently can live with the
virus without falling ill, a hope is to use the discovery to
eventually improve therapies and develop an effective vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN
</P>
<P>
   Money or Power Required. Skis Welcome Too.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel rooms veer from spartan to luxurious, and suites are
said to be in short supply. The rattling railway through the Alps
takes hours to get there. A snowstorm grounded the helicopters of
the wealthy and turned the road snaking up from the valley into a
white-out.
</P>
<P>
   Yet billionaires and presidents attending the privately funded
World Economic Forum in the Swiss ski resort of Davos proved once
again that the gathering, which has no official status, seems
irresistible to the world's elite.
</P>
<P>
   For six days, the big stars of policy, high finance and high
visibility _ from Nelson Mandela to George Soros and Yasser Arafat,
from Al Gore to Kofi Annan and Jane Fonda _ clustered in a concrete
conference center that someone nicknamed ``the bunker'' to debate
topics ranging from executive health to the maladies of the global
economy (the dominant theme).
</P>
<P>
   The forum reaches no binding decisions. But, for participants,
it is supposed to nurture networking and brainstorming among
government leaders and corporate barons, even as it provides a
platform for sonorous pronouncements and encourages debate on
weighty issues. And, of course, for those with energy left over,
Davos is ringed by crystalline ski-slopes that, last week, were in
perfect condition.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALAN COWELL
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
