perfect condition.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALAN COWELL
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Deal for Holbrooke?
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke has agreed to settle an ethics charge that has
stood in the way of his becoming the United States' top delegate to
the United Nations, people close to the case said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who won wide respect in 1995 for leading the talks
that ended the war in Bosnia, quit the State Department in 1996. He
then violated regulations barring contacts with his former
government colleagues by contacting the U.S. Embassy in South Korea
in his new job with an investment-banking firm, the Justice
Department maintained. Holbrooke will reportedly pay $5,000 to put
the affair behind him, while admitting no wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID STOUT
</P>
<P>
   Edison Had a Better Idea &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The routines of wintertime went on in Karaganda, Kazakhstan, as
a bold Russian plan to illuminate the remote Kazakh city at night
with beams of light from outer space turned into a disappointing
fizzle.
</P>
<P>
   Astronauts on the Russian space station Mir were to have bounced
sunlight off an 82-foot mirror in orbit and then directed the rays
toward the ground, lighting up nine cities around the globe with
beams of light a few miles wide and up to ten times brighter than
the full moon.
</P>
<P>
   But the mirror, like a balky umbrella, failed to unfurl
Thursday. On Friday, the astronauts tried again. But the mirror,
made of thin plastic with a metallic surface, once more balked and
was discarded.
</P>
<P>
   The setback can do no good for Russia's ailing space program,
which is trying to steady itself with commercial ties and grandiose
dreams. But it delighted astronomers, who say light pollution from
such mirrors could blind telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   The project's architects, the Space Regatta Consortium, said in
an open letter to astronomers that their goal was to pave the way
for space adventure as well as to serve people on Earth ``through
the hard times.'' _ WILLIAM J. BROAD
</P>
<P>
   Congress Calls In an Expert &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With impeachment dominating the news, it's not easy for Congress
to advance the premise that the rest of government is still
functioning. Which may explain why a 6-year-old was testifying
before a House subcommittee on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Anderson Jr. of Brooklyn won't turn 65 until 2057, but
his appearance was intended to dramatize the debate over how best
to shore up Social Security to meet the demands of retiring baby
boomers and future generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to retire, you must save and invest,'' Richard
advised. ``If you don't you might have to work all your life. No
one wants to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Clay Shaw, R-Fla, chairman of the subcommittee, said
Richard was the youngest person to testify before Congress. Last
year, he was described as the youngest to ring the opening bell at
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Richard, who lives with his mother in the Crown Heights section,
said he learned about finance the hard way: As a punishment for bad
behavior, his father, a financial planner, would make him watch
CNBC, the all-news cable channel.
</P>
</TEXT>
