<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Feb. 7, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled for the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-HISTORY-REVIEW (Undated) _ The ruling dynasty of the
Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan stretches back through the mists of
time to ... May 25, 1946. Of all the artificial Middle Eastern
countries arbitrarily created by the Western powers after World War
I, none was more artificial than the tiny, poor, lawless leftover
patch of desert that would become Jordan. By John Kifner. (`i'
category). WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   DRAFT-REVIVAL-REVIEW (Washington) _ A quarter century after the
last conscripts mustered at boot camp, the idea of reviving the
draft has gained new currency among a small lot of academics,
lawmakers and, even, military commanders. They argue that a
restoration of the draft _ perhaps as part of some compulsory
national service _ would not only answer the personnel crises
facing today's volunteer forces but also provide a much-needed
curative to the military's growing detachment from society. By
Steven Lee Myers. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Inside the section, moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   EX-SPIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Hundreds of former CIA and KGB
agents are working together as business partners to provide
sensitive information to American corporations. These out-of-work
spies from the U.S. and Russia are joining hands in the pursuit of
capitalism, providing protection, intelligence and political risk
assessments to U.S. companies extending their reach to emerging
markets and other global hot spots. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-LENDING-REVIEW (Undated) _ Ever since the global
financial crisis began in East Asia 19 months ago, the public
debate has focused on how to keep poor countries from borrowing too
much money. Now, though, economists and policy-makers have been
struck by a new insight: whenever somebody is borrowing too much,
somebody else is lending too much. So begins a new debate about how
best to restrain the lenders who got the countries into trouble in
the first place. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inside the section, moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Monica Lewinsky is not the first
bright-eyed intern dealt a rude awakening by the realities of
office sex, intrigue, power politics or just plain bad workplace
behavior. A look at the experiences of journalism students sent as
interns into the world of newspapers, TV and radio.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ENGLAND-REVIEW (London) _ In 1386, Michael de la Pole,
Earl of Suffolk, became the first person in history to be
impeached. His case also marked the first appearance of the phrase
`high crimes and misdemeanors.' And there began a long and tangled
process of legal challenge to executive authority by a legislative
body that, somewhat circuitously, brought Bill Clinton to trial in
the U.S. Senate. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-DEPRESSION-REVIEW (New York) _ Depression and
manic-depression, with its wild mood swings, are becoming
recognized as a significant cause of homelessness. Shelters have
long been filled with schizophrenics, people whose hallucinations
and delusions force them out of jobs, homes and relationships. But
the link between depression and homelessness is only now becoming
clear. By Lynette Holloway.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-STOCKS-REVIEW (Washington) _ What would happen if the
government were investing hundreds of billions of dollars of Social
Security reserves in the stock market, and congressional
anti-abortion forces decided that none of this money should be put
into companies that make or import abortion pills? That is the kind
of nightmare foreseen by economists and politicians who oppose
President Clinton's plan to beef up Social Security reserves by
investing some of the money in stocks. Political tampering, Alan
Greenspan said, could endanger `the efficiency of our capital
markets and thus our economy.' By David E. Rosenbaum. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-REDISTRICT-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at the political
implications of dueling census methods. The Supreme Court ruled out
using a method of counting called statistical sampling in doling
out the 435 House seats among the states in 2001. This kind of
sampling, which is used by pollsters and advocated by the Clinton
administration, would help account for the disproportionately large
number of blacks, Hispanics, immigrants, poor people and city
dwellers who have been overlooked by census-takers. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   TIGER-TROUBLE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Here's the high-concept movie
pitch: Escaped Man-Eating Tiger Terrorizes Smalltown U.S.A. Drama
abounds in heart-pounding tale of a suburb suddenly forced to
resolve cultural conflicts in face of primordial threat: a
marauding (actually, it was wandering, but let's invoke dramatic
license) tiger. It's a true story, one that began spinning out late
last month amid the dizzying glare of the New York media. By Joe
Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week. &QL;
</P>
