<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4420 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-820&AMP;ADD     02-06 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PUBLIC HEARS LEWINSKY'S STORY IN VIDEO EXCERPTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: See also IMPEACH-LEADERS, IMPEACH-ROGAN, IMPEACH-SKETCH,
IMPEACH-CAMPAIGN) 
(jw) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the end of President Clinton's impeachment
trial in sight, House prosecutors Saturday showed the Senate
videotaped excerpts from the sworn depositions of Monica Lewinsky
and two other witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time the public had a chance to see Ms.
Lewinsky, 25, speak since her affair with Clinton became known a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Because the transcripts of the depositions had already been
published, no new evidence was presented Saturday. But the
prosecutors clearly hoped that the senators and the public would be
struck by Ms. Lewinsky's youth and vulnerability and that this
impression would work to Clinton's disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   In that vein, Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., the lead-off
prosecutor, said the videotapes showed ``the image of a young
woman, very much like a family member we might know.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogan maintained, ``If her testimony is truthful, then the
president committed the offenses alleged in the articles of
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, in a dark dress with a string of pearls, came
across as a practiced witness, composed with a strong voice. She
often brushed a strand of hair away from her left eye.
</P>
<P>
   Her testimony was familiar. She never varied from her statements
to the federal grand jury about her intimate relationship with
Clinton. And she testified that the president's secretary, Betty
Currie, had approached her to retrieve gifts from the president.
</P>
<P>
   This is a point in dispute that bears on the charge that the
president tried to obstruct justice by hiding the gifts. Mrs.
Currie told the grand jury that Ms. Lewinsky had initiated the
discussions about the presents.
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecutors decided not to call Mrs. Currie to
testify, in part because the Senate limited the prosecutors to
three witnesses and in part because they thought Mrs. Currie's
testimony would not help their case against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan insisted that the prosecutors were not interested in the
president's sexual indiscretion. He declared: ``Throughout all of
this, throughout this presentation, it is important to keep in mind
that we seek no congressional punishment for a man who chose to
cheat on his wife. However, we have a legal obligation to expect
constitutional accountability for a president who chooses to cheat
the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Ms. Lewinsky, excerpts were shown from depositions of
Vernon Jordan, the president's confidant, and Sidney Blumenthal, a
White House assistant.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors mixed and matched excerpts from the three
witnesses to provide a narrative for the case they were building
against Clinton. Rogan called it ``a web of perjury and obstruction
of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan spoke about his efforts to obtain a job for Ms. Lewinsky,
and Blumenthal told of how the president had described Ms. Lewinsky
as a stalker whose sexual advances he had rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said that there was no question in his mind but that he
was acting on behalf of the president when he tried to find a job
for Ms. Lewinsky and that Clinton showed considerable interest in
the matter. But Jordan stressed that he had not been told that Ms.
Lewinsky had been called as a witness in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment suit against the president.
</P>
<P>
   In his grand jury testimony in August, Clinton said he had only
a minimal role in soliciting Jordan's job-search efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors argued that these were elements of Clinton's
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's session, ending the fifth week of the trial, was the
last in the evidentiary stage. Next week, the Senate will hear
closing arguments by the House prosecutors and the president's
lawyers and will then begin deliberating on the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Separate votes on each of the two articles of impeachment _ on
perjury and obstruction of justice _ are expected by the end of the
week. It would require a two-thirds majority to convict the
president and remove him from office. Senators from both parties
agree that acquittal is a foregone conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Senate rules, which were written for the impeachment
trial of President Andrew Johnson in 1868, the deliberations on the
verdict must be in closed session, with no senator permitted to
speak for more than 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan movement is under way to have the debate next week
in public and on television, but it was unclear Saturday whether
the two-thirds majority needed to change the rules could be
mustered. Some senators who want an open debate said they might
reduce the time limit for senators' speeches.
</P>
<P>
   The deposition of Ms. Lewinsky was taken on Monday in the
presidential suite of the Mayflower Hotel here. Jordan and
Blumenthal were questioned on Tuesday and Wednesday, respectively,
in a soundproof hearing room on the fourth floor of the Capitol.
Transcripts of the depositions were published on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The use of videotaped excerpts Saturday was the result of a
compromise.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The House prosecutors, who initially hoped to call more
witnesses, wanted to interrogate Ms. Lewinsky, Jordan and
Blumenthal in person in the well of the Senate. Many Republican
senators supported them.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats did not want the witnesses' testimony to be
presented at all. If videotapes were shown, the Democrats argued,
they should be shown in full.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Senate voted, 70-30, not to have witnesses
testify in person. Then, the Senate voted, 62-38, to permit parts
of the depositions to be presented on videotape. Before the
impeachment trial, videotapes had never been shown on the floor of
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes Saturday, senators continued to discuss
whether and how to censure Clinton for his misconduct. Many
Democrats, though certainly not all of them, favor a formal
condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   This would be a way for them to show their constituents that
while they did not believe that Clinton's actions warranted his
removal from office, they deplored his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are divided. While some favor censure, many others
see such a move as a way to let Democrats off the political hook.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans abandoned an earlier plan to condemn Clinton
with a ``findings of fact'' resolution within the impeachment
process. Almost all Democrats objected to this procedure, and
without Democratic support, Republicans decided not to push the
matter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the outset of Saturday's session, the Senate chaplain, Lloyd
Ogilvie, offered a prayer for Scott Bates, the Senate's legislative
clerk, who was killed Friday night when he was struck by a car
while he was crossing a highway in Arlington, Va. Sen. Trent Lott
of Mississippi, the Republican leader, and Sen. Tom Daschle of
South Dakota, the Democratic leader, gave brief tributes.
</P>
<P>
   In his job, Bates sat beneath the presiding officer in the
Senate chamber and often read documents aloud and called the roll
of senators during votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
