<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-PRINCE-NYT     02-06 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-PRINCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JORDANIAN LEADER'S FIRST TEST LIES IN INTERNAL POLITICS
</HEADLINE>
 (See also JORDAN-HUSSEIN, JORDAN-CANCER, JORDAN-HISTORY-REVIEW) 
(bl) 
By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ As Crown Prince Abdullah formally took charge of
Jordan's government Saturday, experienced observers here said that
internal political challenges _ rather than foreign-affairs crises
_ are likely to present the new leader with his first tests.
</P>
<P>
   Ratified by the Jordanian Cabinet on Saturday as the regent, or
acting monarch, the 37-year-old crown prince now has the
constitutional power to appoint Cabinet ministers, call elections,
and command the army, in which he has spent most of his adult life.
</P>
<P>
   While few analysts here anticipate major political crises in the
first months of the crown prince's rule, they say he will still
have to move in short order to replace at least a few members of
the current Cabinet, including the unpopular prime minister, Fayez
Tarawneh, the 55th of King Hussein's parade of politically weak
Cabinet chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Abdullah voiced his own desire for
what he called ``comprehensive changes,'' including new free-market
reforms and further _ albeit gradual and guided _ democratization.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the first direct challenge to the new ruler, the
opposition Muslim Brotherhood party last week asked to meet with
the crown prince to present its demands for the dissolution of
Parliament and new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Complaining of state media strictures and alleged threats
against its candidates, the Islamist party boycotted the last
general election in 1997, leaving the Parliament with almost no
opposition representation.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslim Brotherhood's unyielding opposition to Jordanian
peace agreements with Israel is only one point of contention. The
party is also a fierce populist defender of subsidies on staple
foods. These subsidies were recently eliminated by the financially
pressed government, setting off riots last year.
</P>
<P>
   Officials who know Abdullah expect him to agree to a request for
a dialogue with the Islamist opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``His style is to pursue a policy of inclusion rather than a
policy of exclusion,'' said Rima Khalaf, a former planning minister
who worked closely with the crown prince on several projects in the
past. ``That should determine the way he deals with the Muslim
Brotherhood and other so-called opposition groups. He is a unifier
by nature.''
</P>
<P>
   But to accede to the Muslim Brotherhood demand for a dissolution
of Parliament could be a risk not worth taking until Abdullah has
consolidated his own hold on power. The current Parliament will
adjourn in March, and, as is customary in Jordan, is not scheduled
to reconvene until October. ``That could buy Abdullah some time,''
said one politician, who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah is universally expected to adhere scrupulously to
constitutional procedures for any government personnel changes.
``The Constitution has been respected all through this ordeal, as
you are all aware,'' said Information Minister Nasser Judeh on
Saturday morning in a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a country of solid institutions,'' Judeh said. ``This
is a country of continuity.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even if broad policies and institutions are unlikely to
change, there is general agreement that the new government cannot
simply continue with the current cast of political characters.
``The real question is when,'' said one former top official.
</P>
<P>
   The most sensitive immediate issue is the fate of senior
officials who owe their positions to Abdullah's uncle, Prince
Hassan, who served as crown prince for 34 years and has especially
great influence in the critical foreign and finance ministries.
</P>
<P>
   If the new ruler is seen to be moving too quickly to replace
Hassan loyalists it could be viewed as an unseemly vendetta. Yet a
failure to install some of his own appointees might be
misinterpreted as a sign of weakness, hampering Abdullah's ability
to rule, political observers said.
</P>
<P>
   The best early indicator of how the crown prince intends to
handle this dilemma may be Judeh himself, the son-in-law of Prince
Hassan. Judeh has been severely criticized for the paucity of state
media coverage of the King's health and plans for the succession.
Most Amman professionals say they have been following the events on
foreign radio and cable television.
</P>
<P>
   Critics saw Judeh's press conference Saturday as the most recent
case in point.
</P>
<P>
   After summoning hundreds of foreign and Jordanian reporters to
what was billed as the first public briefing on the king's health
by the king's doctor, Judeh read a brief official opening
statement, declined to answer questions about the king on the
grounds that the physician would be better equipped to respond.
</P>
<P>
   The information minister then departed, leaving an assistant to
explain to reporters that the doctor would not address the
reporters after all, but a bulletin would be distributed instead.
Hours later, the bulletin had not appeared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4452 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRESERVING-DOCUMENTS-     02-06 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESERVING-DOCUMENTS-775(2TAKES)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FRAMERS OF THE NATION'S CONSTITUTION WORK TO PRESERVE A
HERITAGE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The framers of the Declaration of Independence, in
keeping with the practice of the day, wrote the formal document on
parchment rather than paper so that it would last longer. But
surely few thought that the text they wrote would survive for more
than two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Today, another group of framers confronts the precious
documents. They are scientists, engineers, designers and
archivists, and they will soon begin constructing new encasements
and frames to protect the texts on which the nation is based.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the National Archives and Records Administration is
expected to unveil the design of the new enclosures, airtight cells
of titanium and aluminum that will hold the documents behind
tempered glass in an atmosphere of inert argon gas. The
encasements, resembling large, deep picture frames, will replace
similar enclosures that were made almost 50 years ago and appear to
be prematurely deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
   The integrity of the protective cases is significant because
they hold the foundation documents of the country, known as the
Charters of Freedom. These are the original, parchment sheets on
which are written the Declaration of Independence, the U.S.
Constitution and its first 10 amendments, known as the Bill of
Rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Charters, as they are called, have made the National
Archives building one of Washington's most popular tourist
attractions. Each year, more than 1.2 million visitors wait in long
lines to file solemnly by the documents displayed in the building's
rotunda.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for new encasements arose four years ago when
conservators noticed subtle changes within the sealed,
bronze-framed glass enclosures that have held the documents since
1952. Their observations confirmed hints, first noticed in a 1988
examination, of possible changes that could affect the parchment
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Inspections of the Bill of Rights under special lights showed a
haziness in areas where the parchment made contact with an inner
pane of glass in the case. By 1995, the hazy areas, possible
evidence of unwanted chemical reactions, were becoming more
pronounced. Similar, but less noticeable, changes were detected on
the Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, conservators found tiny white flakes in the
enclosures, believed to be salts coming out of the glass because of
higher than expected humidity in the enclosures.
</P>
<P>
   Norvell M. Jones, chief of the Archives Document Conservation
Branch, said a committee of outside advisers to the agency
concluded that there was no immediate danger to the documents, but
recommended that planning begin for new encasements. ``When we
discovered that the charters had to be re-encased, we saw it as an
opportunity to plan for some other things that needed to be done
with the documents,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The display area in the rotunda of the Archives building is
designed for only four of the seven pages of Charter documents to
be shown at a time, Jones said, with the Declaration of
Independence, the Bill of Rights and the first and last pages of
the Constitution usually on view. The transmittal page to the
Constitution and two middle pages are rarely seen, she said, but
the new plans call for all of them to be encased and displayed.
</P>
<P>
   Archive officials and conservationists also are concerned about
the daily movement of the display pages to and from their bombproof
vault below the rotunda, a source of vibrations that eventually
could deteriorate the parchment sheets and the brittle ink on their
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Planning has begun to redesign the display area to make it more
accessible to the disabled, to exhibit all of the Charter pages at
once, and to secure the documents in an off-hours protective area
that reduces their daily movement.
</P>
<P>
   But designs for the new encasements must be completed before
renovations can be planned around them, officials said. The
encasement project gained momentum when it drew the attention of
the Clinton administration's millennium project, an effort headed
by Hillary Rodham Clinton to save the nation's historic treasures
by the turn of the century. The Pew Charitable Trusts, a foundation
in Philadelphia, donated $800,000 last year to pay for designing
and testing new enclosures.
</P>
<P>
   The Archives selected Heery International, an engineering and
architectural firm, as prime contractor for designing the
encasements and turned to the National Institute of Standards and
Technology, known as NIST, to test and manufacture them. NIST, part
of the Commerce Department, is the former National Bureau of
Standards, the agency that built the original Charter enclosures
five decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Richard Judson, an engineer who is the Archives' project manager
for the encasements, said the existing cases were state of the art
for 1950s technology and appear to have worked fairly well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very nicely done and appear to have maintained most
of their integrity,'' he said. ``But looking back with 50 years of
hindsight, our approach today is somewhat different.''
</P>
<P>
   The older cases consist of a sandwich of three panes of glass.
There is a pane on the bottom, topped by a sheet of pure
cellulose-backing paper on which the document rests, and a thin
glass cover resting atop the parchment to hold it flat. This is
followed by an empty space and a top sheet of glass.
</P>
<P>
   Having a glass sheet touching the parchment itself is the
biggest problem with the old case, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the enclosure was sealed, air was pumped out and it was
filled with pure helium and enough water vapor to produce a
relative humidity inside of 25 to 35 percent. An inert gas is used
in such encasements to purge its atmosphere of oxygen, which
encourages chemical reactions, and impurities.
</P>
<P>
   Parchment, which is stretched and cured animal skin treated to
remove acidity, requires some moisture to keep it from becoming
brittle. Too much water, however, can cause this durable material
to swell and contract and can promote the growth of organisms.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists suspect that more moisture may have been sealed
into the original enclosures than intended, perhaps from the newly
made cellulose-backing paper. Relative humidities above 40 percent
can encourage salt crystals to leach out of older glass, a possible
source of some of the deterioration seen in the old enclosures,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   The Archives established more than 20 criteria for the new
encasements, including high visibility for the documents, weight
limits to allow lifting by two people, the ability to open and
reseal the cases, and a pleasing, dignified appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Norbert S. Baer, a professor of conservation at New York
University and chairman of the committee of outside experts that
advises the Archives, said the new design reflects a philosophical
change from the 1950s. The old enclosures were not designed to be
reopened, he said, and experts then expressed confidence that their
technology would protect the documents for 100 years or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we know more, but have a greater sense of the limits of
technology,'' Baer said. ``Now you recognize that things can go
wrong you haven't anticipated, and you allow for getting into the
enclosure without destroying it if something troubling occurs.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Engineers have settled on a design that starts with a solid
metal base made of aluminum or titanium, with sections milled out
of the bottom to reduce weight, giving the base a waffle
appearance. A final decision on which metal to use has yet to be
made.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the well of this base sits a thin, perforated aluminum
document platform that stands about an inch high on three posts.
This platform is detachable so that it and the attached document
can be removed from the enclosure if it is disassembled.
</P>
<P>
   The document is to rest on a piece of pure cellulose paper, and
both will be affixed to the platform with thin, clear polyester
film clips that exert almost no pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Covering the enclosure and sitting atop the base is a two-layer
sheet of tempered glass bonded with a layer of plastic to resist
shattering.
</P>
<P>
   The enclosure is secured with a titanium metal frame that clamps
the glass against the seal ring when 80 bolts are screwed through
the base into the frame and tightened.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie E. Smith, a chemist who directs materials science work at
NIST, the standards institute, said argon will be used instead of
helium in the enclosure because it is easier to handle and has a
bigger molecule, which is less likely to diffuse out of the
enclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Relative humidity in the new cases will be kept at 40 percent,
slightly higher than planned for the old enclosures, because that
more closely matches conditions outside the cases if they have to
be opened, he said. This helps prevent shock to the document under
these circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The institute's engineers, led by Richard Rhorer and Christopher
Evans, have built a manufacturing model of the casement for testing
in the spring before making a prototype.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers are also sending samples of titanium, which has a gray
finish, to metal-coating companies to see if the tough metal can be
given the bronze color desired for the frame. Rhorer said it was
unclear whether anodization, an electrolytic process that can put a
colored, oxide film on metal, will be able to produce the color and
tone that designers want.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows how many interests are involved in this project,''
he said. ``We normally don't have to be concerned if the color of a
metal is `warm' enough and such things.''
</P>
<P>
   The standards institute is to make nine new encasements, seven
to house the documents and two backups. Two of the cases will be
slightly larger than the others, measuring 39\ inches tall, 37~
inches wide and 3 1/6 inches deep, because the Bill of Rights is
larger than the other documents. The other cases will be the same
height and depth but 33| inches wide.
</P>
<P>
   After testing, the prototype, containing the transmittal page of
the Constitution, will be unveiled in the summer of 2000. The
permanent encasements, containing the seven Charter documents, are
expected to go on display in 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
