<HEADER>
A4473 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LEADERS-ART-7     02-06 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEADERS-ART-720(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE LEADERS FORGE NEW TIES IN TRIAL'S FIRES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Vt., S.D., Miss., Maine, Ga., La., Mo., Ky., Kan.,
Nev.)  (Eds: See also IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-ROGAN, IMPEACH-SKETCH,
IMPEACH-CAMPAIGN) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., remembered the way the
two leaders, seated side by side, leaned in close to each other
during the bipartisan caucus in the old Senate chamber last month.
They were ``whispering and giggling,'' Gorton said, like the
fastest of friends.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., recalled the many occasions over the
last few weeks that a meeting with one of the leaders was
interrupted by an impromptu telephone call to or from the other.
``Both senators like each other,'' Leahy said, citing that as one
reason that ``the Senate didn't spin out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances did not always promote it. The odds were often
against it. But amid the partisan fires of the impeachment and
trial of President Clinton, the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott
of Mississippi, and the minority leader, Tom Daschle of South
Dakota, managed to forge a better relationship than they had ever
had before.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews this week, fellow senators, aides to Lott and
Daschle and the two leaders themselves said that it was an
assiduous effort, an attempt to fashion an amulet against a
protracted, rancorous proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Although it failed on numerous occasions, as deals collapsed and
votes split along strictly partisan lines, senators said the amity
achieved by Lott and Daschle was perhaps the main reason the trial
could end within the next week. They said that the leaders' example
also boded well for the legislative session to come, providing a
beacon of bipartisan harmony in a Congress starved for it in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daschle and Lott speak more in one day than Gephardt and
Gingrich spoke in one year,'' said Sen. John Breaux, D-La.,
referring to Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., the House minority
leader, and Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., whose nearly four-year tenure as
speaker of the House ended with his resignation in November.
</P>
<P>
   Lott and Daschle talk in person, dropping into each other's
office without invitation or hesitation. They talk in the chamber,
rushing into private huddles when tempers flare across the aisle.
They talk on the phone, ringing each other at home or using a
special line reserved for calls between their Capitol offices.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said that on perhaps their most grueling and
disappointing day, when Democrats and Republicans failed to
negotiate an agreement on a bipartisan plan for proceeding or
bypassing the depositions of three witnesses, Lott actually found a
way to reach Daschle in the middle of a Democratic caucus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me on my cell phone just to tell me he couldn't do
it,'' Daschle said, referring to Lott's attempt to fashion some
consensus between the parties. Daschle added that he considered
that heads-up not only a crucial courtesy but also ``a pretty good
illustration of how we manage to get along despite all of this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fond of him,'' Daschle said in an interview this week. ``I
think he's been upfront and fair with me, even when he hasn't been
able to produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott praised Daschle in similar terms. ``We've had a good
relationship, one where we've been honest with each other,'' Lott
said in an interview Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you go through a crucible like this, whether it's
boot camp or pledge week or freshman year, you get closer,'' Lott
said. ``In an odd way, I think the entire Senate, Republicans and
Democrats, may have a better understanding of each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators from both parties said that the leaders had indeed
benefited from being thrown together, for days on end, with a
strong motivation to talk to each other and try to find common
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it eluded them as often as not, senators predicted
that the leaders and other members of the Senate would emerge from
the trial with a greater sensitivity toward each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just Trent and Tom,'' said Sen. Mitch McConnell,
R-Ky., ``Oddly enough, though we've had a lot of partisan votes,
it's been a bonding experience.''
</P>
<P>
   In the cases of Lott and Daschle, senators said, it was also an
experience that both leaders knew would define their political
careers _ and their political legacies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both realized that there would never be a test of their
leadership, in their whole career, that would begin to match, in
its stakes, the impeachment trial of a president,'' Leahy said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, agreed. ``I think they realized
that communication between them would be an essential ingredient in
maintaining the integrity of the process,'' Ms. Snowe said.
</P>
<P>
   They put a high price on politesse, as well. On more than one
occasion, Lott and Daschle gave joint interviews, yielding the
microphone back and forth to each other in a chivalrous
news-conference equivalent of ``After you, my dear Alphonse.''
</P>
<P>
   When they spoke separately, expressing Republican and Democratic
positions at odds with each other, they often granted each other
personal amnesty, insisting that there had been earnest stabs at a
compromise, genuine bids for conciliation.
</P>
<P>
   It was a striking departure from the past. Leahy said that as
recently as a year ago, some of the sniping between Lott and
Daschle was so intense that he pulled them both aside.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and political officials who are close to Lott and
Daschle said that a particular source of friction was Daschle's
belief that Lott sometimes promised more than he could deliver,
getting too far in front of a sprawling, brawling Republican caucus
that he could not always control.
</P>
<P>
   But Daschle said that during the trial, he felt sympathy for the
challenges Lott faced in dealing with the more conservative members
of his conference. Daschle added that if it had been up to Lott
alone, bipartisan resolutions might have been possible from the
very beginning of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a very difficult set of circumstances,'' Daschle
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders do not socialize away from the Capitol and are
in many ways different. Lott, once the head cheerleader at the
University of Mississippi, is more of a performer; Daschle, a
former Air Force intelligence officer, is introverted to the point
of sometimes appearing meek.
</P>
<P>
   But they both come from similar middle-class backgrounds,
graduated to the Senate from the House and are relatively close in
age. Lott is 57. Daschle is 51.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Bob Dole, Lott's predecessor as majority leader, is
more than 20 years older than Daschle, and several senators said
that Dole seldom struck up casual, unplanned conversations with
Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., the minority whip, said Lott and
Daschle had ``a much closer relationship, in terms of how they
talk; they talk at least three times a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said: ``One of the things that has happened between Tom and
me, and it's affected the Senate a little bit, is that we are a
different generation, a younger generation. We have a little
different style.''
</P>
<P>
   One Democratic aide remembered a day during the impeachment
trial when Daschle was holding a meeting with a half-dozen other
Democratic senators in a conference room and Lott popped into
Daschle's outer office unannounced.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle, unperturbed, left the meeting for a few minutes to talk
to him and then brought Lott back into the conference room with him
to chat briefly with the other senators, the aide said. When Lott
left, the aide said, he warmly promised not to make an announcement
about an unspecified development until Daschle said it was all
right.
</P>
<P>
   With the Republicans bucking public sentiment by even holding a
trial, Lott clearly appreciates his investment in keeping it civil,
and he has repeatedly tried to placate Daschle, even when
Republicans were marching in a direction that displeased Democrats,
which was much of the time.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening when Republicans voted to depose three witnesses,
Lott added language to the motion that conditionally gave veto
power to Daschle over the depositions of any additional witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Adhering to the unwritten rules of their apparent pact of mutual
nonaggression, Daschle later spared Lott the wrath he expressed at
the Republican course in general.
</P>
<P>
   Facing television cameras after the vote, he even went so far as
to thank Lott. ``I appreciate very much Sen. Lott's willingness to
consider many of the concerns we had,'' Daschle said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
