<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4488 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCSEC-DEBATE-ART-2TA     02-06 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-DEBATE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY BOOMERS TRUST WALL ST. MORE THAN U.S. GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ga.)   (See also SOCSEC-STOCKS-REVIEW) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For their parents and grandparents, who watched stocks
crash and banks fail, the government was considered the salvation
of a generation that had been betrayed by the financial markets.
But for today's aging baby boomers, who face increasing concerns
about the solvency of Social Security and other federal retirement
programs, it is now the government that cannot be trusted and a
bullish Wall Street that provides some hope.
</P>
<P>
   That dynamic, detected in public-opinion polls and a score of
recent interviews with baby boomers on Atlanta's streets, may
become a critical component of the debate over the future of Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   As the 76.5 million Americans born from 1946 to 1964 move toward
retirement, they are decidedly skeptical about the capacity of the
government to uphold its end of the Social Security bargain, the
polls and interviews suggest. And the same cynicism about the
government also makes many question the wisdom of President
Clinton's recent proposal to save Social Security from bankruptcy
by having the government invest hundreds of billions of dollars in
the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   It is not that they distrust the stock market's ability to yield
greater returns than the low-interest bonds that have long been the
government's investment of choice for the Social Security trust
fund. It is that they distrust the government's ability to invest
the money prudently and without political influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see the federal government being that big a player in
the stock market,'' said Kevin Green, a 36-year-old lawyer who was
taking a break in a downtown park. ``And I can't see that much
money being independently invested without the various interest
groups having some significant say about how it's invested.''
</P>
<P>
   George Watson, a 51-year-old federal court worker, said he had
only ``50-50'' confidence that the money he had paid in Social
Security taxes would come back to him as promised retirement
benefits. And he acknowledged that investing a share of Social
Security reserves in the stock market could provide some
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the question for me,'' Watson said, ``is who chooses what
stocks. With all the scandals and fiddling around in Washington, I
think that's something that would have to be watched. I don't know
if I trust those people.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those interviewed by pollsters said they preferred a
Republican plan that would allow individuals to invest part of
their Social Security taxes in stock funds they chose.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Republican plan say they fear that it would
exacerbate financial inequity among Americans, with those who
understand the stock market benefiting far more than those who do
not. But the plan's admirers say that they like it because, unlike
the Clinton proposal, it would be founded on self-reliance rather
than faith in the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust myself more than I do the government,'' said Debi
Lenox, 48, an interior designer from the south Atlanta suburb of
Peachtree City who was shopping at Lenox Square, one of Atlanta's
upscale malls. ``It's OK if you invest your own money, but playing
with other people's money isn't wise.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those interviewed acknowledged that their attitudes
toward the government and the financial markets differed markedly
from those of their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out of the Depression trusting the government,''
said Larry Britt, 47, an engineer from Oxford, Miss., who was
attending a meeting in Atlanta. ``It was all they had to fall back
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Britt's wife, Mary Ann, 47, an innkeeper, said her parents were
so distrustful of the stock market that they never would have
supported the investment of retirement money in equities,
regardless of who was doing the investing. She said they were not
concerned about the paltry rate of return on the government's
investment of Social Security taxes in bonds, which have yielded an
average of 2 percent to 2.5 percent annually since the taxes were
first collected in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   She said, ``they would have seen that two-and-a-half percent and
thought that it was fine, that it's safe, it's secure and it'll
grow at a steady rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since President Franklin D. Roosevelt signed the Social
Security Act in 1935, that slow, steady growth has been sufficient
to sustain the retirement system. But as the baby boomers mature,
and as medical advances extend life expectancy, the system's tax
receipts will no longer be able to support its obligations. The
Social Security trust fund is projected to run out of money in 2032
if changes are not made.
</P>
<P>
   An array of recent polls show that Americans steadfastly oppose
propping up the system by increasing taxes, reducing payments or
raising the retirement age. And the polls show only modest support
for measures that would burden upper-income Americans, like raising
the amount of earnings that are subject to Social Security payroll
taxes or reducing benefits for those with high retirement incomes.
That has left politicians with few alternatives beyond seeking to
increase the yield on Social Security reserves.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union address in January, Clinton proposed
earmarking more than half of the projected federal budget surpluses
_ $2.7 trillion of the $4.4 trillion surplus anticipated over the
next 15 years _ for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $2.7 trillion, he would invest about $700 billion in
stocks in an effort to capture the robust returns that have become
commonplace on Wall Street. The administration maintains that its
plan would make the Social Security system solvent until 2055.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans generally support the concept of dedicating a
significant portion of the surpluses to Social Security. But they
have expressed concern about the government playing such a heavy
role in the free enterprise system, a factor that also deeply
troubles Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. The
administration estimates that the government would come to own 4 to
5 percent of the value of all shares of publicly traded companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans propose that workers be allowed to divert a
share of their Social Security taxes into private investment
accounts, which they could manage themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That appeals to many Americans who fear that the stock market's
current pace cannot be sustained and who believe that the
government should not be taking financial risks that may be
acceptable for individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know much about the market, but I know it's not always
going to make 20 percent,'' said John Zimmerman, a 38-year-old
geologist in Atlanta for the federal Environmental Protection
Agency. ``Maybe some of the money should be put in there. But
frankly, what I'd really like to see is for the government to give
me everything I've put into the system. Let me manage my own money
and I promise you I won't ask the government for help when I
retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of those interviewed, however, said that many Americans
would not have the financial expertise to invest wisely on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would work because a lot of people don't have
a good knowledge of how the stock market works and they could lose
a lot of money,'' said Rod Jackson, 38, a maintenance man at a
downtown Atlanta office building. ``I'd want the money put into a
savings account. It's much safer and the money would be
guaranteed.''
</P>
<P>
   One point agreed on by virtually all of the baby boomers
interviewed was that they, unlike their parents, could not depend
on Social Security to support their retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be every person for themselves,'' said
Green, the lawyer. ``I don't feel secure at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1403EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4493 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDY-YOUNG07-COX     02-06 3269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDY-YOUNG07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prophet and profit-maker: Andy Young
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Gary Pomerantz and Jane Hansen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's a long way from Selma to Angola.
</P>
<P>
   It's even longer from negotiating for civil rights with the Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr. in the 1960s to now consulting in Africa for
American corporations such as Chevron Oil.
</P>
<P>
   That's the A-to-Z metamorphosis in the public life of Andy Young
_ minister, congressman, ambassador, mayor; Atlanta's most
passionate civic salesman since Henry Grady; Olympic idealist; and
unifier of peoples and continents.
</P>
<P>
   It's a span that measures more than 30 years and a series of
controversies, from his unauthorized meeting with the Palestine
Liberation Organization to his tepid support for Nike's operations
in Third World countries.
</P>
<P>
   Where once Young reached out to Southern whites in the name of
civil rights, now he reaches out to black African nations in the
name of American companies.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 66, and living with his second wife, Carolyn, in
the same southwest Atlanta home he bought for $32,000 in 1967, Andy
Young has morphed again.
</P>
<P>
   He's become Corporate Andy, honing in on Africa, ``the missing
link in the global economy,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He flew about a million miles last year, commands up to $25,000
for a speech (although he speaks for free to black colleges) and
earns more than $200,000 annually for sitting on a handful of
corporate boards, including those of Host Marriott, Delta, Cox
Communications and Archer-Daniels-Midland.
</P>
<P>
   He also serves as unpaid chairman of the Southern Africa
Enterprise Fund _ $100 million designated for economic development
in 11 African nations. President Clinton appointed him to the
position in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our man in the United States'' is how South Africa's retired
Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu describes him.
</P>
<P>
   Young says he spends about 10 days a month in Africa, where he
puts to use his extraordinary network of connections developed
during the decades.
</P>
<P>
   He keeps a hectic, if lucrative, pace; the most exercise he gets
these days is lifting luggage into the overhead compartments on
airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided that there wasn't anybody else (in the U.S.) that
knew as many people in Africa as I did and that also knew as much
about American business and development,'' Young says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me _ it really does _ that the richest continent on
the face of the Earth, in terms of natural resources and raw
materials has the poorest people living on top of the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   In advising American corporations in Africa, Young sees
continuity, not a break from his past. ``My whole career one way or
another has been trying to find common ground between people who
are different.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet at times it seems there are two Andy Youngs: The one he
sees, and the one others see.
</P>
<P>
   Like a chameleon who can't see its ongoing transformations,
Young views his roles in business, politics and the church as one
in the same. He often seizes a preacher's moral high ground,
drawing no boundaries as he moves effortlessly from one role to the
next.
</P>
<P>
   It is the mark of the man and what has often put him at the
center of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Nike and the Olympics
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Young was hired by Nike Inc. to investigate
allegations of human rights violations in its factories in Asia,
including charges of physical abuse of workers and of teen-age
girls paid 20 cents an hour for their labor. Young toured plants in
Vietnam, Indonesia and China and says he found no sweatshop
conditions. His report, which suggested Nike could do better, was
harshly criticized by human rights groups. That criticism ``didn't
bother me in the least,'' Young says. ``I saw people with jobs ...
good jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can get so damned self-righteous trying to be purer than
thou that we miss the major moral issue,'' he says. ``The major
moral issue is that starvation on the planet Earth is a sin and a
shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business right now may be the hope of the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Young's name has surfaced in connection with
the growing Olympics scandal, although no one has provided evidence
of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   He was central to Atlanta's winning bid to host the 1996 Games,
primarily responsible for wooing the votes from Africa. A month
before Atlanta won, Young took boxes of sports equipment to his
friend Jean-Claude Ganga, the International Olympic Committee
member from the Republic of Congo. Young has said that Ganga became
a last-minute convert to Atlanta's bid, withdrawing support of
Toronto's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Now with the Salt Lake City scandal raising questions about vote
buying, Young defends such gifts as ``humanitarian aid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You are expected to help people in need in the Olympic family,
particularly if you come from a rich country such as this,'' he
says. When the president of Mozambique told him his country's
runners lacked protein, Young says he made calls and got
Archer-Daniels-Midland to help donate 56 tons of free food to
Africa. Young says the shipment was made after Atlanta secured the
Olympics, but before the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the Olympics as a tool for helping Africa get on its
feet,'' Young says. ``And I'm still trying to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   He denies an Australian Olympic official's recent charge that he
promised U.S. foreign aid to African IOC delegates in exchange for
their support of Atlanta's bid. As an outgoing mayor in 1990, he
wasn't in a position to give out U.S. funds. He also was busy
running for governor of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is the perception of him, Young says. In
other nations, he says, ``people still perceive me as being a part
of the United States government.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, now Young is a representative of the United States in
his role as chairman of the Southern Africa Enterprise Fund, which
dispenses U.S. foreign aid in Africa, though not until 1997 _ seven
years after Atlanta won the Games.
</P>
<P>
   It's another example of the blurred lines in his life.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Young sees it: ``I have a reputation around the world as
being something of an American government spokesman on issues. In
most countries, and particularly in Australia, people who are in
politics are always in politics. They represent a party and a party
position. We don't have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed as Young's career demonstrates, in the United States,
politicians often move into other areas and other roles.
</P>
<P>
   Politics, poverty and profits
</P>
<P>
   Recently Young sat in the corporate offices of GoodWorks
International on the 48th floor of the SunTrust Plaza. He was
nursing a cold he blamed on impure air circulating in planes.
``It's miserable,'' he said of his frequent flying. ``One of the
things I've been trying to get Delta to take up is there ought to
be some way to pump pure oxygen into the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   GoodWorks is an international consulting firm formed in 1996
with several partners, among them Hamilton Jordan, the former White
House chief of staff for President Jimmy Carter. It was Carter who
appointed Young as United Nations ambassador, a post from which
Young was pressured to resign in 1979 after his visit with the PLO.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as ever, Young makes no apologies for the course his life
has taken, describing the path from civil rights to politics to
corporate business as a logical progression that has its roots in
his life as a country preacher in South Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't preach to people that they were God's children in
a society that said (that) they were second-class citizens, that
they had to sit in the back of the bus or that they couldn't
vote,'' he says. ``One's Christian faith required that you be in
the public arena.''
</P>
<P>
   Those beliefs led him to the civil rights movement and his
association with King. The next step was public office. But Young
became mayor of Atlanta in 1982, the federal, state and local
governments couldn't afford the poverty programs he'd envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if you want to help God's children, and if you want to feed
the hungry, you've got to provide jobs. And that meant establishing
relationships with business.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my interest in being mayor, and my interest in creating
jobs, was never to make money.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he makes plenty of money today. In addition to his
corporate board memberships, and his GoodWorks salary, he earns an
undisclosed amount in speeches, but that's ``not anybody's
business.'' Since mid-January, he says he's made at least 10
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   The lion's share of his speeches, he says, are unpaid, and he
often returns speaking fees paid by church organizations. ``But
when there are people that I know will pay other folk big money, I
don't want to speak for nothing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Caution: Criticism ahead?
</P>
<P>
   Young first traveled to Africa in the fall of 1973 as a
congressman accompanying George Shultz, then U.S. secretary of the
Treasury. When Young travels to Africa today, he goes sometimes as
private businessman, sometimes as government representative,
sometimes as democracy's advocate. He sees no distinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crisis in the world is that so many people are starving
and that the world is on the brink of chaos,'' Young says. ``My
interest now is to get more business involved in Africa. Because I
think that is not only the hope of Africa, but also the missing
link in the global economy is Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   But his association with Chevron illustrates the fine line Young
often walks.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco-based oil corporation has hired Young to be
its bridge-builder to the government of Angola. But farther north
in Nigeria, the corporation is embroiled in a human rights
investigation, stemming from its involvement last May in the
killing of protesters opposed to Chevron's dredging of rivers and
streams.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Environmental Rights Action, in Benin City,
Nigeria, say 121 young people were unarmed and peacefully
protesting the oil company's damage to rivers, streams and
wildlife, when Chevron-hired security forces swooped in on
helicopters and opened fire, killing two and wounding 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the same thing with literally all the oil companies,''
said Nnimmo Bassey, director of the environmental organization.
``They don't like discussion with the people. They prefer to use
troops. This is what is happening in the Niger Delta right now. So
many youths are being killed because they want discussions with oil
companies and with the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Bassey blames Chevron and other oil companies for keeping
Nigeria's military government in power. ``They're like two vampires
joined together in unholy wedlock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Young says no one denies the tragedy occurred, but he disputes
the details. He says he doubts Chevron hired the troops that killed
the protesters, although he admits he has no supporting evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Nigeria was one of the best-run (Chevron) operations
that I'd seen,'' he says. ``The guy knew the issues, was sensitive
to the politics; they were doing a great job of training Nigerians.
You pick on the people who are most vulnerable. Chevron was
vulnerable and visible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened or how it happened, but the oil is
there, it's going to be there. The U.S. needs it, Nigeria needs it.
My consulting role is to try to work out an arrangement where
everybody benefits from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oil-rich African countries, Young says, are critical to the
world economy. For example, Chevron is putting $10 billion into
Angola, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Chevron pulled out of Angola for any reason, Angola would
probably fall apart. Also, it wouldn't be long before we'd start
having long lines at the gas pump.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution in Nigeria, Young says, is a new government, not a
pullout by oil companies. For more than three years, he has refused
to visit Nigeria in opposition to its military government, while
lobbying for the release of his friend, Olusegun Obasanjo. The
pro-democracy general was released from prison last summer and now
is considered a strong contender in the Nigerian presidential
election, scheduled for Feb. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we've been working towards,'' says Young, who
hopes to travel to Nigeria to celebrate his friend's inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   Young's role with Chevron doesn't mean Young is a ``bad guy,''
says Julian Bond, chairman of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, though it could be troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Chevron is behaving badly (in Africa), then someone needs
to put a stop to it, and Andy Young is a person who could do
that,'' Bond says.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, if he serves as an apologist for Chevron,
then he is not being true to ideals he professed when he was with
Dr. King.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bond calls Young's path from civil rights to
Chevron a natural one. ``What he does now on one level isn't
radically different from what he did then,'' Bond says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where there are two groups of people who can (be put together)
for their mutual profit, he connects them. And sometimes it works
to his profit financially. And sometimes, it works to society's
benefit in a nonmaterial way.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hope Franklin, an eminent scholar of the African-American
experience, who chaired President Clinton's race relations
initiative, agrees that Young is a natural link between Africa and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regard him as a crossover person, working both sides,''
Franklin says. ``I think of him as a person blazing a trail and
working in new ways to provide various connecting points across the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   But Franklin says Young should be forthright about Chevron's
dealings in Africa. ``I do have some word that he, like other
Americans, might not be as critical of what's going on as they
should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, who rarely acts defensive, bristles at the remark.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many hungry people has he fed?'' Young says, calling
Franklin ``an old socialist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why, all of a sudden, are so damned many capitalists
self-righteous about other people making money when they make
money?''
</P>
<P>
   And, no, Young says, that is not the business side of him
speaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``What liberals forget is the extent to which they are
beneficiaries of corporations, in terms of their pension funds, in
terms of the cost of oil in their cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Tutu, a Nobel Peace Prize laureate now teaching at Emory
University's school of theology, remains grateful to Young for
drawing U.S. attention to the struggle against apartheid in South
Africa during the late-1970s, when Young was U.N. ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Tutu says, foreign companies are welcome in Africa's
developing countries, but they must be accountable to certain
standards. They can't, Tutu says, prop up corrupt regimes,
recklessly exploit the environment, violate human rights or pay
inadequate wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that from this distance,'' Tutu says, ``the
concern is, it appears that Chevron does not pass muster against
the criteria that I have delineated.''
</P>
<P>
   No dividing line needed
</P>
<P>
   Most of Young's time in Africa now is spent in his private work,
consulting not only for Chevron but several other American
companies he declines to name.
</P>
<P>
   Young estimates that 10 percent to 15 percent of his time in
Africa is devoted to the publicly funded Southern Africa Enterprise
Development Fund.
</P>
<P>
   But that's difficult to quantify, he adds, because he often
combines his private business for GoodWorks with his work for the
fund, as he recently did during a trip to Zimbabwe. Young
acknowledges this overlap, but says it doesn't benefit him
personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``GoodWorks doesn't take any money from governments,'' he says.
``We have no business connection with anybody that's receiving any
funds from the Fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, he adds, he is one of 18 members of a board that
includes, among others, Maurice Tempelsman, the diamond magnate,
and Carl Ware, president of Coca-Cola's Africa Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``By my choice, we have made every decision by consensus,''
Young says. ``One of the reasons why we have been so slow is they
have wanted to be sure about everything they did. So, we work out
the details until everybody is comfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its creation, the Fund has provided loans and equity
investments to 12 projects in six countries. Five of the projects
are in South Africa. According to last year's annual report, in
five years, the Fund has invested only $9 million of the $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   However, in one project in Angola, the Fund is investing
$350,000 in a company whose major customer is Chevron Oil.
</P>
<P>
   But Young says the surest way for the Fund to make sound
business decisions is to tie its equity position and loans to solid
American companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, the guy from Chevron really does the bookkeeping for
this guy, is helping him set up the business,'' Young says.
``(Chevron) wants to help people. They want to try to find a way to
give Angolans jobs, and this is one way to give Angolans jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Young says he sees no need to draw a line between his public and
private roles. ``I could say, `Nobody who has anything to do with
Chevron can get anything from the Fund,' and make myself clean,''
he says. ``But who does that help? Not a soul.''
</P>
<P>
   He points out that Angola is one of the 11 countries the Fund is
supposed to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Marriott went into South Africa _ and I'm on the Marriott
board _ the first thing that I would do, through the Fund, would be
to get somebody black to own a part of that Marriott,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not helping me, and it's not helping Marriott. Marriott
is going to be there anyway. The only question is: Is anybody
underprivileged going to be empowered? And they aren't going to be
empowered unless I'm there, or somebody like me, is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Securing his retirement
</P>
<P>
   As he reflects on his career, Young reiterates that he was never
motivated by money.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls accepting an invitation to travel to Africa with
Carter in January 1986, after his re-election as Atlanta's mayor.
That trip overlapped with the MLK holiday and Black History Month _
a big speech-making time for him. Young says he gave up more than
$50,000 in speeches to go because he believed the trip held a
higher purpose.
</P>
<P>
   But money does matter now, he admits, to secure his own future.
``Because I've been in so many jobs, I didn't have a retirement _
from Congress, from the U.N., from the city. And so, by and large,
all of those board fees are, as much as possible, deferred income,
for a time when I won't be physically able to work.''
</P>
<P>
   He aspires to complete his corporate work in four more years, at
which point he'll be 70 and, he expects, slowing down physically.
He's put on a little weight, but wears it well with his pinstriped
suit and gold cuff links.
</P>
<P>
   One of his remaining goals is to donate $1 million to education,
health and religion. His four children are grown _ he's a
grandfather, too _ and his responsibility, as he sees it, is ``to
future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, who still preaches occasionally at the First
Congregational Church, also wants to write another book. So full
and varied are his life's works that when Young published his
500-plus page autobiography in 1996, the book ended in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't plan to fill in his last 27 years in his next
book. Instead, he wants to write about his vision for the world's
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``People really get nervous,'' Young says. ``They think things
are falling apart. I think they are just beginning to come
together. And I can see how all of this could work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
