<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4497 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPERBOWL-IMPACT07-CO     02-06 1592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERBOWL-IMPACT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Now it's Atlanta's turn to reap Super harvest
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The corporate hospitality tents have vanished, the
stretch limos have been scrubbed, vacuumed and returned to service
carrying starry-eyed newlyweds, and Pro Player Stadium has been
swept clean of every last shred of Roman-numeral-stamped Super Bowl
debris.
</P>
<P>
   Now the torch of America's annual orgy of sports hype and hoopla
heads to Atlanta, host of Super Bowl XXXIV on Jan. 30, 2000. Miami
is left with pleasant memories, a few lingering hangovers and
hordes of exhausted hospitality workers.
</P>
<P>
   And truckloads of cash _ at least to hear boosters tell it.
</P>
<P>
   Although the receipts aren't yet tallied, the National Football
League estimates this year's game generated a whopping $300 million
in economic impact for South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't count the value of a solid week of priceless,
soft-focus media attention showcasing beaches, bikinis and
flower-shirted revelers, along with the opportunity for local
promoters to cozy up with thousands of corporate top guns jetted in
as guests for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell has already predicted next year's
game will generate $250 million for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the premier event for any destination in this
country,'' said Nicki Grossman, president of the Greater Fort
Lauderdale Convention and Visitors Bureau, co-host of Super Bowl
XXXIII. ``The revenues generated are remarkable for a one-time
event, and more important is the boost your image gets. We can buy
all the ads we want, but we'll never be able to target the 150,000
high-rollers and corporate decision-makers you get at a Super
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all economists are buying into the Super Bowl financial
hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really drastically inflated,'' said University of South
Florida economist Philip Porter, who has analyzed taxable sales
revenues from several past Super Bowls. ``All they're doing is
displacing other visitors who would've been there anyway, and to
get the values they're claiming, you'd have to double the amount of
economic activity. They're really blowing smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Not true, other economists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect to Dr. Porter, there are a number of
factors he didn't consider,'' said Robert Canton, director of the
Sports Convention and Entertainment Group for the accounting firm
PricewaterhouseCoopers, which was hired by the NFL to study the
1998 Super Bowl's impact on host city San Diego. ``We took an
independent, objective approach and did an extraordinary amount of
primary research. This is our specialty, and what we found is that
the Super Bowl is the crown jewel of events. In San Diego, it was
worth from $218 to $295 million, depending on the economic
multipliers you use.''
</P>
<P>
   Those multipliers are part of the problem for Porter. While
direct Super Bowl spending _ hotel rooms, rental cars, restaurant
meals, bar tabs, souvenirs _ can be measured with reasonable
accuracy, he believes the NFL and host cities vastly inflate the
value of indirect spending, which happens when those directly spent
dollars get cycled through the local economy. For instance, a
caterer buying food, paying workers or hiring extra workers to
handle a Super Bowl event creates economic ripples that economists
estimate amount to an additional $1 to $2 for each dollar spent.
</P>
<P>
   But Canton and others defend the estimates, and also cite hard
figures to back them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``In San Diego, hotels had a spike of 126,000-room nights over
the previous January, and most were receiving higher rates than
they get in a normal January,'' Canton said. ``San Diego's Gas Lamp
tourist district reported a 100 percent increase in business for
the week of the Super Bowl, with some businesses showing gains as
high as 200 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta doesn't have to leave this Super question to warring
accountants and academics. The city hosted its own Super Bowl in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   A University of Georgia study estimated the game generated $166
million in economic impact, with $76 million in direct spending and
$90 million in indirect activity, according to Jeff Humphreys,
director of the school's economic forecasting unit.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Humphreys says, he may have low-balled the
multiplier effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's too much controversy over these
impacts,'' he said. ``You can't just use multipliers pulled out of
the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter, however, says taxable sales in counties which hosted
five Florida Super Bowls actually show a decline in most of the
years studied.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are government figures anybody can look up,'' he said.
``I'm not making assumptions or multiplying anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But his critics point out that he made no effort to break out
Super Bowl spending from the host county's overall economic
activity. For Miami in 1995, for example, Porter compared the total
taxable sales, which amounted to $1.76 billion that year, to the
average for 1993 and 1994, which was $1.765 billion. The Super
Bowl's comparatively small contribution to the total is too easily
lost in the sea of other economic activity which might vary
significantly from year to year, they insist.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many other variables, and the Super Bowl is a
relatively small ... percentage,'' Humphreys said.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis by Fort Lauderdale's Sun-Sentinel newspaper of the
1995 Super Bowl in South Florida narrowed things down by looking at
taxable sales for the 15 sectors of the economy most likely to be
affected by the game: restaurants, hotels, transportation and
merchandise, among others. The newspaper found a $130 million spike
compared to the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a 6 percent jump in hotel occupancy that year,''
Grossman said. ``And even though January is our high season, the
1995 Super Bowl was the first year we ever approached 100 percent
occupancy in January.''
</P>
<P>
   Another rap on the Super Bowl is that it costs too much for host
cities to put on because the NFL pressures them for concessions,
freebies and upfront cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cities are dealing with the NFL, which is in essence a
monopolist,'' said University of Chicago economist Allen Sanderson,
another skeptic about the game's impact. ``It's not a level playing
field. The NFL has enormous leverage in getting cities to bid
against each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourism promoters, however, say they routinely grant concessions
and up-front cash to attract other events. And the Super Bowl,
while perhaps costing more, also generates more, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year we're hosting the Women's International Bowling
League with 60,000 attendees, and we put up more than half of the
$480,000 we put up to help get this year's Super Bowl,'' Grossman
said. ``But the Super Bowl brought 140,000 people _ and most of
them high-rollers.''
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, South Florida governments contributed $1.2 million
in public money to host this year's game, with an estimated $3.8
million coming from private sources.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta in 1994, the city, the state and Fulton County each
ponied up $300,000 to help stage the game, while other perks and
freebies, from free hotel rooms to waivers on sales tax on tickets
to free parking and free use of the Georgia Dome, kicked the total
package to around $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   For next year's game, the host committee estimates it will need
about $7.5 million, of which $2 million will come from the
hospitality industry, $2 million from the business community and
$3.5 million from local and state governments, according to Atlanta
Convention and Visitors Bureau President Spurgeon Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a darned good investment,'' he said. ``For $7 million,
you're getting $250 million back. We're in the business of filling
hotel rooms, and if we could get the Super Bowl every year, we'd go
for it. You can't buy this kind of attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonbelievers are particularly skeptical of the free-media
argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``That baffles me,'' Porter said. ``When a destination buys an
ad, they control the copy and the image. Here they are inviting
3,000 critical journalists over whom they have no control. There
are going to be critical stories, negative stories. How many
stories about this year's game mentioned dead German tourists and
the 1989 riots during Super Bowl week in Miami?'' But tourism
professionals say the academics can theorize all they want. Their
own real-world experience, they say, backs up the NFL's claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do this from an academic perspective,'' Grossman
said. ``These professors aren't here seeing what we see. There is
no question that Super Bowl visitors spend a lot more than our
normal visitors, and that they bring us more business. It's not Joe
Lunchbucket coming here for the game, it's the president of the
Lunchbucket Corp. That's what our money is buying.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanderson concedes that the Super Bowl brings economic benefits
to a host city, although he believes it often is vastly overstated.
Both he and Porter think the far greater error many cities make in
dealing with the NFL is to put up hundreds of millions of dollars
in public money to build stadiums to attract or keep teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes cities prosper is not hosting Super Bowls, it's
boring, day-to-day stuff like filling potholes, building new parks
and improving schools,'' Sanderson said. ``These things aren't as
sexy or attractive as a Super Bowl, but I think they are a far more
appropriate way for a city to spend its money.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
