<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE _ WASHINGTON - A month before the Bipartisan Medicare
Reform Commission is due to make its recommendation, attention is
focusing on a proposal by its chairman, Sen. John Breaux, D-La., to
change the nature of the elderly health program from one in which
the government defines what benefits the elderly will receive to
one in which the government defines how much money the elderly will
get to purchase their own private insurance. (Lipman, Cox News
Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM _ WASHINGTON _ Feb. 8 marks the third anniversary of the
Telecommunications Act. In 1996, after years of haggling, weary
lawmakers put finishing touches on the massive act, intended to
give consumers more choices and drive prices downward. That hasn't
happened: Today, not a single Baby Bell has been given the green
light to move into long-distance markets. Consumers haven't
benefitted either. Telephone prices have kept pace with inflation,
but they haven't been reduced as promised. And cable rates have
soared at an estimated 7 percent per year. What's more, the telecom
landscape has shifted dramatically. Telephone, cable and wireless
companies are in a frenzy to position themselves for the great
Internet race. The dizzying speed of developments has left
lawmakers and regulators grappling with how to regulate an industry
that is changing more quickly than rules can be written. (Regan,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MOVED in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
