<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ANDY-YOUNG _At 66, Andrew Young, among Atlanta's most defining
figures of the past half century, has morphed one more time: He's
Corporate Andy now, flying a million miles last year, pulling down
$25,000 for some speeches and earning more than $200,000 annually
for serving on corporate boards (Marriott, Delta, Archer-Daniels
Midland). He spends much of his time in Africa now, quietly
consulting for select American corproations such as Chevron. He's
living out a seeming contradiction: the pastor/human rights
activist representing an oil company charged with killing peaceful
protesters. But he, as ever, sees his life as fluid, and seizes the
moral highground. (Pomerantz/Hansen, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SUPERBOWL-IMPACT _ ATLANTA _ As Atlanta prepares to host ithe
2000 Super Bowl, there's some substantial disagreement about how
much economic impact the game has on the host city. Some experts
say it's overblown, but the facts and figures seem to be with those
who say that it's the king of special events, and that its benefits
can be long lasting. (Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GIST _ Virginia planter Samuel Gist wrote a utopian provision
into his will in 1808. He directed that his 300 slaves be freed
upon his death and his plantation turned into a sort of freedman
commune. But his last wishes collided with Commonwealth law, which
required that freed slaves leave the state. After much legal
wrangling following Gist's 1815 death, Virginia courts created an
alternate plan. They set up three ``settlements'' for the Gist
slaves in Ohio. Today, only one Gist settlement remains, in
Highland County _ and it's a legal quagmire. Several families of
descendants of the Gist slaves still live on the land, but none of
them has been able to acquire any of the land. For many years, it
was uncertain who was responsible for ever-escalating back taxes.
To prevent the settlement from being sold at sheriff's sale, slave
descendant Paul Turner, who has been farming much of the land for
25 years, agreed to pay taxes on land he doesn't own. Now, Turner
is trying to get title to his land, as is Charles Peacock, who owns
a junkyard on settlement land and who filed a civil lawsuit against
the county in 1996. ``There wouldn't have been a Gist settlement if
I hadn't come back here and paid the taxes,'' Turner said. ``I'd
like to keep it the Gist settlement because I know what the people
went through who came here.'' (Beyerlein, Dayton daily News) MOVED
FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   RAIN-FOREST _ University of Georgia researchers will become the
latest cadre of specialists scouring the tropics for plant species
that may harbor the next miracle drugs against cancer, heart
disease, parasitic infections and other maladies. Under a new $2.5
million, five-year federal grant, the Georgia scientists will focus
on the homelands of the Highland Maya people in the southern
Mexican state of Chiapas. Five other research teams from other
institutions are conducting searches in eight other countries in
Latin America, Africa and southeast Asia. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
