<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A U.S. MEETING WITH INDONESIA ON ITS ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ A senior American diplomat visiting here on
Friday expressed U.S. support for the coming elections and warned
of deteriorating security in the troubled province of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Roth, assistant secretary of state for East Asia and
Pacific affairs, said many issues remain unresolved, including how
new election laws will be carried out and how to ensure that the
campaign before the June 7 vote remains free of violence.
</P>
<P>
   After meetings with President B.J. Habibie, government ministers
and opposition leaders, he said at a news conference: ``This is not
an ordinary election the people have been used to in Indonesia.
This is one in which there will be a vigorous campaign, many
candidates, many parties and most important _ the outcome uncertain
before the election.''
</P>
<P>
   On East Timor, Roth said current proposals to end the crisis in
the former Portuguese colony gave him a feeling of optimism that a
political settlement was possible. Indonesia invaded East Timor
after Portugal left and annexed it in 1976, but has never received
international recognition for its authority there.
</P>
<P>
   Roth said, however, ``My government is very concerned about the
increase in violence on the ground, the deterioration in the
situation on East Timor itself.'' He said he had discussed East
Timor security issues in ``great detail'' in talks with the chief
of the Indonesian armed forces, Gen. Wiranto.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto told Roth that he supported a proposal by the jailed
East Timorese resistance leader, Xanana Gusmao, that all parties be
disarmed and that a cease-fire and an end to the violence be
declared.
</P>
<P>
   Gusmao, currently serving a 20-year term in a Jakarta maximum
security prison for inciting rebellion, will be released into a
form of house arrest this week, as part of a package of measures
proposed by Indonesia to break the deadlock in the current
negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
