<HEADER>
A4502 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGIA-BRIBES &LR; - &UR; ART-     02-06 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-BRIBES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FORMER SOVIET REPUBLIC, BRIBES LIGHT THE NIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 - ART-NYT   (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STEVE LeVINE  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TBILISI, Georgia _ When they lost light and heat four years ago,
most Georgians could only shiver in the dark. On the way to the
bread lines, they trod carefully to avoid the corpses of those who
had perished scavenging overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Now Marina Kokobadze knows instantly what to do when the power
fails. Pulling a plug from one socket, she presses it into another
_ the socket linked to the ``second electric line'' that a corrupt
meter man installed for $30, plus $10 a month in ``fees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as simple as that,'' said Ms. Kokobadze, 40, sipping tea
near the cherished line leading from her window to an unseen power
source beyond. A common part of the landscape here and in other
suffering parts of the former Communist world, such lines are
slender consolation in a nation once known as the most carefree in
the former Soviet Union, and now among the most miserable.
</P>
<P>
   They attest to the vast corruption that underlies Georgia's
deprivation, choking the nation and deflating trust in its leader,
President Eduard A. Shevardnadze, a man respected abroad for his
role in ending the Cold War as Soviet foreign minister, but widely
criticized at home by both local residents and resident diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1994, some $400 million in unpaid bills for natural
gas and electricity imports finally provoked suppliers like the
government of Turkmenistan to sever the flow of energy Georgia,
creating its most dreadful winter in memory.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's 5.5 million people gradually have learned to cope _
even if in most cases that means a 19th-century existence of
kerosene-fueled space heaters and wood stoves as sources of warmth,
hot water and light. That has generated black humor. In a common
outburst, people in Tbilisi wish for the death of an unspoken
neighbor because, as a goodwill gesture, the government provides
days of uninterrupted electricity to entire blocks when a funeral
is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Only the lucky, like Ms. Kokobadze, can afford the bribe for the
second line _ which is acquired by asking openly at the state power
office. Even her ``fee'' provides only enough power for one lamp
and the television; the ``elite'' option of power 24 hours a day
costs an initial $250, and higher monthly charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot live this way for long,'' said Ms. Kokobadze's
husband, Gia Gogoladze, 44, a builder in Tbilisi. ``Every day,
every year, it is worse and worse, backward and backward, my work
less and less.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Shevardnadze, 71, might argue that this is progress. Under
his leadership, Georgia has recovered from the low of 1993, when
civil war in a breakaway region, Abkhazia, threatened to engulf all
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Shevardnadze, a KGB boss in Georgia in the
Soviet era, outmaneuvered and arrested armed gangs that made much
of the nation lawless.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with the help of the International Monetary Fund, he
launched a national currency that despite a devaluation caused by
Russia's economic chaos is still among the region's most stable.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the work force is idle. Some teachers and policemen
have not been paid in months.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Georgia's IMF program was suspended, largely
because it has failed to improve one of the world's worst tax
collection rates.
</P>
<P>
   Shevardnadze conceded then that corruption has cost the state
``hundreds of millions of dollars.'' Diplomats say it is rampant,
from senior state officials who profit from cigarette, fuel and
alcohol smuggling to taxmen who buy their profitable jobs for
$5,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Soviet times, corruption in Georgia was legendary. Now,
said a Western lawyer who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
Shevardnadze and his compatriots must decide ``whether they want to
be a criminal state or a law-abiding country.''
</P>
<P>
   The electricity shortage exemplifies Georgia's crisis. Diplomats
say at least $15 million of the $82 million in foreign aid granted
since 1994 to fix the power problem has disappeared. Electrical
service has meanwhile worsened, and sabotage _ like repeated
mystery fires at Tbilisi's main generator _ is suspected.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the government sold Tbilisi's electric transmission
system to AES Corp., an Arlington, Va., company. In an interview,
Michael Scholey, AES' director in Georgia, said the company soon
would provide reliable, continuous power to Tbilisi.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, people like Ms. Kokobadze and Gogoladze suffice with
their auxiliary lines, and are grateful they do not live in the
countryside, where, Gogoladze noted ``children don't even know what
this thing called electricity is. When the sun sets, it's just time
to sleep.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
