<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-N     02-06 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   He surpassed the old major league home run record, led his team
to the playoffs and was named the league's most valuable player. As
great as those achievements were, and as gratifying as they were to
attain, they all might have placed behind one other feat Sammy Sosa
performed. He drove in one more run than Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are so competitive,'' Omar Minaya said. ``There was
a competitiveness between them from the start, a friendly
competitiveness. I think it still holds today.''
</P>
<P>
   Minaya, the Mets' senior assistant general manager, was there at
the start, in the Gulf Coast rookie league in 1986. He was the
coach and later the manager of the Texas Rangers' team in that
league, the one on which Sosa and Gonzalez began their professional
careers.
</P>
<P>
   The heroes of two Latin American countries, Sosa from the
Dominican Republic and Gonzalez from Puerto Rico, will be together
again Sunday night when they receive their MVP awards at the annual
dinner of the New York chapter of the Baseball Writers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime during the evening, Sosa undoubtedly will remind his
good friend of their RBI numbers, 158 and 157, good enough to lead
their respective leagues and lead their teams into the playoffs.
But there was that difference of one. The only other time Sosa
drove in more runs, Gonzalez missed nearly half of the season with
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Minaya, then a scout, signed Sosa for the Rangers in July 1985,
giving him a $3,500 bonus. The Rangers signed Gonzalez the
following May, for a $75,000 bonus, and both players reported to
the Gulf Coast League in June. ``The outfielders caught with each
other,'' Minaya said, recalling their first workout, ``and the
first time they played catch they played catch together.'' Their
throwing to each other was somewhat symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell right away there was a competitiveness between
them,'' Minaya related. ``They both had good arms and kids like to
show off their arms. There was a friendship, yet a competitiveness
between them.''
</P>
<P>
   Both players, Minaya said, were very intelligent, but beyond
intelligence and talent, they were different.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a difference in their personalities,'' Minaya said.
``Juan always has been happy. Some people may say he was a little
careless in the way he played the game, the way he worked out.
Sammy has always had that smile, but he had a blue-collar work
ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan would take the lows much better than Sammy. When things
didn't go well, you could see from Sammy's face how he was taking
it. He was under a lot of stress because he knew he was the only
way out for his family.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngsters _ Sosa was 17, Gonzalez was 16 _ lived together
in a complex in Sarasota, Fla. Gonzalez liked to listen to music
and hang out with other players. Sosa was still a kid at heart and
liked talking to children five and seven years his junior. Neither
minor league rookie could hit a curveball.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were definitely strikeout guys,'' Minaya said. ``They
were raw. Juan didn't hit any home runs. He was a real lean, skinny
kid, about 6-2, 6-3, lanky and loose. He was much leaner than
Sammy. Sammy had that raw strength. He would hit balls far. But I
thought Juan would be more of a home run hitter. He was much more
under control. Sammy played out of control like Clemente.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa hit four home runs that first year. He led the league in
doubles and total bases. Gonzalez led in times at bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just saw two raw kids who fit the mold of what we were
trying to do with the Rangers,'' Minaya said, ``getting young
talented players with an upside, kids who could be star players.''
</P>
<P>
   Both would develop into star players, though Sosa did it with
other teams. He and Gonzalez continued playing together in 1987 at
Gastonia (Class A) and in 1988 at Charlotte (A). They began the
1989 season at Tulsa (AA), but in July Sosa was traded to the
Chicago White Sox in a five-player deal that sent Harold Baines to
Texas. The White Sox traded Sosa to the Cubs in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Although they drifted apart, first on different teams, then in
different leagues, Sosa and Gonzalez remained friends and
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep down inside,'' Minaya said, ``they're saying, `How can I
top you next?' Juan got a big contract first, then Sammy got his
contract. I think both keep each other striving for more. They are
aware of each other's accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   Their accomplishments, since that beginning in the Gulf Coast
League, have been considerable.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Reds a Contender
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what are the Cincinnati Reds up to? Does Jim Bowden,
their general manager, have thoughts of trying to steal the
National League Central championship?
</P>
<P>
   No, Bowden said the day after the Reds acquired Greg Vaughn and
his 50-home run bat. That would be an exaggeration. But the NL wild
card? That's another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly we're not the favorites for that,'' Bowden said.
``But if everything goes right, we have to be in the mix.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds have been engaged in a steady pattern of payroll
reduction, slashing a payroll a shade under $37 million in 1997 to
one just under $21 million last year. Even though they planned to
give out more dollars on their paydays this year, they weren't
viewed as a team in contention for anything.
</P>
<P>
   But then they traded Bret Boone, their second baseman, for Denny
Neagle, a costly pitcher, and just last week, even more
surprisingly, sent Reggie Sanders to San Diego for the
higher-priced Vaughn, a potential free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds' lineup will still feature a collection of young
players, such as Sean Casey, Pokey Reese, Aaron Boone, Brett Tomko,
Dmitri Young and Mike Cameron. They will still ``stick with our
payroll constraints,'' as Bowden put it. But they may just throw
their red hats into the wild-card ring with the Mets, the Chicago
Cubs, St. Louis and any other teams unlikely to be division
champions but good enough to compete for the extra playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a deal where we didn't have to give up Casey or Tomko
or Young or any of our top prospects we're trying to build this
team around,'' Bowden said, explaining the Vaughn trade. ``We gave
up three players who weren't going to fit with us for a guy who hit
50 home runs last year. It's the first time in history a guy who
hit 50 home runs was traded the next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting Vaughn from the Padres was not difficult, Bowden said.
Getting approval for the additional expenditure from John Allen,
the Reds' managing executive, was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bumps our payroll,'' Bowden said. ``It puts us $2.2 million
over budget. We'll be in the low 30s instead of the high 20s.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the initial reaction in Cincinnati, though, the
expenditure was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phones haven't stopped ringing,'' the crafty general
manager said. ``People are buying season tickets, daily tickets,
everything. We've brought life back to this town. I thought the
reaction would be positive but not as positive as it's been. This
town's excited. It's still a great baseball town, but it doesn't
rock like it used to rock. It's fun to see the excitement again.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides hitting home runs and driving in runs, Vaughn will help
the Reds in two other ways, Bowden said. With five of the eight
everyday starters 26 years old or younger, he can take pressure
away from them, and he has played in a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a real big proponent all my career of having people
who have been there,'' Bowden said. ``It will just make the younger
guys better.''
</P>
<P>
   No dummy, Bowden has a safety valve if the Reds don't thrust
themselves into the wild-card race in the first half of the season
and the fans become uninterested again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come July 20,'' he said, ``we'll know how much our young
players have developed. If they develop, we'll be better than
people thought we'd be. If not, I'll be sitting at the trading
deadline with Vaughn and Neagle. We gained a valuable asset in this
trade. Maybe we can make a run for it. If not, we have a couple
guys we can trade for some young prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
