<HEADER>
A4506 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-WITNESSES-NYT &LR;      02-06 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WITNESSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WITNESSES FOR THE DEFENSE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Feb. 7:
</P>
<P>
   The airing of Monica Lewinsky's videotaped testimony before the
Senate Saturday was less a legal than a political exercise. Her
comments and those of Vernon Jordan and Sidney Blumenthal added
little to the evidentiary record. What the testimony did provide,
apart from the chance for the nation to see Ms. Lewinsky address
the affair, was another opportunity for the House prosecutors to
try to give renewed velocity to what everyone now knows is a losing
case for removal.
</P>
<P>
   When historians someday consider the impeachment proceedings
against Bill Clinton, they will no doubt be struck by the political
and temperamental ravine that divided the House and the Senate in
this case. That gap has widened with the House impeachment
managers' failure to convince a skeptical Senate that President
Clinton's offenses are large enough to warrant discharging him from
office. The isolation and fervor of the House team were underscored
by the effort to paint the latest comments by Ms. Lewinsky, Jordan
and Blumenthal as crucial new evidence that strengthened the case
against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Asa Hutchinson skillfully used videotape excerpts to
reinforce the circumstantial case that Clinton did his best to keep
his affair with Ms. Lewinsky hidden and to impede the gathering of
testimony and evidence in the Paula Jones civil suit. But Ms.
Lewinsky, who parried many of Rep. Ed Bryant's questions, once
again denied that Clinton had directly instructed her to file a
false affidavit in the Jones case. Jordan ridiculed the idea that
he instructed Ms. Lewinsky to destroy romantic letters she had
written to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lawyer and I'm a loyal friend,'' Jordan told Hutchinson,
``but I'm not a fool.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been clear from the opening days of the trial that the
partisan passions that stirred the House to impeach Clinton never
migrated across the Capitol to the Senate. That is as the framers
hoped when they constructed legislative bodies with such different
constituent bases and election rhythms, and required a two-thirds
majority to remove a president. But it also says something about
this group of House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with their impeachment case is not, as the House
managers would have it, that the Senate has denied the prosecution
a fair chance to present the evidence and witnesses. The problem is
that House Republicans misused the power of impeachment to deal
with presidential misconduct that deserves formal rebuke but not
the ultimate constitutional sanction of overturning an election.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde and his prosecution team will have one last
chance to make their case when they present closing arguments. But
as the trial enters its fifth and probably final week, the only
drama left is whether the Senate will find a way to censure Clinton
as it acquits him of impeachable offenses. This whole affair must
not end without a stinging condemnation of Clinton's behavior by
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, a Democrat, has drafted such a resolution
with the assistance of Robert Bennett, a Republican. It is gaining
support among Democrats. The resolution will need a handful of
Republican votes to pass, and a solid bipartisan majority to be
meaningful. Trent Lott, who has managed the trial with dignity and
respect for the Constitution, can write his place in history by
leading his Republican flock to support a sternly worded censure
resolution. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
