<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-CHECKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES EXTENDING CONTROLS TO GUN SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Saturday that he would ask
Congress to require background checks on all people who bought
firearms at gun shows and flea markets, regardless of whether the
sellers were commercial gun dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton summarized his proposal this way: ``No background check,
no gun, no exceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address, Clinton said that gun shows were
becoming ``arms bazaars, where lawbreakers shop side by side with
the law-abiding.'' A new study by the Justice and Treasury
departments found that ``gun shows are a forum for gun traffickers,
a cash-and-carry convenience store for weapons used to maim and
kill,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1993 Brady Act, firearms dealers licensed by the
federal government must check the background of prospective buyers
to ensure that they are not felons, fugitives or illegal aliens.
Such dealers also must keep records of the sales.
</P>
<P>
   But, federal officials said, these requirements apply only to
licensed firearms dealers and those who must obtain licenses
because they regularly ``engage in the business'' of selling
firearms. The requirements do not apply to unlicensed individuals,
who account for at least one-fourth of the sellers at gun shows,
the administration said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should extend Brady checks and gun-tracing records to any
and all open markets where large numbers of firearms are sold,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Because unlicensed dealers are not required to inspect a buyer's
driver's license or other identification, they may not even know
that the purchaser is under the age of 18, the administration said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration said it had solicited the views of gun owners
and found them opposed to Clinton's proposal. For example, it said,
the National Rifle Association contends that only 2 percent of
firearms used by criminals come from gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Johnson, an undersecretary of the Treasury Department
who supervises the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, said
the president's proposal would define ``gun show'' as any event
where ``two or more people are engaged in a sale of at least 50
firearms.'' Thus, the proposed new requirements would apply to some
flea markets, but not to an individual selling a personal gun
collection at a garage or yard sale.
</P>
<P>
   The restrictions ``do not affect unlicensed persons who buy or
sell a single firearm outside a gun show from another unlicensed
person,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration said that more than 4,400 gun shows were
advertised last year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the president's proposal, a licensed gun dealer would have
to be involved in every sale of firearms at a gun show. Unlicensed
sellers would have to arrange for buyers to go to a licensed dealer
to request a background check, through a computer system operated
by the FBI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1424EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0156 </DOCNO>
