A4510 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      02-06 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS VS. HEAT ... GET READY TO RUMBLE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   While Latrell Sprewell served his suspension last season, he got
his fill of basketball any way he could. Often that meant turning
on the television, where some playoff games made his adrenaline
flow more than others.
</P>
<P>
   He watched in stunned disbelief as Alonzo Mourning and Larry
Johnson began throwing punches in the final seconds of Game 4
between the Knicks and Miami Heat, a moment that upped the
emotional ante in their contentious and ugly rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, I just knew these teams didn't like each
other,'' Sprewell said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since that first-round series, the two
Atlantic Division combatants return to Madison Square Garden
Sunday. If they aren't ornery because of shared history, the fact
that the Knicks and Heat both lost their season openers on Friday
night should make for another decent scrum.
</P>
<P>
   After being nearly run off the Orlando Arena floor in a 93-85
loss, the Knicks may need the Heat to bring out some semblance of a
cohesive basketball team in them. They fell behind by 21 points to
the Magic and never found an offensive rhythm that lasted more than
two straight possessions in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat, meanwhile, melted down the stretch at home against
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to get back on the court because of tonight,''
Johnson said after the Knicks were beaten by Orlando. ``Not because
of Miami. It's not the playoffs. It's going to be a big game for
both of us because we both lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The game marks NBC's first National Basketball Association
telecast since Game 6 of the 1998 finals in Salt Lake City. It may
not be the kind of aesthetically-pleasing encounter the league
wants to showcase to begin the lockout-shortened season. But then,
Knicks-Heat never is.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two seasons, the rivalry's damage has been
excessive. Throw in their Game 5 melee in Miami in May of 1997 _
when Miami came back from a 3-1 deficit to stun the Knicks in the
second round _ and the two teams have lost a combined nine players
to suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning and Johnson were suspended for the final game of the
series last year. Johnson was also forced to miss Game 1 against
Indiana in the conference semifinals and Mourning was supposed to
have served the remaining game of his two-game suspension in this
year's season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the labor dispute, the NBA lifted the remaining game
of the suspension and Johnson was compensated for the money he lost
for missing the Pacers game.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the names and faces have changed since New York
eliminated Miami in five games last May, but the animosity remains
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell is the most prominent new character, a talented player
with a troubled past who could dramatically alter the conference's
playoff picture. The Heat were in contention with the Knicks for
the rights to Sprewell, but backed off a potential trade with the
Golden State Warriors shortly before training camps opened.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Riley's refusal to pull the trigger on the prospective deal
could backfire, given that the starting shooting guard Voshon
Lenard began the season on the injured list with a stress fracture
in his shin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely happy to be with the Knicks,'' said Sprewell,
who led New York with 24 points in the season opener. ``For
whatever reason, I didn't end up there. I might be thinking about
that a little, but it won't affect how I approach the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Given all the jeering, Sprewell fared well in his first game in
14 months, making 8 of 16 shots and throwing down his first dunk as
a Knick with 11:18 left in the third quarter. He returns to the
Garden 10 days after his third-quarter explosion during a preseason
game with the Nets, a 17-point binge that earned him a standing
ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in New York has accepted me with open arms,'' he
said. ``I hope it continues, but I know I have to play well.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of his teammates on Friday night, he resorted to
one-on-one forays in a half-court offense that sapped the Knicks of
their offensive prowess. The ball stopped moving, the points
stopped coming and they literally fell apart in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the things that we talked about that could go wrong
offensively really did,'' said Coach Jeff Van Gundy. ``Even though
we shot a fairly good percentage, we really did not move the ball
the way I hoped to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we did throw the ball inside, we played fairly well. I
think we need to strike some balance between the perimeter and
post.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing also returns to the court against his friend and
nemesis, Mourning, for the first time in more than a year. Ewing
sat out the first-round series last May to rehabilitate a fractured
right wrist that forced him to miss the remainder of the regular
season as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to play, but the doctors told me I couldn't,'' Ewing
said. ``It was rough watching all of the games.
</P>
<P>
   He added after the Magic loss, ``I feel that I'm ready. I've
been working extremely hard. Tonight, we got outplayed, outhustled.
I've got to learn from my mistakes and hope it doesn't happen
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing finished with 17 points and 9 rebounds in 38 minutes
against Orlando. He moved well at times, but also committed foolish
turnovers by stubbornly trying to back his defender into the post
with a high dribble.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Mourning and Miami can cure his and the team's ills after
a less-than-auspices debut. Maybe Riley's Heat will awake from
their opening-night slumber and further expose the Knicks'
deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, based on their history and what's at stake, it
should be good theater. For two warring franchises expected to
challenge Indiana for the conference title, an 0-2 start in a
50-game season is enough to make someone upset.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1432EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
