</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HERST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERMAN HERST JR., AN ESTEEMED STAMP COLLECTOR, DIES AT 89 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla., Va., Ore., London, Barbados)  By ROBERT McG. THOMAS Jr.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Herman (Pat) Herst Jr., who was so enthralled by a stamp he saw
in a Manhattan store window when he was 7 that he grew up to be the
stamp world's most revered dealer, auctioneer and collector and by
far its most garrulous booster and most prolific authority, died on
Jan. 31 at his home in Boca Raton, Fla. He was 89 and had carried
his passion to such an extreme that he started his own postal
service.
</P>
<P>
   To suggest that Herst was a ubiquitous figure in philately would
hardly do justice to a man who once belonged to 81 stamp clubs,
rarely missed a major exhibition, made scores of stamp-scouting
trips abroad, wrote 18 books and thousands of columns about stamp
news.
</P>
<P>
   He gave hundreds of speeches, and spent so much time on his
voluminous personal correspondence that it is a wonder he had any
left over for his myriad other interests, including the American
Civil Liberties Union, Americans United for Separation of Church
and State, Citizens for Religious Liberty and Baker Street
Irregulars.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Herst's contributions to philately were so widely
recognized that he won every honor of consequence in the United
States, including the American Philatelic Society's Luff award, and
several in Britain, where he was so esteemed that he became the
only American ever elected to the board of the august Philatelic
Traders Society.
</P>
<P>
   For all his later achievements in philately, it was some years
before Herst's childhood enthusiasm became his life's focus.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a New York lawyer, also named Herman Herst Jr., who
died when he was 4, Herst adopted the junior. But once his boyhood
friends found that he was born on St. Patrick's Day, he was never
called anything except Pat.
</P>
<P>
   To make ends meet, his Oregon-born mother, Lillian Myers Herst,
played first violin in John Philip Sousa's all-female orchestra,
leaving her rambunctious son so unsupervised that when he was 12
she packed him off to her sister's home in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   After studying international law at Reed College and receiving a
master's degree from the University of Oregon, he returned to New
York in 1932 and was soon working as a $12-a-week runner for a Wall
Street bond house.
</P>
<P>
   A chance delivery to a millionaire stamp dealer, then the center
of American philately, reawakened Herst's interest in stamps and
laid the groundwork both for his career and his later outpouring of
books, beginning in 1960 with ``Nassau Street.''
</P>
<P>
   After organizing his fellow bond house employees into a
syndicate that made a minor killing when Herst tracked down a
supply of a much sought-after series of silver jubilee
commemoratives issued by the Republic of Nauru, a small
island-nation in the central Pacific, he used his profits to set up
shop at in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Herst began holding the auctions that became his stock in trade
and turning out a newsletter, Herst's Outbursts, which established
his reputation for solid expertise and entertaining anecdotes. He
was soon contributing columns to virtually every stamp publication
in the country, a practice he continued until shortly before his
death.
</P>
<P>
   A man who saw stamps, and especially their envelopes, or covers,
as windows into history, Herst, whose concentrations included early
British historical stamps, was an enthusiastic collector.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a vast postwar proliferation of stamps that made
it impossible to collect them all, he became a champion of the
topical collecting movement, in which collectors specialize in
stamps that depict, for example, dogs or nursing mothers, or in one
of Herst's specialties, covers posted from high-altitude places
listing the elevation.
</P>
<P>
   A two-year sojourn in England in the late 1930s made him a
familiar figure to British stamp collectors, so much so that when
Herst, who had returned to the United States with an English wife
in 1938, made his first postwar visit to London, in 1948, he
received a standing ovation when he walked into the Stampex show.
</P>
<P>
   Herst's appearance, he was told, was the first sign that the
British stamp business was returning to normal after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Thereafter, British dealers hoarded American stamps for Herst.
</P>
<P>
   Herst was as well-known in New York, where his office became
such a popular gathering spot for idlers that to get some work done
he closed it in 1945 and moved his operations to Shrub Oak, N.Y.,
40 miles north of Manhattan in Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   It was a reflection of Herst's impact on the little community of
674 people that when he moved into a house across from the post
office, the 100,000 pieces of mail generated by his business each
year led it to be upgraded to second-class from third-class status.
</P>
<P>
   Even then there were no deliveries from Friday to Monday, a
matter of some inconvenience for a town that served as a weekend
getaway for New Yorkers. So in 1953, having discovered an obscure
1862 law that allowed such supplemental services, Herst opened a
private mail service, using first his children and later his German
shepard, Alfie, to deliver the mail for 2 cents a letter.
</P>
<P>
   In time, his privately issued stamps, including one depicting
Alfie, became collectors items even as his initiative led scores of
other philatelists to set up similar private post offices across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Herst continued to hold regular auctions in New York until 1973,
when he and his second wife moved to Florida, where he quickly
became the state's leading philatelist and donated his extensive
library to Florida Atlantic University.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his wife, Ida, Herst is survived by two children,
Kenneth, of Springfield, Va., and Patricia Held of Centerville,
Va.; two stepchildren, Gary K. Busch of London and Gail C. Busch of
Manhattan; six grandchildren and four great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Even in his later years, however, Herst never forgot the stamp
that caught his eye when he was 7 and awakened his interest in
philately. How could he? The tricolor Barbados design showing a
ship became the pattern for a throw rug he kept in his house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
