<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MILLROSE-GREENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENE IS RUNNING RIGHT, WHICH MEANS VICTORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By RON DICKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ World's Fastest Human: It's a title that rarely
sticks.
</P>
<P>
   But Maurice Greene, who has worn the distinction for a year, has
a plan to keep it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole year is about being injury free,'' Greene said
Friday night after winning the 60 meters in the Chase Millrose
Games at Madison Square Garden in 6.51 seconds. ``An injury can be
traumatizing to a career. The best way to run injury free is to run
technically right.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene, 23, won every indoor race he entered in 1998 and set a
world indoor record in the 60 meters of 6.39 seconds. Outdoors, he
cracked 10 seconds in the 100 meters 10 times, earning the No. 1
ranking in the world after being No. 2 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Every Monday, Greene bounds into the track stadium at UCLA and
gushes about the California weather and the privilege of doing what
he loves to do. His coach, John Smith, and his training partners,
Jon Drummond and Ato Boldon, listen patiently before they get on
with their workout.
</P>
<P>
   Greene calls the 30-year-old Drummond ``old and fat'' in
practice. On race day, Greene says nothing. All Drummond said he
heard Friday were ``the whispers, the little giggles, the little
rap songs'' from the other sprinters.
</P>
<P>
   Greene has a reputation for steely concentration which can block
out the mind games that often precede a sprint. But he suffered a
rare mental lapse in front of 15,822 fans Friday night. He broke
last out of the blocks and had to surge in the final 10 meters to
edge Drummond for the second straight year. ``I need to work on my
reaction time,'' Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said: ``If you beat Maurice, it's because you've done
everything right. When Maurice is on top of his game, he's
difficult to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   When his game is off, Greene compensates with acceleration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He blew right by me, which he does,'' Drummond said.
</P>
<P>
   Greene will run today in Boston, at the U.S. indoor
championships in Atlanta on Feb. 26-27 and the at world indoors in
Japan the following week. He thrives on the intimacy of indoor
track meets.
</P>
<P>
   Greene celebrated his Millrose victory by tossing out T-shirts
with ``Phenomenon'' silk-screened on the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to peak for the world indoors because I have a
long outdoor season,'' he said. ``If I do what I'm doing now, I
believe I'll win indoors.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene is pointing toward the world championships in Seville,
Spain, in August, the biggest meet besides the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Smith believes Greene is capable of running in the 9.8's in the
100 meters, threatening Donovan Bailey's world record of 9.84.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's vow to stay injury free stems from painful experience.
After winning three straight Kansas state high school 100 and 200
titles, Greene pulled a hamstring muscle so badly in 1994 that he
missed a year. He bounced back to stun Carl Lewis in the Texas
Relays the following season and placed second in the national
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, he blazed through 100-meter heats of 9.84 seconds
(wind-aided) and 9.96 before withdrawing from the national final
because of cramps.
</P>
<P>
   Greene has logged other disappointments. He trudged to a
seventh-place finish in a quarterfinal heat of the 1996 Olympic
trials.
</P>
<P>
   The next season, after winning the 100 at the world
championships, Greene was poised to anchor the United States'
4-by-100 relay team, but he never got the baton. The squad was
disqualified for an out-of-zone pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't pay attention to losing,'' Smith said. ``He pays
attention to winning.''
</P>
<P>
   He is, after all, the World's Fastest Human.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves that title,'' Drummond said. ``He won the world
championships. He's the world indoor record holder. Respect
that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
