u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-GIULIAN     02-06 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL   OBSERVER: WALLS AND STONEWALLS AT NEW YORK'S CITY HALL
 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELEANOR RANDOLPH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The police officers along the new fencing outside
City Hall are reasonably civil. On a recent weekday, an officer sat
in his patrol car and asked a prospective visitor, ``What is your
business here?''  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Being a mere citizen no longer counts as an adequate response.
One needs an official badge, an appointment, a good reason. This is
not the people's City Hall; there is no eating lunch or holding
big, unfriendly rallies on its sunny front steps. It is Fortress
Rudy, Mayor Giuliani's walled castle.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the wall is supposed to be temporary construction
fencing while the city upgrades the surrounding park. What remains
permanent will be for safety's sake. There are real nuts out there
with guns, terrorists with plots. No prudent person could oppose
consistent safeguards against the general danger and stringent,
well-explained responses to specific threats. Some inconvenience is
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the scene is Lafayette Park in Washington or lower
Manhattan, balance and atmospherics count. The same walls that
protect against the bad or even the weird also keep out the
do-gooder, the honest dissenter and the creative eccentric. They
can chill the civic air where democracy must breathe. The delicate
balance between security and freedom at City Hall seems to have
tilted, at least for now, in favor of the chain-link fence.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more disturbing is the thought that these fences
stand as a visual metaphor for how New York City now operates. The
barriers to City Hall are compounded by other barriers to public
data, to information, to even talking to anyone in the city
government except the man with the microphone, Giuliani himself.
 &UR;  &LR; At a forum last week sponsored by the Columbia University Graduate
School of Journalism, First Amendment lawyers and journalists told
war stories about what it is like to try to cover the city's
business. Some of it was your usual grumbling by reporters who are
not happy unless they are standing on the chalk marks at a murder
scene. But most of the complaints were about the extraordinary
difficulty of gathering the bits and strands of data that should be
available to anyone in a free society.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Pressman of WNBC, now president of the New York Press Club,
groused that, ``No administration in my experience has been so
heavy-handed.'' Pressman's experience covers eight New York mayors,
he said, back to William O'Dwyer, who left office in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Browne, senior managing editor of The Daily News, fumed
about how the state's Freedom of Information Law, called FOIL, has
now become exactly that under the Giuliani administration. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``You have turned the law on its head,'' Browne told Giuliani
supporters at the breakfast. Obtaining ordinary information like
restaurant inspections or the list of people at a mayoral reception
can now require a process that takes three months. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  The law intended to open data to the press and public is being
used to ``delay, delay, delay,'' Browne said.
</P>
<P>
   The media and their customers are not the only victims here. The
Giuliani administration has often locked its most routine filing
cabinets to public-interest groups and even other government
agencies. The City Comptroller, in a recent report on New York
police officers holding civilian jobs, gives eight pages of details
about how hard it was to get the city's police department to
cooperate. The State Comptroller's office has been forced to sue
the mayor for basic information.
</P>
<P>
   In other First Amendment cases, including two filed by The New
York Times for access to information, the law has not been friendly
to the Giuliani administration. The city has lost a dozen or so
court battles over freedom of access and information, and some
lawyers have begun to wonder whether the real goal may not be
winning but stalling.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor protests that he is out there personally answering
questions from the press and public every day, but some questions,
just like some citizens, fare better than others.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked recently whether former Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato was in City Hall to lobby about a soccer team, Giuliani
scoffed. D'Amato is ``just like anyone else who can come in and
talk about possibilities,'' the mayor said.
 &UR;  &LR;  Anyone else, of course, still has to get through the fence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
