<HEADLINE>
NO TREATS FOR THIS HONORED HOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's a floppy, 4-year-old basset hound from Plano, Texas. They
are the members of a 123-year-old private men's club who make or
break dogs like him with impunity. But Ch. Morningwood Ulysses S.
Grant has a bone to pick with the scions who run the Westminster
Kennel Club Dog Show.
</P>
<P>
   Why won't they let him show himself off at their show? He is,
after all, something of an Adonis for his low-slung breed.
</P>
<P>
   The 71-pound hound, nicknamed HRH _ for His Royal Highness _ by
his handler, Pat Willer, hoofed it to 65 dog shows last year and
finished 1998 ranked the second-best basset in the nation. That
more than qualified him to compete in the Westminster show at
Madison Square Garden Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not receive anything resembling royal treatment from
the dog show's entry committee. In fact, his $40 entry was refused,
because its arrival at the show superintendent's office in
Greensboro, N.C., on Nov. 12 was recorded at 8:08 a.m., one minute
after Westminster's limit of 2,500 entries had been received.
</P>
<P>
   According to show officials, entries for the 1999 show opened
and closed in a record seven minutes. By the time MB-F Inc., the
99-year-old company that manages the show and presides over its
controversial entry process, had recorded the 11th bundle of
entries delivered that morning _ the one that contained HRH's form
_ the quota had already been reached.
</P>
<P>
   Among those first 2,500 were sprinkled representatives of 152 of
the 153 breeds recognized by the American Kennel Club (only the
Finnish spitz was missing), plus a full slate of top contenders and
familiar faces.
</P>
<P>
   None of the nine bassets who made the cut have HRH's
credentials. But it's the luck of the draw that makes the process
democratic, according to Westminster administrators, who estimate
they receive 5,000 entries for the 2,500 spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a more equitable way to process the entries,
Westminster's willing to listen,'' said Thomas Bradley, a club
member who also functions as Westminster's public relations agent.
``But so far, the wheel is still round.''
</P>
<P>
   And HRH is still odd man out. So when the rest of the hounds
strut their stuff for the cameras at the Garden on Tuesday, HRH,
who stood a serious chance of going best-in-breed because of the
absence of Ch. Deer Hill's Great Gatsby, the nation's No. 1 basset
and No. 2 dog all-breeds, will be at home with Willer in Sulphur,
La.
</P>
<P>
   HRH's owner, David Keene, is so peeved on behalf of his spurned
hound that he has threatened legal action. He would not be the
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get offered bribes by owners who want their dogs let into
Westminster, we've been threatened with bodily harm by owners whose
dogs didn't get into Westminster, and we hear all the time from
lawyers who are going to investigate the entry process,'' said
Dorie Crowe, vice-president of the family-run MB-F, which
coordinates and produces dog shows across the country. Crowe denied
that anything such as a favor to other owners involved in the
refusal to admit Keene's well-respected basset to this year's show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not about to do something that could jeopardize the
reputation of a 100-year-old company for the sake of one entry,''
she said. ``We could lose our license.''
</P>
<P>
   Keene wouldn't mind seeing that; but because the recording of
entries is a closed process, he has only his raised hackles for
proof of malfeasance. A basset-loving vice-president of the Summit
Acceptance Corp in Plano, Keene is not the first owner of a
champion canine to be shut out of Westminster in what he considers
dubious circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's 10,000 people who'd like to talk about this, like to
see some accountability for how the system works, and 9,999 who are
scared to,'' he said. ``If I knew my entry got there at 1 p.m. I
wouldn't say a word, but it was signed in at 8:08 a.m. And why is
it that the very top dogs and top handlers always get in?'' Keene
said he hired a mathematician who calculated the odds of
Westminster's being able to represent its full 153-breed roster in
just seven minutes ``at four million to one.''
</P>
<P>
   Keene is the first owner to make his anger public, and fears
that if he is correct that Westminster picks and chooses among its
entries, he and his hound could find themselves blackballed next
year, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Catch-22,'' he said of his complaint. ``But let me tell
you, this really takes the wind out of your sails. It's like having
a goal, and going by the book and doing everything right that it
takes to get there, and then at the end being told you can't get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Keene and his wife, Barba, campaigned HRH heavily, and
successfully, last year, spending $50,000. After a decade in
bassets, they knew that they finally had a true champion, and more.
Which is why this hurts more.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when HRH was a puppy, Barba Keene was undergoing
chemotherapy for breast cancer. HRH, for reasons best known to him,
decided she couldn't live without him. Her sick bed was his bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd be lying there in pain, and he'd let her grab onto him
and hold him as hard as she needed to,'' David Keene said. ``They
bonded unbelievably; he was right there for her then. It's broken
her heart that he didn't get to go to Westminster this year after
he's done everything in the show ring to earn his way.''
</P>
<P>
   Willer, the dog's trainer, said, ``This year we've heard more
complaints about entries than ever.'' Willer has been in the dog
business for 30 years and terms it ``very paranoid and very
political.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the entry process is closed to us tells me all I
need to know,'' Willer said. ``I wouldn't go as ballistic as the
Keenes did, but I'm extremely disappointed we didn't make it to
Westminster. They shouldn't say they've got the most prestigious of
all the dog shows if they're not letting all the best dogs in.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
