<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MANCO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARIS MANCO, TURKISH POP STAR AND TELEVISION PERSONALITY, DIES AT
56
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ISTANBUL _ The folk and pop singer Baris Manco, who had great
cultural influence in Turkey and became one of the country's most
beloved figures, died here on Monday. He was 56 and lived in
Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people, many in tears, turned out on
Wednesday for his funeral, which was broadcast live on national
television. ``Today, we as a nation feel pain in our hearts for
having lost a great artist and a good friend,'' Culture Minister
Istemihan Talay said in his eulogy.
</P>
<P>
   Manco wrote and recorded more than 200 songs, many of which not
only became hits on the pop charts but also found their way into
the rural popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   He was an arresting personality who dressed outlandishly in
clothes he designed himself, and he covered his fingers with rings.
In the 1970s, when Turkey had only a single state-owned television
channel, he was offered appearances on condition that he cut his
flowing hair. He refused, and the authorities finally relented,
making him the first representative of the alternative youth
culture to appear on Turkish television.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his songs, Manco was known widely for his weekly
television program. He was its host for nearly a decade, making it
the longest-running Turkish television show. The first segment was
aimed at young people, and a generation of Turks grew up with his
children's songs, like ``My Friend the Donkey.''
</P>
<P>
   The second part consisted of travel documentaries. Manco
traveled continually, and his documentaries helped educate Turks
about foreign countries, peoples and cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Besides bringing the world into Turkish living rooms, he was
also an unofficial Turkish ambassador. His songs were translated
into many languages, and he was awarded official honors in several
countries. He had wide followings in Arab countries, Central Asia
and the Caucasus and was especially popular in Japan, where he
produced children's programs.
</P>
<P>
   In a flood of front-page commentaries after his death, Turkish
newspapers hailed him as one of the few Turks who managed to bridge
the gap between the educated elite and common people.
</P>
<P>
   Manco was born in Istanbul on Jan. 2, 1943, and began his career
by founding a rock band when he was in high school. He studied
graphic design and textile design in Belgium, where he was later
made a Chevalier of the Order of Leopold II. He is survived by his
wife, Lale, and two sons, Dogukan and Batikan.
</P>
<P>
   An avid collector, Manco had a fleet of British cars from the
1950s and important collections of Japanese and Chinese porcelain,
19th-century Orientalist paintings and Art Deco and Art Nouveau
glassware.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his proudest possession, however, was his first name,
which means ``peace'' in Turkish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
