A4520 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTHRAX07-COX     02-06 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHRAX07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking spotlight off anthrax threats lessens incidents in some
cities
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Anthrax. It is everywhere and nowhere. And in between
are dozens of local and federal law enforcement, fire and health
departments running ragged in response to threats of the deadly
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Attorney's Office in Buffalo, N.Y. A night club in Los
Angeles. An abortion provider in Wichita, Kan. A Catholic school in
Indianapolis. All have been victims of anthrax scares in the past
six months.
</P>
<P>
   To date, every threat of anthrax contamination in the United
States has been false, according to the FBI, which leads
investigations into such cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI views these as the bomb threats of the '90s,'' said
Paul Moskal, an FBI agent in Buffalo, where a spate of anthrax
threats received last month was partially linked to teen-agers.
``Given the world situation, you have to take these threats
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason: airborne anthrax is deadly. If spores of the
bacteria, naturally found in livestock, get into a person's lungs,
their toxins can multiply rapidly, causing severe illness or death.
For more than a decade, terrorists have threatened to use anthrax
to wage germ warfare in the United States and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Cities that have lived through numerous anthrax threats and
``copycat'' scares, such as Buffalo and Los Angeles, have developed
an effective response.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to downplay it and low-key it,'' said Moskal. ``The
threats died down here after the local media didn't cover them.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories about anthrax threats no longer make the front page of
the Buffalo News. Typically, they are briefs inside the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's response Thursday to an anthrax scare at Midtown's
Colony Square is typical for a first-time threat: a swarm of
firetrucks, police, ambulances, FBI agents, terrorism experts,
public health officials and a Hazmat team dressed in special blue
suits made for chemical and biological warfare. Buildings are
evacuated, streets sealed off, temporary shower stalls erected and
decontamination rituals undertaken to remove the invisible germ.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain procedures are in place and have to be followed. Until
we determine what the substance is, we don't treat them as
hoaxes,'' said Jay Spadafore of Atlanta's FBI office. ``I don't
even like to use the word `hoax.' They are all felonies.''
</P>
<P>
   Conviction of deploying _ or threatening to use _ a chemical or
biological weapon of mass destruction could result in life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``People caught will be punished and punished severely,'' said
Moskal. ``These are not pranks. This is not like pulling the fire
alarm at school. Lives are put in danger responding to these
calls.''
</P>
<P>
   The calls also tie up police, firefighters and paramedics, who
could be responding to legitimate emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, the cost of responding to one anthrax incident
was estimated by at $50,000. Southern California stores, nightclubs
and schools were among the targets of a round of threats in
November and December.
</P>
<P>
   But after three false alarms, L.A. emergency officials took
another tack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met with all the principals involved in response and with
the FBI, and the FBI told us if you don't send out the red lights
and sirens to these calls, the (copycat anthrax) threats would
trickle off, and sure enough they did,'' said Darrell Higuchi,
deputy chief of the L.A. County Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Anthrax threats now are handled in the same manner as bomb
threats in Los Angeles, Higuchi said. The police dispatch just one
special team to the scene that then quickly assess the credibility
of the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of ways of assessing the credibility of these
threats, but we can't really going around discussing them,''
Higuchi said. ``We don't want people knowing what we do know and
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``We haven't had any (anthrax) threats since the
seven incidents in late November and December.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
