<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Costs of gun violence difficult to trace
 &HT;    WITH NRA-INFLUENCE
 &HT;    By Carlos Campos
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the city of Atlanta filed suit against 14 gun
makers last week, it claimed that taxpayers have for too long borne
the cost of police, emergency services and other expenses related
to the deaths and injuries caused by their products.
</P>
<P>
   But putting a price tag on those costs is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the attempts that have been made focus not on police
costs, but on health care costs associated with treating gunshot
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Although the city is asking for millions of dollars, Mayor Bill
Campbell could not provide the specific costs the city must bear
due to homicides, suicides and accidental shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not do health-related issues, but nevertheless, there
are of course costs that we suffer, police costs ... just the
incalculable cost of family tragedy,'' the mayor said. ``I think
it's incalculable, really.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based Centers for Disease Control and Prevention,
which has declared gun violence a national epidemic, hasn't
attempted to assign a public cost to gun-related deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to measure the costs of gun violence even on a
medical level,'' said Grady Memorial Hospital emergency room
physician Dr. Arthur Kellerman, who also heads Emory University's
Injury Control Center. ``One, very few cities have systematically
collected information on the magnitude of their gun problems. And
second, one of the biggest issues in gun violence is the long-term
disability and length of recovery for gun violence victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulton and DeKalb county taxpayers, who contribute between $90
and $100 million per year to Grady, often end up absorbing the cost
of caring for gunshot victims, Kellerman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The costs are very real and they're not often borne by the
victims,'' Kellerman said. ``A substantial percentage of victims in
urban areas, and in rural areas, don't have health inurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there have been several attempts to put a cost on
gun-related deaths and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Vernick, professor of public health and associate director
of the Johns Hopkins Center for Gun Policy &AMP; Research, said widely
cited research includes:
</P>
<P>
   _ A study published in 1995 in the Journal of American Medical
Association in which a professor at the University of California at
Davis estimated the national health care costs for gun-related
injuries at $4 billion for one year.
</P>
<P>
   _ A 1992 study by another University of California at Davis
professor, estimating that 80 percent of health care costs for
gun-related injuries are borne by taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Vernick noted that those studies only look at health care costs,
not police costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post in 1997 traced the costs to taxpayers of
treating a teen-ager paralyzed after he was struck by a stray
bullet. In just 14 months, the cost of a trial, the teenager's
medical treatment and rehabilitation, and the convicted defendant's
prison stay totaled $268,496. The newspaper estimated that future
costs could climb as high as $1.79 million _ for a single shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
