A4522 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NRA-INFLUENCE07-COX     02-06 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NRA-INFLUENCE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NRA continues to influence Southern politics
 &HT;    By Charles Walston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In Southern politics, the postcard listing the
endorsements of the National Rifle Association is a powerful
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Although opponents of the nation's largest gun rights group say
its clout in Washington has declined, they admit the NRA still
wields enormous influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are places where the NRA endorsement is the kiss of
death,'' said Kristen Rand, director of federal policy for the
Violence Policy Center, a Washington-based anti-gun group. ``But
they still have a lot of power in a lot of Southern legislatures.''
</P>
<P>
   That has been demonstrated this year in states such as Georgia,
where the NRA is pushing a bill that would outlaw lawsuits against
gun manufacturers by local governments. The city of Atlanta filed
such a suit Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill easily passed the House and unanimously cleared the
Senate Public Safety Committee, but hit a snag on the Senate floor
Friday when some Atlanta Democrats teamed with Republicans to delay
it on a procedural vote. The Republicans indicated, however, that
they voted against the measure only in an effort to expand it to
the manufacturers of all products, not just guns.
</P>
<P>
   While Atlanta is the fifth city to file a lawsuit against gun
makers, Georgia is the first state where the NRA has tried to pass
a bill to block such suits, said James Baker, the NRA's chief
lobbyist. The choice to fight the battle here is no coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Georgia is one of our stronger states,'' said Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia lawmakers who would defy the NRA face a double-barreled
threat: votes and money.
</P>
<P>
   The group claims 93,000 members in Georgia, and most of them
vote, said Baker. Hence the power of the orange postcards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our members are very much activists when it comes to
their gun rights,'' said Baker. ``They also vote in a higher
percentage than the population at large, which makes them a very
potent force in any election or legislative battle.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to rallying its troops behind candidates it
endorses, the NRA is a generous campaign contributor. The group's
political action committee spent about $5 million in federal and
local races around the country last year, according to reports it
filed.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, the NRA Political Victory Fund gave $52,321 to state
and local candidates in 1998, and $41,550 to federal candidates. In
1997, the Victory Fund gave $21,500 to state candidates.
</P>
<P>
   All of the federal candidates in Georgia who got NRA money last
year were Republicans, reflecting the group's national leaning. But
the Victory Fund also supported many Democrats in state races,
including Gov. Roy Barnes, who got the maximum $5,000 contribution
from the group.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
