<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Feb. 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dry and chilly conditions will return to the Northeast on Sunday
as high pressure builds near Lake Huron and circulates Canadian air
into New England. Brisk winds and a few flurries will begin the day
in the northern Appalachians, but sunshine will dominate along the
North Atlantic coast. Clouds will stream into southern New England
by the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A disturbance developing over the lower Ohio Valley will spread
a shield of clouds and rain from eastern Missouri to the Middle
Atlantic states. The northern edge of the precipitation should
stretch from near Chicago to Cleveland. Wet snow may develop from
central Pennsylvania to southern New England on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   A wedge of very mild, moist air will occupy the eastern Gulf
states. Drier air pushing east from Texas will trigger several
strong thunderstorms in the South. Florida and the Southeast Coast
will remain bright and quite warm.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific air flowing east from the northern Rockies will
encounter cold air over the northeast Plains. Clouds will thicken
and a little snow may fall near the border. A cold front crossing
the Rockies will be accompanied by gusty showers in the valleys and
heavy wet snow on the west-facing slopes of the mountains. Onshore
winds will reach gale force from northern California to Vancouver
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain will drench central and northern California with
flooding possible in some sections. High pressure in the Four
Corners region will promote dry and more pleasant conditions for
the desert Southwest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Feast or Famine  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It has been a real roller coaster pattern of wet and dry across
the Northeast and Middle Atlantic states this past year. So far,
1999 has been quite wet. Since January 1st, Boston has accumulated
more than 7 inches of rain and melted snow while nearby New York
City registered its fifth-wettest January. The moist conditions are
similar to the start of 1998, when New York measured its wettest
first-six-month period of record. In between the two moist periods,
however, the region was very dry, with both New York and Boston
averaging monthly precipitation deficits of between 2 and 3 inches.
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
