u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-HISTORY-PARKING-NY     02-06 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-HISTORY-PARKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORNING RUSH HITS A SNAG CALLED HISTORY 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARSIPPANY-TROY HILLS , N.J. _ In suburban New Jersey, as in
most auto-dependent societies, a worker's day usually begins in a
car backing out of a driveway. Physical principles being what they
are, there has to be a parking space at the end of that trip.
</P>
<P>
   For Mike Lassell of Lake Hopatcong, that crucial space is at the
Beverwyck Park and Ride here. His daily challenge is to find one in
time to catch the green-and-white Lakeland bus before it pulls out
for the 45-minute trip to Manhattan, where he works as a medical
records analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting here early is the key,'' Lassell said on a chilly
morning last week, ``especially if the weather's bad. If it's
snowing, people dump their cars and jump on the bus, and this place
fills up early.''
</P>
<P>
   But try as he might _ Lassell leaves his house about 6:30 each
morning _ he and his fellow commuters are in one sense hopelessly
late. They had been expecting a roomier parking lot and an easier
start to the day, but their hopes have run up against someone who
got here even earlier than they. Much earlier.
</P>
<P>
   George Washington, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Because of high demand, the Town of Parsippany-Troy Hills and
the State Department of Transportation decided more than a year ago
to double the number of spaces at the lot to about 400 by expanding
it down the hill it occupies along U.S. Highway 46.
</P>
<P>
   No one was too surprised when the first bites by the backhoes
exposed an early habitation. Road engineers are used to doing
accidental archeology in this old and densely populated state.
Digging for state road 29 south of Trenton, for example, uncovered
the remains of a house that Gen. Washington had ordered burned in
1777 because its owners were Tories. Work on state road 55 in South
Jersey brought up early Indian settlements.
</P>
<P>
   But the ruins at the Beverwyck site turned out to be more than
ordinary: local historians determined that they were the remains of
a manor house, the seat of the 2,000-acre estate of Lucas Von
Beverhoudt, a gentleman farmer and rum importer. It was he who
named the estate Beverwyck.
</P>
<P>
   ``A northern Mount Vernon,'' said John Dourgarian of the State
Department of Transportation. A place Washington and his officers
must have visited. Work stopped for further exploration, and
drivers fumed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's infuriating,'' said Edward Ruhl, a Manhattan banker who
drives in from the farm country near the Pennsylvania line. ``They
tell us to get out of our cars and take public transportation, but
they hold us up on our parking for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Angry commuters wrote to transportation officials demanding that
work resume. Pressured by commuters and local officials, the state
decided last fall to continue with plans for the park-and-ride.
</P>
<P>
   Then archeologists played their trump card: Beverwyck was not
just about Colonial times, they said in public letters and phone
calls to officials and reporters, but about slavery and therefore
race. A 1769 advertisement described the farm's slave holdings, and
shackles were found there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The archeology of this site promises to be of surpassing
interest to those of African descent as well as to scholars in
general,'' R. Alan Mounier, the president of the Archeological
Society of New Jersey, wrote to the State Commissioner of
Transportation in December. The Archeological Conservancy, a
national organization, offered to take over the site.
</P>
<P>
   Public officials decided to start looking for another bus stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got two very valid social issues here: the need to
preserve our history and the need to preserve our environment by
getting people out of their cars and into mass transit,'' said Mimi
Letts, the mayor of Parsippany-Troy Hills. ``And what we have here
are those two very basic issues coming head to head with each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   The state, which owns the land, has not decided who will
administer the site, but it will not become a park-and-ride.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
