<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUNTING-LICENSES07-CO     02-06 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNTING-LICENSES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hunting in cyberspace
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An article about the decline in hunting license sales
in the February 1999 issue of Gun World magazine sent tremors
through America's hunting community. It would have done the same
for the hunting industry, but businessmen already had felt the
impact of the loss, nationwide, of some 296,000 hunting license
sales in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The loss supported figures by some who predicted that hunting
would be almost nonexistent in America by the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
   Such a prospect made the industry rumble into motion last year
in a search for the cause of the problem and a solution.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, it turns out, is nebulous. The possible reasons
include the price of the license, hunting access, wildlife
management programs, game populations, hunting regulations,
urbanization and industrialization, weather and even the
installation of a new record-keeping system. They're still trying
to pin it down.
</P>
<P>
   Solutions? Some were introduced at last week's SHOT (Shooting,
Hunting, Outdoor Trade) Show at the Georgia World Congress Center.
</P>
<P>
   The show, sponsored by the National Shooting Sports Foundation,
is billed as the world's premier exposition of firearms,
ammunition, archery, cutlery, outdoor apparel, optics, camping and
related products services.
</P>
<P>
   Some 17,000 buyers from around the world were there to stock up
for next year. What they heard from Buckmasters should be
comforting.
</P>
<P>
   When the 400,000-member deer-hunting organization based in
Montgomery was still in its infancy, founder and CEO Jackie Bushman
said the biggest problem he faced was having some kind of overall
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike waterfowl, turkeys or other game with organizations named
after them, Buckmasters couldn't mount drives to save the deer.
Endangerment isn't a white-tail deer problem.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, Buckmasters did come out with a plan to save an
endangered species: the hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Bushman is putting the fate of the industry in the hands of
children with a cutting edge tool, a hand-held computer game.
</P>
<P>
   Called Buckmasters Deer Huntin, this $25 toy could be a powerful
recruiting instrument for urban kids who can't get into the woods
anytime they want but sure know their way around a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Trading on kids' love of outdoor games, Radica, which produces
Buckmasters Deer Huntin, also produces the best-selling Sport Bass
Fishin, Lunker Bass Fishin and Ultimate Bass Fishin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't get 'em out in the woods, let's bring the woods to
them,'' Bushman said.
</P>
<P>
   Deer Huntin does it, offering a virtual hunting training ground
each time it's played.
</P>
<P>
   In the same news conference, Bushman also announced that GT
Interactive Software will publish a Buckmasters hunting game for
PCs.
</P>
<P>
   GTIS is the company that produces Deer Hunter and Deer Hunter
II. Deer Hunter was the No. 2 seller in the PC games industry, and
the new Deer Hunter II currently leads the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Buckmasters' theory: ``Get 'em interested on the computer, and
some are bound to go do the real thing.''
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS GADGETS
</P>
<P>
   Rekindling interest in hunting is just one facet of a show that
requires four days to cover from end to end.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of useful and neat products are on the way. A few
examples are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Genesis knife: Michael Collins introduced the Genesis,
manufactured by Edge Design, Inc. The knife appears to be yet
another tactical folder but in fact is a practical, multipurpose
tool with some thoughtful engineering. The drop-point blade is the
difference. Named Best Buy of the Year at the 1999 Blade Show, the
Genesis retails from $129.99. Info: (314) 863-3343, (770) 428-6870,
http://www.ediknives.com
</P>
<P>
   _ Survival in a Sardine Can: This little package is packed with
pain killers, antibiotics, matches, bouillon, a tea bag,
dehydration tablets, chewing gum, a fish hook and line, a razor
blade, a waterproof bag, a signal mirror, a fire starter cube and
more. Suggested retail: $12. Info: (719) 488-1999.
</P>
<P>
   _ Swiss-Tech ScrewZall: In about three years, Larry Legg's first
invention, the Swiss-Tech Micro Technician has produced about $4
million in sales. Legg keeps on inventing, and his latest product,
the ScrewZall, features a key-ring-sized set of screwdrivers, four
in all (two Phillips, two flatheads), and a key ring to go with it.
Suggested retail: $12.95. Info: (800) 414-8799;
http://www.swisstechtools.com
</P>
<P>
   _ KaDooty: With primitive weapons season about to expand in
Georgia with the probable addition of a black-powder season, the
KaDooty will be popular with archers and muzzle-loader fans. With
muzzle-loaders, it's a ram rod, cleaning rod, super tamper and
bullet extractor. With a bow, it's a fully adjustable bow
stabilizer. Suggested retail: $149. Info: (318) 477-7502,
http://www.kadooty.com
</P>
<P>
   _ La Griffe: The handiest thing knife builder Ernie Emerson had
at the SHOT Show hangs on a string around the neck. Called La
Griffe _ French for claw _ it's about 3 inches long with a
claw-shaped blade. The handle has holes in it for a better grip.
Police types like it for a backup weapon, but the shape and the
secure grip make it a great little tool for field-dressing a deer.
Suggested retail: $69. Info: 310-542-3050,
http://www.emersonknives.com
</P>
<P>
   _ Pocket Chain saw: One of the most effective tools at the show
comes in a can about the size of a can of shoe polish. Inside is a
28-inch length of chain saw with 124 bidirectional teeth, plus two
rings that connect to each end. Put sticks through the rings, put
the saw on some wood and cut away. Suggested retail: $19.95. Info:
(248) 588-1150.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
