<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN EMBASSY ATTACKS IS FORBIDDEN TO CALL MOSQUE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Texas) (bl) 
By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A new dispute has broken out in the prosecution of
the embassy bombings in Africa over the government's refusal to
allow a defendant to make a phone call to a Muslim leader in
Arlington, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Wadih el Hage, a naturalized U.S. citizen who had
lived in Arlington, had asked to speak to the imam of a mosque
there in the hope that other members of the congregation would
contribute to his bail.
</P>
<P>
   But a federal prosecutor told Judge Leonard Sand of U.S.
District Court in Manhattan last week that the government ``has
specific concerns'' about the imam, Moataz Al-Hallak, who leads the
Islamic Society of Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors did not elaborate about those concerns in court and
declined comment after the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute comes amid a debate about the restrictive conditions
under which the suspects are being held in New York. El Hage and
his co-defendants are imprisoned in the Metropolitan Correctional
Center under a rarely used rule that allows officials to strictly
limit an inmate's contacts to prevent future ``acts of violence and
terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the provision, officials may segregate inmates and
restrict their mail, visits, phone calls and interviews with the
news media. The government may take the action when it believes
there is substantial risk that an inmate's communications ``could
result in death or serious bodily injury,'' the rule says.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Hallak, who has not previously been mentioned in the case or
been charged with any crime, said the government's concerns were
baseless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what they are talking about,'' Al-Hallak said
when he was reached by phone last week. He said his mosque was
religious and educational, and that he condemned violence. ``We are
just people focusing on a humble mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Hallak said that el Hage was well liked in their community
and that he found the allegations against him difficult to accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Hage, as far as we know, is 100 percent innocent,''
Al-Hallak said. ``But if it is proven that he is guilty, we're the
first to condemn this action. But you cannot start dealing with
people as the communist countries used to, that everybody is guilty
until he is proven innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   In court last Tuesday, el Hage's lawyer, Bruce McIntyre, told
Sand that if the phone call was permitted, it would be in English
and that he expected it to be monitored by the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Because prosecutors have refused to specify their concerns, it
is impossible to know precisely what they fear might happen if el
Hage speaks with the imam.
</P>
<P>
   But the language of the rule suggests that they believe el Hage
might try to use Al-Hallak to pass along a coded message.
</P>
<P>
   In court records, prosecutors have asserted that el Hage is
deeply involved in a terrorist organization led by Osama bin Laden,
the Saudi exile suspected of organizing the embassy attacks in
August.
</P>
<P>
   El Hage, whom prosecutors describe as the former personal
secretary to bin Laden, has been indicted on charges that he
conspired with bin Laden to kill Americans abroad, and that he lied
to federal investigators.
</P>
<P>
   In one document, the government accused el Hage of living ``a
life of deception'' and ``acting as a front for a terrorist
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   El Hage has pleaded not guilty to the charges.
</P>
<P>
   One clue to the government's position may lie in the extradition
papers the United States has filed against another suspect in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   That suspect, Khalid al-Fawwaz, has been accused of helping to
disseminate bin Laden's calls for attacks on Americans around the
world. In the extradition papers, the government has included
international phone records that, they say, belong to al-Fawwaz and
show how he spread bin Laden's message around the world. One 1995
call went to the Arlington mosque.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Hallak, who said he has been at the mosque 12 years, said he
had never heard of al-Fawwaz, and did not remember such a call.
``Even if he called our organization, by itself, it doesn't mean
anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In court last week, McIntyre said el Hage wanted to speak with
Al-Hallak merely to assure him that he would return to court if
freed on bail.
</P>
<P>
   But with the government opposing bail on any terms, Sand seemed
disinclined to allow the phone call.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no point in having some broad petition submitted to
members of the congregation of the mosque'' if the exercise is not
going to be meaningful, Sand said. It would ``just raise false
expectations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a typical case,'' he added, ``and the government
has made known its concerns with respect to communications.''
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre said after the court hearing that he planned to move
expeditiously to seek bail for el Hage, even without the phone
call. He contends that el Hage has strong ties to Arlington: he had
worked in a tire shop there, his family still lived there and he
had helped out in the mosque.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's precisely the type of person who should be given bail,''
McIntyre said.
</P>
</TEXT>
