</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BATTERY-REAL-940(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILLING IN THE BLANKS AT BATTERY PARK CITY
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I get a headache if I don't hear the sound of
piledrivers,'' said James Gill, the chairman of the Battery Park
City Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Hold the aspirin.
</P>
<P>
   So many projects are under way at Battery Park City that the
92-acre landfill along the Hudson River, a once-blank slate on
which politicians and planners have been writing for four decades,
is actually running out of room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going like the hammers of hell,'' Gill said. Two
thousand apartments in eight buildings, a Ritz-Carlton and an
Embassy Suites hotel, an addition to the Museum of Jewish
Heritage-A Living Memorial to the Holocaust and a home for the
Skyscraper Museum, two public schools, four ferry slips and a
15-screen multiplex are newly finished, in construction or being
designed. If Gill had his way, the recently merged National
Association of Securities Dealers and American Stock Exchange would
be in the mix, too.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the current boom involves 10 of the remaining 18
undeveloped parcels. And Gill said he has ``every intention'' of
allocating the rest of the available lots on his watch. ``Battery
Park City sat doing nothing for a long time,'' he said. ``I want to
get as much built as is humanly possible while the market
continues.''
</P>
<P>
   John La Mura, the president and chief executive of the
authority, underscored a ``need to reflect carefully'' on what
comes next. ``If commercial buildings in lower Manhattan are
becoming residential,'' he said, ``where do people recreate? If the
residents who live here say, `We enjoy this ratio of open space,'
with each new apartment building, that ratio diminishes.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she does not always see eye-to-eye with the authority,
Anne Compoccia, the chairwoman of Community Board 1 in lower
Manhattan, agrees that things are advancing quickly at Battery Park
City _ too quickly. ``They should slow down and think about what
they're doing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, growth always induces growing pains, and Battery Park
City is not immune. The loss of open space has meant the eviction
of Cirque du Soleil, which pitched its tent for 10 years on the
landfill. A six-year struggle has yet to be resolved between the
authority and the unit owners in the Hudson View West condominium
over the ground rent and payments in lieu of real-estate taxes. And
the expansion plans at the Holocaust memorial have been postponed
for the moment by a dispute over financing between Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   There is also much tension between Gill and La Mura, both
appointees of Pataki, although they insist it has not hampered
significant decisions.
</P>
<P>
   More substantively, the authority is torn between its fiduciary
responsibility to get top dollar for development sites, its
municipal responsibility to make Battery Park City a lively
citywide attraction and its social responsibility to insure that
neighborhoods are diverse and desirable.
</P>
<P>
   A tug-of-war between the community and the authority over an
``interim'' ballfield, for example, was only partly resolved by the
authority's assurance that the field will be made permanent. The
question now is what happens to the development potential _ 870,000
square feet, roughly 870 apartments _ represented by the baseball
diamonds, tennis and basketball courts. Gill said the total value
of the land if fully developed would be $100 million. Were the
authority to forgo that revenue, he said, it would amount to ``the
most expensive Little League field in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   What the authority will do instead is shift most of the unused
development rights _ perhaps 700,000 square feet _ to other parcels
in the north neighborhood, which will yield larger buildings on
those sites than were called for in the master plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more we develop,'' Gill said, ``the more revenue we
generate.''
</P>
<P>
   The authority estimates it will turn over $44 million to New
York City this year, after operating expenses of $21 million and
debt service of $65 million on $1 billion in bonds. Total revenues
are $131 million, of which $119 million comes from ground rents and
payments in lieu of real estate taxes. The authority owns the land
and leases it to developers until the year 2069.
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter of the operating budget goes to maintain the
generously landscaped parkland, which is the prime attraction of
Battery Park City to many New Yorkers _ and a lure for development.
``I look at it as leveraged money,'' said Robert Serpico, the
authority's chief financial officer. ``You're spending money to
make money.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty percent of the space at Battery Park City was set aside
for parks, plazas and esplanades under the 1979 master plan by the
architects Alexander Cooper and Stanton Eckstut, during the
chairmanship of Richard Kahan. The plan called for 14,000 housing
units (4,550 have been built and 2,000 are in the pipeline) and 6
million square feet of commercial space, a goal that was met by the
World Financial Center and exceeded with the construction two years
ago of the New York Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The original plan of 1969 envisioned a population of 50,000 _
two-thirds of them middle- and low-income families _ and employment
for 35,000.
</P>
<P>
   Today, some 40,000 people work in the World Financial Center,
including the Mercantile Exchange and its Commodity Exchange
division. About 8,000 people live in Battery Park City, but it is a
far less diverse population than was envisioned. ``We've got too
many yuppies,'' Gill said. ``I mean, we like yuppies. But enough
already.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want Battery Park City to be an elitist community,''
he said. ``I don't think that's healthy for any community.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To broaden the age mix, the authority has awarded a development
site in the north neighborhood to Brookdale Living Communities of
Chicago, a national builder of high-end, independent-living
quarters for the elderly. Its 14-story, 220-unit building, the
Hallmark, was designed by Lucien Lagrange and Schuman Lichtenstein
Claman Efron. The $50 million project is to open next year.
</P>
<P>
   Residents will have to be at least 62 years old. Fees are to run
from $3,400 a month for a studio apartment to $8,500 for a
two-bedroom unit with a den, which is to include daily breakfasts
and 20 dinners, housekeeping and linen service, some utilities, a
health clinic in the building and other features.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the amenities that Battery Park City has to offer as it
gets built up, it's a great place to retire and grow old,'' said
Mark Schulte, president and chief executive of Brookdale.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the authority is encouraging more families
with children to settle in Battery Park City through the
construction of larger apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started to develop the north, we put an emphasis on
family-sized apartments,'' said Enid Feist, vice president for
policy and operations at the authority.
</P>
<P>
   In Tribeca Bridge Tower, which the authority developed itself
and now plans to sell, there are no studio apartments and only 21
one-bedroom units. But there are 128 two- and three-bedroom units.
Depending on size and location, a three-bedroom apartment rents for
$4,500 to $6,000 a month. The authority set aside 30 apartments for
families who cannot afford those rents but earn too much to qualify
for the ``80-20'' program. The architects were Costas Kondylis,
John R. Menz &AMP; Richard Cook and Pasanella &AMP; Klein Stolzman &AMP; Berg.
</P>
<P>
   At the base of the tower is Public School-Intermediate School
89, with room for 850 students, which opened in September. ``If you
live in our building, you can send your kid down the hall to
school,'' Gill said. ``If the kid is smart enough when he gets to
high school level, he can go to Stuyvesant'' _ right across
Chambers Street.
</P>
<P>
   Another step toward economic integration is ``80-20'' housing,
in which 80 percent of the apartments are rented at market rates
and 20 percent are subsidized and made available to those earning
50 percent or less of the median income for New York City. In
return, developers obtain real-estate tax abatements and
lower-interest financing through tax-exempt bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Compoccia said that was far from a panacea. ``I'm
middle-class,'' she said. ``For argument's sake, give me the
opportunity to live in a place like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Four new buildings at Battery Park City are in the ``80-20''
program:
</P>
<P>
   _ River Watch, a 9-story building with 209 units, developed by
the Brodsky Organization and designed by Hardy Holzman Pfeiffer
Associates and Schuman Lichtenstein. Occupancy is expected in June.
</P>
<P>
   _ A 9-story building (yet to be named) with 208 units, developed
by the DeMatteis Organization and designed by the same team as
River Walk. Occupancy is expected late this year or early in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tribeca Park, a 27-story building with 395 units, developed by
the Related Companies and designed by Robert A.M. Stern and
Kondylis. It is to open in May.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tribeca Pointe, a 43-story tower with 340 units, by Rockrose
Development Corp. Tenants have begun moving in.
</P>
<P>
   Tribeca Pointe dramatically illustrates the impact of the
``80-20'' program. Two-bedroom apartments rent on the market for
$3,285 to $4,760 a month. But a family of four with a total annual
income between $19,090 and $25,100 could have qualified for a
two-bedroom apartment at $525 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's truly like winning the lottery,'' said Kevin Singleton,
vice president and general manager of Rockrose Development. Chance
does figure into it, since priority is determined by numbers
assigned to the applications as they are randomly pulled from mail
bags. There were more than 3,000 applicants for 70 apartments at
Tribeca Pointe, said Sofia Estevez of Rockrose.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Rockrose was designated the developer of a site at
21 River Terrace in the north end. Designed by Gruzen Samton, the
27-story building will have 300 to 330 units. None will be
subsidized. And Rockrose will pay the equivalent of full
real-estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   A significant footnote at 21 River Terrace is that one of the
bidders was Avalon Bay Communities, a real-estate investment trust
based in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing that has changed recently is that
national real estate companies are responding to the authority's
RFPs,'' said Jon McMillan, vice president of the Landmark America
development concern in Portland, Maine, and former planning
director at Battery Park City.
</P>
<P>
   Other national companies arriving at Battery Park City include
Promus Hotel Corp. of Memphis, Tenn., which is allied with Forest
City Ratner Companies in the construction of a $163 million,
14-story mixed-use project on Vesey Street, which is to be
completed in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Bisected by a 140-foot-high, art-filled public atrium, the
building will contain a 4,000-seat multiplex operated by Regal
Cinemas of Knoxville, Tenn., which calls itself the largest motion
picture exhibitor in the world; a 463-room Embassy Suites Hotel and
a New York Sports Club. The architects are Perkins Eastman, with
interiors designed by Alexandra Champalimaud.
</P>
<P>
   The next hotel at Battery Park City, opening in 2001, is to be a
250-room Ritz-Carlton, which will occupy the lower floors of a
38-story tower planned by Millennium Partners on the southernmost
parcel. The deluxe hotel chain, based in Atlanta, has not been in
New York for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The $175 million project includes a permanent, rent-free home
for the Skyscraper Museum, which has wandered from space to space
since its founding three years ago. On the 14th floor will be a
restaurant with an outdoor terrace overlooking the harbor. Above
that will be 150 condominiums. The architects are Gary Edward
Handel &AMP; Associates and the Polshek Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In designing the tower, the architects attempted to move beyond
the existing esthetic in the residential neighborhoods, where
guidelines carefully specify traditional-looking brick and masonry
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   While the north side of the Ritz-Carlton Downtown will hew to
that, the south and west facades will have a 35-story curtain wall
of glass, representing a ``more progressive esthetic,'' said Todd
Schliemann, a partner in the Polshek firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lighthouse'' was a word used both by Schliemann and by Scott
Keller, a partner in Gruzen Samton, which designed Tribeca Pointe
at the opposite end of Battery Park City, also with a broad expanse
of glass in its upper floors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a beacon for the whole of Battery Park City,''
Keller said. ``As such, it should reflect not only the residential
buildings but the office buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   With the two critical end sites accounted for, the authority is
focusing on a huge parcel in the middle, Site 26, north of the
World Financial Center. Officials estimate it could accommodate 1.4
million square feet of commercial development. It was in play last
year as a possible site for the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   World Financial Properties, the successor to Olympia &AMP; York,
which owns and manages the World Financial Center, has proposed
building a new home for the National Association of Securities
Dealers and American Stock Exchange on Site 26.
</P>
<P>
   NASD chief administrative officer Michael Jones said last week
that Battery Park City ``certainly could be'' a site but that no
decision had been made yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to see Nasdaq-Amex decide to stay downtown,'' said
Carl Weisbrod, president of the Alliance for Downtown New York.
``And certainly one of the most attractive sites downtown is
Battery Park City.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Mercantile Exchange chairman Daniel Rappaport believes
it might be especially fruitful if Nasdaq and Amex were only a
block away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having them as neighbors would lead us perhaps to becoming
more involved in joint ventures.'' Rappaport said.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange is one of the most surprising features of Battery
Park City, in that nothing about its restrained, gray-flannel
facade betrays the sheer pandemonium within, where two
25,000-square-foot trading floors seethe with hundreds of brokers
and traders swarming around circular pits.
</P>
<P>
   Clad in the eye-popping colors of a medieval pageant, shouting
and gesturing wildly, they buy and sell futures and options in
crude oil, heating oil, gasoline, natural gas, platinum, copper,
silver and gold.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Shearman, a natural gas trader, said he liked the extra
room in the ring, better places to eat and a gym in the building.
But the biggest change in his routine since the exchange moved from
the World Trade Center is that he commutes by ferry. ``It's a nice
little ride across the river,'' he said, ``and I'm right at the
building.''
</P>
<P>
   Shearman is in good company. About 13,000 passengers a day use
the small, floating ferry terminal. The Port Authority of New York
and New Jersey is planning a permanent new one, doubling its
capacity to four slips. The $24 million project is to open in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing West Street to Battery Park City sometimes seems like
more of a challenge than crossing the Hudson, especially for
children, the elderly or disabled. There are three pedestrian
bridges over the roadway but the elevators are not yet working at
the bridge that joins the north end to Tribeca. The authority is
considering a fourth bridge, around Morris Street, La Mura said, as
a link the burgeoning south neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   With the perspective of 20 years and 20-20 hindsight, Eckstut
said one problem with the 1979 plan was the necessary assumption
that the Westway highway would be built along the Hudson River,
affecting the orientation of Battery Park City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The project essentially turns its back to the city,'' said
Eckstut, now a principal in Ehrenkrantz, Eckstut &AMP; Kuhn. While he
sees things in need of ``tweaking'' _ the listless retail space in
the World Financial Center, the lack of meaningful waterfront
activity _ Eckstut sounded generally satisfied with the plan as it
evolved. ``It really feels and looks like New York, which was our
goal,'' Eckstut said. Where development has veered from the plan,
he finds it is usually positive. For instance, he said, ``There's a
whole emerging cultural district that we never anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   That district is anchored by the Museum of Jewish Heritage and
Holocaust memorial, completed in 1997 to designs by Kevin Roche,
with interiors by Patrick Gallagher.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is planning a $44 million east wing, containing an
auditorium, galleries and viewing rooms for the archives of Steven
Spielberg's Survivors of the Shoah Visual History Foundation. Roche
and Gallagher would collaborate again.
</P>
<P>
   New York museums are typically knit to the surrounding urban
fabric but a visit to the Museum of Jewish Heritage helps dispel
the sense of incongruity in its isolated location at Manhattan's
tip.
</P>
<P>
   After circling the windowless first-floor galleries on Jewish
life a century ago, then the windowless second-floor galleries on
the Holocaust, a visitor arrives at a hexagonal rotunda on the
third floor, with a tall glass case enclosing a Torah scroll that
was to have been exhibited in a museum of the ``extinct Jewish
race'' in Prague.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that case is a row of windows. And out the windows are
Ellis Island and the Statue of Liberty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
