<HEADLINE>
CITY COUNCIL SUPPORTS FURTHER OVERSIGHT OF LOS ANGELES POLICE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The City Council has moved to strengthen civilian
oversight of the Los Angeles Police Department despite opposition
from the police chief.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the council voted, 11-0, with four members absent, to
support an ordinance that would shield the identity of
whistle-blowers in the department and protect them from retaliation
for bringing accusations of wrongdoing to the attention of the
inspector general, who is now Deirdre Hill. The post is a civilian
position, created after the police beating of Rodney King and the
ensuing riots to give the public greater oversight of the
department.
</P>
<P>
   The measures in the ordinance, requiring a final vote on
Tuesday, are to a great extent already contained in the city's
civil service codes and in federal employment law, said
Councilwoman Laura Chick, the author of the ordinance. She said the
law was needed to show that the city was serious about police
oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a very strong message to the public, the Police
Department and the commission: that we intend to persevere in
ensuring the integrity and the responsibilities of the inspector
general,'' Ms. Chick said.
</P>
<P>
   The whistle-blower ordinance grew out of an incident last year,
in which Sgt. Jace Kessler sent a complaint to the inspector
general concerning remarks made by Chief Bernard Parks about police
union officials. (He called them ``tired old men.'') The complaint
letter was read by the Police Commission's executive director,
Joseph Gunn, and turned over to Parks.
</P>
<P>
   To protect officers from retaliation, Councilman Mark
Ridley-Thomas requested an investigation of the handling of the
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The department's first inspector general, Katherine Mader,
resigned last fall after less than three years in the job, saying
that her civilian bosses on the Police Commission were undercutting
her authority. Since her resignation, officials have engaged in a
highly public debate over the scope and power of the inspector
general position.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the Police Department has had a high degree of
independence from City Hall, the result of measures passed in the
1930s to insulate the department from any corrupt elected
officials. But the department has come under public pressure in
recent months from officials who want to ensure that the police are
responsive to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The council has backed other measures intended to strengthen the
hand of the inspector general, including broad authority to
initiate investigations and release reports to the public without
substantial changes; unrestricted access by the inspector general
to department documents, and requirements that Police Commission
decisions to cut off investigations be made public.
</P>
<P>
   But a report by the city attorney's office last month said the
council did not have the authority to enact most of the other
measures. As a result, they are expected to be included in a
referendum scheduled for a vote in June to overhaul the city's
charter.
</P>
<P>
   The measures have been opposed by Parks, himself a strict
disciplinarian who dismissed 54 officers last year, a record for
the city.
</P>
<P>
   In letters to the City Council, Parks said the reform proposals
gave the inspector general too much power and were a potential
hindrance to effective law enforcement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Changes which allow duplicate investigations, officers to hide
behind confidentiality even though they are sworn to come forward
with the truth, and a position accountable to no one until after
the damage is done will surely and inevitably deny the people of
this city the peace and safety they deserve,'' Parks wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chick said the department must have oversight beyond its own
internal checks and balances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw what happened in this city when the department is
scrutinizing itself,'' she said. ``We have the history to remind
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
