<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4548 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMERCIAL-DBLCLICK-R     02-06 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMERCIAL-DBLCLICK-REAL-660(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SKATING ON THE ICE TO LOGGING ON TO THE WEB
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``This space is going to scream `new media,' '' said
Kevin O'Connor, the chairman and chief executive of Doubleclick
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The space he was referring to was the 16th floor of the building
at 450 W. 33rd St. at 10th Avenue. For years it was better known as
Sky Rink, one of the few places in midtown where skaters and ice
hockey players could practice their skills. (The rink has since
moved to Chelsea Piers.)
</P>
<P>
   Now the 50,000-square-foot, column-free space is to be converted
into the headquarters of Doubleclick, a company that acts as a
broker for advertising on the World Wide Web and measures the
efficiency of the ads. The company is one of the fastest growing of
the computer-based communications companies in the city's so-called
Silicon Alley, hiring on average of a person a day during the last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also leasing 100,000 square feet on the 12th
floor of the 33rd Street building so it can consolidate all its
operations under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   Doubleclick is the first company of its kind to secure economic
incentives from New York City and state to expand its operations
locally, rather than keep a headquarters in the city and shift
other office-jobs to other locations. The company will receive a
total of $5.1 million if it stays in place and meets job growth
targets.
</P>
<P>
   Rents in the building, which is owned by the John Hancock
insurance company, have recently ranged from the low to mid-20s per
square foot annually.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being long and wide, the 16th floor space has
volume, with 26 feet between the floor and the bottom of the steel
trusses that support the roof. According to Frederic M. Strauss, an
architect with the Phillips Group, this layout permits the
construction of mezzanines totaling about 11,000 square feet under
city zoning rules.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than place the mezzanine around the periphery of the
space, as is most common, Strauss has proposed building
two-story-high structures within the confines of the former ice
rink space. The two-story enclosed structures would be used largely
as meeting rooms and would stand out against the backdrop of
low-level cubicles that would probably occupy the rest of the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   To further add dramatic impact to the space, the mezzanine-level
rooms would be linked by a second-level catwalk stretching
diagonally almost completely across the rink space.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the interior space, the 16th floor also includes
two sizable deck areas totaling about 20,000 square feet, in the
front overlooking 10th Avenue and in the back facing the General
Post Office building. Those decks would be used to provide
amenities like a basketball court, a running track and a shaded
dining area to the mostly young staff members, who are expected to
work long hours. (A rock climbing wall has also been discussed, but
does not appear on current renderings of the project.)
</P>
<P>
   ``People spend so much time at work that you need a place where
people want to be,'' O'Connor said. He said the market for
technically qualified employees was so competitive in New York that
pleasant working conditions were an important consideration for
young people deciding on which of several job offers to accept.
</P>
<P>
   Other new-media companies have equipped their work spaces with
exercise rooms, pool tables and pingpong tables.
</P>
<P>
   A little over three years ago Doubleclick was two people,
O'Connor and his co-founder, Dwight Merriman, working in a basement
in Atlanta trying to cook up an Internet-based business. Today the
company has 500 employees worldwide (375 in New York), operates in
a dozen countries and is publicly traded, having sold an initial
public offering in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The company's first 3.5 million shares were offered at $17 a
share, but jumped to $26.75 at the close of the first day of
trading. The stock has been extremely volatile since then, trading
as low as $13.50 and as high as $114.62 and recently has been
trading at about $100 a share.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The company name derives from the two quick strokes of a button
on a computer's mouse control needed to make changes on a screen.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said the company had the choice of relocating to the
West Coast, famously the home of technology-based start-up
companies, or New York. ``We decided to come to New York because
New York is the advertising capital of the country and this is
where our customers are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Having a base of operations in New York was also a help in the
company's international expansion. ``Being from New York gives you
a lot of credibility overseas,'' he said. ``The attitude is that
anyone who can build a business in New York is real.''
</P>
<P>
   This rapid growth has helped keep the company on the forefront
of technical development but has presented practical difficulties.
``My biggest challenge has been real estate,'' O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   Doubleclick people now are spread over six different floors of
two buildings, one at 41 Madison Ave., at 26th Street, the other at
245 Fifth Ave., at 28th Street. ``Sky Rink gets us together
again,'' he said, using the old name of the 16th floor as shorthand
for both floors in the 33rd Street building.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to find that attractive, but he said that without the
financial incentives, the company might have looked elsewhere. ``We
would have always kept a core sales group in New York, but there
are a lot of people in the back office and engineering who do not
have to be there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal with the city's Economic Development Corp.,
Doubleclick gets $1 million to keep its operations in the city and
will get $3 million more if the number of jobs in the city grows to
756. The Empire State Development Corp. contributed $900,000.
</P>
<P>
   Doubleclick officials said the space being rented on 33rd Street
could accommodate as many as 1,000 people, giving some indication
of their expectations for growth.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Millard, president of the EDC, said the city had
targeted new media as an engine for economic growth. ``The Giuliani
administration is committed to the growth of Silicon Alley,'' he
said, using another term for the concentration of computer-based
companies in Manhattan. ``And we want to send a message to the rest
of the country that New York is behind this industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Developing the industry locally while it is in its infancy is
important, he said, because of the jobs it is likely to generate as
it grows. To the extent that new-media companies prosper in New
York, they will help moderate the influence of financial services
firms that now dominate the economy and extract huge incentives
from the city by threatening to move.
</P>
<P>
   The Web is the first new type of media to be introduced since
the widespread distribution of television half a century ago,
according to Wenda Harris Millard, executive vice president for
marketing and sales at Doubleclick and no relation to the EDC
president. ``Cable was not really a new medium,'' she added. ``It
was just a different means of distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubleclick executives first looked at the space on 33rd Street
last summer, but it took until just last month to conclude a deal,
in part because the company's requirements kept changing. ``This is
the only deal I've ever been involved in where the amount of space
tripled during the negotiation,'' said Scott Schneider, a lawyer
with Loeb &AMP; Loeb who advised on the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the nature of its business, Doubleclick operates
around the clock and on all days of the week _ in industry
parlance, ``24/7.'' As a result it arranged for exclusive use of
two ground-floor loading bays and two freight elevators in the
onetime warehouse building to move equipment in and out as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Because it once housed a major bank's computer center it is well
equipped with electrical power and telecommunications equipment,
brokers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed space like this,'' O'Connor said. ``The buildings we
are in now close at 6 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   With the 10-year agreements now signed, Strauss said he would go
into more detailed design than was possible when it was not clear
exactly what would be included in the lease. Doubleclick officials
said they hoped to move into the building in November.
</P>
<P>
   The massive 1.6 million-square-foot building, which occupies two
blocks along 10th Avenue, is also home to WNET, the public
television station better known as Channel 13, and The Daily News.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
