<HEADER>
A4550 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAVANNAH-RENEW-REAL-2     02-06 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAVANNAH-RENEW-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ARTS COLLEGE HELPS SAVANNAH'S REVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LYN RIDDLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ In 17 years of working in Chevron's finance
department, Robert Cunningham never thought he was preparing for a
career as an innkeeper. But this city of grand homes and leafy
squares changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, he and his wife, Judy, moved here from
Rowayton, Conn., settling into a four-story Georgian town house
built in 1856 by one of that era's most prominent lawyers. They
bought it for $1 million, but it needed little renovation. It is
now the Jesse Mount Inn, named for the lawyer who built it.
</P>
<P>
   The Cunninghams are part of a wave of newcomers to this city,
which has seen a sharp upturn in its downtown recently. Not too
many years ago, many grand homes stood nearly ruined by neglect as
their owners abandoned the downtown. Large commercial and
industrial buildings were empty as well.
</P>
<P>
   But Savannah has benefited from a most unusual redevelopment
tool _ a private arts college that has invested $30 million over
two decades buying and repairing 52 downtown buildings for its own
use.
</P>
<P>
   This, in turn, renewed interest in renovating hundreds of
residences in the Savannah Historic Landmark District, raising
property values by at least 15 percent, said Cora Bett Thomas, a
real estate broker who specializes in selling homes in the district
_ at 2.2 square miles the largest in the nation. Some homes have
doubled in value, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school saved this community, you cannot overstate that,''
said Ms. Thomas. ``In the 1980s we thought this city _ the historic
district _ wouldn't survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Savannah, 10 miles up the Savannah River from the Atlantic, was
Georgia's first city. Established in 1733 by a young member of
Parliament, James E. Oglethorpe, it was to have been an
experimental village, where England's poor would make silk and
other products. But the silk factory burned, destroying the
cocoons, and its 10 acres of grains and fruit froze after five
frigid winters.
</P>
<P>
   But Oglethorpe had fashioned a brilliant urban design, with
small neighborhoods surrounding 24 squares. All but three remain,
flourishing with towering live oaks and burgeoning azaleas. Rich
cotton planters _ their fortunes secure thanks to the cotton gin,
invented by Eli Whitney, who had come to Savannah from Yale to
teach on a cotton plantation _ built many of the ornate homes
encircling the squares.
</P>
<P>
   One such house, beside Madison Square, served as the
headquarters of Gen. William Tecumseh Sherman, who ended his march
to the sea here near the close of the Civil War, sparing Savannah
but burning down dozens of other cities in Georgia and South
Carolina. He telegraphed President Abraham Lincoln from Green
Meldrim House, now a museum, telling him that he was giving him
Savannah as a Christmas present.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1950s, downtown shops, offices and the grand homes were
vacant as whites moved to the city's outskirts. Residents got a
wake-up call in 1954 when the city market and adjacent Ellis Square
were demolished for a city-owned parking garage.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, the Davenport House, a Federal-style house built
in 1820 on Columbia Square, was to be razed for a funeral home
parking lot. But seven women raised $22,500 overnight to buy the
house, saving it from demolition. Later that year, they formed the
Historic Savannah Foundation. In 1966, the historic district was
designated.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say some 1,200 buildings have been restored
since, many of them because the Savannah College of Art and Design
renovated a commercial building next door.
</P>
<P>
   The college began in 1979 as a dream of Richard and Paula Rowan,
who had worked in a number of jobs in education in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Rowan, the college president, said he and his wife had selected
the city simply because ``it is architecturally rich, and it is
beautiful.'' Ms. Rowan is the provost and has been responsible for
the design and planning of the renovations.
</P>
<P>
   The first building the college purchased was the Savannah
Volunteer Guards Armory. Built in 1892 in the Romanesque Revival
style, the 36,000-square-foot building was converted into
classrooms and the first administrative offices. Before the school
opened, the teachers painted the interior of the building, which
now houses the graphic design department and production laboratory.
That first year, 71 students enrolled. This year, some 4,500 attend
the college, which offers a wide variety of undergraduate and
graduate degrees in art, theater, film and architecture.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the college bought vacant buildings in the historic
district. Often they were structures no one could imagine a use
for. One, the Chatham County Jail, cost it nothing. A group of
Eastern Airline pilots had bought it, but after a series of
scuttled plans they offered it to the college without charge. Now
it houses offices and the cellblock will be converted into a
fitness center within a year.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, the former Hamilton Electric building, on the
riverfront, purchased for $176,240 and renovated at a cost of $2.1
million, has been transformed into Hamilton Hall, a space for
shooting movies and commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can drive a car over it on the second floor because of the
huge pilings underneath,'' Rowan said. His own office is in what
once was the studio and offices WTOC, the CBS-TV affiliate here.
SCAD-TV, the college station, broadcasts from there now. Its
50-foot tower provides income from leases with mobile phone
companies and television stations.
</P>
<P>
   An old movie theater was bought for $205,000. The college spent
$1 million converting it for live theater as well as movies. It
opened four months ago with a show by Tony Bennett, the singer, who
also painted a picture for the college to auction.
</P>
<P>
   Because of all the construction, the college maintains its own
design team and construction arm. Soon to be finished is the
college's new library in what used to be Levy's Department Store.
The building and $850,000 was given to the school by Federated
Department Stores.
</P>
<P>
   But the college has not been without its detractors. In 1993,
former faculty members accused the college administration of
operating a for-profit business with a nonprofit tax exemption and
lying about admissions statistics. The college sued the former
employees for attempting to take over the school and they
countersued. All the lawsuits were settled three years later; the
agreements were not made public.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent inquiries from accrediting agencies found in favor of
the school. Last week, the Chatham County Superior Court ruled that
the school was entitled to claim tax exemptions for two diners it
operates. A former tax assessor had argued the diners were
for-profit businesses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thomas, the real estate broker, said tourism here has
benefited greatly from ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil,''
the book by John Berendt, later the basis for a movie, based on the
murder trial of Jim Williams, a wealthy local antiques dealer who
eventually was acquitted of shooting to death his companion in one
of the Historic District's grandest homes.
</P>
<P>
   But the college, she said, has brought permanent residents.
Faculty and staff members, now numbering more than 700, have bought
homes as have the parents of students. Some parents have moved to
the area permanently, Ms. Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   A house used in the movie across from the Cunninghams' inn
recently sold for its listed price of $498,000 the first day it was
on the market. An Atlanta developer plans a complete renovation of
the 3,800-square-foot clapboard Greek Revival house as a residence.
The Koger house on the opposite side of the historic district
recently sold for $3.25 million to the Panoz family, owners of
Chateau Elan, a resort in north Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Their daughter, Donna Sparks, paid $2.1 million for a
10,000-square-foot home nearby and converted it into an inn. Known
as Granite Steps, the house was formerly owned by Williams, the
murder defendant, and was featured in the movie as well. She and
her husband, Randall, live in the inn's garden-level apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The Cunninghams have been happy running their inn, but have
decided for the sake of their family life to sell. Innkeeping is a
time-intensive business, Cunningham said. They have listed the inn
with Ms. Thomas at an asking price of $1.5 million. And they have
told her that they plan to buy a smaller house in the historic
district.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1523EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
