<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4552 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-VOICES-NYT     02-06 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-VOICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACH-HUTCHINSON, IMPEACH-DELAY, IMPEACH-LEWINSKY,
IMPEACH-ENGLAND-REVIEW)
</HEADLINE>
 
THE REACTION: Intently Watching a Show That No One Wanted to See 
 (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-WITNESSES, IMPEACH-TEXT, (bl) 
By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Looking up from her morning exertions on a stationary
bicycle, Rena Kahn gave the famous young woman on the television
screen a cool, but not unsympathetic, appraisal.
</P>
<P>
   ``She seems like she's really in control, like they prepped her
really well,'' said Ms. Kahn, nodding toward the videotaped image
of Monica Lewinsky playing on the set hanging above her exercise
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Then she gave another look. ``But whoever does her hair, well, I
don't know,'' added Ms. Kahn, with the briefest shake of her head.
``And the poor thing has really ballooned up.''
</P>
<P>
   The television debut of Ms. Lewinsky _ talking, smiling, biting
her lip and sometimes pausing with a contemplative glance skyward
as she pondered questions from the House impeachment managers _
elicited some compassion but only fleeting interest Saturday in the
``cardio room'' of the Synergy Fitness Club in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate trial, instead of the customary sports programming,
was displayed on every television in the room, at a reporter's
request, but Ms. Lewinsky was barely audible over the sound of
pounding feet and labored breathing.
</P>
<P>
   But seeing was the thing, because few people had caught sight of
the former White House intern over the last year except as a frozen
image in a newspaper photograph, a fast-moving figure ducking into
a limousine or caught, in an often-replayed moment, wearing a
jaunty black beret and reaching up to give President Clinton a hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sad, in a way, that we're seeing this,'' said Ms.
Kahn, the director of international business at Deloitte &AMP; Touche,
as she watched a snippet of Ms. Lewinsky's testimony. ``We already
know all the details.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the health club patrons stared out the wall of windows
onto Park Avenue or pointedly ignored the televisions as they read
books or lost themselves in the music of their portable
audiocassette players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather watch something else,'' conceded Charles Wimer,
a lawyer and regional manager of a title company, as he jogged
earnestly on a treadmill. But he watched the trial anyway,
expressing surprise at Ms. Lewinsky's appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought she'd look better,'' he said. ``For a young kid, she
doesn't look good to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Wimer said he feels some sympathy for the young woman. ``I
always thought, from the accounts I read, that this was not an
innocent kid,'' he said. ``But the fact is, he's powerful and she's
the one who has to stand up and testify while he stays in the White
House and has his cronies cover for him.''
</P>
<P>
   While he did not expect to be watching the impeachment trial
while exercising at Synergy, Wimer said he would happily watch Ms.
Lewinsky telling her story in her own words in a less formal
setting. ``That, everybody will watch,'' he said. ``Everybody is
anxious to hear what she has to say without being in a judicial
atmosphere, when she's a lot more relaxed and not under
cross-examination.''
</P>
<P>
   As he built up speed on his stationary bicycle, Michael Prince,
34, a reporter for Business Insurance magazine, watched Ms.
Lewinsky parry a few questions from her congressional
interrogators. He said she impressed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see some life in her, a little snappy something,'' he
said, adding that she was ``not a ditzy Californian as many people
have made her out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Durando, a publishing company executive who was
maintaining a punishing pace on his treadmill, below a row of
televisions, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She looks better than she first did when she became a public
figure,'' he said. ``She's had a little help with her personal
look. The hair's still big, but it's under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, Rona Siegel kept her eyes on the screen as she
pushed and pulled and strained on a cross-training machine. Ms.
Siegel was once an agent for fashion models and evaluated Ms.
Lewinsky's appearance, and imagined her inner life, with a
professional's dispassionate cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica looks good,'' she said. ``She puts herself together
well, but what she did was unrealistic. How many 50-year-old men
are going to leave success and power and go off with a
24-year-old?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Siegel, who now owns Tatoo Fotography Management in
Manhattan, said she also found Ms. Lewinsky ``very composed'' in
the witness chair. ``By now she's been interviewed 25 times, so
after awhile it doesn't intimidate you anymore,'' she observed.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Siegel, with her experience handling teen-age girls and
models no older than Ms. Lewinsky was when she met the president,
also said she was not fooled by composure, a mature wardrobe and a
well-coifed head.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that age, you're young emotionally,'' she added. ``I used
to send 15- and 16-year-old girls around the world. They think they
know what they're doing, but they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   A young woman pounding away on a treadmill, who said her name
was Lauren but refused to give her last name, took a different
tack. Ms. Lewinsky's black suit and string of pearls were pretty,
she said, though her circumstances were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's just a girl who fell in love with her boss,'' Lauren
said, resolutely running in place. ``He just happens to be the most
powerful man in the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1524EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
