u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-100PERCENT-AWARD0     02-06 0282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-100PERCENT-AWARD07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gaither Award to Basnight
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ North Carolina A&AMP;T running back Mike Basnight received
the Jake Gaither Award on Saturday during the 100 Percent Wrong
Club's annual awards banquet at the Hyatt Regency in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The award, named for the legendary former Florida A&AMP;M football
coach, is presented annually to the top player from a historically
black college. Basnight, a 6-foot-2, 230-pound running back,
injured a knee midway through the season and played in only eight
games, but rushed for 943 yards and finished his career with 2,544.
</P>
<P>
   Basnight was the most valuable player in the Blue-Gray All-Star
Classic, leading the Gray team in rushing with 74 yards and scoring
a pair of touchdowns. North Carolina A&AMP;T coach Bill Hayes is
convinced that Basnight has a future in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got it all _ size, speed ... just an outstanding young
man,'' Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a team player who really wants to excel. We don't know
how fast he is because he seems to be just a step in front of the
guy trying to tackle him. He's got what you call `competitive
speed.''' Basnight was chosen as the Gaither Award recipient over
eight other candidates: Florida A&AMP;M quarterback Pat Bonner, Morris
Brown wide receiver Brelon Jones, Jackson State wide receiver
Sylvester Morris, Mississippi Valley State linebacker Terry Houzah,
South Carolina State safety Jermaine Derricott, Savannah State
cornerback Reggie Jackson, Virginia State wideout Damon Thompson
and Livingstone defensive lineman Ronnie Washburn.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
