<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves: `I don't think this team quit; we got beat'
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons coach Dan Reeves, just a few days removed from
his team's 34-19 loss to the Denver Broncos in Super Bowl XXXIII,
was still sullen. However, he wasn't depressed as he reviewed the
season.
</P>
<P>
   When a team that had just seven winning seasons in its first 32
years goes 16-3 and sets a slew of team and individual records,
there is room for only so much gloom.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves disagreed with the notion that his team sealed its fate
with a frazzled week of preparation, in which several players were
more than a little boisterous and families were allowed to stay at
the team hotel.
</P>
<P>
   He also continued to insist that the Saturday-night arrest of
free safety Eugene Robinson on charges of soliciting oral sex from
a female undercover Miami police officer did not cost the Falcons
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we prepared ourselves and made decisions based on what
we thought was best,'' he said. ``We can't turn the ball over four
times against hardly any team, end up minus-three in turnovers and
win. We're a football team that's got to do things exactly right,
and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of things went right for the Falcons this year, however,
as major injuries were kept to a minimum, a soft schedule worked to
their advantage and several players, including running back Jamal
Anderson and quarterback Chris Chandler, had the best seasons of
their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Most pundits picked the Falcons to finish in the middle of the
NFC West. Instead, they won the division title for just the second
time and came from behind to beat the heavily favored Vikings on
the road in overtime in the NFC Championship Game and record a
franchise-record 11th win in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal (before the season) was to make the playoffs, and
then anything's possible,'' Reeves said. ``From that standpoint, it
was a little bit of a surprise. I don't think this team quit; we
got beat. I don't think it's embarrassing to be an Atlanta Falcons
fan because we lost.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
