<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Browns don't count on bountiful draft
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Cleveland Browns brain trust of president Carmen
Policy, general manager Dwight Clark and coach Chris Palmer spent
last week examining the list of players available in Tuesday
afternoon's expansion draft and came away stating the obvious:
There simply aren't many quality young performers in the 150-player
pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players that we take,'' Palmer said, ``probably will
comprise the bottom one-third of our roster.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland can select between 30-42 veterans but must spend 38
percent of its salary cap. Such high-profile players as Baltimore
wideout Michael Jackson, Denver defensive end Neil Smith, Packers
wide receiver Robert Brooks and New Orleans quarterback Heath
Shuler are available. But most of the name veterans either are in
decline, have been injured recently or carry high salary-cap
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Look for the Browns instead to grab some bargains, such as
Pittsburgh nickel cornerback Jason Simmons, Tampa Bay defensive
tackle Marcus Jones and Dallas defensive linemen Antonio Anderson
and Hurvin McCormack.
</P>
<P>
   Clark also knows that if the Browns are going to select Kentucky
quarterback Tim Couch with the first overall pick on April 17,
they'd better get some veteran offensive linemen. Look for Patriots
guard Todd Rucci and perhaps Chicago tackle Andy Heck to be among
the first players taken by the Browns.The Johnson derby
</P>
<P>
   While the Minnesota Vikings theoretically can afford to retain
both Randall Cunningham and Brad Johnson, the real-life
implications of having two high-priced quarterbacks in the
salary-cap era will force a trade of the latter. Baltimore rookie
coach Brian Billick certainly is interested in former student
Johnson, but might have to battle Seattle for him. Seahawks coach
Mike Holmgren called Vikes counterpart Dennis Green last week to
get a feel for the asking price. The reply was that it will cost
the Seahawks, who can't count on youngster Jon Kitna yet, a quality
defender such as end Michael Sinclair. The eight-year veteran has
41 1/2 sacks the last three seasons, with a league-high 16 1/2 in
1998. Getting him would allow John Randle to move back inside to
tackle, or Sinclair could replace end Derrick Alexander if he
departs in free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos' Davis sore
</P>
<P>
   Denver tailback Terrell Davis played the Super Bowl with a
strained groin bad enough to keep him out of practice six days
before the game and severely limit his work in the Wednesday
practice, when backup Derek Loville took most of the snaps with the
No. 1 unit. ``It was sore, real sore, but word never got out about
it,'' Davis said. Coach Mike Shanahan, fined $15,000 by the league
for not reporting an injury to John Elway during the season, listed
Davis as ``probable'' all week. Davis will miss today's Pro Bowl
because of a shoulder injured in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Tip sheet
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Browns don't take Glenn Foley in the expansion
draft, the Jets plan to be rid of the veteran quarterback. Bill
Parcells hopes to sign Patriots reserve Scott Zolak, a free agent,
to back up Vinny Testaverde. ... Cincy owner Mike Brown has granted
agent Steve Zucker permission to seek a trade for wide receiver
Carl Pickens. The team will slap a ``franchise'' label on Pickens,
then try to deal him before the draft. ... New Orleans is trying to
trade for Giants cornerback Carlton Gray. ... He wasn't invited to
the scouting combine workouts later this month, but scouts are hot
on the trail of Fort Valley State defensive end Peppi Zellner, an
upfield pass-rusher with 4.58 speed. ... Buffalo will sign
defensive end Phil Hansen, the leading tackler at his position in
the past four seasons, to a three-year contract extension soon. ...
There now are whispers that the proposed Turner-NBC league won't
kick off until 2001. ... Kansas City is interested in Steve DeBerg
as its quarterbacks coach. ... Detroit middle linebacker Stephen
Boyd is one of the top unrestricted free agents, but teams will be
wary of his injury background. A second surgery to repair an
injured shoulder might be necessary. ... Kerry Collins (New
Orleans) and Trent Green (Washington) are the top free-agent
quarterbacks. When the market opens for business Friday, though,
the guy getting the most action might be Chiefs backup Rich
Gannon.Shedd-ing their cap
</P>
<P>
   Oakland is $19.6 million over the '99 salary-cap figure and
Raiders vice president Bruce Allen obviously is scrounging for
every penny. Allen last week proposed lowering the salary of backup
wide receiver Kenny Shedd from $500,000 to $400,000. The $100,000
difference would be recouped if the four-year pro caught four
passes, scored one touchdown or returned four kickoffs. As of
Thursday, nine teams were over the '99 cap. San Francisco, about
$25 million over, already has cut cornerback Marquez Pope and
tailback Terry Kirby. Agent Pat Dye Jr. already has been told that
cornerback Antonio Langham and tight end Irv Smith won't be back,
and linebacker Ken Norton Jr. and free safety Merton Hanks also
could be on the Niners' hit list.
</P>
<P>
   Thin crop
</P>
<P>
   The pool of unrestricted players is expected to be the leanest
in years when the signing period begins Monday. Here's how one NFC
personnel director rated the top 12, with a disclaimer that several
either would re-sign by Friday or be designated ``franchise''
players: LB Jamir Miller (Arizona), CB Dale Carter (Kansas City),
WR Antonio Freeman (Green Bay), WR Carl Pickens (Cincinnati), DT
Santana Dotson (Green Bay), DE Chad Bratzke (Giants), C Wally
Williams (Baltimore), SS Carnell Lake (Pittsburgh), QB Kerry
Collins (Saints), SS Robert Griffith (Vikings), OT Orlando Brown
(Ravens) and WR Rob Moore (Cardinals).
</P>
<P>
   No laughing matter
</P>
<P>
   The fallout from the Eugene Robinson incident even caused
difficulty for one Denver player. On ``The Tonight Show'' on
Tuesday, wide receiver Ed McCaffrey jokingly told host Jay Leno
that his wife was upset because Robinson ``only offered her $20
earlier in the week.'' Lisa McCaffrey rose from her seat in the
audience and flipped her husband a dirty bird of a different kind.
``After the show she told me, 'It's sofa city, sweetheart,'''
McCaffrey said Wednesday after spending Tuesday night on the couch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
