</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BOUCHARD07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bouchard still part of hockey scene
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dan Bouchard was in goal when the Ice Age came South
in 1972 with the creation of the Atlanta Flames, and he was the
last of them remaining when it melted away eight years later with
the team's move to Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the NHL prepares its Atlanta return after a 19-year
absence, Bouchard remains right where it all began _ living in his
adopted hometown and still very much a part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of tending goal in the NHL, the Montreal native is
behind the bench as coach of the Life University Skating Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   With little fanfare, Bouchard started the hockey program at the
Marietta school in 1995 and turned it into an instant success. With
a roster loaded with Canadians, Life finished second in the
American Collegiate Hockey Association's Division II tournament its
first season, then won the national title the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard isn't ready to stop there. Life, again ranked No. 1 in
its region, is a favorite to win a third championship in a row the
first week of March in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a way to give back to a sport that has given me so
much,'' said Bouchard, who retired in 1986 after 14 seasons and 288
victories with three franchises. ``I'm really enjoying myself. This
is a long way from the NHL, but it's been fun.''
</P>
<P>
   That he is coaching at a college named Life carries special
meaning for Bouchard, 48. Nine years ago, he wasn't sure what the
rest of his life would hold or how much time he had left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very scary,'' said Janet, Bouchard's wife of 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   Suffering from dizziness and a progressive loss of hearing,
Bouchard underwent a series a tests that revealed a tumor behind
his left ear. The growth was benign, but the neurosurgery required
was tricky. Side effects were possible, with no guarantees of a
complete recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``They needed to cut me open to see if a goalie really had a
brain,'' Bouchard can say now with a laugh. At the time, jokes
weren't funny.
</P>
<P>
   The operation at Emory University Hospital was supposed to take
about eight hours. It lasted closer to 15. A growth about the size
of a tangerine was removed.
</P>
<P>
   The operation was a success, but Bouchard lost the hearing in
his left ear and the side of his face was temporarily paralyzed
because of trauma to the facial nerves. For nearly a year, his left
eyelid was stitched partially shut as a precaution while the facial
nerves rejuvenated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked a fright for a while,'' Janet said. ``It wasn't a
good time to be between hockey jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bouchard landed a job as goalie coach with Quebec Nordiques,
one of his former teams, and held it until Pierre Page was fired
four years later.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard was in business in Atlanta when he was approached about
helping start a hockey team at Life. It was something he decided he
couldn't pass up.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, hockey is a club sport at Life, and teams in the
American Collegiate Hockey Association can't give athletic
scholarships. But with Bouchard as coach, the program goes as
first-class as possible. Although attendance for home games at The
Cooler in Alpharetta is usually only about 200 to 400 people, Life
has the resources to travel by plane on at least three round trips
per season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between our team and some of the ones we play
is like night and day,'' high-scoring winger Jason Lyewski said.
``We're on a completely different level.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheduling is Bouchard's biggest frustration. ``I want to play
better competition, but teams won't play us or are too far away.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Southeastern teams don't have the skill or experience to
match Life, whose 24 players include 14 Canadians and average 24
years old. The Skating Eagles beat Florida 8-0 and 13-0 last
weekend, and Georgia Tech 16-2 earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Canadians came South because of Bouchard, but most
were lured by Life's chiropractic program. All but seven players
hope to be chiropractors. Both goalies _ Jarred Buffie and Eric
Legault _ came to Life from Canada for that reason; getting to work
with a former NHL goalie is a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   As a player, Bouchard was emotional on the ice and outspoken off
it. But he practices tender loving care in English and French with
his goalies, keeping instruction on technique simple and
concentrating on the mental part of the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sometimes gets on the other players,'' Buffie said. ``But
not with us. He is always encouraging. He knows what we are going
through, and it really helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard, who someday would like to return to the NHL, has
conducted several clinics for the Atlanta Thrashers. He is
confident the NHL expansion team will be a success at the gate when
it opens play next fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old Flames fans were great,'' remembered Bouchard,
recalling the chants of''Bou-chard, Bou-chard, Bou-chard!'' at the
Omni. ``I always knew Atlanta would get another team. I just didn't
think it would take this long.''
</P>
<P>
   DAN BOUCHARD FILE
</P>
<P>
   _ Birth: Dec. 12, 1950, in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Home: Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   _ Family: Wife Janet, and children Jordan and Lindsay.
</P>
<P>
   _ Update: Coach at Life University, which has won two American
Collegiate Hockey Association Division II titles in a row. Life
will go for another title at the ACHA tournament the first week of
March in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   _ NHL career: Played 14 seasons (1972-86) with the Flames,
Nordiques and Jets, winning 288 games. Only original Atlanta Flame
still with the team when the franchise moved to Calgary in 1980.
Led NHL goalies in games (64) and victories (32) in 1978-79.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
