<SLUG> BC-NY-SUSPECT-SHOT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICERS MAY TESTIFY IF A FEDERAL INTERROGATION IS RULED OUT
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic on the scene of the shooting is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl) 
By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four police officers who killed an unarmed West
African immigrant in a fusillade of 41 gunshots will waive immunity
and testify before a Bronx grand jury this week if they receive
assurances that a federal inquiry will not intervene and expose
them to whip-sawing between federal and state prosecutors, a person
close to the officers said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A day after federal officials announced that they were joining
the Bronx district attorney in the investigation of the death of
22-year-old Amadou Diallo last Thursday, there were no major
developments in the investigation of a case that has raised a storm
of protest from community and religious leaders, African-American
groups, politicians and acquaintances of the slain man.
</P>
<P>
   But the intervention of the federal officials, who said only
that they would be working closely with District Attorney Robert
Johnson, appeared to be subtly affecting the behind-the-scenes
legal maneuvering to obtain first-hand accounts of a shooting whose
only witnesses appear to be the officers who fired the fatal
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   What the officers and their lawyer, Stephen Worth, are worried
about is the possibility that federal officials could preempt the
state grand jury after they testify, and summon them before a
federal grand jury, said the person close to the officers, who
spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the officers told substantially the same story before
the state and federal grand juries, this person said, they might be
caught in contradictions, however minor, that might cast doubt on
their accounts and expose them to criminal prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   Worth, a lawyer hired by the officers through the auspices of
the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, declined to comment
Saturday on whether his clients would be willing to waive immunity
and testify, or to say whether they would insist upon any
conditions in exchange for their testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``They re not afraid of talking,'' Worth said. ``But it is my
advice that they not do so until we see which agency is going to
handle this.''
</P>
<P>
   Worth said the officers did not intend to speak publicly about
what happened, but he noted that they were aware of the public
outcry over the case and felt sorrow over the death of a man said
to be a devout Muslim and a hard-working street peddler who had
never been in trouble with the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``These men are human beings,'' Worth said of the officers.
``They have a job to do, and they try to do it well. They did not
wake up and say, `Let's shoot a street peddler today.' They
recognize the tragedy that a man died, and was not armed at the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, detectives continued to search for witnesses on the
Wheeler Avenue block, in the Soundview section, where the shooting
occurred. But, as on Thursday and Friday, they found no one who
acknowledged having seen the shooting in the vestibule at No. 1157.
</P>
<P>
   Protests over the shooting continued Saturday. A half-block from
Diallo's door, about 30 people, rallying under the banners of the
Progressive Labor Party, marched in a circle with signs that read:
``Smash Police Brutality,'' ``Stop Killer Cops,'' and ``Destroy
Police Terror with Communist Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   A prayer vigil and rally was scheduled for 2 p.m. Sunday at the
scene of the shooting by the Rev. Al Sharpton. Diallo's father, a
businessman currently working in Vietnam, was on his way to New
York, but it was not clear whether he would be present for the
rally. He is to take the body home to Guinea, West Africa, later
this week for burial.
</P>
</TEXT>
