<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STRIP-CLUB-SHUT-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGAL LANDSCAPE CHANGING FOR CITY'S X-RATED BUSINESSES 
</HEADLINE>
 (rk) 
 By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When police officers and building inspectors
descended on a popular Queens strip club, Goldfingers, to shut it
down a few nights ago, many of the club's neighbors were delighted
and relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have hundreds of kids here day and night, so do I think it's
good that it's closed _ yes, absolutely,'' said Joann Ciorciari,
the manager of the Lost Battalion Hall, a Parks Department
recreation center on the block next to Goldfingers in Rego Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men have a right to go see women dancing naked,'' she said.
``But you should put it where it belongs and not near homes and
places where children go.''
</P>
<P>
   The youth center, the largest in Queens, and the apartment
buildings that line Queens Boulevard near the club are precisely
the reasons city officials were able to padlock Goldfingers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the city started enforcing a new zoning law in July
regulating ``adult establishments,'' the owners of Goldfingers
bought the club a few extra months by admitting minors and creating
what the club called a nonadult game room, where customers could
play chess, dominoes and jacks.
</P>
<P>
   But a state judge ordered the club closed last week, calling the
club's changes a ``transparent sham'' intended to evade the law,
and labeling the owners' reasoning ``absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark D. Alonso, a lawyer for Goldfingers, said that the club's
owners had not yet decided whether to appeal the judge's decision,
to turn the club into a regular nightclub or to close down for
good.
</P>
<P>
   The Goldfingers decision was one of two significant court
victories for the Giuliani administration, both of which narrowed
loopholes in the zoning law that had allowed many sex
establishments to remain open.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the appellate division of the state Supreme Court
emphatically overturned a judge's ruling that had allowed a
Manhattan topless club to stay open as a nonadult establishment on
the ground that it admitted minors.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions underscore the ever-changing legal landscape
governing the city's X-rated businesses. Earlier, topless clubs and
video shops had won a handful of court victories that punched
loopholes in the zoning law and frustrated the Giuliani
administration. Ultimately, future rulings and appeals could bring
further changes.
</P>
<P>
   In Queens, the closing of Goldfingers was hailed as a major
victory by local officials, who had battled for years to rid the
area of strip clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Goldfingers is the last of four adult-entertainment clubs to be
closed in the residential neighborhoods of Rego Park and Forest
Hills. While other clubs, with names like Wiggles and Runway 69,
prompted louder and more vehement protests, Goldfingers was one of
the main reasons why Queens officials helped draft legislation to
make sex shops and strip clubs illegal within 500 feet of schools,
churches or other sex shops.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Manhattan officials had pushed for similar
legislation to rid Times Square of sex shops, but politicians in
the other boroughs resisted, fearing that the sex shops would head
into their neighborhoods if they were driven from Times Square. As
it turned out, the redevelopment of Times Square had the same
effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goldfingers was definitely one of the places that triggered
the legislation,'' said City Councilman John D. Sabini, whose
district encompasses Goldfingers and the Lost Battalion Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they started cleaning up Times Square, these places
started popping up on the natural byways out of Manhattan, like
Queens Boulevard and Northern Boulevard. The problem is, these
byways may move fast, but there are also lots of people who live
along them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR;  &LR;  (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rachel Pradhan, 17, who lives in the Queens Boulevard Tower
apartments, down the block from Goldfingers, waved good riddance to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's degrading to have a place like that around,'' she said.
``It's not something you want around your house. Guys would come
out of there at all hours making all kinds of noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Ciorciari said that while her recreation center is essentially
closed to children under 15 at 6 p.m. when the after-school program
shuts down, dozens of teen-agers fill the center's basketball
courts, weight room and boxing center late into the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you think that these boys didn't know about that place,
you must be out of your mind,'' she said. ``I'm sure some of them
have been in there, and that's just not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Alonso, the Goldfingers lawyer, had argued that once the
nonadult game room was created, less than 40 percent of the club's
floor space was dedicated to sex entertainment and thus the club
complied with previous court rulings that allowed such businesses
to stay open.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Arthur W. Lonschein of state Supreme Court in Queens
found that the game room was not open to the public when city
inspectors visited the club, and ruled that the club therefore
exceeded the limit.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also mocked the club's claim that the addition of the
game room meant that Goldfingers could not legally be classified an
adult-entertainment club. ``No one would pay $10 to enter this
place to play chess, or jacks or tiddlywinks,'' he wrote in his
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge is saying that it's not enough to have a 60 percent
nonadult space, but it has to be as busy as the other areas, too,''
Alonso said. ``So if more people went to see `The Blue Room' just
to see Nicole Kidman naked instead of going to hear the dialogue
with their eyes closed, does that make that theater an adult
theater?''
</P>
<P>
   While lawyers continue to dispute the application of the 40
percent limit, Walter L. McCaffrey, a Queens city councilman who
spearheaded the sex shop zoning law, said the limit was never meant
to apply to strip clubs but was intended to address the inventory
of adult video and book stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were debating the law, we said explicitly that the
limit did not apply to live entertainment, because how do you have
a strip club that's only 40 percent naked?'' he said. ``There's no
such thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Karan Sunar, a father of three young girls who often eats at the
Burger King next to Goldfingers, offered a suggestion for where
Goldfingers might move.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very family-oriented area,'' he said. ``Those places
don't belong here _ maybe in Manhattan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
