<HEADLINE>
THE DEMISE OF THE GLOWING PUCK  
 RETURNING TO NEW ENGLAND ROOTS  
 MORE THAN BRAGGADOCIO 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to legend, if the puckhog sees his shadow in early
February, it means 19 more weeks of hockey. And so it is. The
playoff pairings won't be determined until after the income tax
deadline, and the Stanley Cup won't be won until shortly before the
summer solstice. Until then, in arenas across the continent, over
intrusively loud speaker systems, the recorded rock bands play on.
And on. They will, they will, ROCK YOU!
</P>
<P>
   Another loud annoyance, the Fox network, begins its lame-duck
season Sunday with several regional telecasts, including the
Rangers at Boston. Viewers will note one improvement through
deletion: Fox no longer uses the glowing puck that baffled and
irritated so many fans for several seasons. The glowing rubber took
the most heat, but it was really the least of Fox's many sins.
</P>
<P>
   Worse were its confusing, end-zone camera angles during live
action, which will probably return. If Fox producers and directors
wanted to learn how to present hockey the right way, they would
simply watch and copy the technical experts at the MSG network, who
wisely use high and wide camera angles from the side during live
action while saving the cute stuff for replays and whistle stops.
But Fox reinvented the puck, so don't tell them what to do. In
keeping with its prime-time style, Fox should add a recorded laugh
track to its hockey camera work.
</P>
<P>
   But let's not be too negative because there will be
improvements. Instead of taking more than 15 minutes to finish its
cluttered pre-game show, Fox will permit games to start at eight
minutes after the hour. Still, Fox intermissions again will be
longer than usual and so will its four television timeouts during
each period. Lou Lamoriello, general manager of the Devils,
recognizes the timeout problem, even in non-Fox games when the
breaks are only 70 seconds. ``The important thing is getting the
games to have a flow and have the fans enjoying what they are
seeing,'' Lamoriello said. ``Our commercials really have hurt that.
Even the players, it hurts them sometimes to get out of the flow.''
</P>
<P>
   RETURNING TO NEW ENGLAND ROOTS
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, freshly flowing from Thursday's 8-4 victory over
Mark Messier's Vancouver Canucks, will face a bunch of Bruins who
were 0-6-1 in the seven games before Saturday afternoon's visit to
Philadelphia. The Rangers and the Bruins are among several teams
contending for the eighth and final playoff berth in the Eastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   A key Ranger for Fox and fans to watch will be Brian Leetch, the
captain and attacking defenseman, who will be returning to his New
England roots. Now that Leetch has ended his 23-game goal drought
by scoring his seventh of the season Thursday, he might begin the
burst of production that could carry his team to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problem has been when we don't get enough chances and
don't put the puck in the net,'' Leetch said. ``I've had a lot of
opportunities during that streak. I think about it more when we are
not winning. It was good to get it out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Leetch played at Boston College and has been more productive
against the Bruins than against some opponents. In 34 games, he has
36 points, including two assists in a 3-3 tie earlier this season.
Over Leetch's career, Harry Sinden, the Bruins' general manager,
has aimed the occasional barb toward Leetch, implying that he is
not the caliber of either Bobby Orr or Ray Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   MORE THAN BRAGGADOCIO
</P>
<P>
   Such debates are fun for fans, but the stakes for Leetch this
season are bigger than braggadocio. He could become an unrestricted
free agent on July 1. Although his play has improved over last
season, Leetch is still not the game-breaker he was during
Messier's Ranger captaincy from 1991 through 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason could be the style of Coach John Muckler, who
does not let Leetch gamble as much as some past Ranger coaches.
Another reason may be the style of Wayne Gretzky, whose curls at
the opposing blue line take away the space that Leetch needed to
join rushes during the Messier years.
</P>
<P>
   When Leetch was left out of the All-Star Game two weeks ago, it
was not so much an unfair snub as it was a leaguewide recognition
that his play is no longer at the level of a Norris trophy
candidate. More than most Rangers, Leetch suffered hurt feelings
when Ranger bosses let his friend, Messier, leave as a free agent.
By ending his goal slump against Messier's team Thursday, Leetch
may have turned a symbolic page. He also used to complain that
Fox's electronic puck bounced around too much, and he doesn't have
that to worry about now.
</P>
<P>
   There is still plenty of time _ months, remember? _ for him to
rally his team into the playoffs and boost his profile for free
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Should Leetch fail, his market value will dwindle and he will be
forced to watch the entire tournament from home, including those
aggravating telecasts on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
