<HEADER>
A4563 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-GUNS-NYT     02-06 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATAL BARRAGE BY POLICE RENEWS DEBATE OVER SEMIAUTOMATIC HANDGUNS
</HEADLINE>
 (See also NY-SUSPECT-SHOT) 
(bl) 
By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The type of gun used here by four police officers
last week in the fatal shooting of an unarmed West African
immigrant is the weapon of choice among law enforcement agencies
across the country in the continually escalating arms race between
the police and criminals, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The barrage of 41 bullets sprayed at 22-year-old Amadou Diallo
in the vestibule of his Bronx building early Thursday morning has
revived questions about the safety of semiautomatic handguns, which
fire faster and carry more bullets than the .38 caliber revolvers
they replaced in the New York City Police Department six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani defended the use of 9 mms and
praised the New York force for ``being just about the most
restrained police department in the country,'' even as he described
the shooting as a ``terrible tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that there is no clear link between semiautomatics
and the number of shootings by police, and that officers are likely
to get higher-powered weapons rather than go back to traditional
handguns.
</P>
<P>
   More than 99 percent of the nation's municipal police forces
with more than 100 officers now authorize the use of semiautomatic
weapons, with 74 percent of the agencies choosing 9 mm handguns
like the ones involved in the New York incident, according to a
forthcoming study by the federal Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   New York was among the last to switch to semiautomatics; most
cities opted for more firepower in the mid-1980s, many prompted by
a 1986 shootout in Miami in which FBI agents ran out of bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threats nowadays are a lot more than they were years
ago,'' said Robert DelCore of the International Association of
Chiefs of Police. ``If you go back 30 years, you'd have a guy who
might have pulled a gun at you but who wouldn't fire. Go back 20
years, maybe they'd fire at you, a little Saturday Night Special.
Now it's escalated to where they carry little machine guns. You've
got to be prepared to meet the threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Criminologists said there had been no studies comparing the
number and severity of police shootings with semiautomatics vs.
revolvers, and a spokesman for the New York City Police Department
said he could not separate statistics based on the type of weapon
used. While several experts said anecdotal evidence indicates that
the number of shots fired per incident increases when guns such as
the 9 mm are used, they also noted that the number of police
shootings _ in New York and across the nation _ has declined
sharply even as the semiautomatic weapons have become standard
issue.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the rate of fatal police shootings per 1,000
officers was 0.48 last year, the lowest since 1985, and lower than
the rates in Chicago, Dallas, Miami, Philadelphia or Washington.
The number of shootings, and the shots fired per incident, have
fallen with the crime rate during the last four years: There were
344 shootings with an average of 5 rounds fired in 1995, and 249
incidents with an average of 3.4 shots fired last year, according
to Inspector Michael Collins, an NYPD spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The critical question in analyzing police shootings, law
enforcement experts said, is why officers pulled the trigger, not
which guns they were using.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the gun is, because they can all kill, the bigger
problem is the quick trigger,'' said David Lerner, a spokesman for
the Center for Constitutional Rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more about training, accountability and protocol
than it is about the weapon,'' said Paul Chevigny, a law professor
at New York University. ``I don't want to sound cold-hearted;
Diallo might be alive if they hadn't had automatic weapons. But I
don't think it makes that much difference.''
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, the difference would likely have been in
the number of shots fired. Two of the four officers emptied their
16-bullet magazines in the incident: Had they been carrying
revolvers, they would have had just 6 bullets each before needing
to reload. The medical examiner says 19 bullets hit Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference is in the impact of the bullets hitting their
target. Experts said that several bullets fired from a 9 mm gun
could hit a man without knocking him down, which could lead
officers to continue shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``These bullets would be passing through him so fast that he
could still be standing,'' explained Steven Edwards, who oversees
police research for the federal government's National Institute of
Justice. ``You have to remember this is happening in nanoseconds.
There's fright and flight that are operating here as well. It's not
something as rational as it may sound.''
</P>
<P>
   The police favor the 9 mm handguns not only because they
discharge quickly, unloading up to 18 bullets in about four
seconds, but because they carry more rounds and can be reloaded
simply and fast.
</P>
<P>
   As a semiautomatic, the 9 mm, like the .38 caliber revolver it
replaced, fires only one round each time the trigger is pulled. But
it recocks itself after each shot, placing another bullet in the
chamber, and thus can release a succession of bullets quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Lighter than the .38, the ``9,'' as it is known, rests more
naturally in a shooter's palm, and often increases accuracy. But
the real attraction is the magazine, which holds up to three times
as many bullets as a revolver, and the ease of reloading. A 9 is
refilled in a two-step process that takes about four seconds, can
be done in the dark, and has been compared to popping a disk into a
computer; reloading a revolver takes two hands, eight separate
movements, and about 12 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   New York originally allowed magazines of just 10 bullets, and
now uses clips of 16. The city also commissioned a special device
that increases the amount of pressure needed to pull the trigger,
from about 5.5 pounds to about 12 pounds. Most patrol officers use
semiautomatics, though a handful of veterans have kept their .38s,
officials said. All four of the officers in the Bronx shootings had
9 mms; two were Sig Sauer models, one was a Glock and one was
manufactured by Smith &AMP; Wesson, police said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the potential for increased number of rounds
fired, critics question the reliability of the 9 mms.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's like saying Porsches are faster and more
powerful than Chevys, so we should equip the cops with Porsches,''
said James Fyfe, a criminologist at Temple University who
questioned the shift to nines. ``Chevys start every morning.''
</P>
<P>
   But the public does not like seeing the police outgunned. Police
shootings with large numbers of shots fired cause little outrage
compared with incidents like the Los Angeles bank robbery in 1997
in which officers had to borrow weapons from a gun shop to battle
suspects with machine guns.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than reconsider the move toward 9 mms, police departments
are looking at even more powerful guns: 15 percent of the municipal
departments currently authorize 10 mm semiautomatics, according to
the upcoming Justice Department study, 41 percent use .45 calibers
and 50 percent use .40 calibers. (9 mms are comparable to .357
calibers.) Some departments, experts say, are now allowing officers
to carry fully automatic rifles in their cars rather than shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's a genie you can put back in the bottle,''
said Edwards. ``The lingering concern would be whether there is
adequate policy and enforcement and training having to do with how
many shots you fire and when to stop shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Walsh, vice president of New York's Police Benevolent
Association, said the semiautomatic handgun ``is a tool of
necessity today,'' and noted that New York police officers are
``trained to shoot to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If an incident is stopped in one round, then we shoot one
round,'' he said. ``If it's stopped in five, it'll be that many.''
</P>
<P>
   While it remains a mystery why all four officers fired, and
fired so many times, in the Bronx shooting, Fyfe said that, in
general, he is more troubled by incidents in which only one officer
out of a group fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wonder what he saw that no one else saw,'' Fyfe
said, speaking hypothetically. ``If you think about the options
here, you either have four homicidal maniacs who happen to be
working together, or you have four rational guys who all saw the
same thing. The chances are, you don't have four homicidal
maniacs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1546EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
