<HEADER>
A4565 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-KRUSHENICK-NYT     02-06 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KRUSHENICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICHOLAS KRUSHENICK, 70, ABSTRACT AND POP ARTIST
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nicholas Krushenick, a New York painter whose bold,
posterlike paintings were often called abstract Pop, died Feb. 5 at
Mount Sinai Medical Center in Manhattan. He was 70 and lived in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was liver cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Krushenick was born in New York in 1929 and attended DeWitt
Clinton High School in the Bronx. He studied painting at the Art
Students League and at the informal painting school overseen by the
Abstract Expressionist Hans Hofmann, whose theory of ``push-pull''
promoted the use of bright, contrasting colors to activate a
painting's space.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1950s Krushenick made collages of somewhat geometric
figures, and he had his first solo show at the Camino Gallery in
1957. The next year he quit his job in the frame shop of the Museum
of Modern Art and, with his brother John, founded the Brata
Gallery, an early 10th Street artists' cooperative. The artists who
showed at Brata included Al Held, Ronald Bladen, George Sugarman
and Yayoi Kusama. Like Krushenick, they were all seeking more
straightforward, hard-edged alternatives to the emotionalism of
Abstract Expressionism.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1960s, Krushenick had solidified the geometric
aspect of his work into simple abstract motifs sometimes suggestive
of landscapes, sometimes of billboards, whose shapes were outlined
in heavy black lines. Although similar to the paintings based on
cartoons that Roy Lichtenstein and Andy Warhol were making,
Krushenick's paintings kept their distance from the images of
commercial art.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, Krushenick began to show in uptown galleries, including
Graham, Fischbach and Pace (now Pace Wildenstein), where he had
three shows between 1967 and 1972. His most recent New York
exhibition was at the Mitchell Algus Gallery in 1997. He was a
visiting artist at many art schools and universities and taught
from 1977 to 1991 at the University of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Krushenick's work is represented in many public collections in
the United States and Europe, including the Museum of Modern Art,
the Metropolitan Museum of Art and the Whitney Museum of American
Art in New York; the Museum of Fine Arts in Dallas; the Los Angeles
County Museum of Art; the Walker Art Center in Minneapolis, and the
Stedelijk in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Julia, and a son, Shawn, both of
Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1547EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4566 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FEATURE07-COX     02-06 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FEATURE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leaving a landmark: Saying goodbye to the Gardens
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Danny McDonald wasn't there for the Beatles. He didn't
make it for visits by Winston Churchill or Muhammad Ali or Evel
Knievel or the King (Elvis) or the Queen (Elizabeth _ actually she
was only a princess at the time).
</P>
<P>
   But McDonald won't forget his first visit to the old brick
building once labeled ``the church of hockey'' by Wayne Gretzky,
who grew up an hour away in Brantford, Ontario. It was 26 years
ago, and McDonald was going to his first training camp with the
Toronto Maple Leafs, Day 1 of his Hall of Fame career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked into Maple Leaf Gardens and just sat in the dark in
the stands,'' he said. ``The only light was from the exit signs. It
was the most peaceful time I remember. I remember someone coming up
to me ... asking for an interview, and I asked him to wait 10 or 15
minutes. I just wanted to sit there, soaking it in.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald paused before adding, ``Moving to a new building makes
all the sense in the world from a business standpoint. But from a
purist standpoint, when this building's gone, a big part of hockey
will go with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maple Leaf Gardens' date with a wrecking ball remains uncertain.
But its existence as the last of the NHL's six original venues ends
this week. The Leafs will host Carolina on Wednesday and Chicago on
Saturday before moving to the new Air Canada Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackhawks game will come 67 years and three months after
the Leafs opened the Gardens with a 2-1 loss to Chicago in 1931.
Fans paid 95 cents to $2.75 for admission. Scalpers are getting
$3,500 for Saturday. A lottery was held for 500 pairs of seats ``in
the grays,'' the upper level, and entries arrived from as far away
as Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a kid growing up in Canada, it was like going to Yankee
Stadium,'' said former Leaf Darryl Sittler, whose 10-point night at
the Gardens in 1976 has survived Gretzky's and Mario Lemieux's
assault on the record books. ``The first time I visited there, I
couldn't believe how big it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Big? Size is everything in pro sports, but the Gardens' capacity
of 15,726 is considered undersized by today's standards and seats
4,000 fewer than the new arena. Maple Leaf Gardens has pictures of
old players hanging in the corridors, ushers who have worked there
past retirement age and a lot of history, but not much else. The
building has hosted lacrosse, track and field, speed skating,
beauty pageants, church services, bicycle races, ballets, circuses,
orchestras, operas, choirs, memorial services, political rallies,
roller derby, bingo, rodeos, softball, aquatic shows, water polo
and weddings.
</P>
<P>
   The first NBA game was played there: New York Knickerbockers 68,
Toronto Huskies 66.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies survived only a year. Most of the memories revolve
around the Leafs and their late owner, Harold Ballard. Ballard once
caused a revolt among players when he fired coach Roger Neilson.
When he was unable to find a replacement immediately, he rehired
Neilson a few days later _ and asked the coach to step out behind
the bench with a paper bag over his head, then lift it on cue and
shock the fans. Neilson declined.
</P>
<P>
   Ballard also painted the logo of his other toy, the CFL's
Hamilton Tiger Cats, on the ice, which didn't please fans of the
Toronto Argonauts. There also was the time he billed construction
improvements at his house to the Maple Leafs, resulting in a fraud
conviction and one year in prison, and the time he was seen after
the circus late one night riding a motorcycle on the Gardens' floor
_ in the nude and with a female circus worker on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Former Atlanta Flame Tim Ecclestone, who grew up in Toronto and
played briefly with the Leafs, recalled when he was first traded to
Toronto, ``Jim Gregory, the general manager, took me upstairs,
where (Ballard) had a three-bedroom apartment. I walk in, and
Gregory introduces me, and Mr. Ballard says, 'We're proud to have
you with us, Jim.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ecclestone, McDonald and Sittler will be among some 150 alums in
attendance Saturday. There will be ceremonies after the game and a
parade Feb. 19 to carry the four Stanley Cup banners from the old
arena to the new one. The Gardens will be used for junior games and
a practice site for at least two years. But if it is not
financially viable, it will be leveled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be fun, seeing the pictures and all the old
doormen and ushers again,'' McDonald said. ``The place has been
like a second home for a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
