<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLEAST07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Yech, New Yech
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here are two more reasons for New Yorkers to move to
New Jersey: 1. the Rangers; 2. the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Scenes from Manhattan: Despite an 8-4 win over Vancouver last
week, the Rangers are floundering with one of the league's top
payrolls, and the heat is on general manager Neil Smith. New York
is in danger of missing the playoffs for the second season in a
row, and the Wayne Gretzky window might close after this year.
Rangers czar Dave Checketts denies speculation that Smith is gone
if the team falls short of the postseason again: ``Neil is doing
nothing more than carrying out what everybody in the organization
agreed on: To build the foundation of a club that will be good for
a long time. We wanted him to get the team younger and faster and
get size. He's done that with the moves he's made. ... We knew
there would be some pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Scenes from Long Island: General manager Mike Milbury dealt
talented young defenseman Bryan Berard to Toronto for goalie Felix
Potvin. Milbury then fired himself as coach and promoted assistant
Bill Stewart, who prefers Tommy Salo as his starting goalie. No
wonder. Potvin lost his first five starts as an Islander, yielding
an average of 4.47 goals per game, and allowed six goals in six
minutes against Ottawa. Can it get worse? Yes. Rich Winter, Salo's
agent, says his client will not play for the Islanders next year.
If that's true, Salo could be in a Thrashers uniform. Most teams
will protect only one goalie in the amateur draft, and the Isles
won't look good if they give up on Potvin after dealing Berard.
</P>
<P>
   NEW START
</P>
<P>
   With everything going right for Philadelphia general manager Bob
Clarke of late, it wouldn't be surprising if the Flyers can
rehabilitate Russian defenseman Andrei Kovalenko, who was acquired
from Edmonton in the three-way deal involving Alexandre Daigle. The
final straw with Kovalenko for Edmonton GM Glen Sather was a curfew
violation _ partying all night after a game in Los Angeles, then
missing the team charter the next morning. Clarke is not going into
the project blind: Of Kovalenko, he said, ``His reputation precedes
him. He likes his beer, but a lot of good players have drunk a lot
of beer over the years. If we find out his off-ice stuff isn't
good, we won't keep him.''
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres, who have hit a lull, admit to jealousies between
players. It even got to the point that Michal Grosek asked coach
Lindy Ruff to be put on a new line because he felt Miroslav Satan
was shooting too much to keep his scoring streak alive. Forward
Dixon Ward said, ``It's like a marriage. It's always great after
the honeymoon. The true test is when things aren't going well and
how you react. You either get divorced or find a way to get through
it.'' ... Alexei Kovalev had three goals and seven points in 14
games with the Rangers. Since being traded to Pittsburgh, he has 12
goals and 23 points in 28 games. ... The surprising cover boy on
the NHL's new stat and history annual, ``Total Hockey,'' is Buffalo
right wing Rob Ray. His reasoning: ``Orr, Howe, Ray. Maybe they
were looking for someone with a short name.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
