<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers GM continues scouting
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Don Waddell Over the World Tour continues. After
spending four days at the NHL general managers meetings in Palm
Springs, Calif., the Thrashers GM was scheduled to scout four
Canadian juniors games in three days over the weekend and a Calgary
Flames game Monday night before returning to Atlanta on Tuesday.
... There were no significant developments at the GM meetings, but
Waddell was quizzed often by his fraternity members on the team's
plans. Informal discussions already have begun about potential
trades or side deals before the expansion draft in June. Expansion
clubs often will agree not to draft specific unprotected players in
exchange for compensation from the respective clubs. Most of the
attention continues to be on goaltending. Dallas (Roman Turek) and
Detroit (Norm Maracle) are uncertain of plans with their
sought-after backup goalies. ``There was a lot of dialogue about
certain players this week,'' Waddell said. ``But I think what we've
found is (that) patience in our business is priceless. The longer I
don't make a deal, it works in the best interest of the team. Teams
have 48 hours after the last playoff game to make trades. Right
now, other GMs are just feeling me out.'' ... There were no
proposed rule changes made in Palm Springs, and the issue of
whether to take out overtime was tabled until the next meetings
during the playoffs. ... The Thrashers this week will announce an
inner-city street-hockey program to be held in conjunction with the
NHL and Nike. Willie O'Ree, the first African-American player in
NHL history, and team goaltending consultant Andy Moog will be in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   LAND SHARKS
</P>
<P>
   San Jose players and coaches groused about having to start the
season with two games in Japan. But that's heaven compared with
this: The Sharks began a 10-game, 17-day road trip Wednesday, the
longest uninterrupted trip in league history. The Calgary Flames
had 11 road games in a row in 1987-88, but there was an
intermission to wash socks; the All-Star break came after three
games. ``It was an absolute nightmare,'' said former Flames goalie
Mike Vernon, now with the Sharks. San Jose players will log 7,123
air miles, flying to Phoenix, Los Angeles, Phoenix again, Chicago,
St. Louis, Tampa Bay, Florida, Detroit, Buffalo and Washington. But
the Sharks have to blame themselves. They operate their own arena,
and they booked a tennis tournament (Feb. 8-14) and an ice show
(Feb. 17-21) back to back.
</P>
<P>
   GOON WATCH
</P>
<P>
   The most and least penalized teams this season, based on average
minutes per game.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders _ Trailers
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver _ 22.4 _ Ottawa _ 10.8
</P>
<P>
   Chicago _ 21.9 _ Toronto _ 12.4
</P>
<P>
   Colorado _ 21.7 _ Dallas _ 12.9
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo _ 20.5 _ Philadelphia _ 13.2
</P>
<P>
   Florida _ 19.7 _ N.Y. Rangers _ 13.2
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE/UNQUOTE
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix forward Jeremy Roenick, recalling his time with coach
Mike Keenan when both were in Chicago: ``He scared the (heck) out
of me and made me the player I am today. He grabbed me by my
throat, threw me into the boards and told me if I ever passed (up)
on a check, I'd never play for him again. I swear to God I thought
I saw the devil.''
</P>
