<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLWEST07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Problems surface for Wings in Woetown
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Remember all those warm and fuzzy stories during
Detroit's run to its second consecutive Stanley Cup last year? Long
gone. Here's a six-pack of problems: 1. Backup goalie Norm Maracle
was charged with speeding and drunken driving last week. 2.
Defenseman Larry Murphy suffered a concussion when he was run into
the boards by New Jersey's Krzysztof Oliwa. Murphy was sidelined,
the league did not suspend Oliwa and, worse, none of Murphy's
teammates went after Oliwa, who also had taken a shot at Steve
Yzerman. 3. Sergei Fedorov has been critical of coach Scotty Bowman
for giving him limited playing time and shuffling lines. 4. Detroit
continues to hover barely above .500 and is struggling against
teams with winning records. 5. Three starting defensemen are out
with injuries, including free-agent acquisition Uwe Krupp. 6.
Brendan Shanahan finally ended a 15-game goal-scoring drought the
other night _ but the Wings lost at home to the mediocre Rangers.
Shanahan remains central to trade rumors. ``No one has come to me
and told me anything,'' Shanahan said. It might not be a bad time
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE BAIT
</P>
<P>
   One sidelight to the trade rumors involving Los Angeles
defenseman Steve Duchesne: He has a no-trade clause in his contract
and would have to approve any deal. The Kings re-signed Duchesne as
an unrestricted free agent before the season, but he has been a
$10.75 million bust. He was expected to improve the power play but
had only three goals and 17 assists through 50 games, and L.A. has
the third-fewest power-play goals in the league. Those facts, and
that Duchesne never has been a physical player, is wearing on coach
Larry Robinson and general manager Dave Taylor. Taylor reportedly
offered Duchesne to Philadelphia for forward Alexandre Daigle,
since dealt to Tampa Bay, but was turned down. Robinson on
Duchesne: ``We've got a style we play, and you've got to get
involved physically. He plays too much with his stick.'' Duchesne
on Duchesne: ``It's been a struggle for me, and nobody wants to get
out of this struggle more than I do.''
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Blues are 0-59-10 when trailing after two periods
since November 1996. ... Having exhausted all other avenues to
relieve symptoms of post-concussion syndrome, the Blues' Geoff
Courtnall is trying acupuncture. ... Nashville coach Barry Trotz on
the perceptions of a first-year team: ``Every time a team loses to
us, you would have thought the world ended.'' ... Colorado goalie
Patrick Roy on his two-year, $14.5 million extension: ``It means I
can break as many TVs as I want.'' The reference was to smashing
video equipment in a locker-room tirade earlier this season. ...
Despite sellouts and the league's best record, Dallas owner Tom
Hicks claims the Stars will lose between $3 million and $12 million
this season, in large part because of their $39 million payroll and
the lack of revenue from suites at Reunion Arena. The latter, at
least, will change in 2000 when Dallas moves into a new building.
Hicks anticipates the value of the franchise, which he bought for
$84 million in 1995, will jump to between $150 million and $200
million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
