<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4571 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-AIRLINE-850(2TAKE     02-06 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AIRLINE-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LOW-COST AIRLINE PLANS TO FLY OUT OF KENNEDY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ga, N.C., Pa., Texas, Utah, Vt.)  (rk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 39-year-old Utah entrepreneur backed by George
Soros and several other big investors has raised a record $130
million to start the first major new low-cost airline at one of New
York's three main airports in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The new airline, which is temporarily being called New Air until
a permanent name is chosen, intends to start flying this fall to
four cities from Kennedy International Airport at prices as much as
80 percent below current fares. After three years, it plans to
serve as many as 50 destinations.
</P>
<P>
   New Air has been in the works for two years but its plans were
made official on Friday, when it filed an application with the
Federal Transportation Department in Washington for crucial takeoff
and landing slots at Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   It follows the announcement in December that Southwest Airlines,
the country's most successful low-cost carrier, will start flying
to four cities from MacArthur Airport on Long Island on March 14.
</P>
<P>
   Both Southwest and New Air could usher in a new era of low-cost
flying not seen in New York since People Express started flying out
of Newark International Airport in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 20 years, New York, which is the country's biggest
travel market, has seen average fares on short flights rise
slightly, while ticket prices on comparable routes in much of the
rest of the nation have fallen 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that after a low-fare airline enters a
market, ticket prices drop at all airports, even to destinations
that the new airline does not serve, and passenger traffic rises as
more people find they can afford to fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be good for everybody, except the big
airlines,'' said David Neeleman, the entrepreneur who spearheaded
the new venture and will be the airline's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   New Air will be the most richly capitalized start-up in aviation
history. In addition to $40 million from funds run by Soros, the
New York-based financier and philanthropist, the venture has the
backing of other large institutions, including the venture capital
arm of Chase Manhattan Bank.
</P>
<P>
   New Air has the enthusiastic support of key politicians,
including Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Gov. George E. Pataki, Sens.
Charles E. Schumer and Daniel Patrick Moynihan and much of the
state's congressional delegation and the Queens borough president,
Claire Shulman.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for political support from New York lawmakers, New
Air has pledged to make either Buffalo, Rochester or Syracuse one
of its first destinations and eventually to serve all three. They
are among the 20 cities in the country with the most expensive
average air fares, according to the Transportation Department.
</P>
<P>
   Neeleman said he has not yet decided where else the airline will
fly first, though he is considering a city in Florida. Other
possibilities include Atlanta; Burlington, Vt.; Charlotte, N.C.;
Pittsburgh, and Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The airline's filing said that once it starts flying to Dallas,
it planned to charge $169 for a one-way unrestricted ticket that
currently costs $818 on a major carrier. An advance-purchase
one-way ticket to Dallas would cost $89, according to the filing,
compared with $221 on a major carrier now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned about this when I started flying upstate in the
campaign,'' Schumer said last week. ``The ticket would be $400 and
you would be lucky if you got a bag of peanuts. There was an
arrogance at the two carriers _ US Air and Delta Express _ because
they knew they had no competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling airline is going to need all the help in
Washington it can muster to get the landing and takeoff slots it
needs to operate at Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 1960s, the federal government has restricted
flights at the airport during the peak hours of 3 p.m. to 8 p.m.
Major airlines like American Airlines and Trans World Airlines
control most of the slots.
</P>
<P>
   Neeleman's attraction to Kennedy is that aside from those
afternoon and evening hours, when most international flights arrive
and take off, the airport is hardly used.
</P>
<P>
   But while it can fly freely to and from Kennedy in the morning
and late evening, New Air needs slots for the important afternoon
hours, when most business travelers want to get home.
</P>
<P>
   To meet its plan of flying to 50 cities by 2003, New Air has
asked the right to add 25 slot exemptions each year for the next
three years. (Each slot equals one opportunity a day to take off or
land.)
</P>
<P>
   Schumer made lowering air fares in the region a campaign pledge.
Last week, he held a get-acquainted session in his Washington
office between Neeleman and New York members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In January, he wrote a letter to Transportation Secretary Rodney
E. Slater that was also signed by Moynihan and four upstate
congressmen urging him to help New Air.
</P>
<P>
   The request for afternoon slots is certain to meet strong
opposition from the major airlines at Kennedy. But Schumer is
confident that New Air will get the slots it needs. ``I am
optimistic that DOT will understand the problem and try to solve
it,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   New Air would be the first carrier to make Kennedy its hub. The
airline will fly the newest narrow-body jets, either the Boeing 737
or the Airbus A320, which are much quieter than older airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   New Air will also need gates at Kennedy, which is currently
undergoing a $7 billion facelift. Though a terminal for a low-cost
domestic carrier is not in the master plan, Neeleman said the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey, which operates all three New
York-area airports, has been very helpful. ``They have several
options for us,'' he said. ``We're very confident that we will have
a great place.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with its low fares, New Air may face an uphill battle
persuading customers to fly out of Kennedy, which is difficult to
reach from Manhattan and has become more unattractive of late
because of the renovations there.
</P>
<P>
   But Neeleman said travelers would make up any extra travel time
on the runway because Kennedy has far fewer take-off delays than
does Newark or La Guardia Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Success in the notoriously perilous airline industry is far from
certain. Scores of new airlines were started in the 20 years since
the industry was deregulated in 1978. Most failed. Only one,
Phoenix-based America West Airlines, has become a major carrier.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, at least, New Air looks strong. Though only 39,
Neeleman already has a successful record as an entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, at the age of 23, he helped start Morris Air, a
low-fare airline based in Salt Lake City. After Morris Air was sold
to Southwest for $130 million in 1993, Neeleman walked away with
$20 million. He went on to help start Westjet, a low-cost airline
based in Calgary, Alberta, and a technology company that designs
airline reservation systems, which he recently sold to Hewlett
Packard.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he was committed to shaking up the airline industry
by providing a high level of service at low prices. New Air will
only have electronic tickets. Check-in will be automated so that
passengers can simply walk up to a kiosk at the terminal, swipe
their credit cards through a scanner, choose a seat on a computer
screen, and then receive a boarding pass, all without having to
deal with an agent.
</P>
<P>
   First, of course, New Air needs a new name. Neeleman's original
plan was to call the airline Virgin America. But a deal with
Richard Branson, the successful British entrepreneur who owns
Virgin Atlantic Airways, fell apart last year because federal laws
prevent foreigners from owning more than 25 percent of a domestic
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Neeleman then decided to call the airline Taxi _ the planes were
to be painted yellow with a black checkerboard stripe _ but he
cooled on the idea after he was informed that taxis do not exactly
project an image of safety and cleanliness to New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Which points to one stumbling block facing Neeleman in his aim
to make New Air ``New York's hometown airline.'' Born in Brazil,
where his father was a foreign correspondent for United Press
International, and raised in Salt Lake City, Neeleman has never
lived in the New York area.
</P>
<P>
   He said that many of his top executives, including New Air's
president, David J. Barger, who formerly ran the Continental
Airlines hub in Newark, were longtime New Yorkers who make up for
his lack of experience.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as the school year is out in June and his wife gives
birth to the couple's ninth child, he intends to move East from
Salt Lake City with his family and dive right in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to buy a year's worth of Broadway tickets up front
and go every month,'' he said. ``That commits me so the months
don't go by and I don't go.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
