<SLUG> BC-SKI-MAIER-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAIER, A RUNAWAY TRAIN, RUMBLES TO DOWNHILL TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)  (lb) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAVER CREEK, Colo. _ Barreling down the Birds of Prey downhill
course like a freight train, Hermann Maier of Austria let nothing
get in the way of his second gold medal in the World Alpine Ski
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old Maier, his body strong and fluid, finished the
1.6-mile course in 1 minute 40.60 seconds. In second place, winning
the silver medal, was Maier's closest rival on the World Cup
circuit this year, Lasse Kjus, 28, of Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Kjus was .31 of a second behind Maier. In third, was 27-year-old
Kjetill Andre Aaamodt of Norway, who won the bronze medal with a
finish of 1:41.17.
</P>
<P>
   For Maier, known as the Herminator for his derring-do on skis,
victory Saturday was not crucial, but it was surely satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I have now what I want,'' Maier said as he headed out
of his hotel Friday for a downhill training run. ``I have won a
gold medal in the world championships, and now for me, it is over.
If I win another medal in the downhill, then that is good too.''
</P>
<P>
   The results only added to Austria's dominance of this event. In
racing so far, the Austrian team _ both men and women _ have
captured seven of the 12 medals. The competition ends Feb. 14.
</P>
<P>
   The downhill course, known to be one of the toughest in the
world, was as hard as it gets Saturday. A cloud cover and light
snow cut down on visibility as a record crowd of about 2,100
onlookers rang bells, waved flags, and cheered their countrymen.
But on top of the hill, skiers shivered in a cutting wind as their
eyes surveyed a course of sheer ice and fall-away turns.
</P>
<P>
   Two American entries, Daron Rahlves, of Truckee, Calif., and
Paul Casey Puckett, of Crested Butte, Colo., both took massive
falls that sent them hurtling down the slope. Neither appeared to
suffer more than bumps and bruises, although Rahlves was taken to a
local hospital for a checkup.
</P>
<P>
   Maier rode the gates Saturday as if they were put there for him
to mow down.
</P>
<P>
   When other skiers fought gravity at The Brinks, a treacherous
section at the top of the course, Maier hugged the fall-line. On
the final jump at Golden Eagle, he soared as if shot from a
slingshot.
</P>
<P>
   Kjus, who skied right after Maier, made few mistakes. He knew he
had to match his World Cup rival's exacting performance.
</P>
<P>
   It is paradoxical somehow that the two top downhillers in the
world _ Maier and Kjus _ are known as much for their calamitous
free falls as for their masterful runs to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Maier, the bold Austrian, and Kjus, the demure Norwegian, have
survived tumbles on the slopes that might easily crush a lesser
mortal. Perhaps that's why neither seemed particularly unnerved by
prospects of the downhill race here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The pair shared a gold medal last Tuesday in the super-G
competition. With that came more reason to feel self-confident and
secure. It was an unprecedented outcome in a world championship _
that the two fastest racers would finish with the exact same time
to one-hundredths of a second.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For Kjus, talking about the short-haul seemed to work better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I know what the fast way down is,'' he said Friday of
the pending downhill. ``It is a difficult course. But it is quite
short, and once the top part is over, the last part is not so
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of these two champions, leaders in overall World
Cup points this season, that serious mishaps are left behind.
Forget Maier's chilling fall during the Olympic Games last Feb. 13
in Nagano, Japan. Like a boulder set loose from a cliff, he bounced
down a downhill course that stopped him only when the mountain had
had enough.
</P>
<P>
   As if to show the hill he wasn't about to be had, Maier went on
to win Olympic gold medals in the super-G and giant slalom.
</P>
<P>
   For Kjus, the bout with nature came during a World Cup race Jan.
12, 1996, in Kitzbuehel, Austria. Like a cannonball gone awry, Kjus
hurtled through space wondering if he would ever turn right side up
again. The accident left him with a severe concussion. But at the
time, it was just a sidebar to his ranking as overall World Cup
champion that year.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, the spill took its toll. It is only this
season that Kjus appears to be fully recovered.
</P>
<P>
   He was plagued with a neck strain through most of the 1997
season, then rallied somewhat last year with 10th overall in the
World Cup. He also won Olympic silver medals in the downhill and
the combined.
</P>
<P>
   For Maier, the lion in him still roars. Having moved into ski
racing in 1995 from life as a bricklayer, Maier has soared from No.
106 overall in 1996, to No. 1 last season on the World Cup circuit.
And this season so far, he is in the lead again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
