<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4595 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-HALL-OF-FAME-NYT &LR;      02-06 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HALL-OF-FAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME RUN RACE AND SOME YANKEES' MAGIC ENDS HALL OF FAME'S SLUMP
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Texas, Pa., Md.)   (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ Catherine Walker knows crowds, especially
those in this pretty-as-a-picture town, and particularly when it
comes to its centerpiece, the red-brick structure that is the
Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, white-haired and with a smile as winning as Sammy
Sosa's, is the supervisor of attendance at the museum, and has
lived all her life in Cooperstown. She remembers distinctly the day
the Hall of Fame opened its doors, June 12, 1939, and held an
induction ceremony for 25 of the greatest players of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 8 years old,'' she said, ``and I remember Babe Ruth,
friendly as could be, walking down Main Street to the barber shop
for a haircut, and all the kids in town following him. It was quite
a crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   That was when baseball was uncontested as the most popular sport
in America. But times and circumstances change, and baseball has
been as susceptible to the fates as a windblown foul ball. In the
last few years, baseball had fallen on hard times, and the crowds
to the baseball shrine declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It began with the lockout and the shutting down of the World
Series in 1994,'' she recalled. ``Older people especially got sick
about it and turned away. But now things are different, especially
for the young people. I think Cal Ripken got it going when he was
breaking the longevity record in 1995, and then last year the
Yankees season and the McGwire-Sosa home run race. But the faith of
fans has been renewed. It's reflected in the crowds here. And you
see license plates from all over the country, from Texas and
California, and everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last quarter of 1998 _ in the months of October, November
and December, the Hall of Fame experienced record attendance with
37,542 going through the turnstiles in October, 14,017 in November
and 5,458 in December. Attendance in January declined because of 44
inches of snowfall in the area, according to Jeff Idelson, a
spokesman for the Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for the first time since 1993 _ the year before the
last lockout _ the Hall of Fame saw an increase in attendance. In
1993, the total attendance for the year was around 407,047, second
highest in history _ some 13,000 behind the record set in 1989.
This past year, the total attendance figure was 330,504 (through
Dec. 29), the seventh-highest in museum history, and a 16 percent
increase from the 1997 figure of 284,708.
</P>
<P>
   ``Activity at the museum was on the upswing all summer,''
Idelson said, ``but after what McGwire and Sosa did, and the
Yankees, it continued into the winter. The season was historic, and
I learned that people were coming here to get as close to history
as they could without actually having been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the visitors to the Hall recently was a 14-year-old named
Anthony Clarkson, who was wearing a red St. Louis Cardinals cap,
even though he lives in Dallas. He was accompanied by a cousin he
was visiting in Philadelphia, Jodie Findley, a sales manager for a
photo company, and a friend from Dallas, Jody Pruitt, also 14.
</P>
<P>
   They were looking over the exhibit that greets the visitor upon
entering the Hall. In three glass-encased exhibits are Roger Maris,
Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa memorabilia. Clarkson's attention was
drawn particularly to the baseball that McGwire hit for his 62d
homer last season, breaking Maris' all-time record of 61, the pair
of bats in which he hit most of his homers from No. 50 to No. 70,
as well as McGwire's red ankle-high baseball shoes
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always wanted to see the Hall of Fame,'' said Clarkson,
``and, yes, McGwire and Sosa heightened it even more for me.''
</P>
<P>
   His cousin, Jodie, said: ``We were really pumped to see the Hall
of Fame. We got up at 6 in the morning to drive up here from
Philadelphia _ took about five hours.''
</P>
<P>
   David Antell drove up from Waldwick, N.J., with his family, his
wife, Joy, and their three children, Jeremy Joseph, 11, Emerald, 4,
and Ayla, 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Joseph' in Jeremy's name was for Shoeless Joe Jackson,''
said Antell, a wine consultant. ``We're big baseball fans, but
we've never been to the Hall of Fame before. We thought this would
be a good time to finally make the trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy said he was interested in ``the Babe Ruth stuff.'' But he
was also impressed with the Yankees' 1998 World Series trophy,
which is on loan to the museum until March, when it moves
permanently to the Yogi Berra Museum in Upper Montclair, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Down Main Street, about a block from the Hall of Fame, is a
memorabilia store named, ``Third Base: Last Stop Before Home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fuel's in the tank,'' said John Kurdziolek, owner of the
establishment. ``Business has increased dramatically, and of course
we're totally dependent on the Hall of Fame. We've seen the biggest
surge in years in the last several months. Our most popular item
has been Mark McGwire jerseys. We can't keep them in stock. We sold
150 to 200 in just a few months. We sold about 50 Sosa jerseys, but
remember, he was second to McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street is ``Mickey's Place: A baseball and sports
emporium.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees are the big thing with our customers,'' said Jeff
Stevens, the proprietor. ``This last season stirred a lot of
excitement, but some of our biggest sales are still the old
Yankees. And the Joe DiMaggio autographed baseballs are probably
our hottest item at this time. It started when Joe got sick in the
fall, and these balls may be among the last he may ever sign.
Before this, the Mickey Mantle autographed ball sold for $350, and
the DiMaggio ball for $295. But the demand was so great for
DiMaggio that we raised the price twice, to $325 to $350.''
</P>
<P>
   There were also several Albert Belle baseball cards under glass.
How do those sell? ``They don't,'' said Stevens, in regard to the
notorious baseball curmudgeon. `
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the museum, Anthony Clarkson, the youngster from
Dallas, was musing among the baseballs from the game's no-hitters,
including those of his idol, Nolan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthony said that the next time he comes here, it'll be for
his induction,'' said his cousin, Jodie Findley. She smiled.
``Well, it's America and it's baseball and anything is supposed to
be possible, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Which seems also to include a come-from-behind triumph, at this
time, for baseball, the Hall of Fame and the sale of Mark McGwire
jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
