<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BENEDICT-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS COACH MOONLIGHTS BY CHANGING HIS STRIPES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most baseball players and coaches spend the off season playing
golf or hunting or fishing. Or making the rounds on the banquet
circle.
</P>
<P>
   Not Bruce Benedict. If you want to find the Mets' bench coach
from November to the middle of this month, he is most likely in a
college town somewhere down South refereeing a basketball game. He
has made whistle stops in the bigs of the Southeastern Conference
and in the boondocks of the National Association for
Intercollegiate Athletics. And he has probably stayed in more
hotels than Willy Loman.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Benedict has refereed games from Syracuse to
Miami to California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've kind of touched all the spots,'' Benedict said.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict regularly works games in the SEC, the Ohio Valley and
Trans America Conferences, the Division II Peach Belt Conference,
the Division III Southern Collegiate Athletic Conference and NAIA
District 27.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, his schedule took him through a veritable
glossary of Tennessee towns _ Clarksville (Belmont at Austin Peay),
Cooksville (Murray State at Tennessee Tech), Monteagle (DePauw at
the University of the South) and Knoxville (Alabama at Tennessee).
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, Benedict's tour had him visiting three states in
six days, from Alabama on Monday (Talladega College) to Tennessee
on Tuesday (Tennessee-Martin) and Nashville on Wednesday
(Vanderbilt against Georgia), to Florida on Saturday, when Florida
was host to Mississippi in Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a person that likes to stay busy,'' Benedict said. ``This
enables me to stay in a competitive environment all year long.''
</P>
<P>
   And how. And once Benedict dons the black and white vertical
stripes of the referee uniform, gone is the anonymity of being a
bench coach, a job he has held with the Mets the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, I tell people I didn't realize how bad a baseball
player I was until I started refereeing,'' said Benedict, a former
catcher, who played from 1978 to 1989 with the Atlanta Braves. ``At
basketball games, people were close enough to talk where I could
start hearing it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Benedict began refereeing basketball games at the high
school and junior high levels, along with some junior college
games, while he was still catching for the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that took some guts, to play like I was playing at the end
of my career,'' Benedict said.
</P>
<P>
   By 1990, he was doing Division I college games. This is his
eighth season as an SEC referee. He has done games this season at
Kentucky and Auburn, two of the top-ranked teams in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's two different worlds, really,'' Benedict said of his
summer and winter jobs. ``With the Mets, I'm at the top level of
pro sports. Then I go back to another level. It's a great fit for
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I root for the Mets all year long, and then I go to the
colleges and could absolutely care less who wins.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There is one major adjustment Benedict must make however.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is in baseball, you go into a town for three or
four days and check into a nice hotel,'' Benedict said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In basketball, it's a one-game series. There are three things
about college basketball that are very tough. One, getting to the
game. Two, doing the game. And three, getting to the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the problems Benedict has faced have been
weather-related. Ice storms. Plane troubles. He said he has never
missed a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've been running in, changing clothes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part with doing so many games at so many different
levels may be having to adjust to the different talent levels and
knowing what to call _ and what not to _ based on the players'
skills in places from Rupp Arena to a small college gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have to remember is that although places vary in size
and people, these games _ especially the in-conference ones _ mean
just as much to NAIA schools and their players, coaches and fans as
they do to a Georgia or a Vanderbilt,'' Benedict said. ``Obviously,
the skill level is different. But that's part of your development
as an official.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, as long as Benedict has a job in the major
leagues, he can develop only so far. By the time the conference and
national tournaments roll around, Benedict is at spring training.
His March madness is spent in Port St. Lucie, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Benedict will just have to satisfy himself with
watching it on television, as he does every spring. He insists he
does not enter any NCAA pools.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when the players are filling out their sheets, I tell them
I am available for consultation purposes,'' Benedict said. ``For a
small fee, of course.''
</P>
</TEXT>
