<HEADLINE>
GOLF BUSINESS HASN'T BENEFITED FROM TIGER WOODS AS MUCH AS IT
THOUGHT IT WOULD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the Tiger Woods era is off to a rocky start for many in
America's golf business, most Kansas City area golf enterprises
seem to be faring reasonably well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's at the national or local level, however, one thing
seems certain: Tiger's explosive arrival on the scene created
business expectations that were too high. Conversations with area
golf course and golf shop operators lead to a couple of
conclusions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The overall level of golf activity hereabouts has been good but
not great since Tiger turned pro, but those who anticipated a burst
of equipment sales growth have been disappointed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's happening locally is occurring against an industrywide
backdrop of discouraging developments. The equipment industry is a
disaster area. Some well-known names have failed and the stock
price of most survivors has plunged. Meanwhile, many course
operators are complaining that the new-venue glut is harder to deal
with than a 600-yard par-five hole playing against the wind. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the late '80s a National Golf Foundation study concluded the
industry needed to develop a golf course a day for a decade to keep
up with the rise in players. It was generally considered an
impossible challenge, but it happened. Unfortunately, golfing
population growth has lagged predictions and is now about 26
million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if Tigermania didn't exist, though. Many adults with
no previous interest in golf now watch golf on television if Tiger
is in the hunt. More significant, however, is how everyone in the
business raves about the explosion of youngsters taking to golf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Queen, manager of golf course operations for Overland
Park, calls the increase in junior golfers at his courses
``phenomenal.'' Jeff Johnson, head professional at Sunflower Hills
in Wyandotte County, is seeing a similar trend out his way, where
junior golf ``has just gone crazy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the state line, Pat Zuk, head professional
at Kansas City's Swope Memorial, also sees more junior golfers.
Many of them are being introduced to the game at the Blue River
Golf Academy, which was established to introduce urban youngsters
to golf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Marquardt, director of golf operations at Paradise Point
golf complex in Smithville, attributes much of local golf's
relative health to Kansas City's being ``very affordable.''
Paradise Point, Marquardt said, expanded from 18 to 36 holes
several years ago because of the rising demand for group events. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marquardt also is proud of how he's sustained his golf shop
sales, which some course operators have de-emphasized. He's done
it, he says, by focusing more on corporate customers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in equipment sales is as upbeat, however. Jack
Davis, owner of a well-known Lenexa golf shop for nearly 25 years,
says last year was his softest year since '78. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of like being in the oil business,'' he said.
Much of the problem, he believes, is the trend toward more
expensive high-tech clubs, which prompts golfers to delay new
purchases. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The consensus is that Tigermania's full economic impact is at
least 10 years away, until today's juniors become working adults
and start generating the income needed to buy costly new
equipment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; tag1:Jerry Heaster's column appears Wednesday, Friday, Saturday
and Sunday. To reach him, write the business desk at 1729 Grand
Blvd., Kansas City Mo., 64108. To share a comment on StarTouch,
call {(816) 889-7827} and enter {2301}. Send e-mail to
{jheaster &LR; kcstar.com}
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
