<BODY>
<SLUG> BC--KAN </SLUG>
  
 VISIT TO JESSE JAMES COUNTRY IS ENGlISHMAN'S DREAM COME TRUE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 11:30 a.m. Tuesday, Jesse Tonks, who has lived his entire
life in the heart of England's industrial Midlands, walked through
the doors of the historic Jesse James Home in St. Joseph to view
the spot where the famous outlaw died. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've waited 55 years for this moment,'' Tonks said. ``This
place is part of my family tradition.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That tradition, an odd one as you shall see, has been passed
from Tonks to Tonks since 1882. It has persisted for almost 117
years despite the fact that not a single Tonks, living or dead,
ever met Jesse James or, for that matter, knew much about him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think he was from Texas,'' said Tonks, 65, who
retired last year as an oil rig inspector. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And though Tonks has done a good bit of on-the-job traveling _
43 countries in all _ he had never set foot in Missouri before last
week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've been trying to get here for most of my life,'' he
said. ``It's been my dream.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That long-held hope began to come true in December when Tonks
entered a dream-trip contest titled ``Places to Remember,''
sponsored by the London Daily Express, which is nationally
distributed in Britain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tonks' entry letter so intrigued the Express editors that they
plucked him from Midlands obscurity, declared him a winner and
quickly made arrangements to send him to the heart of Jesse James
country: Kansas City and St. Joseph. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The contest is to celebrate the upcoming millennium,'' said
Jay Iliff, a feature writer for the Express who accompanied Tonks
on his American journey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked our readers to write us about the places they most
wanted to go and why. We're awarding 52 trips this year and
featuring one each week in the paper.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the contest began, the Express has been flooded with
strange and moving tales. In fact, said Iliff, he arrived in
Missouri hard on the heels of a trip to Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia,
with another contest winner. There, 35 years ago, as an infant, the
winner accidentally had been tossed into a monsoon drain and then
dramatically rescued. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the sort of thing we're after,'' Iliff said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tonks, though, almost missed his great opportunity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never won a thing in my life,'' he told his family when
they urged him to enter the national contest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, go on, Dad,'' said his daughter Susan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, then, Tonks took pen in hand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I am named after Jesse James, the outlaw,'' he began. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He added that his father before him was named Jesse, as are his
own son and several nephews. All in honor of Jesse James. And so,
he concluded, he wanted more than anything to visit Missouri and
finally see for himself what this long Tonks tradition was about. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His entry letter stirred immediate interest at the Express. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``All these generations of Jesses in the middle of England, and
all named after a notorious American outlaw,'' said Iliff. ``Well,
that would catch your eye, wouldn't it?'' &QL; 
The Tonkses' long and emotional connection to Jesse James began
with a man named Jack Barnes, who was Jesse Tonks' maternal
great-uncle. Barnes was afflicted with an incurable wanderlust that
led him first to sea and eventually to the center of America. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Midlands town of Nuneaton whence he came _ and where he
is remembered still _ Barnes' traveling ways achieved legendary
status. People there called him the ``Pennsylvanian Tramp.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``With a name like that, I suppose he must have spent a lot of
time in Pennsylvania,'' said Tonks. ``But I have no idea why.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1741EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4625 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAMES-DREAM SECONDTAKE-KAN &LR;    02-06 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMES-DREAM, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 SECOND TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (no idea why.'')
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Barnes eventually drifted westward in America and
happened to be in St. Joseph on April 3, 1882, the day Jesse James
was killed. Such stunning proximity to a historic event proved
irresistible to the folks at home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Barnes came back for a visit that very year,'' said
Tonks. ``My family were all farm laborers in those days, and except
for the Pennsylvanian Tramp, none of them ever got more than five
miles from home. Well, a story like that, it would be exciting to
them, wouldn't it? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, my grandfather was so thrilled by it that he named
his own son Jesse. And that son was my father, who became a
professional footballer (soccer player) and bookmaker. And he named
me Jesse, too. I first learned the reason from my dad and my Uncle
Tom when I was 10. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad and my uncle were great drinking companions _ with the
beer, like _ and one time when they were drinking together, they
told me the whole story. It intrigued me so much that I've wanted
to visit Missouri ever since.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This Tonksian obsession has thrived through generations _ until
now, that is. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In all there have been four Tonkses named Jesse. The fifth was
supposed to be Tonks' first grandson. But his daughter-in-law
rebelled and named the boy Ashley James instead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that certainly broke the chain, didn't it?,'' said
Tonks' wife, Margaret, who was born in Scotland. ``But that's the
youngsters for you, isn't it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Jesse and Margaret Tonks finally entered the James Home, they
were greeted by Gary Chilcote, the museum director and one of the
world's foremost James authorities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Come in here, where Jesse actually stood when he was killed,''
Chilcote said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almost reverently, the Tonkses walked together into the parlor
where the deed was done. Jesse Tonks quickly noted the framed
needlepoint sampler that James was supposedly straightening at the
moment he was shot in the back of the head. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, there are two stories about that,'' Chilcote said.
``One is that Jesse was straightening the picture frame, the other
is that he was dusting it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't think the dust would come into it at all,'' said
Margaret Tonks. ``I can't see a famous outlaw like that doing much
dusting.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chilcote nodded as he led the way into an adjoining room where
the results of the 1995 exhumation of James' body are on exhibit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Over here,'' he said, ``you can see Jesse's head twisting
slowly in the wind.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to a perfectly cast reproduction of James' skull. The
32 pieces of skull bone found in the outlaw's coffin were
duplicated and reassembled during the study. They are now displayed
on a rotating pedestal. The fatal bullet's entry path is marked by
a bright orange tube. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Fantastic, that,'' said Jesse Tonks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In front of the skull there are re-creations of James' teeth
cast from the originals. (All that actually remained of James was
ceremonially reburied after the 1995 study was completed.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to a museum placard, the flattened surfaces of James'
molars resulted either from low-grade tobacco or ``perhaps a
lifestyle that caused him to grit his teeth a lot.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Brilliant!'' Tonks murmured, staring hard at the skull and the
flat-surfaced teeth as he brushed from his cheek what seemed to be
a tear. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor old Jess gets a bit emotional about this,'' said Peter
Corns, an Express photographer, or ``snapper'' as they're often
called in England. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday we were at the James farm in Kearney,'' Corns added,
``and when Jess was thanking everyone for what they'd done for him,
a little tear crept into the old eye, you know.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While in Kearney, Tonks laid a wreath on Jesse James' grave and
posed for a photograph wearing a broad-brimmed Stetson. That
picture was much on his mind as he finished his Missouri sojourn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the Royal Navy, and I belong to an ex-serviceman's
club at home,'' he said. ``And I just know I'm going to have the
Mickey taken out of me when my friends see me in a cowboy hat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But I know what I'll say in return. I'll tell them: `I've been
to Missouri. I've seen where Jesse James was born and died. Where
have you been?' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before Tonks left St. Joseph to begin his journey home, he
explained what finally happened to the Pennsylvanian Tramp. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he died in Canada during the 1930s,'' Tonks said. ``He
died a wealthy man. Apparently he struck gold in the Yukon.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the fabled Midlands hobo left no will and had no birth
certificate, so his fortune went to the Canadian government. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end we got only his story,'' Tonks said. ``But it's a
good story, isn't it?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
