A4632 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     02-06 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS ADOPT DEFENSIVE POSTURE ON SPRING FEVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The swamp buggies are gassed up and ready to roll. In a mere 10
days, pitchers and catchers will join the alligators at Charlotte
County Stadium. Spring training is nearly here for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to winter? Winter seems like a blur. And
winter was definitely a blank, at least for the grandiose plan of
adding Randy Johnson or Roger Clemens to the city of Arlington tax
roll.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Rangers whiffed on the No. 1 off-season priority.
Didn't get Johnson, didn't get Clemens, didn't get done what needed
to be done. So why not raise ticket prices? So they did. I hate it
when I have to whine like this. But it's the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Then again.
</P>
<P>
   In most other baseball locales, they actually gaze with envy
upon the local baseball situation. For example, San Diego, where a
World Series team has been dismantled this winter, all in the name
of cost-cutting. And this came even after taxpayers went to the
polls and approved in November the financing of one of those
get-rich-now new stadiums for Padres' ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, go to the bottom of the financial batting order in
baseball, and you will find, among many, the Kansas City Royals.
That team sold recently for $75 million. How do you explain this
winter to those fans that Kevin Brown ($105 million), Mike Piazza
($91 million), Bernie Williams ($87.5 million) and Mo Vaughn ($80
million) have suddenly become worth more than your entire
franchise?
</P>
<P>
   And while mumbling over no Johnson or Clemens in the Rangers'
rotation is legitimate, it's also a bit muffled since concerted
effort by management was never a question.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hicks is a newcomer to baseball, but an experienced hand at
putting together billion-dollar corporate deals. When Johnson
decided to sign with Arizona, all Hicks could do was smile and say,
``I've never heard of a business where you offer a guy $12 million
a year and he turns you down.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Johnson rejection, and after Toronto waffled on
trading Clemens, general manager Doug Melvin signed Mark Clark and
Mike Morgan for the rotation, and then handed over the keys to
manager Johnny Oates. Hoping for a Mercedes, Oates ended up with a
Ford (Clark) and a Studebaker (the 39-year old Morgan).
</P>
<P>
   Except, as expected, Oates was driving home the opposite point
when the Rangers hosted a media gathering Friday at The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have come out of the winter with a much better rotation,
and better overall pitching,'' he said, attempting to shoot down
the theory of no Johnson, no Clemens, no improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Know why?'' added Oates. ``Because of Rafael Palmeiro's Gold
Glove at first, Mark McLemore's health at second, a full season
with Royce Clayton at short, a solid Todd Zeile at third, a forever
Gold Glover (Pudge Rodriguez) behind the plate, two very underrated
defensive players at the outfield corners (Rusty Greer and Juan
Gonzalez) and Tom Goodwin's speed in center.''
</P>
<P>
   You see, of course, where Oates is going with this.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stunk on defense last season ... flat stunk,'' said Oates,
frowning at the memory. ``This is the most improved area of this
team. This will make our pitching much better. Last season, we
couldn't catch a cold in flu season. I had no problem with our
pitching, it was our defense I hated.''
</P>
<P>
   Such optimism about the rotation can obviously be debated. But
there's also no denying the defensive shortcomings of '98, which
were severe. The free-agent signing of Palmeiro is a huge upgrade
over Will Clark at first base, and also in the batting order. And
once Clayton arrived in August, he played the most consistent
shortstop in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many Roger Clemens and Randy Johnsons are there?'' said
Oates. ``One of each. They are true No. 1s. None of our five guys
will be true No. 1s. But none are fives either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will score our runs, we will play good defense, and we will
have a rotation that gives us innings and keeps us in ballgames.
I'll take my chances with that. Anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Helling, Aaron Sele, Clark and John Burkett are set for
that rotation. The fifth member will either be Esteban Loaiza or
Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Is that enough to again win the American League West? Maybe. Is
that enough to overcome something like the Yankees in the
postseason? Heavens no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait and see,'' answered Oates.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I think I will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
