<P>
   IMPEACH-MAIN _ WASHINGTON _ Monica Lewinsky appears via
videotape before the Senate. (Foskett/Carr, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/IMPEACH-SCENE _ WASHINGTON _ The thought that may have
lingered in the minds of many Americans as they watched the
unfolding saga of Bill Clinton and Monica Lewinsky came to this:
The president of the United States is 52 years old. His partner in
history's most famous extramarital relationship is 25. This is well
known. But never before had Americans seen and heard Lewinsky. When
they did, the disparity in age and power between Clinton and
Lewinsky seemed that much greater, some said. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-BAXTER _ WASHINGTON _ Fate arranged a cruel irony for
the U.S. Senate on the day it allowed Monica Lewinsky's videotaped
image and voice into its presence. (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TV _ ATLANTA _ Monica Lewinsky's appearance rarely rose
to anything more than a long-awaited curiosity; like the rest of
this historic trial, it was hardly great TV. (Jubera, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE _ WASHINGTON _ A month before the Bipartisan Medicare
Reform Commission is due to make its recommendation, attention is
focusing on a proposal by its chairman, Sen. John Breaux, D-La., to
change the nature of the elderly health program from one in which
the government defines what benefits the elderly will receive to
one in which the government defines how much money the elderly will
get to purchase their own private insurance. (Lipman, Cox News
Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM _ WASHINGTON _ Feb. 8 marks the third anniversary of the
Telecommunications Act. In 1996, after years of haggling, weary
lawmakers put finishing touches on the massive act, intended to
give consumers more choices and drive prices downward. That hasn't
happened: Today, not a single Baby Bell has been given the green
light to move into long-distance markets. Consumers haven't
benefitted either. Telephone prices have kept pace with inflation,
but they haven't been reduced as promised. And cable rates have
soared at an estimated 7 percent per year. What's more, the telecom
landscape has shifted dramatically. Telephone, cable and wireless
companies are in a frenzy to position themselves for the great
Internet race. The dizzying speed of developments has left
lawmakers and regulators grappling with how to regulate an industry
that is changing more quickly than rules can be written. (Regan,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MOVED in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH ILLUSTRATION and PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ANDY-YOUNG _At 66, Andrew Young, among Atlanta's most defining
figures of the past half century, has morphed one more time: He's
Corporate Andy now, flying a million miles last year, pulling down
$25,000 for some speeches and earning more than $200,000 annually
for serving on corporate boards (Marriott, Delta, Archer-Daniels
Midland). He spends much of his time in Africa now, quietly
consulting for select American corproations such as Chevron. He's
living out a seeming contradiction: the pastor/human rights
activist representing an oil company charged with killing peaceful
protesters. But he, as ever, sees his life as fluid, and seizes the
moral highground. (Pomerantz/Hansen, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SUPERBOWL-IMPACT _ ATLANTA _ As Atlanta prepares to host ithe
2000 Super Bowl, there's some substantial disagreement about how
much economic impact the game has on the host city. Some experts
say it's overblown, but the facts and figures seem to be with those
who say that it's the king of special events, and that its benefits
can be long lasting. (Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GIST _ Virginia planter Samuel Gist wrote a utopian provision
into his will in 1808. He directed that his 300 slaves be freed
upon his death and his plantation turned into a sort of freedman
commune. But his last wishes collided with Commonwealth law, which
required that freed slaves leave the state. After much legal
wrangling following Gist's 1815 death, Virginia courts created an
alternate plan. They set up three ``settlements'' for the Gist
slaves in Ohio. Today, only one Gist settlement remains, in
Highland County _ and it's a legal quagmire. Several families of
descendants of the Gist slaves still live on the land, but none of
them has been able to acquire any of the land. For many years, it
was uncertain who was responsible for ever-escalating back taxes.
To prevent the settlement from being sold at sheriff's sale, slave
descendant Paul Turner, who has been farming much of the land for
25 years, agreed to pay taxes on land he doesn't own. Now, Turner
is trying to get title to his land, as is Charles Peacock, who owns
a junkyard on settlement land and who filed a civil lawsuit against
the county in 1996. ``There wouldn't have been a Gist settlement if
I hadn't come back here and paid the taxes,'' Turner said. ``I'd
like to keep it the Gist settlement because I know what the people
went through who came here.'' (Beyerlein, Dayton daily News) MOVED
FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   ANTHRAX _ ATLANTA _ Anthrax. It is everywhere and nowhere. And
inbetween are dozens of local law enforcement, fire and health
departments run ragged by increasing number of threats of exposure
to the deadly bacteria. The U.S. Attorney's Office in Buffalo. A
night club in Los Angeles. A Catholic school in Indianapolis. All
have been victims of anthrax threats the past six months, with it
their occupants subjected to elaborate and expensive response
protocol. What these cities learned from their spat of anthrax
scares could help Atlanta agencies dealing with this city's first
such threat. (Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GUNS _ ATLANTA _ The cities that have sued the gun industry, now
including Atlanta, say they want to recoup the costs of gun
violence from gun makers, such as police services, emergency
services, uninsured victims, etc... But what are the real costs to
cities. The answers are hard to come by. Atlanta doesn't know, and
health experts have occasionally done studies that vary. And what
does Atlanta plan to do to prove its case anyway? (Campos, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/NRA-INFLUENCE _ ATLANTA _ Gauging the strength of support for
the NRA. (Walston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   RAIN-FOREST _ University of Georgia researchers will become the
latest cadre of specialists scouring the tropics for plant species
that may harbor the next miracle drugs against cancer, heart
disease, parasitic infections and other maladies. Under a new $2.5
million, five-year federal grant, the Georgia scientists will focus
on the homelands of the Highland Maya people in the southern
Mexican state of Chiapas. Five other research teams from other
institutions are conducting searches in eight other countries in
Latin America, Africa and southeast Asia. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
