<HEADLINE>
50 GAMES WITHOUT JORDAN NOT A BAD THING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't look now, but NBA owners and players have stumbled onto an
unlikely potion breathing life into their previously comatose
league:
</P>
<P>
   The lockout and Michael Jordan's retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of positive fallout produced by those two
seemingly negative events, the NBA opened its irregular season this
weekend amidst an almost unprecedented buzz.
</P>
<P>
   The lockout lopped off 32 meaningless games, forced a
headline-grabbing free-agent period, and moved players to interact
positively with the fans who pay their salaries.
</P>
<P>
   As for Jordan's departure, it gave hope to 28 teams previously
harmless in the shadow of the Bulls' dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a shorter season players won't get burned out and fans
won't get burned out,'' Heat coach Pat Riley said. ``With Michael
gone it's anybody's championship, and with every game being so
important, it's going to be very exciting, very competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the league should get a clue and make Feb. 1 the
start of the 50-game regular season from now on.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody cares about NBA games in November or December anyway, and
82 is just too many. What do league officials boasting the ``every
game is important in a 50-game season'' mantra say before next
season's return to 82? ``Aw, some of these games will be important,
some won't''?
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of their own incompetence, the NBA has fallen into the
successful blueprint: a two-week training camp/free-agency period
at the end of January, two free exhibition games, a 50-game regular
season starting Feb. 1 (after the NFL and before major league
baseball), league-wide parity, and the normal six-week playoff run.
If you must have an All-Star Weekend, move it to mid-March, just
before the NCAA's Madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our image had been suffering, unrelated to the work
stoppage,'' NBA deputy commissioner Russ Granik said. ``Having gone
through it, I do believe \Rthe lockout\S will restore better
relations between management and the players, and both of them with
the fans. I think players have come to realize how important that
connection is. Maybe, long term, the lockout actually will have
some benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jordan/lockout mixture is giving us young stars like the
Lakers' Kobe Bryant re-signing with their teams, previously aloof
players like the Blazers' Isaiah Rider staying after practice to
sign autographs, and veterans like 37-year-old Derek Harper playing
one more season in hopes of finally winning a ring.
</P>
<P>
   It gave us clear-cut villains like the Celtics' Kenny Anderson
(who complained about struggling to pay insurance on his nine
cars), the Heat's Alonzo Mourning (who said he didn't care if fans
understood what he called the players' financial strife) and Kurt
Thomas (who reneged on his word to the Mavericks to take more money
with the Knicks). It also gave us heroes like the Nets' Jayson
Williams (who donated $20,000 to arena employees after signing his
$100 million deal), Tom Gugliotta (who turned down almost $30
million to sign with the Suns over the Timberwolves), and the Suns'
Danny Manning (attempting to become the first professional athlete
to return from three reconstructive knee surgeries).
</P>
<P>
   Apathetic during the lockout, ``I ``Still'' Love This Game!''
fans are again excited. Having showed owners the path, it's up to
the NBA to follow the road to success.
SPOTLIGHT ON ...
MASHBURN NOT ALL THUMBS AS HE RECOVERS FROM INJURY
</P>
<P>
   Former Maverick franchise cornerstone Jamal Mashburn is off the
trading block in Miami and on schedule for an unlikely return from
last season's nasty thumb injury.
</P>
<P>
   Last Feb. 13 in Detroit Mashburn fell awkwardly on his right
thumb, fracturing it in 16 places. Doctors inserted two screws in
the thumb, told Mashburn he might never play again and would
certainly never regain normal use of the hand.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago Mashburn, offensive option No. 3 for the Heat behind
Tim Hardaway and Alonzo Mourning, shocked himself by simply
reaching down and picking up a ball with one hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've scored 50 points in a game,'' said Mashburn, ``but that
was the biggest thrill in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Mashburn, who scored the 50 against Scottie Pippen at the United
Center in 1994, was rumored to be headed out of Miami as coach Pat
Riley pursued Latrell Sprewell. But now Riley, after being
impressed by Mashburn in training camp and needing a third scorer
in the wake of shooting guard Voshon Lenard's injury, says he sees
the 26-year-old small forward maturing into the player he
envisioned when he acquired him from Dallas for Kurt Thomas, Sasha
Danilovic and Martin Muursepp on Feb. 14, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``People started doubting me for a while, and I kind of doubted
myself,'' said Mashburn. ``But I showed before the injury I was on
my way back. And now, palming that ball is a sign I'm going to get
all the way back.''
IN THE PAINT OFFBEAT BEAT
</P>
<P>
   Cavaliers All-Star forward Shawn Kemp is working to drop off the
extra 30 pounds he put on during the lockout. And, he rid himself
of some emotional baggage as well.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp, who has fathered seven children with six women, finally
addressed his situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just an NBA problem; it's the nation's problem,''
Kemp said of out-of-wedlock pregnancies. ``I know what I did was
wrong. Now I've got to live with it and be the best person I can
be.''
BEST AND WORST
</P>
<P>
   Worst ceremony: The Bulls are planning a special night to honor
Phil Jackson and retire a jersey in his likeness. Had they simply
honored him last year, they could've had the NBA leader in career
winning percentage and owner of six championships still on their
bench. Only Red Auerbach of the Celtics, Red Holzman of the Knicks,
Jack Ramsay of the Trail Blazers and Frank Layden of the Jazz have
had jerseys retired in their honor.
</P>
<P>
   Best botching of a No. 1 overall pick: With Jim Jackson signing
with the Blazers last week, the Warriors now have absolutely
nothing to show for Joe Smith, the first pick in the '95 draft.
They traded Smith and Brian Shaw to the Sixers last year for
Jackson and Clarence Weatherspoon, who signed with the Heat.
QUOTE OF NOTE
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe the fans will come back. What are they going
to do when they're flipping around the TV? Stop at ``Three's
Company'' instead of the Sonics and Lakers? I don't think so.'' _
Sonics coach Paul Westphal.
CRYSTAL ROUNDBALL
</P>
<P>
   Pre-season predictions for '99's postseason awards:
</P>
<P>
   MVP: Karl Malone, Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive player of the year: Scottie Pippen, Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Coach of the year: Jerry Sloan, Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Sixth Man of the year: Kobe Bryant, Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie of the year: Paul Pierce, Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   All-NBA: Gary Payton, Sonics; Reggie Miller, Pacers; Scottie
Pippen, Rockets; Karl Malone, Jazz; Tim Duncan, Spurs.
DRIBBLING AROUND THE EAST
</P>
<P>
   How far have the Bulls fallen? They were 15-point underdogs
Friday night at Utah. ... The Knicks definitely have a new look at
power forward, where they traded grizzled warrior Charles Oakley
for Marcus Camby, who missed two days of practice and an exhibition
game with a deep blister. ... Give the Nets' computer geeks credit
for the signing of free-agent forward Scott Burrell. Coach John
Calipari wowed Burrell with a video play book that used footage of
Burrell superimposed into a Nets uniform.
DRIBBLING AROUND THE WEST
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal wanted Tom Gugliotta, now it's Dennis Rodman.
Guess he and power forward Elden Campbell don't do lunch often.
``We tried to make some moves, but I guess other teams really don't
want to help us,'' O'Neal said of Minnesota turning down a
Gugliotta-for-Campbell-and-Eddie Jones deal. ``So from now on I'll
hold a personal vendetta against Minnesota. They're added to the
list.'' ... Bigger Country: Grizzlies center Bryant Reeves showed
up for camp at 318 pounds, or 40 more than last season. He's lost
his starting job to journeyman Tony Massenburg.
INSIDE THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   Only 11 players have scored 20,000 points and grabbed 10,000
rebounds in their NBA careers. Knicks center Patrick Ewing, with
22,096 points, needs 213 rebounds to join this exclusive club:
(active players in bold) Player Points Rebounds Kareem Abdul-Jabbar
38,387 17,440 Wilt Chamberlain 31,419 23,924 Karl Malone 27,803
11,384 Moses Malone 27,409 16,212 Elvin Hayes 27,313 16,279 Hakeem
Olajuwon 24,433 12,206 Robert Parish 23,334 14,715 Elgin Baylor
23,149 11,463 Charles Barkley 22,823 11,836
</P>
<P>
   Walt Bellamy 20,941 14,241 Bob Pettit 20,880 12,849
</P>
