<HEADLINE>
JOURNALIST CONTRADICTS BLUMENTHAL'S `STALKER' DENIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House prosecutors turned over to the Senate on
Saturday a sworn affidavit of a journalist who contradicted White
House aide Sidney Blumenthal's videotaped claim that he never
divulged President Clinton's initial claim that Lewinsky was a
``stalker'' who made sexual demands of him.
</P>
<P>
   British journalist Christopher Hitchens, a contributor to Vanity
Fair and The Nation magazines, said in an affidavit signed Friday
that Blumenthal told him and an unidentified person over lunch on
March 19, 1998, that Lewinsky was ``a stalker'' and that the
president was ``the victim' of a predatory and unstable sexually
demanding young woman.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal also disseminated the same account to other
journalists, Hitchens said.
</P>
<P>
   In his deposition, Blumenthal said he met with Clinton in the
Oval Office on Jan. 21, 1998, the day the Lewinsky story broke in
the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said Clinton told him that Lewinsky referred to
herself as a ``stalker,'' and that she would either have an affair
or claim she had an affair with Clinton to prove the nickname
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, in the deposition, said he never shared the
information with journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The second House impeachment article accusing Clinton of
obstructing justice specifically alleges that the president spread
false stories about Lewinsky so aides would repeat them in front of
the grand jury. It does not accuse Clinton of disseminating them to
journalists, but proof that White House aides were the source of
such stories would be embarrassing to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, a witness contradicting Blumenthal could expose
Blumenthal to a charge of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from Blumenthal, a journalist who
wrote for the Washington Post, the New Republic and the Nation
before going to the White House in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to House prosecutors said their investigators were alerted
to Hitchens version of events late last week and secured a sworn
affidavit from him on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
