<HEADLINE>
MONICA LEWINSKY STARS IN VIDEOTAPE DEBUT AT CLINTON TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   EDS: Editing, trims throughout)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Videotapes rolled at the Senate impeachment trial
Saturday as senators and the American public saw Monica Lewinsky
for the first time tell her now-familiar story of sex,
job-searching and a false affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   There were no dramatic revelations during the six hours of
arguments and video, and the Senate appeared headed for an
almost-certain vote to acquit President Clinton later this week on
the two impeachment articles charging perjury and obstruction of
justice.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the public debut of Lewinsky on videotape
dominated the proceeding as senators and the American public saw a
poised young lady talk about her relationship with the president of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on four large TV monitors set up in the Senate
chamber, Lewinsky appeared calm and composed, wearing a string of
pearls and a dark top, her lips glossed pink. She punctuated her
sentences by brushing her black, helmet-like hair off her face or
flicking it back with a shake of her head.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, asked about her response to presidential confidant
Vernon Jordan's suggestion that her ``problem'' was that she was in
love with Clinton, Lewinksy flashed an embarrassed smile and said:
``I probably blushed or giggled or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about how she felt about Clinton now, Lewinsky said, ``I
have mixed feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors used Lewinsky's testimony and that of
presidential confidant Vernon Jordan and White House aide Sidney
Blumenthal to bolster their case that the president lied in his
August 19, 1998, grand jury appearance about his affair with
Lewinsky, and obstructed justice by encouraging her to file a false
affidavit in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Lewinsky's statement that Clinton didn't ask her to lie
and that there were no explicit promises of a job in exchange for
her silence, prosecutor Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., argued that the
testimony of Lewinsky, Clinton and others taken together shows how
Clinton ``wove a web of perjury and obstruction.'' Rogan was her
main questioner at the videotaped deposition last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors zeroed in on Clinton's 2 a.m. phone call to Lewinsky
on Dec. 17, 1997, when he informed her that her name had come up on
the witness list faxed to the White House by Jones' lawyers.
Clinton also suggested Lewinsky could sign an affidavit to avoid
testifying.
</P>
<P>
   The video showed Lewinsky being asked about Clinton's suggestion
she could say her frequent Oval Office trips were to see
presidential secretary Betty Currie or bring Clinton letters.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky said she had heard those words before. Secrecy and
denial, she said, ``was part of the pattern of the relationship ...
I knew I would deny the relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky ultimately signed an affidavit denying the relationship
on Jan. 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also a videotape excerpt showing Lewinsky recalling
that Currie called her on Dec. 28, 1997, and saying she would drive
by Lewinsky's apartment to pick up a package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume (Currie) meant the gifts,'' Lewinsky said, referring
to gifts she had received from Clinton that were being sought by
Jones' lawyers. Currie retrieved the gifts and stashed them under
her bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way the Betty Currie could know to come and get the
gifts was the president telling her to do so,'' Rogan said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also focused on Jordan's claim that at a critical
juncture in December 1997 Clinton didn't tell him that Lewinsky's
name was on the witness list.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said ``it would have been helpful'' to have this
information as he dialed influential corporate friends in high
places to find Lewinsky a job.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said he did not learn that Lewinsky was on the Jones
witness list until Dec. 19, 1997 _ 13 days after Clinton first
learned it.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors argue Clinton and Jordan intensified the job
search for Lewinsky that month in order to keep her from telling
the truth about her affair with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's legal team argued that Lewinsky's testimony ``is so
clear, it exonerates the president,'' as one of the lawyers, Nicole
Seligman, put it.
</P>
<P>
   In excerpts played by the White House legal team, Lewinsky
recalls Clinton suggesting in the Dec. 17, 1997, phone call that
she could sign an affidavit, but she insisted: ``There was no
discussion of what would be in the affidavit.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she understood the implication of filing a false
affidavit, Lewinsky responded: ``I don't think I necessarily
thought at that point that it would have to be false.'' That
accords with Clinton's contention that he believed Lewinsky could
sign a truthful affidavit denying a sexual relationship because
they had not had sexual intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   Senate reaction to the videos ranged the spectrum of party
affiliation and political conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've heard is devastating to the White House,'' said Sen.
Larry Craig, R-Idaho. ``Now we know why the White House fought to
the bitter end on disallowing those videotapes... once you bring
all those personalities together, the story becomes complete.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig continued: ``The president didn't tell (Lewinsky) to lie,
but she obviously understood that she was to tell a story that was
a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig said Lewinsky at last had deflated White House attempts to
smear her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American public could see Monica Lewinsky for the first
time as Monica Lewinsky. Is she a stalker today? No. Is she a
predator? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Bond, R-Mo., said he felt the videos were
``very powerful,'' and that Lewinsky ``came across as very straight
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was deja vu all over again,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy,
D-Vt., who sat in on all the depositions.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats scoffed that the videos didn't tell them anything new.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors are ``making the best case they can, but
there's nothing new in the videos,'' said Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., accused House prosecutors of
changing their theory of the impeachment case against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've gone from a conspiracy theory to `No one knew, but the
president,''' Boxer said, referring to Lewinsky's denial of
pressure on the affidavit and Jordan saying the president failed to
tell him about Lewinsky's name on the Jones witness list as he
searched for a job for her in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very strange theory,'' Boxer said. ``If nobody felt any
pressure, nobody made any connections, what happened? Nothing. I
think (prosecutors) hurt themselves badly.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, outside the Senate chamber during breaks, senators
batted the idea of a censure resolution back and forth with little
evidence they were close to agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tapping into that emotion should be fairly easy,'' said Sen.
Robert Bennett, R-Utah, who has worked with Sen. Dianne Feinstein,
D-Calif., to come up with bipartisan agreement on a censure
resolution. ``But finding the right set of words that can get
everyone in general agreement on the same idea is not so easy.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted between 60 and 80 votes for censure.
</P>
<P>
   Other senators, particularly conservative Republicans, said they
opposed censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a pat on the butt saying `Go home, you bad boy,'''
said Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, said censure would set a ``bad
precedent'' for the future. ``What the American people want us to
do is get back to our business,'' DeWine said. ``People will be
shocked if an hour or a day after an up-or-down vote on
impeachment, we are back in the U.S. Senate debating the
president's conduct...It is not the job of the U.S. Congress to
punish the president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
