r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BASEBALL-REPORT-T     02-06 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE THE REDS CREDIT FOR TRYING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Reds are making a brave attempt at being decent
this year.
</P>
<P>
   You have to salute their audacity, but also wonder if they can
carry this through an entire season or if general manager Jim
Bowden will be forced to dismantle come July 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds greatly improved their starting rotation by acquiring
Denny Neagle from the Atlanta Braves in November and they added
badly-needed power to their lineup last week when they traded for
San Diego Padres outfielder Greg Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle joins Brett Tomko and Pete Harnisch to give the Reds a
nice front to their starting rotation. It could get even better if
pitching coach Don Gullett can get either Jason Bere and/or Steve
Avery back to where they once were.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn and shortstop Barry Larkin, who is no longer looking to
be traded, provide veteran anchors to a young lineup with
considerable potential. First baseman Sean Casey, right fielder
Dmitri Young and center fielder Mike Cameron all have a chance to
be pretty good offensive players.
</P>
<P>
   The moves, which will bring the Reds payroll up to $31 million,
should at least make the Reds a contender in the National League
Central. They were 77-85 last season, but are easily the most
improved team in the division.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Astros still have the best team, but aren't as good
as they were at the end of last year after losing Randy Johnson.
Their biggest acquisition this off-season was third baseman Ken
Caminiti, but that overlooks the fact that Sean Berry and Bill
Spiers were an extremely productive platoon combination last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs only real move was signing free agent catcher
Benito Santiago. They acquired pitcher Jon Lieber from Pittsburgh,
but lost Mark Clark to free agency. The St. Louis Cardinals
upgraded their bullpen with Scott Radinsky and Ricky Bottalico, but
failed to address their crippled starting pitching. They acquired
shortstop Edgar Renteria and outfielder Eric Davis, but lost
outfielder Brian Jordan and second baseman Delino DeShields.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad the Reds couldn't afford another $16 million for,
say, free agent third baseman Dean Palmer ($7 million), closer Mike
Timlin ($4 million) and Clark ($5 million) to help their rotation.
Then they would have a legitimate pennant contender.
</P>
<P>
   Instead the Reds have to count on Aaron Boone at third, unproven
Gabe White as their closer and either Avery or Bere to come through
as starters. It's also unlikely they'll have enough money to make
the big midseason trade all contenders look for to boost their
chances down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Reds manager Jack McKeon has to hope his team comes
together in the first few months of the season. Otherwise Bowden
would have to pull the plug and unload Neagle, Vaughn and maybe
even Larkin.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost an impossible task trying to compete as a
small-market team. One mistake or a key injury could cause the
whole thing to unravel and cost an owner millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the Reds are making a legitimate attempt.
CLEMENS VS. CLARK
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens is a much better pitcher than Mark Clark. The
Toronto Blue Jays were 24-9 last year during Clemens 33 starts
while the Chicago Cubs were 12-21 when Clark started for them.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would be better off with Clemens on their staff
rather than Clark. But would it have been better to have traded for
Clemens rather than signing Clark as a free agent?
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the previous four years.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox and the Blue Jays were a combined 65-50 when
Clemens started for them in 1994-97. That includes a Cy Young Award
season for Toronto in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   During that same period, Clark's teams - Cleveland, New York
Mets and the Cubs - were 63-42 when he pitched. That's a .600
winning percentage compared to a .565 winning percentage for
Clemens' teams.
</P>
<P>
   Again, nobody is saying Clark is the better pitcher. Clemens had
a 2.84 ERA during that stretch while Clark's ERA was 3.97 and three
of those seasons were in the National League. Clemens also pitched
50 more innings per year.
</P>
<P>
   But Clark is also five years younger and makes $3.5 million less
- if you don't have to renegotiate Clemen's contract.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest thing is the Rangers didn't have to give up Ivan
Rodriguez, Rusty Greer, Rick Helling or valuable minor league
prospects to get Clark.
</P>
<P>
   That's why they were better off signing Clark than trading for
Clemens.
SHORT HOPS
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, trying to stem the exodus out of San Diego, will
attempt to work out a long-term contract extension with reliever
Trevor Hoffman during spring training. He can be a free agent after
the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians are concerned shortstop Omar Vizquel might hold out
in spring training because the club refuses to re-negotiate his
contract. Vizquel signed a six-year contract after the 1995 season
worth $3 million per year with an option for a seventh season. But
now he's unhappy his salary is well below what Roberto Alomar (four
years, $32 million), Jose Offerman (four years, $26 million) and
others are getting.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the price you pay for long-term security and general
manager John Hart is right in refusing to renegotiate. After all,
Vizquel wouldn't be giving any money back had he suffered a
career-ending injury.
</P>
<P>
   Phillies catcher Mike Lieberthal, who missed the final two
months of last season with a pelvic stress fracture, has told
manager Terry Francona he's close to 100 percent after an intensive
off-season of rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles manager Ray Miller wants to use Albert Belle as his No.
3 hitter, meaning Will Clark will bat cleanup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
