<SLUG> BC-BKW-RUTGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE POWERS RUTGERS PAST BOSTON COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESTNUT HILL, Mass. _ Rutgers women's basketball coach C.
Vivian Stringer has a lot of reasons to smile these days.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off Saturday's 71-52 victory over Boston College at the
Conte Forum, the Scarlet Knights are 20-4 overall and 12-1 in the
Big East. They are ranked 12th nationally and have won 10 of their
last 11 games and 14 of their last 16.
</P>
<P>
   In the Big East, they trail only Connecticut (19-3; 12-1 heading
into Saturday night's game at Miami).
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights were led by Tammy Sutton-Brown's 18 points
and a stingy defense that held No. 20 Boston College to 31.5
percent shooting. Tomora Young fished with 16 points, 14 in the
first 8{ minutes. And Tasha Pointer had 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun to coach this game and exciting as well,'' Stringer
said. ``We got good looks at the basket and we were able to take
good shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers opened by making its first four shots, including three
three-pointers by Young in a 68-second span, to pull to an 11-0
lead 2:14 in.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Knights' man-to-man defense that set the tone of
the game. Ranked second in the country and first in the Big East,
Rutgers defense allows only 55.6 points a game and has held
opponents under 50 points six times this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't played man-to-man in a game this year,'' Stringer
said, ``but the players were very focused. We found our
killer-instinct today.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston College (17-5, 9-5), which lost its second straight,
scored its fewest points this season. Becky Gottstein scored 12
points and Whitney Steele 11 for the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   In only her fourth year at Rutgers, Stringer has guided her
program back to national prominence. She called Saturday's effort
on the road against a ranked opponent a confidence-booster to
propel her players into the stretch drive.
</P>
<P>
   This year Rutgers hosts the Big East tournament, and with only
five games remaining on their schedule, the Scarlet Knights are
eyeing the No. 1 seed. Their toughest test will come next Saturday
when they host No. 6 Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Their ultimate goal, of course, is an appearance in the Final
Four in San Jose, Calif., next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
