<HEADER>
A4650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE07-COX     02-06 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chance to `meet' Lewinsky gives case against Clinton
credibility, some say
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The thought that may have lingered in the minds of
many Americans as they watched the unfolding saga of Bill Clinton
and Monica Lewinsky was on the lips of Laura Emons on Saturday
after she spent the morning at Clinton's impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man could have been her father. I think that would hurt
him more than anything,'' said Emons, a Chespeake, Va., who was
spending a weekend in Washington with a girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the United States is 52 years old. His partner
in history's most famous extramarital relationship is 25. This much
is well known.
</P>
<P>
   But never before had Americans seen and heard Lewinsky. When
they did, the disparity in age and power between Clinton and
Lewinsky seemed that much greater, Emons said.
</P>
<P>
   If the outcome of the impeachment trial is a foregone conclusion
and Clinton is to remain in office _ as senators and most everyone
else believe _ then Lewinsky's first public appearance via
videotape Saturday might have been aimed at the court of public
opinion and, perhaps, history.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to arguing the perjury and obstruction of justice
charges, the prosecutors also seemed to try to portray Clinton as a
lowlife, a user of women who cared so little about them that he was
willing to tell crude lies about them to trusted aides.
</P>
<P>
   Spectators, especially women, leaving the packed gallery after
15 minutes or an hour of watching the former White House employee,
commented on Lewinsky's credibility as a witness and prosecutors'
success in weaving a sordid tale of her affair with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've read all about this, but somehow hearing it gave the
story some more credibility,'' Sharon Jarvis, a suburban Milwaukee
resident, said. ``She just speaks in a conversational tone.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion that giving people a chance to ``meet'' Lewinsky
would change minds was a key component of the prosecution's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.), addressing
reporters during a break in the trial, called the presentation
compelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have finally had the chance to see live people talking
about what had happened,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said several callers to his office Saturday lamented the
Senate's decision not to have live witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.), who opposed having Lewinsky
testify in person, said the prosecutors' ability to use videotaped
excerpts of the depositions of Lewinsky, Washington lawyer Vernon
Jordan and Clinton aide Sidney Blumenthal enhanced their
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The video probably was more powerful and coherent than it
would have been if we had the natural disorder of witnesses and
objections, the normal courtroom confusion,'' Coverdell said.
</P>
<P>
   The first image of Lewinsky showed her with her right hand
raised, swearing an oath to be truthful in last week's deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry (D-Mass.) provided spectators the first
noticable reaction, a shake of his head and a rueful smile.
</P>
<P>
   One theme that ran through reactions to the videotape was that,
despite Lewinsky's evident youth, she had the self-assurance of
someone who knew what she wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's conversations with Clinton, Jordan and Oval Office
secretary Betty Currie sometimes makes it seem that ``she had the
whole White House at her beck and call,'' Chrisann LaPorte of
Franklin Lakes, N.J., said.
</P>
<P>
   Muffy Rowe of Hawthorne, N.J., LaPorte's friend, chimed in,
``She knew what she was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet LaPorte and Rowe, both stay-at-home mothers of two young
children, said Lewinsky's testimony made a powerful impression on
them and altered their view of Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear to me he lied and obstructed justice,'' LaPorte
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she would admit to an affair, Rowe said, ``If I was
being deposed I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Their reaction to the presentation is the one prosecutors hope
to establish in the record of the trial, whatever its outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``My 4-year-old is at the age when he is learning right from
wrong,'' LaPorte said. ``How can we condone this kind of lying?''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors' use of Lewinsky, Jordan and Blumenthal on tape
may not have changed any minds in the Senate, and certainly did not
affect the views of some spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Keith and Darlene Kerr, new to the Washington area, said that
the effort to show Lewinsky as the girl next door had not moved
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the videos would have been better with some background
music,'' Keith Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   Jose J. Rodriguez of Alexandria said Saturday's session
persuaded him that Republicans had undertaken ``a political attempt
to get rid of President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez markets political paraphenalia, including buttons that
offer a racy look at the sex scandal and its cover up.
</P>
<P>
   The lasting impression Rodriguez said he took from Lewinsky's
videotape is of an impressive woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see how she became a presidential girlfriend,'' he said.
``She can be my girlfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
