A4651 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TV07-COX     02-06 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TV07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Battle of snippets' proves anti-climactic
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We were up and we were in front of our TVs at 10 a.m.
Saturday morning for one reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``An ignoble impulse,'' CNN's Jeff Greenfield admitted, speaking
for many of us, of why he'd be watching Monica Lewinsky's
videotaped testimony during Saturday's very special episode of the
Senate impeachment trial. ``(I) just want to see the real-life
person who almost got the president removed from office.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, there she was: Lewinsky, raising a pudgy
hand while taking her oath. She looked, Greenfield later put it,
``like an early 1960s college graduate, with her pearls and her
hair that way.... Monica looks very young to be with a middle-aged
man.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a curious moment, watching her, looking for something,
anything, we hadn't seen before. ``The fascination factor,'' PBS's
Margaret Warner explained, ``of finally putting a human face on
this trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Lewinsky's appearance rarely rose to anything more than a
long-awaited curiosity; like the rest of this historic trial, it
was hardly great TV. Locally, ABC, NBC and Fox didn't even air it,
while CBS stuck around until the House managers took their first
break. A year ago, Greenfield said, ``the atmosphere would have
been electric.'' On Saturday, it felt anti-climactic.
</P>
<P>
   We looked _ stared _ for something more charged than another
unreeling of the evidence, of testimony that Lewinsky would be
giving, as attorney Mark Braden said on CNN, ``for the gazillion
and oneth time.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we were looking for a kind videotaped version of Linda
Tripp's audio-taped phone converstations: a lovestruck
mistress-scorned gossiping in Valley-speak about the Big Creep.
</P>
<P>
   The best we got Saturday was her sipping a glass of water
through a straw and, and when asked if she was a resident of
California, her answer: ``I'm not sure where I'm a resident right
now. But that's where I'm living.''
</P>
<P>
   She was mostly just poised and straightforward and at ease; when
she couldn't remember something, she answered a lot like Vernon
Jordan, whose testimony also ran on Saturday, and said she stood by
her grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they hear one more time `I stand by my grand jury
testimony,' I think the House managers are going to jump out of
their suits,'' said PBS's Paul Gigot.
</P>
<P>
   It was mostly, said CBS's Bob Schieffer, ``a battle of
snippets'' _ clips and excerpts and soundbites of the videotape
that each side spliced to its advantage. The picture that resulted
was disappointingly incomplete _ more a sampling than a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really seeing her as a person yet,'' said PBS's Tom
Oliphant. ``What they're presenting is not her, but a part of her.
Each side will show a part of her, but you won't see her.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Saturday was a lot like a real trial, something
TV has always had trouble with.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Today's) proceedings remind us of that fact,'' said CBS's Dan
Rather. ``On televison, we are used to watching courtroom dramas
that are tidy, scripted and determined in advance. But real life is
messier... real life is less like the TV show `Perry Mason' and
more like the movie `Rashomon.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After surely throwing some of his audience with that overly
off-handed allusion to the 1951 Oscar-winning film from Japan,
Rather really revved up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same events can be perceived very differently by different
people. Truth is never absolute,'' he waxed. ``It is more often a
matter of grudging compromise. So it is in the video testimony you
have been watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Following that lordly lecture, Rather crashed back down to
earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We return now,'' he said, ``to regular programming.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
