<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4660 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MAIN07-COX     02-06 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MAIN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewinsky comes across as `bright, clear' in dueling video clips
shown to Senate
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr and Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pressing their case before a national television
audience, House Republican prosecutors and White House lawyers
offered dueling video snippets Saturday of the woman at the center
of the perjury and obstruction of justice case against President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   For the House prosecutors, putting Monica Lewinsky's videotape
deposition before the Senate marked a last-ditch effort to win over
the court of public opinion after realizing they have all but lost
the Senate vote to remove the president from office.
</P>
<P>
   For the White House, it was an opportunity to clear the
president of the allegation that he encouraged Lewinsky to file a
false statement to lawyers pursuing a sexual harassment lawsuit
against the president. They also hoped to fend off the charge that
he enlisted his friend Vernon Jordan to help Lewinsky get a job in
exchange for not cooperating in that lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a black jacket and a single strand of pearls,
Lewinsky appeared confident and poised in her answers to questions
about whether the president encouraged her to file a false
statement in the Paula Jones sexual harassment suit. At various
times during the day-long hearing, the prosecution and the defense
used the same video bites to make opposing points.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides zeroed in on the most serious charge against Clinton,
that he obstructed justice in his efforts to conceal his
relationship with Lewinsky. Prosecutors mentioned only in passing
the charge that Clinton lied to a federal grand jury, a claim that
many senators have said is the weakest.
</P>
<P>
   Closing arguments in the trial are scheduled for Monday before
the Senate debates a motion to open the deliberations to the
public, and then goes into jury deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   In making the case for the prosecutors, Rep. James Rogan
(R-Calif.) told the senators any one of them could have known a
young, impressionable intern like Lewinsky. Was it right for the
president to have impulsively used her for his own gratification
and then launched a scheme to conceal that affair?
</P>
<P>
   Life is about making the right choices, Rogan said. Had the
president's ``bad decision'' to have an affair with Lewinsky ended
with adultery, the Senate would not be conducting a trial, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seek no punishment for a man who cheated on his wife,''
Rogan said. Rather, the prosecutors are seeking punishment for a
man who had ``cheated the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Summing up the House case, Rep. Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.)
delivered an emotional plea to convict Clinton of the two charges
against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a nation of men or kings, we are nation of laws.''
Graham said. ``That's what this case is about. For God sakes,
figure out what kind of man we have here in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they fought hard to prevent House prosecutors from
airing the videotaped depositions of Lewinsky, Jordan and White
House aide Sidney Blumenthal, Clinton's lawyers nonetheless
liberally aired long segments of the depositions to make their case
that the president never explicitly told Lewinsky to lie in her
Jones case affidavit or to get rid of the many gifts he gave her.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Seligman, one of Clinton's personal attorneys, accused
House prosecutors of using the video excerpts to distort the
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mangers have cleverly snipped here and there to tell their
story,'' Seligman said. ``They have distorted, omitted and they
have created a wholly erroneous story.''
</P>
<P>
   Seligman aired long portions of Lewinsky's deposition in which
she told House prosecutors that Clinton never instructed her how to
complete her affidavit in the sexual harassment suit.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors pointed out that Clinton also never told Lewinsky to
tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The managers ask you to convict the president based on his
silence,'' Seligman responded.
</P>
<P>
   In the day's only moment of levity, Graham made reference to the
early-morning telephone call Clinton made to Lewinsky on Dec. 17,
1997, in which he told her she was on the Jones case witness list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I come from, you call someone at 2:30 in the morning,
and you're up to no good,'' said Graham, prompting loud guffaws
from both Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors also sought to use Lewinsky's deposition to
bolster their case that Clinton ordered his personal secretary,
Betty Currie, to retrieve gifts from Lewinsky that he had given to
her over the course of their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way Betty Currie would know to pick up the
president's gifts would be if the president told her to,'' Rogan
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Seligman reminded senators that neither Lewinsky nor Currie
ever said that Clinton told either of them that he was behind the
gift retrieval, and she quoted Lewinsky saying that she had decided
on her own that she would give to the Jones lawyers only
``innocuous gifts'' that would not arouse suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica Lewinsky had made her own decision for her own reasons
not to produce gifts,'' Seligman said. ``It is time for this
tireless pursuit of the president to come to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   After reviewing the videotaped depositions for most of the week,
some senators could barely contain their frustration at having been
brought in on a Saturday to view snippets of the videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking of making a constitutional point of order that
this is cruel and unusual punishment,'' joked Sen. Patrick Leahy
(D-Vt.).
</P>
<P>
   ``The trial has been over for several days,'' said Sen. Chris
Dodd (D-Conn.). ``This is water torture.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said that Lewinsky came off poised, bright and
well-spoken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, she's a fine young woman, from what I can tell,''
said Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   But Larry Craig (R-Ind.) said he thought the House prosecutors
had put on a stellar case and that the videotaped witnesses filled
in holes of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's obviously bright, clear,'' Craig added. ``The public is
seeing her for the first time as Monica Lewinsky, not as the White
House wants to see her. Is she a stalker today? No. Is she a
predator? No. I think they (the public) are seeing something they
may not have expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton (R-Wash.) said the House prosecutors made
their most convincing case to date with Saturday's presenation.
``Not to say that votes were changed in the Senate,'' he said,
``but it was a dramatic presentation for the nation as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
