<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4666 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BOB-STOOPS-TEX     02-06 1561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOB-STOOPS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW HE'S THE BOSS: OU'S STOOPS FACES NEW CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the personnel decisions made by NCAA Division I-A
athletic directors, this one ranks among the toughest:
</P>
<P>
   When is a bright, promising assistant ready to assume the mantle
of head football coach and direct your highest-profile program?
</P>
<P>
   Promoting the right guy can lead to decades of success and
stability. Witness Joe Paterno at Penn State or former Nebraska
coach Tom Osborne. Both men rose from the assistant ranks at their
respective schools to become legends, combining for a record of
562-129-6 and five national championships in 58 seasons (33 years
for Paterno, 25 for Osborne).
</P>
<P>
   Selecting the wrong up-and-comer, on the other hand, can prove
disastrous. Three years after Oklahoma officials entrusted their
program to John Blake, a former Sooners player and NFL assistant
who had never been a coordinator at any level, regents voted to
fire him in the wake of a 12-22 mark that stands as the worst
three-year stretch in the history of the school's football program.
</P>
<P>
   What is interesting, however, is that Oklahoma officials
replaced Blake with another man who will open the 1999 season with
a career mark of 0-0 at the Division I-A level: Bob Stoops, a
former Florida defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   If Stoops follows the lead of Blake, the Oklahoma program is in
trouble. If he follows in the footsteps of two lifelong assistants
who made OU their first stop as head football coaches _ Bud
Wilkinson and Barry Switzer _ the Sooners' return to glory is just
around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Lest anyone forget, the once-unproven Wilkinson and Switzer
combined for a record of 302-58-8 while working in Norman, Okla.
Each won three national championships. No other OU coach has won
one.
</P>
<P>
   Why should Sooners fans, who have not experienced a winning
season since 1993, believe Stoops' tenure will follow more closely
the path taken by Wilkinson and Switzer than Blake? Administrators
and peers point to a variety of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   For the past five years, rival college coaches have identified
Stoops, 38, as one of the game's elite assistants who seemed headed
down the fast track to success. Blake never received such
widespread acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   Stoops has served as a defensive coordinator for the past eight
seasons at two schools (Florida and Kansas State) that have posted
multiple top-10 finishes, including a 1996 national championship in
Stoops' first year at Florida. Blake never had been in charge of
either offense or defense before being hired in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest difference, in the estimation of Oklahoma
athletic director Joe Castiglione, rests with intangibles:
organization skills, accountability, and a confident presence that
should play favorably with alumni and media members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt Bob Stoops had experienced everything about the game
but having that head coach title,'' Castiglione said. ``He has been
in all the big games, over and over again. He constantly prepares
in a high-visibility arena. Everywhere he's been, he's been an
individual who has risen to the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stoops will have the backbone to stay the course and have guts
enough that, if a judgmental error is made here or there, he'll
admit it. But he'll fix it and go on. He has exhibited tremendous
leadership qualities and that, with his preparation and personal
commitment to strong values, I felt was a super fit. This is
something that's got to be long-term.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoops, who received lukewarm reviews on his first recruiting
class, will not face the acid test until September, when the
Sooners open the 1999 season. But he said he feels comfortable in
his new role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I've been has given me great preparation to be able to
handle this position,'' said Stoops, who has been an assistant
coach at Iowa (1983-87) and Kent State (1988), as well as Kansas
State (1989-95) and Florida (1996-98). ``All I can say is, `I feel
very comfortable in this position.' I feel I can attract and get
the kind of staff that knows how to build and win championships. I
believe in time, I'll be a guy that fans will be happy with.''
</P>
<P>
   Until someone has proved his mettle as a head coach with the
won-loss record, impressions created by actions taken as an
assistant are the only means of judging an up-and-coming talent.
Little things, say coaches and administrators, mean a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Willingness to handle interviews and alumni gatherings sharpen
much-needed people skills. Success as a coordinator implies
probable success overseeing the entire program, especially if that
coach is willing to delegate responsibilities to fellow assistants.
A zeal for pounding the pavement as a recruiter suggests you will
be aggressive in pursuit of the talent necessary to turn around a
downtrodden program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys sit around and don't want to do any of those
things,'' said Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum. ``Then, they turn
around and ask, `How come I wasn't the head coach?' Well, you
didn't do anything head coaches have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going to every clinic and speaking to every A&AMP;M
club I could \Ras an assistant\S because I was putting money in the
bank for here or somewhere else. They're not always fun deals. But
it's what you do if you want to do this job.''
</P>
<P>
   Because an assistant's attributes must be judged by others,
Slocum said body language is important for the aspiring head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot comes down to intangibles,'' Slocum said. ``The way they
carry themselves. The way they dress. The comments they make. As a
head coach, you'll have a bunch of situations where ... you have to
bite the bullet and go on. Guys having the composure in those
situations to take the high road and see the big picture separates
some of the guys from the also-rans.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoops, in the estimation of peers, scores well in those areas.
But how can administrators confidently project him to be a
program-turner if his career record is 0-0? Simple, said Ohio State
coach John Cooper. They can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to gut instinct as to when a guy is ready,''
Cooper said. ``It's something that happens over a period of time,
but I don't know if there is a certain point you know for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a successful head coach, the No. 1 thing you've got to
do is recruit. You show me a coach who has a good record, and I'll
show you a coach that's got good players and has had a good
schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind skill as a recruiter, Cooper ranks the ability to
delegate responsibility and a grasp of the big picture as the
primary attributes needed to succeed as a Division I-A head
football coach.
</P>
<P>
   Some, such as Arkansas athletic director Frank Broyles, favor a
coach with a background on offense because he will have more
experience in calling plays. Others discount that as a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a myth,'' said Switzer, the former OU and Cowboys'
coach. ``Defensive coaches know more about offense than most
offensive coaches. What do they study all day long? They look at
other people's offenses. They game-plan to stop other people's
offenses. They see how people are attacking them and how they are
vulnerable. A football coach can coach all phases. It doesn't make
any difference what side of the ball he happens to coach.''
</P>
<P>
   What is significant, say coaches and administrators, is the
record of the school where you served as a top assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you haven't been around a program that's the best, you
don't know how to create one yourself,'' said David Boren,
Oklahoma's school president. ``That's a big asset for Bob Stoops.
He's been exposed to winning programs. He knows what `standard of
excellence' means.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoops has coordinated defenses that ranked among the nation's
top 15 in total defense the past five seasons. His 1995 unit at
Kansas State led the nation (250.8 yards per game), and his 1998
unit at Florida ranked 11th nationally, allowing 286.6 yards per
game.
</P>
<P>
   But a hidden plus, in the estimation of A&AMP;M offensive
coordinator Steve Kragthorpe, may be the fact that Stoops holds a
bachelor's degree in marketing from Iowa, where he played defensive
back from 1979-82. The growing emphasis on the business end of
college sports convinced Kragthorpe, 33, to complete his master's
degree in marketing in 1990 before entering the coaching ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``College athletics is corporate America now,'' said Kragthorpe,
33, who turned down a chance to be the head coach at North Texas
after the 1997 season. ``It's not like it was 25 years ago, where
the AD was a former coach. Now, the AD is a former executive who
runs the business aspects of the athletic department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having an MBA is something in my favor. With the money head
coaches are making now, it's a high-profile position. It's not just
about coaching football. It's like being a CEO. In becoming a head
coach, you lose the fact you get to coach a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet to earn the right to become a head coach, you must show
enough aptitude for the X's and O's to be perceived as a major
contributor to a school's success. How soon that aptitude is
rewarded with a chance to direct a Division I-A program is anyone's
guess.
</P>
<P>
   At Oklahoma, school administrators have deemed this to be Bob
Stoops' time. Eventually, his won-loss record will prove whether
they were correct.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
