<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 2/6/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ATLANTA -- Feb. 6, 1999 -- SOCSEC-DEBATE, 2-6 -- For
today's aging baby boomers, who face concerns about the solvency of
Social Security and other federal retirement programs, it is now
the government that cannot be trusted and a bullish Wall Street
that provides hope. ``I can't see the federal government being a
player in the stock market,'' says Kevin S. Green, left, 36, a
lawyer.'' Rod D. Jackson, right, 38, a maintenance man says, ``A
lot of people don't have knowledge of how the stock market works
and could lose a lot of money.'' (Alan S. Weiner/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) POUND RIDGE, N.Y. -- Feb. 6, 1999 -- DOGSHOW-PREPARE,
2-6 -- Casey, a golden retriever who is almost 6 years old, with
Lisa Smith his owner and trainer during a treadmill workout. Casey
is among 2,500 entrants competing on Monday and Tuesday at Madison
Square Garden in the 123d annual Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show,
the premier competition in the world of organized dogdom. Many dog
owners employ professional handlers to tackle all the hard work.
Ms. Smith, a perky woman of 33, does it all herself. (Joyce
Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 6, 1999 -- IMPEACH-ROGAN, 2-6 -- Rep.
James E. Rogan, R-Calif., speaking with reporters Wednesday, after
he led the House prosecutors' interrogation of Sidney Blumenthal,
the White House adviser. As one of the 13 House prosecutors trying
to persuade the Senate to remove President Clinton from office,
Rogan, 41, has greater name recognition in his second term than
many of his colleagues do after decades in office. (Justin Lane/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 6, 1999 -- IMPEACH-LEADERS, 2-6 --
Amid the partisan fires of the impeachment and trial of President
Clinton, Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, right, defers a
question at a recent news conference to the minority leader, Tom
Daschle of South Dakota, in an example of their efforts to bring
civility to a potentially explosive situation. Some say the
leaders' example provides a glimmer of hope for upcoming
legislative debates and a glimpse of bipartisan harmony in a
Congress starved for it in recent years. (Justin Lane/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Feb. 6, 1999 -- FAMILY-TREES-3, 2-6 -- A
family tree exercise for a third-grade class at Friends Seminary, a
private school in New York. Many teachers have now realized that
family tree assignments can take a toll on some students,
especially children from nontraditional backgrounds, and have now
made the projects more flexible. In many cases, teachers now assign
family time lines, family orchards and essays that give children
more freedom in telling their personal histories. (Chang W. Lee/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Feb. 6, 1999 -- FAMILY-TREES-2, 2-6 -- Linda
Chu, a private schoolteacher, encourages students to create family
trees, an almost universal elementary-school project that helps
children connect with their ancestors. Several years ago, Ms. Chu
noticed that the task was a drain for children from nontraditional
backgrounds. ``I now let them include whoever is important to them
instead of demanding that they fill out the blanks for a mother and
father who may not be there,'' says Ms. Chu, a teacher at Friends
Seminary. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. -- Feb. 6, 1999 -- FAMILY-TREES-1, 2-6
-- Donna Collymore, a single parent, and her adopted daughter,
Amara, 6, creating a family tree with all their loved ones,
including Ms. Collymore's parents, Amara's birth parents, aunts and
uncles on Ms. Collymore's side and even a best friend. ``In this
school assignment you're not asked to place the leaves in any
particular order or how the person was related to you. It gives us
great flexibility, which is the way it should be,'' says Collymore.
(Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) KANO, Nigeria -- Feb. 6, 1999 -- NIGERIA-ELECTIONS, 2-6
-- Alhaji Abubakar Rimi, center right, a northern candidate for the
presidency of Nigeria, who rejects a supporting a southerner for
the presidency of Africa's most populous nation, in order to heal
divisions. Although powerful Northerners are considering supporting
a southerner, as Nigeria prepares to hold presidential elections on
Feb. 27, no single leader seems capable of healing the political
gash. (Norimitsu Onishi/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) AMSTERDAM, Netherlands -- Feb. 6, 1999 --
AMSTERDAM-CRASH-INQUIRY, 2-6 -- Maria Herts, left, whose sister and
brother-in-law were killed in the crash of an El Al plane in
southern Amsterdam in 1992, and her cousin, Morena Vreetaal, at a
commemorative service in October. More than 1,100 other rescue
workers and residents believe they were somehow contaminated that
night by the burning aircraft and its mysterious cargo, which was
revealed last October to include vats of chemicals that can be used
in the manufacture of the deadly nerve gas Sarin. (Marlise
Simons/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) AMMAN, Jordan -- Feb. 6, 1999 -- KING-HUSSEIN-2, 2-6 --
Jordanian children help keep a vigil outside the hospital where
King Hussein is being treated on Saturday. As many continue to pray
for a miraculous cure, Jordan's government transferred full powers
on Saturday to Crown Prince Abdullah, the 37-year-old heir to the
throne, making him king in all but name. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) AMMAN, Jordan -- Feb. 6, 1999 -- KING-HUSSEIN, 2-6 --
With King Hussein unconscious and near death Saturday, a Jordanian
woman clutches his photograph and cries over her monarch. As many
continue to pray for a miraculous cure, Jordan's government
transferred full powers on Saturday to Crown Prince Abdullah, the
37-year-old heir to the throne, making him king in all but name.
(Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) GRAND LAKE, Colo. -- Feb. 6, 1999 -- SNOWMOBILE-BAN, 2-6
-- Ken Todd of Littleton, Colo., starting a snowmobile for Linda
Abel on the Trail Ridge Road at Rocky Mountain National Park.
Environmental groups are trying to ban the machines in national
parks. In Colorado this recreational conflict has come as
snowmobile riders have expanded their reach with more powerful
machines. ``The extremists would have the parks shut down to
everybody,'' says Todd. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
