<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4669 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DAYTONA-POLE07-CO     02-06 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DAYTONA-POLE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stewart nearly steals Gordon show
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. Tony Stewart, attempting to qualify for his
first Winston Cup start, nearly pulled off the improbable Saturday
in Daytona 500 qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, a former Indy Racing League champion, held the pole for
NASCAR's biggest event with only 14 drivers left to run two
qualifying laps at Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Stewart and his No. 20 Pontiac team, two-time
defending Winston Cup points champion Jeff Gordon was among them.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who will look to join Cale Yarborough as the only driver
to win three points titles in a row when the '99 season opens Feb.
14, added his first pole position at Daytona to his staggering list
of career achievements. On the second of two qualifying laps,
Gordon, who ran third-to-last out of 57 drivers, covered the
2.5-mile tri-oval in 46.138 seconds in his Chevrolet, an average
speed of 195.067 mph. It was the fastest qualifying mark for the
Daytona 500 since Davey Allison posted an average of 195.955 in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really an incredible lap for us to run that late,''
Gordon said. ``It was a little nerve-racking. ... We gave it
everything we had in practice (on Friday). I thought that was
everything we had, but we were able to get a little bit more out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more incredible was Stewart, who would have become the
first driver to win the pole in his Winston Cup debut since Dick
Hutcherson did it in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, the 43rd driver out of the pits, bumped Mike Skinner
and the No. 31 Chevrolet from the pole with an average of 194.599
mph. Rusty Wallace, who qualified second, held the pole for more
than an hour before being unseated by Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shaking when I got out of the car,'' Stewart said. ``I
couldn't believe it. ... It's a good way to start your coming-out
party.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 27, won the '97 IRL title and then spent last year
learning the stock-car ropes with his first full Busch Grand
National schedule. He had five top-10 finishes in 22 Busch starts
in 1998, but few expected him to make an immediate impact on the
Winston Cup scene.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gordon, Stewart's career started driving midget and sprint
cars in Indiana. They've met only once in competition _ a midget
race in Indianapolis in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Stewart will be starting outside Gordon on the front row of
the 41st Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that is ironic is that my rookie season at the ('96)
Indy 500, I almost sat on the pole,'' Stewart said. ``I was on the
pole for about 3 1/2 hours and then (someone) broke it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ended up starting on the front row of my first Indy 500. And
now to start on the front row of my first Daytona 500 ... well, I
guess it will be a good trivia question down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
