<HEADER>
A4670 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-NASCAR-NOTES07-CO     02-06 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-NOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wallace on pole today for shootout
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Rusty Wallace, who held the pole for the
Daytona 500 before being bumped out of the front row by Jeff Gordon
and Winston Cup rookie Tony Stewart, holds the pole for today's Bud
Shootout.
</P>
<P>
   The Shootout, a race of 25 laps with one mandatory pit stop,
features the 14 drivers who won pole positions in Winston Cup races
last season.
</P>
<P>
   John Andretti, who won the pole at the March race in Atlanta,
isn't eligible for the Shootout because his No. 43 Pontiac doesn't
have the required Budweiser decal. That's because car owner Richard
Petty doesn't want his STP team endorsing a brewery.
</P>
<P>
   The Shootout will follow an 11 a.m. qualifying race of 25 laps,
which will feature drivers that had the second-fastest qualifying
times last year.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who finished sixth in Saturday's qualifying at 194.187
mph, won the first Daytona Shootout last year.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Shootout will collect $108,000 of the $512,000
purse.
</P>
<P>
   MILESTONE FOR STEWART
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup rookie Tony Stewart, who had the second-fastest
qualifying time at 194.599 mph Saturday, will be the second rookie
to start his first Daytona 500 on the front row.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Ryan started outside pole winner Ramo Stott in the 1976
race, after three drivers, including A.J. Foyt, were disqualified.
That race ended with David Pearson holding off Petty in a dramatic
finish.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's outside pole is the best start for a rookie in his
first Cup race since Kenny Irwin started second at Richmond on
Sept. 9, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   SCHRADER MOVING UP
</P>
<P>
   Veteran driver Ken Schrader, who finished fourth in last year's
Daytona 500 after starting the race in the No. 31 position, posted
the third-highest qualifying time Saturday at 194.553 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader, in his third year with the No. 33 Chevrolet owned by
Andy Petree, finished last year's 500 after severely injuring his
sternum in a crash in one of the Gatorade 125 qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
   THIS AND THAT
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte, who won the pole last year in the No. 18 Pontiac,
could manage only a 19th-place effort at 193.162 mph. ... Kenny
Irwin, last year's rookie of the year, struggled at 191.469 mph.
... Rookie Buckshot Jones of Tucker was at 189.641, while Bill
Elliott of Dawsonville was at 190.977 mph.
</P>
<P>
   SPEEDWEEKS SCHEDULE
</P>
<P>
   _ Today: Bud Shootout, noon.
</P>
<P>
   _ Monday: Daytona 500 second-round qualifying, 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tuesday: Daytona 500 third-round qualifying, 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wednesday: Winston Cup and Busch Grand National practice.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thursday: Gatorade 125-mile qualifying races for Daytona 500,
12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Friday: Discount Auto Parts 200 Goody's Dash Series, 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Saturday: NAPA Auto Parts 300 Busch race, noon.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sunday, Feb. 14: Daytona 500, 12:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
