   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 6, 1999 -- IMPEACH-ROGAN, 2-6 -- Rep.
James E. Rogan, R-Calif., speaking with reporters Wednesday, after
he led the House prosecutors' interrogation of Sidney Blumenthal,
the White House adviser. As one of the 13 House prosecutors trying
to persuade the Senate to remove President Clinton from office,
Rogan, 41, has greater name recognition in his second term than
many of his colleagues do after decades in office. (Justin Lane/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 6, 1999 -- IMPEACH-LEADERS, 2-6 --
Amid the partisan fires of the impeachment and trial of President
Clinton, Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, right, defers a
question at a recent news conference to the minority leader, Tom
Daschle of South Dakota, in an example of their efforts to bring
civility to a potentially explosive situation. Some say the
leaders' example provides a glimmer of hope for upcoming
legislative debates and a glimpse of bipartisan harmony in a
Congress starved for it in recent years. (Justin Lane/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
