<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. BEATS GERMANY, 3-0  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Bruce Arena closed the door to the U.S.
team's locker room, the sweetness of Saturday's upset of Germany
still new, and shouted, ``Today the best team won!''
</P>
<P>
   Arena, appointed head coach of the U.S. men's national team in
October, is trying to instill confidence in his revamped team, and
he wanted his players to understand that Saturday's dominating 3-0
victory before 17,259 at Alltel Stadium was no fluke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's result will be a surprise around the world,'' Arena
said later. ``It's not surprising in our locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the U.S. men's team's first victory over Germany in
four tries. It was also a rematch of last year's World Cup opener,
which Germany won, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't seem to matter that just two players on each side who
started the World Cup game also started Saturday. Or that German
Coach Erich Ribbeck complained that his team had practiced for only
five days.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was thorough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a clear 3-0 victory,'' said midfielder Claudio Reyna,
the U.S. captain. ``It wasn't three lucky goals. It was three
well-deserved goals. And we honestly could have had more. We let
them know in the first minute that we were here to play and that we
weren't going to give them the respect we did in the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our attitude,'' forward Cobi Jones added, ``was `Take no
prisoners.'''
</P>
<P>
   That pressure led to the three goals in a 10-minute span of the
first half. It left Germany facing a 3-0 halftime deficit for the
first time since 1993 when it played mighty Brazil in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously, all three scorers are playing for German-based
teams.
</P>
<P>
   The United States began its scoring binge in the 16th minute,
when Jovan Kirovski dribbled past defender Markus Babbel, planted
and hit a perfectly aimed 22-yarder into the net's right corner. It
sailed just past goalie Oliver Kahn, who made a diving attempt.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to loosen up the hosts, who were not only playing
before a national U.S. television audience but upwards of 20
million on German television.
</P>
<P>
   In the 24th minute, midfielder Tony Sanneh electrified the
partisan crowd with a breakaway. He outmaneuvered German midfielder
Jens Jeremies for the loose ball and zeroed in on Kahn. The goalie
burst toward him to limit his angle, but Sanneh slipped a shot by
him on the left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got there a little late and I just tried to go hard on the
tackle,'' Sanneh said of his collision with Jeremies. ``He didn't
go in so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Now feeding off their success, the Americans added a third goal
just two minutes later. This one came on a wide-open six-footer by
Reyna, after a nifty combination of passing from Chris Armas to
Eddie Lewis to Reyna.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth goal was in the offing, but Kirovski's angle shot in
the 45th minute missed just to the left.
</P>
<P>
   Amid increased talk that the tradition-rich Germans are doomed
to world soccer mediocrity, they seemed to fit that role perfectly
Saturday. Far too often, they left gaping holes in which the United
States could maneuver. And their offense was virtually nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. goalie Tony Meola, the former MetroStar, had to stop only
eight shots, just one of which appeared threatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't much to do,'' he said. ``It was more organizing
things than making plays. But that's because our defense didn't
allow them to do much.''
</P>
<P>
   Arena found that the Germans' last nine goals had come from
accurate crossing passes, so he challenged two of his midfielders _
Sanneh and Lewis _ to shut down that aspect of Germany's offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very rare that U.S. players own the flanks in games of
this type,'' Arena said, ``especially against the likes of the
German team.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost 200 German journalists were here for the game. One asked
Arena how the Germans, considering their standing in world soccer,
could play so badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't say they played so badly,'' the coach said, a bit of
irritation in his voice. ``It's one of those days where everything
went right for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1911EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4689 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOGSHW-PREPARE-ART-2T     02-06 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOGSHW-PREPARE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGIMEN IS RELENTLESS FOR A TEAM PURSUING THE PINNACLE OF DOGDOM
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (HLW)  
 By N.R. KLEINFIELD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUND RIDGE, N.Y. _ Casey was pretty relaxed. To be honest, he
was fast asleep under the kitchen table. This with mere days to go.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Smith was not relaxed. Questions raced through her head.
Were Casey's whiskers flat enough? What about his toenails? And how
were those teeth? He was known for his great teeth.
</P>
<P>
   She would get to those things. For now, she had to put Casey on
the treadmill.
</P>
<P>
   ``C'mon, Casey,'' she said. ``Let's do our workout. C'mon,
boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey, who is almost 6 years old and a dog, is among 2,500
entrants competing on Monday and Tuesday at Madison Square Garden
in the 123rd annual Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show, the premier
competition in the world of organized dogdom. Casey's event is on
Tuesday, when he will have about two minutes to convince the judge
that he is the most exquisite golden retriever on earth, or at
least the finest specimen among the 47 in the show.
</P>
<P>
   How well Casey _ formally known as Ch. Goodtime's Best Case
Scenario _ does in that fleeting moment heavily depends on what he
was born with, but it also takes punctilious grooming and
exercising. How effectively his owner, Ms. Smith, trots him around
the ring matters a lot, too. Understandably, many dog owners employ
professional handlers to tackle all the hard work. Ms. Smith, 33,
does it all herself.
</P>
<P>
   She lives in Pound Ridge in a white brick house with a golden
retriever mailbox, massive amounts of dog hair on the welcome mat
and a painting of Casey over the hearth. Her husband, Daniel
Selmonosky, is an investment banker who is a lot less interested
than she is in dog shows. He has a habit of alluding to them as
``the bottomless black hole.'' Besides Casey, they own six other
golden retrievers, three cats, tropical fish and a horse. ``I'm
threatening a parrot,'' Ms. Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   She put Casey on his ``Jog a Dog'' machine and twirled the dial
to top speed. As he chugged away, she egged him on. ``C'mon, Case,
that's it,'' she said. ``Go, Case.''
</P>
<P>
   Well into the 15-minute routine, Casey began to flag. Ms. Smith
delivered the ultimate expression of support. She sang the theme
song from ``Rocky.'' Casey picked up the pace.
</P>
<P>
   Finished exercising, Casey jumped onto the grooming table and
Ms. Smith worked on his coat. ``I'm removing hair where there is
too much,'' she said. ``Making it smoother. The hair is an ongoing
thing. I have to do more and more as we get near the show.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of constant shows, Casey is in semiretirement and
competes only in major events. His last show was in August. Being
off the circuit, Ms. Smith said, had turned him into a ``flab
muffin.'' In early December, she put him back on a regular exercise
regimen to ready him for Westminster.
</P>
<P>
   Two or three times a week, Ms. Smith tosses a ball with him for
a half-hour. Three times, she takes him for a three-mile walk,
though the walks have shortened as Ms. Smith has grown bigger. She
is seven months pregnant. And he goes on the treadmill five or six
times a week.
</P>
<P>
   He is bathed pretty much weekly, and then blow-dried with a
giant dog blow dryer that emits cool air at great force. Hot air
would burn his coat and skin. It takes two hours to dry him. ``I
hate blowing him dry,'' Ms. Smith said. For Casey, it's just one
more thing in a show dog's life.
</P>
<P>
   He eats twice a day, getting Eukanuba medium breed for puppies,
Eukanuba lamb and rice for adults, Nutro natural choice performance
food, Bill Jac ``fresh frozen'' food and Dog Bloom, a vitamin
supplement. Casey also gets table scraps, though he can't stand
onions.
</P>
<P>
   The dogs entered in this year's Westminster represent all 153
recognized breeds and varieties (Rhodesian Ridgebacks, schipperkes,
Portuguese water dogs, etc.) except, for no apparent reason, the
Finnish spitz. The entrants will be reduced by the judges to the
152 best in breed, which are then split into seven groups (i.e.,
the hound group, the sporting group, the working group). The seven
dogs anointed best in group then confront one another in the final
showdown for the best in show award. There's no prize money, just
ribbons, trophies and glory.
</P>
<P>
   The dogs are judged on conformation _ their looks and structure.
Attitude counts. Brains are fairly unimportant. There are no tricks
to perform as in obedience trials. (Casey, though, has a good head
on his shoulders; he has excelled at obedience, too.) The dogs must
behave, however. A dog that mauls a judge never does well. Casey is
extremely well behaved, though at one show, as the judge bent over
him to take a closer look, Casey burped in his face. Another time,
he relieved himself on a plant in the ring and still won, causing
Ms. Smith momentarily to rethink her ring strategy.
</P>
<P>
   For all the buildup of Westminster, it is over in a blink. Each
dog gets an ``individual,'' a once-over that lasts roughly two
minutes. The judge feels the dog and casts an appraising eye over
it, then tells the owner a pattern (triangle, down and back) in
which to ``gait it'' around the ring. ``It's a lot of work for two
minutes,'' Ms. Smith admitted.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   What constitutes dog perfection varies by breed. For golden
retrievers, the judge considers the straightness and firmness of
the back, and the quality of the muscle tone. The tail should come
to the hock of the leg. The ears should not be set too low, or else
water will get in when it swims.
</P>
<P>
   The golden retriever is a dog that is supposed to go out and
hunt all day, even if most of its hunting is done at a dog food
bowl. Hence the muzzle is supposed to be deep and wide enough to
carry a duck. (Casey more often carries a ball.) It should have
tight feet for efficient swimming and to insure that thorns don't
get between the toes when it is chasing fowl.
</P>
<P>
   Casey rates highly in all these categories, and he is excellent
at ``free stacking,'' which is standing in place without any
adjustments to his position by a handler. ``He has a lot of
attitude and he's very square,'' Ms. Smith said proudly.
</P>
<P>
   Even though her mother breeds dogs and did the dog show circuit
throughout her youth, Ms. Smith did not plan to enter the dog world
herself. She was born in Atlanta, where her father had a drum
reconditioning business. She moved north about 10 years ago. ``My
husband was working 100 million hours a week,'' she said. ``I
didn't know anyone. My mom sent me a dog.'' Before long, she began
showing the dog. Her mom sent her more dogs. It became a life
style.
</P>
<P>
   She started doing local shows in 1991, and in 1996 and 1997 she
campaigned Casey around the country. She worked as an accountant
and then as a counselor for at-risk children, but she quit to spend
more time with her dogs. Doing the circuit costs about $60,000 a
year, mostly for travel expenses and advertising. It is pretty much
obligatory that owners place advertisements in dog publications
like Dog News and The Canine Chronicle thanking the judge after a
dog does well at a show. These also help acquaint other judges with
a dog so they will be thinking highly of it in future competitions.
``It's promoting your product,'' Ms. Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Merely to enter Westminster, a dog must be an American Kennel
Club champion, meaning the animal has amassed 15 points at shows.
Casey attained that stature when he was 2. He has won one best in
show in Riverhead, N.Y., more than a dozen bests in group and
innumerable bests in breed. In 1996, he ranked No. 6 in the nation
among golden retrievers.
</P>
<P>
   This will be Casey's fourth go at Westminster. Twice he received
an Award of Merit, an honor bestowed on the top 10 percent of a
breed class, and Ms. Smith feels he narrowly missed winning best in
breed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, Ms. Smith took Casey to a handler's class in
White Plains for a final tuneup. The teacher, Joyce Diamond, called
out instructions: ``OK, let's move them in a triangle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, show me the bite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, take him straight down and back.''
</P>
<P>
   As she led Casey around the ring, Ms. Smith moved at a swift yet
refined trot, as if she and Casey were desperately late for an
appointment but still wanted to look good.
</P>
<P>
   The handlers held ``bait'' in their hand to get the dogs to do
the right thing. Ms. Smith employed Pup-Peroni, a jerky snack. For
the Garden, she will ``up the ante'' and go with liver. Anything is
permissible, short of live birds. A few handlers have been known to
use pheasant wings.
</P>
<P>
   At the Garden, nothing should be left to chance. The rings are
usually slippery. Ms. Smith plans to take a spritzer filled with
Coke and spray the pads of Casey's feet. The sugar affords him
traction. Some of the other owners favor 7-Up or Pepsi, but Ms.
Smith really likes Coke.
</P>
<P>
   She pays close attention to what she wears. Early on in her
showing days, she wore a red outfit and Casey got second in his
group, a red ribbon. She never wore red again. Instead she favors
blue, the color of a first-place ribbon, and purple, the color of
best in breed ribbons. And she likes black because Casey has won a
lot on her black days. She's going with black on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Casey gets nervous if Ms. Smith gets nervous, and the
Westminster show makes her nervous. So she will bring along mints
to suck on. ``It masks the adrenaline in your breath,'' she said.
``If Casey smells adrenaline, he gets worried about me. I don't
want him worried.''
</P>
<P>
   For Monday, the last chance to prepare, Ms. Smith has the day
all mapped out. ``I'll give Casey a bath and do the final
grooming,'' she said. ``I'll chop off his whiskers so he's flat.
I'll cut his toenails to get them as short as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey likes to turn in around 11 p.m., first hopping onto Ms.
Smith's bed and then settling onto the bathroom floor. But he needs
a good night's sleep. Ms. Smith will sequester him in the den at 8
p.m. and have him sleep on the couch there. On Tuesday morning,
there will be no breakfast. It's no good to trot around a ring on a
full stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's just hope for the best. Shaq from California would
have to be the favorite among the golden retrievers, since he ranks
first in the country, but sports are full of upsets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Casey won, I wouldn't go back,'' Ms. Smith said, gazing
lovingly at him. ``He would be done. I would be so happy I would be
beside myself. Casey would get a big steak for dinner. And I would
hope I don't fall on TV.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
