u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-KING-BOS &LR;      02-06 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-KING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING'S SON TAKES POWER AS HUSSEIN LIES DYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ King Hussein's oldest son, Crown Prince
Abdullah, left the hospital where his father lay dying Saturday to
take an official oath giving him rule over Jordan's Hashemite
kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   The short ceremony was the first official recognition that the
63-year-old, cancer-stricken monarch has, as longtime personal
physician Dr. Daoud Hanania put it, ``no hope of recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanania, who has been a close friend of the king for nearly a
half century, visited Hussein Saturday and said that the king was
kept breathing by a respirator. He said the massive kidney and
liver failure meant that the king's death was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   As Jordanians and the Hashemite clan that rules them prepared
for the loss of a beloved leader, Abdullah, 37, _ who until two
weeks ago was a commander of an elite military unit who never
expected to be king _ raised his right hand and read from the
Jordanian constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear by almighty God to preserve the constitution and serve
the nation,'' he said during a small ceremony in the prime
minister's office with a life-size oil painting of his father
looming behind him.
</P>
<P>
   The oath technically makes Abdullah the regent of the royal
palace, or acting ruler. The swearing-in is usually a routine
procedure for the crown prince when the king leaves the country.
But it is the first time in 46 years of rule that Hussein has not
held the throne while he was in his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   And it is the latest step in the official succession of
Abdullah. For 34 years it was the king's brother, Prince Hassan,
who was made regent in the king's absence. That was until last
month, when Hassan was sacked by Hussein in a tumultuous week of
palace intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah, the king's oldest son, takes the reins of power in
this important Middle East nation as an inexperienced and untested
leader. But many palace observers say that Abdullah has inherited
the important qualities of his father. He is polite, caring,
straightforward, and unassuming _ traits that over decades
engendered trust in the king among heads of state from the Arab
world to Israel and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   There were some early signs of a lack of confidence in the young
king-to-be as Jordanians flocked to banks and currency exchange
shops to sell the local currency, the dinar, for US dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no need to worry. This is a country of solid
institutions and of continuity,'' Information Minister Nasser Judeh
said at a packed press conference.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton responded by bolstering the strategic US ally
in the Middle East. Clinton said he would ask Congress this week
for an additional $300 million in economic aid.
</P>
<P>
   While financiers might have had reservations about the future,
Jordanians from all over the country showed emotional support for
the king and his family.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 people from throughout Jordan flocked to the
entrance to the Al Hussein Medical Center. In the afternoon, Queen
Noor, accompanied by her son Hamzah, 18, passed through the crowd.
Her head covered in a white veil, she looked tired and shaken. But
she shook hands, smiled, and thanked people for their warm support
and concern.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd waved Jordanian flags and posters of the king, and
loudly chanted, ``God Save the King!''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout a cold, rainy day and into the night, the crowd
remained in a quiet vigil. Some held candles that flickered in a
raw wind blowing in from the desert. Men lined up for Muslim
prayers, holding their hands up to the heavens and praying from the
Koran. A group of Christian women gathered in a semicircle,
clutching beads and chanting the Rosary in Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the hospital, the king lay unconscious in a royal suite
that was specially designed for the family.
</P>
<P>
   Hanania, who is the former director of the hospital, was one of
the people outside of the family allowed to visit the king
Saturday. Hanania is a heart specialist and not on the team that is
treating the king. But as a personal physician to the king for 17
years, he provided insight into his grave condition.
</P>
<P>
   He said reports that the family was struggling to decide whether
to disconnect the respirator were false. He said the king still had
brain function, which could be determined because his pupils were
dilating and he still had some reflexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the absence of brain death, no one would think of switching
off the respirator. The philosophy is: Let nature take its
course,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors were not using dialysis machines to help his failed
kidneys to function because his lymcancer was too advanced, he
added. When asked whether the respirator could allow the king to
linger for weeks or months, he said, ``In theory, it could go on
for a long time. But if that is coupled with his general condition
. . . then the span, I would think from my experience, is days.''
</P>
<P>
   The king was kept heavily sedated. He lay dressed in a hospital
gown with the tubes of a respirator inserted in his throat and
pumping life into his lungs. He has regained consciousness only
intermittently since he was rushed home from Minnesota's Mayo
Clinic on Thursday after futile cancer treatments. The family said
that when he dies, they would prefer a burial within 24 hours, in
keeping with Islamic custom.
</P>
<P>
   The suite has an emergency care room where the king lay as well
as an operating theater and bedrooms. Queen Noor and Hamzah were
staying there to be with Hussein through the night. The decor is
simple with modern paintings adorning beige-colored walls. In dim,
soothing light, family members gathered in sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kissed his forehead,'' said Hanania, ``and said goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanania, who first met the king when they were teenagers
studying in London, said that it was fitting that the king was
spending his final days in the hospital where he showed so much of
his legendary kindness and generosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would call about a poor patient who needed surgery, an
ordinary shepherd or soldier, and he would check on him daily,''
recalled the former hospital director. ``He is sincere _ he doesn't
do it to be popularized. And therein lies his grip on this country.
It is his love of his people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
