<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-TEXAS-SOUTHERN-CAL-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Reflecting on a 9-8 loss to Texas yesterday,
Southern California coach Mike Gillespie offered a succinct
analysis of his team's weekend thus far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, frankly, that we are all embarrassed by our defense
and our bases on balls,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For a while it seemed as if the defending national champions had
traded in the wooden bats they used on Friday for wooden gloves in
this one.
</P>
<P>
   Canceling a 14-hit attack of their own, the Trojans (1-2)
committed five errors to hand Texas (4-0) seven unearned runs, then
fell short with a late rally before a crowd of 4,978 at Disch-Falk
Field. The final in the three-game series is scheduled for 1 p.m.
today.
</P>
<P>
   The teams used aluminum bats, but nothing could rescue the
Trojans from themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Texas took a 2-0 lead in the second inning on Mike Pumo's single
after USC starter Barry Zito _ who was a third-round pick of the
Rangers last year _ loaded the bases with a hit and two walks.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans had a solo home run in the fourth, but missed a
chance to tie the game when third baseman Beau Craig was called out
for tagging too early on a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Cal unraveled in the bottom half when left fielder
Dominic Correa dropped two fly balls, and Texas shortstop Jason
Moore capped a four-run inning with a blast over the 375-foot sign
in left center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was the third most-surprised person in the stadium
when that happened,'' said Texas coach Augie Garrido, celebrating
his 60th birthday, ``after the kid that dropped the fly balls and
Coach Gillespie. But I was happy.''
</P>
<P>
   In defense of Correa, who had three hits, including a two-run
homer, Gillespie said, ``Those may have been the first two fly
balls he's ever seen in his life. He's an infielder, but we're so
banged up we had to use him out there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Zito departed after misplaying a short tapper and
a sacrifice bunt and walking in a run. The Longhorns got another in
the seventh on two errors by shortstop Seth Davidson, playing with
a protective mask over a healing broken jaw.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans rallied for seven runs in the final three innings _
including three in the ninth _ but closer Phil Seibel struck out
second baseman Justin Gemoll with two men on to save it for the
Longhorns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
