<HEADLINE>
EAST TIMOR FEARS TROJAN HORSE IN INDONESIA INDEPENDENCE OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Twenty-three years after Indonesia invaded East
Timor and began a bloody rule, the former Portuguese colony has
never been closer to gaining independence.
</P>
<P>
   But Timorese leaders who have risked their lives for a chance at
self-rule _ the topic of UN-sponsored talks beginning here Sunday _
say they do not want independence: at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been so focused on raising public awareness about our
cause that we didn't seriously think about the structure of a
government,'' said Constancio Pinto, an advocate of independence
who began his struggle as a 14-year-old guerrilla in the Timorese
jungles. ``This is what we have been fighting for, but what happens
after independence?''
</P>
<P>
   What happens, he fears, is a replay of transitions to
independence by Portugal's former colonies from Guinea to Angola:
chaos followed by decades of civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Pinto, now 36 and a graduate student at Columbia University,
agrees with other Timorese independence advocates who say they need
a three- to five-year transition to ease the birth pangs of
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Their hesitation to embrace Indonesia's offer _ some see it as a
threat _ of independence underscores the key dilemma for the
Timorese. With no experience governing or maintaining order, the
Timorese still must rely on Indonesia to guarantee a smooth
transition to self-rule.
</P>
<P>
   But Indonesia is willing to lend a hand only if the Timorese
agree to surrender considerable control over police, defense and
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no obligation to prepare the people of East Timor to
walk towards their independence,'' Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas said Friday. ``We are not colonialists.''
</P>
<P>
   Portuguese and Indonesian diplomats have reached agreement over
a blueprint for an autonomous Timorese government, according to
Pakistani diplomat Jamsheed Marker, the UN mediator overseeing the
talks. But the two sides remain at an impasse over whether the
arrangement would will lead to independence.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers of Portugal and Indonesia will try to
agree on a plan to disarm thousands of civilian militia members
responsible for carrying out a crackdown on Timorese residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have now arrived at an understanding as far as we can go,''
said Marker, adding that negotiations were expected to intensify
over the next several weeks. ``The curtain has come down on the
first phase our negotiation and is about to go up on Act II.''
</P>
<P>
   East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, has lived under harsh
Indonesian military rule since the Portuguese left in 1975 and the
Indonesian troops invaded. It was annexed by Jakarta a year later,
an act that has not been recognized by the United Nations. More
than 200,000 Timorese have died under Indonesian rule, human rights
advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of Independence for East Timor has always been a
sensitive issue in Indonesia, whose national motto is ``Unity in
Diversity.'' The leaders of this fragmented nation composed of
13,000 islands, 300 ethnic groups and more than 350 languages, have
long feared that Timorese independence would energize separatists
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is East Timor the thread that unravels the ball of Indonesian
national integrity? Can East Timor be an economically viable
state?,'' asked Adam Schwartz, a lecturer at Georgetown and Johns
Hopkins universities. ``We don't have a good answer to either
question. But East Timor has been poor under the Portuguese, poor
under Indonesia, and it will probably be poor under the East
Timorese.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest violence was prompted by the surprise Indonesian
decision on Jan. 28 to grant immediate independence _ and it has
cast a pall over the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-government militias armed by the military have clashed with
Timorese civilians, leaving more than 30 dead, driving more than
6,000 people into hiding and raising the specter of another
bloodbath.
</P>
<P>
   One militia leader, Kansio Lopez, acknowledged last week that
his forces had used weapons on loan from the army to kill 10 rebel
sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesia military, with 10,000 troops in East Timor, insist
that the militias were being armed to protect themselves from
pro-independence rebels if Jakarta pulls out of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Pinto and other Timorese independence advocates, who have been
meeting with UN officials on the sidelines of the New York talks,
accuse Indonesia of intentionally fomenting turmoil to frighten the
Timorese into abandoning their drive for full independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indonesia is trying to create another civil war,'' Pinto said.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Ramos Horta, Timorese opposition leader who won the Nobel
Peace prize with Timorese Bishop Carlos Belo in 1996 for their
autonomy efforts, appealed to the Timorese for calm. He said he has
had discussions with the United Nations over a proposal to send UN
observers and truce forces to East Timor to disarm the militias and
to ensure a safe democratic transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The East Timor people need not panic,'' he said. ``We can
invite the United Nations to take responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's approval would be required before the UN
peacekeeping operation could be created. While Jakarta's has yet to
approve it, US officials pressed the government to consider a UN
presence in East Timor to check the worsening violence.
</P>
<P>
   It would ``break the cycle of violence and restore confidence,''
said a US assistant secretary of state, Stanley Roth, who met with
Indonesian officials last week.
</P>
<P>
   Roth also expressed optimism that the impasse can be cleared.
``I have been working on East Timorese issues for 19 years,'' he
said. ``This is the first time in that 19-year period that I am
optimistic that there is a basis for a political settlement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
