<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4709 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      02-06 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VIEWS LEWINSKY TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica S. Lewinsky emerged on videotape Saturday at
the center of President Clinton's impeachment trial, as House
managers played her recorded testimony for the Senate and millions
of television viewers in an effort to bolster their case.
</P>
<P>
   The session thrust the House managers and Clinton's lawyers into
harsh conflict over Lewinsky's account of circumstances stemming
from the source of the impeachment saga: her sexual affair in the
White House with the 42d president.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing Clinton of engaging in ``a broad tapestry of
corruption,'' Representative James F. Rogan, a House manager from
California, argued that Lewinsky's testimony had underscored ``why
a just and proper verdict in this body would be to replace him as
president with Vice President Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour presentation by the House managers, and a 2
1/2-hour rebuttal by Clinton's lawyers, constituted the entire
witness phase of the impeachment trial, and represented the last
act of the proceedings before both sides deliver closing arguments
Monday. Deliberations will follow, leading to vote on Thursday or
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyer, Nicole Seligman, argued that Lewinsky's
testimony had ``undermined'' Rogan's assertion, and had proved that
``the opposite is true.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have distorted, they have omitted, and they have created
a profoundly erroneous impression,'' Seligman said of the
presentation, which also featured video clips of testimony by
Clinton, his friend Vernon E. Jordan Jr., and White House adviser
Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   With the Senate considered certain to acquit Clinton of the
impeachment charges, Saturday's debate had the air of an empty
exercise. Still, the videotaped presentations gave the House
managers and White House lawyers one of their last chances to sway
public opinion and a small number of wavering senators.
</P>
<P>
   For Lewinsky, the session marked the first time she has been
seen publicly telling her version of the yearlong scandal. Wearing
a conservative black outfit and a pearl necklace, Lewinsky spoke
confidently but carefully in the video excerpts about her knowledge
of Clinton's alleged perjury and obstruction of justice in trying
to cover up their affair.
</P>
<P>
   Her testimony inspired widely varying reviews from the senators
who will decide Clinton's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American public has seen Monica Lewinsky for the first
time as Monica Lewinsky, not as the White House would want you to
see her,'' said Senator Larry E. Craig of Idaho, chairman of the
Senate Republican Policy Committee. ``It certainly has been
devastating to the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts said the session
provided scant new information and was ``a total waste of the
Senate's time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This may play very well on television to have Monica Lewinsky,
but the people back home will be able to watch Monica Lewinsky on
Barbara Walters if they want to,'' Kennedy said. ``This is just a
blatant and flagrant partisan effort to demean the president,
embarrass the president, humiliate the president, and poison the
political atmosphere, and it's basically inexcusable.''
</P>
<P>
   In styles as different as their positions, the House managers
patched together a pastiche of short video clips to hammer home
their points, before Clinton's lawyers countered with relatively
lengthy excerpts of Lewinsky and Jordan rebutting the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The images filled four large video monitors in the Senate
chamber and television screens around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers launched their presentation by juxtaposing
the image of Lewinsky taking an oath last week to testify
truthfully in her deposition with and a clip from Clinton wagging
his finger last year and denying he had engaged in ``sexual
relations with that woman, Ms. Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene set the foundation for the House managers to unfurl a
flurry of video snippets to support their charges that Clinton had
manipulated Lewinsky, Jordan, Blumenthal and others in his alleged
coverup. The clips presented no surprises, because complete written
transcripts were released Friday of the Lewinsky, Jordan and
Blumenthal depositions.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan said the video presentation illustrated that Clinton had
failed to learn that one ``bad choice,'' his adulterous affair with
Lewinsky, might lead to more bad choices if he ignored the
potential consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``That simple primer on life encapsulates the political and
personal legacy of Bill Clinton,'' Rogan said. ``His is a
continuing pattern of indulging all choices and accepting no
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats accused the managers of lashing out in
frustration as the House case against Clinton fades into history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we suffered the excessive zeal of managers who don't
understand that we're very familiar with the facts, and that this
is not going to change any votes,'' said Senator John F. Kerry.
``What we did was participate in a Republican effort to impact
public opinion, and it's inappropriate for the Senate to be used
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers, Seligman and David E. Kendall, each played
video clips that showed Lewinsky rebutting every major allegation
against Clinton, including charges that he had encouraged her to
file a false affidavit and conceal evidence to thwart a sexual
harassment lawsuit that Paula Corbin Jones filed against him and
settled for $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The testimony of Ms. Lewinsky has seriously damaged the
managers' case and confirmed that it is time for this tireless
pursuit of the president to come to an end,'' Seligman said.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment charges narrowly passed the House in December,
largely along party lines. But the House managers have continually
lost ground in the Senate, and several GOP senators said privately
that as many as 15 Republicans may join all 45 Democrats in voting
against the perjury charge.
</P>
<P>
   The obstruction allegation is considered the stronger of the two
counts, but even that charge may not receive 50 votes, far fewer
than the 67 required to remove a president.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise move, Senator Robert C. Byrd, a West Virginia
Democrat, said in an interview to be broadcast Sunday that he
believes Clinton's actions constitute high crimes and misdemeanors,
although he did not say how he will vote. Byrd last week had filed
a motion to dismiss the case against Clinton, but it was defeated.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during Saturday's presentation, Representative
Lindsey O. Graham of South Carolina suggested that Clinton's
wrongdoing had included a phone call to Lewinsky at 2:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I come from, if you call somebody at 2:30 in the
morning, you're up to no good,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   Senators burst into laughter, but Graham maintained a straight
face as he gazed at his notes.
</P>
<P>
   With polls showing the public is eager for the trial to end,
Senate leaders have tried to hasten the process. Chief Justice
William H. Rehnquist joined them Saturday, as he rebuffed the
Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, when Lott suggested taking a
break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's keep going,'' Rehnquist said, interrupting Lott and
drawing applause.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the Senate chamber, senators continued to haggle over a
way to sanction Clinton without removing him from office. Democrats
united behind a draft censure resolution that would cite Clinton
for ``shameless, reckless and indefensible behavior'' that could
create ``disrespect for the laws of the land.''
</P>
<P>
   But only three Republicans had expressed support for the plan:
Senators John H. Chafee of Rhode Island, James M. Jeffords of
Vermont, and Robert F. Bennett of Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Other senators were waging a struggle to open the final
deliberations to the public. It would take 67 votes to change the
rules that require the closed-door deliberations, and senators in
both parties said the outcome is too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   Each senator will have up to 15 minutes to speak during the
deliberations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
