<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS PREPARE FOR BULLS RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Video reviewer and first-year Clipper coach Chris
Ford has seen the tape and had praise for the production values.
</P>
<P>
   But he'd prefer to change the ending.
</P>
<P>
   When the tape of Friday's opener with Phoenix had ended, the
Suns rode off into the moonlight with a 101-92 victory. According
to Ford's review, there were too many chase scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get better conditioning,'' said Ford, who watched
as his frontcourt was left in the dust by the fast-breaking Suns'
frontcourt. ``We need our bigs to be able to run the floor. You're
not covering your man if you're shoulder to shoulder. We've got to
be out ahead of him.''
</P>
<P>
   To correct this problem, the Clippers rehearsed sprinting up and
down the court during Saturday's practice at Veterans Park
SportsComplex in Carson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to have any more jogging up and down the
court,'' Ford promised.
</P>
<P>
   OLD GUARDS RETURN
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's game with Chicago provides a Sports Arena return for
ex-Clipper guards Ron Harper and Brent Barry. Harper left the team
after the 1993 season to succeed the retiring Michael Jordan as the
shooting guard in Chicago. Barry, who was traded to Miami last
season, recently signed with the Bulls to do the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   They scored 18 and 13 points, respectively, in Friday's
season-opening loss at Utah.
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL AND THE BULLS
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who was pleased with the first-game performance of Michael
Olowokandi, said the rookie center could get more minutes against
the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on how it goes,'' Ford said, ``but he may get more
time. I think he was very patient Friday in making his moves.''
</P>
<P>
   In 22 minutes against Phoenix, Olowokandi scored 14 points,
grabbed six rebounds and blocked a shot.
</P>
<P>
   SHERMAN'S TANK LOW
</P>
<P>
   Newly acquired point guard Sherman Douglas looked a cheeseburger
or two beyond fighting trim in Friday's opener, which arrived one
day after the nine-year veteran did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, he's not there yet,'' Ford said of Douglas'
conditioning, ``and he knows it. He'll get there soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas had two assists and no points in four minutes against
the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   While he works into game shape, Darrick Martin will continue to
run the team. Martin had 11 points and six assists in his matchup
with the Suns' Jason Kidd, but most of that damage was done in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Darrick did a great job,'' Ford said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
