<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4711 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LEWINSKY-BOS &LR;      02-06 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEWINSKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATION SEES POLITE, POISED STAR WITNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vixen or victim? When the nation saw and heard
Monica S. Lewinsky for the first time Saturday, it wasn't so clear
that the world's most famous White House intern is either.
</P>
<P>
   The polite, poised, and pearled woman on the videotape played at
the Senate impeachment trial of President Clinton didn't resemble
either the desperate, lovesick child dumped by the man she derided
as ``The Big Creep,'' or the giddy presidential stalker who craved
phone sex with a guy she nicknamed ``Handsome.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from an occasional shy grin, wistful look, or chin-jutting
pout, Lewinsky was the perfectly composed and coached witness who
appears well on her way to recovering from one awful year and
looking for rehabilitation from all the terrible things that have
been said about her.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't, of course, the woman House managers trying the case
against Clinton really wanted in the spotlight. An innocent young
victim, manipulated and destroyed by a deceiving president, was the
Monica they had hoped to portray.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica Lewinsky is an intelligent, articulate young woman who,
until recently, held untarnished hopes for tomorrow, like any other
recent college graduate,'' Representative James Rogan, a California
Republican, told senators Saturday as he introduced excerpts of the
videotape. ``That hope was drastically altered when she was
subpoenaed in a lawsuit against the president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogan repeatedly called Lewinsky ``Monica,'' while referring to
the other videotaped witnesses, Clinton's friend Vernon E. Jordan
Jr. and White House aide Sidney Blumenthal, as ``Mr. Jordan'' and
``Mr. Blumenthal.''
</P>
<P>
   The subtle message, delivered to a Senate where the average age
is over 50, was not of disrespect for 25-year-old Lewinsky, but to
highlight her youth.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she didn't look that young. For her videotaped
deposition, taken in the presidential suite of the Renaissance
Mayflower Hotel last Monday, Lewinsky chose a black V-necked dress
with a strand of pearls. No baseball cap, no beret with a shiny
hatpin, and certainly no Gap logos or labels.
</P>
<P>
   Her appearance, too, was more come-of-age than teenage: Dark
liner circled her wide brown eyes, and a helmet of shiny black hair
framed her face. Her smile, though infrequent, was warm and
engaging, and her gestures _ including scratching her nose _ seemed
natural.
</P>
<P>
   In manner, however, Lewinsky was all business. This is, first of
all, a woman who has recounted her affair with the president 23
times and knows her subject. She also is represented by two of
Washington's most respected defense lawyers, Jacob Stein and Plato
Cacheris, and it was clear from Lewinsky's occasional glance their
way that they were coaching her from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   But the most striking contrast was between the serious,
confident witness and the delusional, emotional Valley Girl who
described herself as ``sooooooo naughty'' on the telephone tapes of
former friend Linda R. Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   In the portions of the videotape played Saturday on television
and on four large monitors in the Senate, Lewinsky's choice of
words was careful, her responses clipped. ``Correct,'' she answered
over and over again. And her behavior was unfailingly polite,
addressing as ``sir'' the House manager who, with the others, had
demanded that she testify.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Lewinsky's smooth delivery was downright soothing
compared with the fractured questions of Representative Ed Bryant,
the Tennessee Republican and House manager whose interrogation of
Lewinsky is heard but not seen on the tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica doesn't come across as stupid or silly, but rather as
focused, thoughtful, and someone who knows what she wants to say
and says it,'' said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a political analyst at
the Claremont Graduate University in California, who got up early
to watch the Senate trial. ``She is neither an innocent, vulnerable
child nor some kind of vixen. She is a woman who seems to me fully
understood what she was doing and weighed the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffe said Lewinsky did not hurt the president's case, even
though White House lawyer Nicole Seligman blasted the House
managers, who she said took the videotape and ``cleverly snipped
here and there'' to distort her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The president's defense team ran longer excerpts of the Lewinsky
video to bolster their case that the president had not obstructed
justice by telling Lewinsky to lie under oath about their
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors and the defense obviously intended to leave that
relationship alone, but Lewinsky could not help but recall it, with
some tenderness, from time to time in her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   How did she respond when Jordan had asked if she were a friend
of the president's? ``My memory right now is I said something about
seeing him more as a man than as a president, and I treated him
accordingly,'' Lewinsky told Bryant softly.
</P>
<P>
   How did she respond when Jordan suggested she was in love with
the president? ``I probably blushed or giggled or something,''
Lewinsky said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   And was it unusual for the president to phone her at 2 a.m.?
Lewinsky, in a word, answered: ``No.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1950EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
