<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4715 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-BOS &LR;      02-06 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS' VERDICT ON THE VIDEOS: A COLLECTIVE YAWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It had all the makings of a theatrical coup d'etat:
Monica S. Lewinsky, center screen, her voice echoing through the
silent Senate chamber as her face lit up four video displays. After
a year, the dark-haired former intern was going to come alive.
</P>
<P>
   But when House prosecutors finally pushed ``play'' on her taped
deposition, there were no explosive reactions on either side, no
senators bursting outside to express a change of heart. Many had
watched tapes of the witness earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   And though some senators gave favorable notices to Lewinsky
early Saturday afternoon, by the end of the day, even her girlish
nods and crisp answers seemed to bore many.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched all the tapes, so it's sort of a rerun for me,''
admitted Senator John Warner, a Republican from Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The only excitement involved another witness, former White House
aide Sidney Blumenthal, who testified that he never told reporters
that Lewinsky was a ``stalker'' when the story about her affair
with President Clinton broke.
</P>
<P>
   In a sworn affidavit released late Saturday, journalist
Christopher Hitchens contradicted that testimony, saying Blumenthal
used the word ``stalker'' several times over lunch on March 19,
1998. Hitchens, who writes for Vanity Fair and The Nation, also
swore Blumenthal said ``that the President was `the victim' of a
predatory and unstable sexually demanding young woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit could cause problems for Blumenthal. But even as
it circulated throughout the Capitol, members on both sides
acknowledged it was unlikely to alter the outcome of the
impeachment trial, and may not even be admitted into the public
record unless the trial rules change. At times, the presentations
of videotaped depositions seemed to have just as little effect.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon, as video clips were interspersed with arguments
on both sides, senators appeared largely underwhelmed. During
Blumenthal's deposition, Senator John H. Chafee, a Republican from
Rhode Island, was dozing off. Senator Arlen Specter, a Republican
from Pennsylvania, yawned repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   As the last segments of Lewinsky tape were played, more than a
dozen Democrats were absent from their seats. Senator Patrick J.
Leahy of Vermont called it ``cruel and unusual punishment'' to have
to sit through the testimony. More than once, Senator Joseph R.
Biden of Delaware leaned over his desk to chat with Senator John F.
Kerry of Massachusetts, who laughed and rolled his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find this whole thing incredibly boring,'' Biden, said
during a break, ``incredibly out of whack, incredibly useless.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he weren't just a little bit curious, Biden replied:
``Zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the afternoon, many senators emerged like amateur
critics at a movie preview, eager to offer vague descriptions of
what they did or did not like.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Chuck Hagel, a Republican from Nebraska, said the video
presentation of spliced remarks, which strung together the
testimony of three witnesses and of President Clinton, was ``very
strong, much more effective than the written depositions.'' Senator
James M. Jeffords, a Vermont Republican, said the videotapes
``helped with their presentation very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Many said the videotapes were at least intriguing, and predicted
they would give the public a fuller picture of the former intern _
a perspective senators have been gaining over the last week,
viewing the tapes in private.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Fred Thompson, a Republican from Tennessee, said that
``when you've heard so much about a person, and then for the first
time you see that person, you're probably going to have different
feelings about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most offered positive reviews of the star witness herself,
sizing her up largely as ``decent'' and ``intelligent.'' Senator
Frank Lautenberg, a Democrat from New Jersey, was one of the few to
raise his eyebrows when asked his impression, saying he ``got the
feeling she was relatively unsophisticated and trying to help the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Ron Wyden, a Democrat from Oregon, said she's a ``decent
person . . . and not just because she spent all that time in
Oregon,'' where Lewinsky attended college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she has her heart in the right place, with that health
care program, for example, that she was involved in,'' Wyden said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the outcome of the Hitchens affidavit remained
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   According to Representative Bill McCollum, one of the House
prosecutors, the impeachment rules preclude managers from entering
it into the public record. For that to change, he said, it would be
``up to the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Jack Reed, a Democrat from Rhode Island, said the
affidavit was ``collateral at best'' to the impeachment trial,
although he did admit that Blumenthal could be investigated or
prosecuted by the Justice Department later on. Leahy dismissed the
statement altogether, saying, ``We're getting statements coming
over the transom.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, senators watched the testimony in question.
Blumenthal denied being a source for reporters on the negative
characterization of Lewinsky, saying, ``I have no idea how anything
came to be attributed to a White House source.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
