<HEADLINE>
GOOD NEWS FROM KANDI-GRAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After one week of gritty research into basketball
dialects, we have made the translation to NBA-speak and decided
that ``O-lo-wo-kan-di'' does not mean ``La-Rue Mar-tin.''
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't mean ``Ben-oit Ben-ja-min.''
</P>
<P>
   But it does mean the Clipper curse will be adjusted to define
the profane mutterings of disappointed critics, crestfallen
comedians, and opposing centers who must deal with the rising
potential of the NBA's No. 1 draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   The professional name, for those of you whose tree houses are
not pulling in that illegal cable feed, is Michael Olowokandi. And
he means business.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, based on seven days of inclusive scrutiny, we are here to
insist the 7-foot rookie from Pacific will not become the buster
that was LaRue Martin. Martin was the Loyola of Chicago terror
chosen No. 1 overall by Portland in 1972. The halcyon days of LaRue
were as brief and substantively bankrupt as ``The Magic Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Better still is Olowokandi's habit of arriving at the arena with
an appropriate sneaker for each foot, eliminating comparisons to
Benjamin, the Clippers' unfortunate choice at No. 3 overall in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   Can we summarize our pique by designing a corresponding movie
title? Not a problem. Let's go with ``Forget Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy is where Olowokandi suited up for his first six
professional games, recording alarming averages of 7 points and 5
rebounds in action limited by his employer's knowledge that the
23-year-old soon would be leaving for the NBA. It also should be
underscored that in what passes for European hoop savvy, the player
assigned to the low post is little more than a prop.
</P>
<P>
   So those who embraced wire reports that condemned the Kandi Man
as another Clipper catastrophe without witnessing his game
themselves should drop by the Sports Arena this evening. The
Clippers are matched with the Chicago Bulls, whose bench rotation
could allow Olowokandi to test the defensive power brought to light
by Bill Wennington.
</P>
<P>
   OK, dancing on the skull of ground-bound centers such as
Wennington and Luc Longley (Friday's unwitting foil) is not enough
to quantify success. So we'll list quickness, strength, footwork,
resilience, desire and sound coaching as reasons why Olowokandi
should be the building block that holds up the Clippers' curve at
the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   And the kid seems remarkably wise, which will allow him to know
where to stand when that expected anvil falls from the Clipper sky.
</P>
<P>
   BOARD SILLY
</P>
<P>
   So, Laker fans have decided the name ``Dennis Rodman'' has a
certain ring to it.
</P>
<P>
   They realize the Worm has done more quality and highly
publicized rebounding than anyone this side of Elizabeth Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   But do they realize the Chicago Bulls were able to weather his
attention-hugging storm because Rodman could identify with the
coach, Phil Jackson, who happens to be a reconstituted hippie?
</P>
<P>
   Do they realize Jackson erred on the side of karma when Rodman
missed a road game with the ``flu'' just one night after spending
an evening throwing back kamikazes in a Chicago bar?
</P>
<P>
   Do they know Jackson sent Rodman home from New York when the
party-worn Worm arrived for the morning shoot around looking like
death eating a cracker?
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls had maturity, something the Lakers have yet to be
accused of.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers fans remember how Rodman's dyeing circus temporarily
ruined the San Antonio Spurs? Yeah, Dennis was golden in Detroit,
but that was before he brought his ego to the wrong alter.
</P>
<P>
   Old Pistons coach Chuck Daly was interested in bringing Rodman
to Orlando, but with Bo Outlaw around, there seems to be no need to
hire a (feather) boa outlaw.
</P>
<P>
   ROOKIE REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   The hits among first-year players on opening night:
</P>
<P>
   Boston forward Paul Pierce (Inglewood High, Kansas) scored 19
points and grabbed nine rebounds in a loss to Toronto. His Raptors
counterpart, the athletically freaky Vince Carter (North Carolina)
had 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   Sixers guard Larry Hughes (St. Louis) had 11 points and nine
rebounds in 16 minutes; Raef (Fear spelled backward) LaFrentz
(Kansas) had 11 and 7 for the Nuggets (LaFrentz may not be strong
enough to excel at center or quick enough to defend power
forwards); Michael Dickerson (Arizona) had 15 points against the
Lakers, and Sacramento point guard Jason Williams (Florida) had 21
points in his debut.
</P>
<P>
   The misses:
</P>
<P>
   Dallas forward Dirk Nowitzki (Germany) started, played 16
minutes, scored two points and had no rebounds. Seattle's Jelani
McCoy (UCLA) was one of several rookies who spent Friday as a
spectator.
</P>
<P>
   SHOT-CLOCK VIOLATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Among post-lockout disappointments is Vancouver center Bryant
``Pig Country'' Reeves, who reported to camp with 41 spare pounds.
It has been speculated that Reeves spent much of January eating the
food passed over by teammate Shareef Abdur-Rahim during Ramadan.
... Former Long Beach State star Bryon Russell has been slowed by a
groin injury, but started and scored 15 points in Friday's win over
Chicago. According to sources in Utah, the groin injury did not
occur on the last play of Michael Jordan's career. ... Tony Battie,
who had one of the shortest Laker careers in team history, started
at center for the Celtics in their opener vs. Toronto. Kevin
Willis, who started for the Raptors, had 28 points and 16 rebounds.
... In his Denver debut, ex-Laker Nick Van Exel missed 9 of 15
field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
