<HEADER>
A4719 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-UPDATE-HNS &LR;      02-06 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
SENATE VIEWS VIDEOTAPE OF LEWINSKY'S TESTIMONY
<TEXT>
<P>
   By GREG McDONALD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica Lewinsky made her long-awaited appearance in
the Senate impeachment trial of President Clinton Saturday,
testifying on videotape that she did lie about her affair with the
nation's chief executive but that it was not part of a plan to
obstruct justice as House prosecutors charge.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful deposition from the poised young woman, who wore a
single strand of pearls while she was being questioned under oath,
seemed to reinforce arguments by Clinton's defense team that she
was not coached to lie for him and he did not try to buy her
silence with a job.
</P>
<P>
   Her image appearing on four large TV monitors set up in the
Senate chamber, Lewinsky seemed to answer the questions put to her
calmly, sometimes smiling and sometimes looking pained by the
descriptions of her relationship with Clinton, for whom she
confessed she still has ``mixed feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I would deny the relationship,'' she said at one point,
seeming to confirm the prosecution's charge that the president
persuaded her to testify falsely about their affair. But in another
excerpt played by Clinton's lawyers, Lewinsky emphatically denied
that Clinton encouraged her to lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would remember something like that, and I don't,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is extraordinary testimony. Why? Because she corroborates
the president,'' Clinton attorney Nicole Seligman told senators as
both the House prosecution and defense teams began their closing
arguments in the first impeachment trial of a president since 1868.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides will conclude their presentations on Monday, and
the Senate could vote on whether to convict or acquit Clinton of
perjury and obstruction of justice charges by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her assertions that Clinton did not try to manipulate
her, Republican prosecutors contended that Lewinsky's personal
views of his conduct have nothing to do with ``what was in the
president's mind'' when he was trying to hide their illicit
relationship from lawyers in the Paula Jones sexual harassment
lawsuit and from independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   They insisted that he used everything and everyone at his
disposal in a ``sinister scheme'' to keep their relationship
private.
</P>
<P>
   To support those allegations, they also presented videotaped
depositions from Clinton friend Vernon Jordan and White House aide
Sidney Blumenthal, who both testified that the president did indeed
mislead them about his relationship with the former White House
intern.
</P>
<P>
   Taken all together, the prosecutors argued, the testimony
clearly shows the president sought to manipulate the people who
were closest to him so they would present a picture of his
relationship with Lewinsky that he knew to be false.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president wove a web of perjury and obstruction of
justice,'' said Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., who led off as the
House prosecution began its final arguments.
</P>
<P>
   In his presentation, Rogan described Clinton's relationship with
Lewinsky as that of a ``predator'' whose conduct amounted to sexual
harassment in the workplace. Declaring that Clinton ``impulsively
began using her for his gratification the very first day he spoke
with her,'' Rogan said Clinton later tried to use her to help him
stonewall the Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Under normal circumstances, Rogan told the senators at one
point, Clinton's conduct might be viewed as nothing more than an
attempt by a wayward husband to hide an extramarital affair. But he
contended that it progressed to much more than that because Clinton
tried to get Lewinsky to lie under oath for him and lied to
Blumenthal and Jordan, knowing that they might be called as
witnesses and repeat what he told them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to keep in mind that we seek no congressional
punishment for a man who chose to cheat on his wife. However, we
have a legal obligation to expect constitutional accountability for
a president who chooses to cheat the law,'' Rogan told the
senators, who are expected to vote next Thursday or Friday on
whether to remove Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   In their arguments, which will continue on Monday, prosecutors
are making one last attempt to convince the Senate that the House
was right to impeach Clinton on charges of committing perjury and
obstruction of justice. But so far there is little indication that
they will be rewarded for their efforts by garnering the 67 votes
needed to convict and remove Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, senators appeared to focus more of their
attention on how best to censure Clinton for his conduct than
whether prosecutors had presented enough evidence to warrant
removal. The Democrats hoped to win support for a proposal they
were floating that would declare the president guilty of
``shameless, reckless and indefensible behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   A second bipartisan proposal also was being floated by Sens.
Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., and Robert Bennett, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Both proposals could be offered at the conclusion of the trial.
But some Republicans, though interested in finding the president
``guilty of something,'' as one put it, said censure would be too
weak a punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, for instance, joked with reporters
that it would amount to no more than ``a pat on the butt.''
</P>
<P>
   The senators, as they have done throughout the trial, rushed to
the cameras after Saturday's proceedings to provide their spin on
the day's events.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the president described the prosecution's
videotaped presentation as ``political theater,'' aimed at saving a
case that is now unsalvageable. In the end, they said, the
videotaped excerpts only bolster the president's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think minds were probably changed, but you never
know,'' said Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa., praised prosecutors for
doing ``a very credible job.'' He said the White House defense
amounted to ``attacking the messenger instead of the message.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a view prosecutors were well aware of as they walked
the Senate through what they contended was a conspiracy to commit
crimes orchestrated by the president, regardless of what Lewinsky,
Jordan and others thought about it.
</P>
<P>
   In a final plea for support, Rep. Lindsay Graham, R-S.C., told
senators that he knew House prosecutors had been an irritating
presence in the chamber for the last month and had saddled them
with a terrible dilemma that everybody wants to be over. He called
on them to vote their consciences, but said he could see no other
outcome than for them to declare to the American people that ``our
president'' had committed crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants this over so bad you can taste it, including
me. But let's don't leave a taste behind that history cannot
stand,'' Graham said. ``No fair-minded person in my opinion could
come to any other rational conclusion than that our president
obstructed justice, that our president committed perjury in front
of a grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers, who had been opposed to the airing of the
videotaped depositions, ended up using greater portions of them,
particularly Lewinsky's, than the prosecution to make their case
that Clinton committed no crimes.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, they showed a Lewinsky excerpt denying outright
the prosecution's contention that she and the president discussed
how she would file a false affidavit in the Jones case. Seligman
accused the prosecutors of taking excerpts from the tapes out of
context.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have distorted, they have omitted, and they have created
a profoundly erroneous impression,'' Seligman said.
</P>
<P>
   Then in a direct slap at the prosecutors, she accused them of
trying to build a circumstantial case against the president to
perpetuate a partisan campaign to bring Clinton down that began
from the first moment he was elected to office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for this timeless pursuit of the president to come
to an end,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
