<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GALLERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL PEOPLE ON TAPE FUEL RARE FASCINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Shortly after 10 a.m., after senators were stunned
by news that a beloved legislative clerk had been killed by a car,
and after a chaplain prayed for divine guidance, four flat-screen
televisions placed strategically in the Senate chamber filled with
the visage of Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In the galleries, a cross-section of America collectively leaned
forward. After a buildup comparable to the coming release of the
new ``Star Wars'' movie, Lewinsky was finally on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Students from Walton High School in Marietta, Ga., visiting
Washington under a program designed to give teenagers a
``close-up'' look at government, got as close as any student of
history could get to a presidential impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really surprised,'' said Jennifer Brezel, 17, one of the
Walton students. ``She was supposed to be this bimbo. I thought she
was really intelligent.''
</P>
<P>
   If interviews with those who watched the videotaped deposition
in the Senate galleries are an indication, the impeachment trial of
President Clinton came to life Saturday in a way that perhaps it
had not since the story first broke a year ago. While the senators
are familiar with the details of the case, it was evident that many
others watching thought they were hearing key information for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   They were impressed when Lewinsky testified that the
presidential secretary, Betty Currie, had called Lewinsky before
collecting gifts the president had given to Lewinsky _ a key to the
House managers' case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It confirmed my belief that he obstructed justice,'' said
Christy Steinhauser of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph Quarles, a Maryland teacher and a Clinton supporter,
said an afternoon of watching video testimony had more impact on
him than anything he had heard before. Until Saturday, he said,
``we have only been able to read about it.'' Saturday, he said,
``it was visual. You can hear it, see it, feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarles expressed bewilderment after watching the testimony of
the White House aide, Sidney Blumenthal. Blumenthal described how
the president had denied having sexual relations with Lewinsky, and
said Clinton had rejected Blumenthal's advice to stay away from
``troubled people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My perception now is a little skewed,'' Quarles said,
referring to his view of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when the White House defense team had its chance to air
video clips more favorable to the president, the reaction toward
Clinton improved. In one clip, for example, Lewinsky was seen
saying the president had never told her to lie in her affidavit
denying sexual relations with Clinton. ``He didn't discuss the
content of the affidavit with me at all, ever,'' Lewinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   That was persuasive to Kevin Norman, a George Washington
University student. ``I was very impressed by the defense,'' he
said. ``It proved that Clinton was not incriminating himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Even among those who thought Clinton was guilty of the charges
against him, many said they still did not want him removed from
office.
</P>
<P>
   The day began on a somber note, as senators learned that Scott
Bates, the Senate's legislative clerk, had been killed Friday night
while walking across the street in a Washington suburb. Bates had
been in the Senate longer than most senators, starting as an intern
in 1970 and eventually rising to legislative clerk. Earlier last
week, as has been his job for years, Bates's booming voice was
heard calling the roll on the vote that allowed the videotaped
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Bates's chair in the well of the Senate was empty, a
black ribbon draped across it. A vase of flowers was placed at his
desk. The loss of his familiar voice had brought Senate employees
to tears.
</P>
<P>
   Amid this atmosphere, the Senate abruptly turned on the
televisions, and the voice of the young woman who had an affair
with the president of the United States filled the chamber.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 1956EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
