<DOCNO> NYT19990206.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4724 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-BOS &LR;      02-06 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BALANCE, CONSTITUTION IS HOLDING UP,   EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Senate moves this week toward the conclusion of the
impeachment saga, many historians and legal scholars see a glimmer
of good news.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that the constitutional process, devised 212 years ago,
still works.
</P>
<P>
   By allowing a simple House majority to impeach President
Clinton, it let a president accused of serious crimes be held to
account. By mandating agreement by two-thirds of the senators, it
evidently will protect him from being thrown out of office on a
partisan vote and against the wishes of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   And if politics was a key reason for President Clinton's
impeachment journey, the Constitution _ by making Congress rather
than the courts his navigators _ seems to have ensured politics
will end it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how ugly it has been, no matter how cumbersome,''
said Jeffrey Abramson, a professor of legal and political studies
at Brandeis University, ``it testifies to the brilliant structural
mechanisms conceived by the Founding Fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the academic debate about whether the document should be
read literally or reinterpreted with time, constitutional scholars
said its language about impeachment had proven problematic but
effective.
</P>
<P>
   By not defining ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' more precisely,
for instance, it permitted the rancorous debate that has framed the
second trial in history to eject a president. But by erecting high
hurdles and leaving the task to Congress, the analysts said, the
Constitution accomplished its core aim of making removal
exceedingly difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of Clinton's trial, most Americans would
agree that his impeachment, at a minimum, has damaged his place in
history. And to the extent that his critics want him punished,
analysts said, at least that much had been accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   The Founding Fathers considered placing the process in the
courts. If they had gone the strictly legal route, the allegations
of perjury and obstruction of justice might have posed a greater
danger for Clinton losing his job.
</P>
<P>
   By infusing the process with politics, however, they allowed for
the possibility of his staying in office even if a majority of his
judge-jurors _ the 55 Republican and 45 Democratic senators _
ultimately believe he committed serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are politicians, with considerations quite apart from
determining guilt or innocence,'' said Robert H. Bork, a
constitutional scholar and former federal judge whom President
Reagan nominated to the Supreme Court and who was rejected in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us might not like the outcome, and I certainly don't,
but that's the way it's playing out . . . and it's certainly a
result of the fundamental decision by the framers to leave this in
the hands of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal and political analysts stressed that the Constitution's
authors did not foresee many developments, such as television, that
have reshaped the political world since they wrote the government's
guiding document. In terms of the impeachment process, several
changes have particular significance: the growth of a two-party
political system, and the election of the Senate by popular vote.
</P>
<P>
   Because large, well-organized parties did not exist when the
Constitution was conceived, most authorities believe its barriers
were designed to protect a president from ``factions'' that might
band together. At the same time, since senators were appointed by
their states' governors or legislatures, they were intended to make
judgments without directly factoring in the constituent pressure
that House members were meant to feel.
</P>
<P>
   The development of opposing parties, coupled with the 17th
Amendment in 1913, making the Senate an elected body, deeply
changed American politics.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, even as they praise the Constitution for its
enduring wisdom, many historians and constitutional scholars are
disheartened by the six months of proceedings on Capitol Hill.
Although the system appears to have worked this time, the
impeachment sends ominous signals for the future.
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps their harshest criticism, many analysts say the House
has set far too easy a standard for succeeding presidents.
</P>
<P>
   There is disagreement among the experts, as there is within the
Congress and the public, about whether the charges against the
president rise to the level of high crimes and misdemeanors. But
for the majority who believe they do not, there is a gnawing fear
that an unintended precedent has been set.
</P>
<P>
   The fear is that members of both parties, when upset about
political defeats or the personal behavior of a president of the
opposing party, will feel freer to attempt impeachment if they hold
a majority of seats in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that the Senate follows its present course and does not
eject Clinton from the Oval Office, the analysts said, this process
may have the effect of making future US representatives act with
even fewer constraints. They could think, for example, that they
could politically entangle and personally embarrass the chief
executive, without risking a constitutional crisis, because his
removal was rendered so unlikely by the Constitution's two-thirds
vote requirement in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Senate is going to continue to refuse to remove
presidents,'' said Alfred Rubin, a legal historian at the Fletcher
School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University. ``But I see a real
danger . . . that the House . . . is going to want to gain
political advantage . . . by simply bringing up charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin and others said that prospect appeared to be heightened by
the ideological chasm between, and the solidarity within, the
Democratic and Republican Parties.
</P>
<P>
   Two factors could reduce the chances of this pessimistic
prediction coming to pass.
</P>
<P>
   First, many if not most members of both parties have talked for
years about amending the law on special prosecutors. After the $40
million-plus investigation by Kenneth W. Starr, it appears that a
majority is ready to kill the statute this year.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, future lawmakers will be denied the resources
that the House Judiciary Committee relied upon to build its case
against Clinton. That would not necessarily prevent legislators
from pursuing another president, but their work would be harder.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the disapproval of the Republicans' drive may act as a
deterrent for politicians down the line, particularly if that
disapproval translates into GOP losses in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest May, a political historian at Harvard, said the
two-thirds requirement in the Senate is so imposing a political
``restraining force'' that it will be nearly impossible to remove
any president. May doubted that a 67-senator majority could have
been gathered to oust Richard Nixon if he had not left voluntarily
because of the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   A politician less adept or less ``shameless,'' he said, might
have taken the same route rather than fight the battles or suffer
the humiliations that this president has.
</P>
<P>
   May suggested that if the charges are serious enough, and if the
public outcry is sufficient, only the House impeachment process
itself can realistically force a president's departure _ through
resignation. He argued that the House should therefore take its
responsibility far more seriously than it has in this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to see what public service is served by having an
impeachment that cannot lead to conviction,'' May said. ``The only
excuse for it would be that it was, in fact, a response to a broad
public demand. But it was not . . . so one could be tempted to
concluded that the motivations were political.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
