<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-FLYERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS MAKE A POINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ With little to show the last three weeks but
frustration, frayed nerves, and splintered confidence, the Bruins
left here Saturday with a 2-2 tie against the mighty Philadelphia
Flyers. A point earned. Some battle fatigue diminished. An ounce of
confidence regained.
</P>
<P>
   Paced by Sergei Samsonov's two goals _ his first strikes in a
month _ the Bruins stayed on the cusp of playoff contention by
cutting down the Flyers' high-fliers: Eric Lindros, John LeClair,
Mikael Renberg, Rod Brind'Amour et al. The Bruins are now a grim
1-8-3 in their last 12 games, but at least for an afternoon, they
found a way to cope and compete with one of the NHL's biggest,
strongest, most successful contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the game plan, you know,'' said Boston captain Ray
Bourque, after logging his requisite 35-plus minutes. ``We wanted
to battle, be strong _ do that, and hopefully you survive. We were
able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   With the postseason approaching, it's all about hanging on now.
The second half has been nothing short of disastrous for a club
that last season righted itself after its worst season in 30 years.
They began Saturday parked in ninth place in the Eastern
Conference, 2 points behind the Panthers for the No. 8 _ and final
_ playoff spot in the conference, a jumble of pieces poured out of
a jigsaw puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``All points now are good,'' said coach Pat Burns, his club able
to manage leads of 1-0 and 2-1 before settling for the tie. ``You
have to put 'em away now, like squirrels putting away acorns. Put
'em away and save 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov scored his first of the afternoon (No. 16) at 2:23 of
the first period, connecting on a stuff at the left post after
linemate Jason Allison hit Ron Hextall with a backhand sweep. The
lead, rare for Boston these days, held up through the first period,
as the Bruins outshot the Flyers, 12-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not come out with guns blazin', '' said Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   It took the Flyers, with only one loss in their previous 23
games, until 13:53 of the second period to knot it. Chris Therien
grabbed a loose puck near the right corner, curled out from above
the near circle and beat netminder Rob Tallas with a 20-foot
wrister.
</P>
<P>
   The day's outcome might have been different had P.J. Axelsson
been able to convert on a breakaway at 8:10 of the second. Sent in
alone from just outside his offensive blue line, the scrappy
checker closed to the doorstep and tried to slide a forehander
through Hextall's five-hole. But Hextall, subbing for No. 1 John
Vanbiesbrouck, made a quick drop and turned it back.
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov struck for the 2-1 lead with 29 seconds to go in the
period, this time left with acres of open net after a Bourque blast
from above the right circle was blocked. The ricochet came to
Samsonov in the slot and he popped in a high forehander before a
diving Hextall could regain position in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Effort hasn't been our problem,'' said Burns. ``What we've
lacked is some goal scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers were able to dodge the loss when Lindros popped in
his 29th at 5:22 of the third period. Standing on the goal line to
Tallas's left, his back to the rearboards, he shoveled a backhander
toward net that eluded Tallas on the near side. Just as Lindros
flicked his wrists, Hal Gill closed in and the puck popped off
their two blades and into the net. If not for the deflection, the
2-1 lead might have stood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was square, and I thought I had a good chance,'' said
Tallas. ``The view I had, I thought he was going to the far side
(right post). But it just got deflected.''
</P>
<P>
   Now come the Rangers, who visit FleetStreet Sunday afternoon.
Two of the conference's cellar-dwellars, looking to stay in the
playoff hunt. The season is getting late, available points fewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this game can only help us,'' said Bourque. ``We went
out and battled hard, and have a point to show for it. Now we've
got to feed off that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
