<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BRUINSWOES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS NEED MORE THAN A MINOR REPAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ New parts arrived on the team charter here Friday
afternoon. In times of trouble, the Bruins turned their lonely,
losing eyes to Cameron Mann and Antii Laaksonen, a pair of Baby B's
tossed back into the tailspin that had the Bruins a moribund 1-8-2
as they took on the swashbuckling Flyers Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Remember a couple of weeks back, when coach Pat Burns said this
was no time for auditions? Well, ring the gong, because it is now.
</P>
<P>
   The front office badly miscalculated the club's depth last
summer, opting not to pursue trades or sign free agents, believing
that Burns could wring even more out of the lot that made it to
last year's playoffs. Almost two-thirds of the way into the 1998-99
season, the Bruins still don't have a legitimate second line, and
the blue line suddenly looks in dire need of a facelift. The need
was there in August, but no one was paying attention, the euphoria
of a decent 1997-98 season hiding many ills.
</P>
<P>
   Will an infusion of AHL youth save the season? Doubtful. If any
of the Providence kiddie korps truly impressed Burns in training
camp, it wouldn't have taken him until early February to agree to
give the likes of Laaksonen and Mann another look. Now with a
playoff berth in the balance, and the varsity in deep decline,
they've got to step in and make a real impact? It's an extremely
unreasonable expectation. In fact, if they can step in and
contribute significantly in these conditions, it will underscore
another miscalculation (i.e. shouldn't they have been here
earlier?).
</P>
<P>
   Burns may now look obstinate, waiting this long to acquiesce and
call up some fresh, young legs. But, in most cases, he has had two
training camps to judge all contestants, and his eye is sharp
enough to know who's ready for The Show, who needs more seasoning,
who won't make it past the threshold.
</P>
<P>
   The bet here is that nothing the Bruins have in the AHL today is
going to influence the outcome in Boston. Getting back Kyle McLaren
(shoulder) will help immensely, but in two weeks the Bruins could
be 6-8 points out of a playoff spot. Looking for a miracle to come
rolling up Route 95 now is folly.
</P>
<P>
   The cruel lesson of January-February '99 is that Harry Sinden
and Mike O'Connell have to go out this summer and find a handful of
legitimate NHLers, three or four forwards and one or two
defensemen. Said another way, they are one line and a defensive
pair away from really getting in the game. It's too late to be
looking for all that now. Way too late.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   More living proof that expansion drafts aren't stocked with so
many loads of coal: The Ducks last week inked netminder Guy Hebert
to a three-year pact worth $11.9 million. The 32-year-old
Duckstopper was claimed off the St. Louis roster in the '93
expansion round. Remember, too, that Dominik Hasek, now making $7
million in Buffalo, went unclaimed in that same draft. With Hebert
and Patrick Roy (two years/$14.5 million) now signed to new deals,
there won't be an elite netminder available in this summer's free
agent swap meet, which could pad the accounts of Kirk McLean, Chris
Terreri, and Arturs Irbe . . . Don't be surprised to see the
struggling Capitals, on course to miss the playoffs after reaching
last year's Cup final, unload some high salaries with the March 23
trade deadline approaching. Ex-Bruin Adam Oates would be a prime
candidate. He'd be a good fit in Phoenix, where he could anchor a
No. 2 line, perhaps with old pal Rick Tocchet on his wing. Buffalo
also would make sense for Oates. The Sabres could do a lot with a
center _ any center . . . The Red Wings might know this week
whether defenseman Uwe Krupp will require season-ending back
surgery. Meanwhile, the rumor mill churns, with the Wings possibly
getting Mark Tinordi from Washington for Mathieu Dandenault.
Another possibility is Brendan Shanahan getting dealt to New
Jersey. Shanahan's numbers are down (37 points/50 games into
weekend action), and he doesn't have the kind of grit normally
expected of a true power forward. Shanahan's first four seasons
were spent at Exit 16W, prior to his going to the Blues as a free
agent in '91 . . . Before taking over in Vancouver, Marc Crawford
took the standard coaching sabbatical and worked as a color
commentator in Canada (like Microphone Mike Milbury at ESPN). ``I
liked the job,'' said Crawford. ``But I didn't think as a coach,
because I was too busy thinking of things to say. And there were
always guys yelling in my ear, `Wrap it up, wrap it up.' '' . . .
Last week's GM meetings in California didn't produce anything that
rattled the boards. The subject of tie games came up, as expected,
but there was no grassroots support for a tie-breaking format
(shootouts, etc). The subject isn't dead, but the debate isn't
lively.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how the financial morass in Pittsburgh will shake
out, but keep in mind that Jaromir Jagr's salary will increase by
nearly 100 percent, to $8.9 million, next season, and then top out
at just over $10 million in 2002-03. If the Penguins are going to
stay in Pittsburgh, it may come at the expense of having to deal
Jagr, which would lead to some creative trade packaging. The guess
here: a couple of established, very young players, and perhaps as
many as five first-round draft picks. To wit: Boston would have to
part with the likes of, say, Kyle McLaren and Sergei Samsonov, and
also give up the handful of picks. Jagr turns 27 next Monday. Wayne
Gretzky was 27 when the Oilers realized in the summer of '88 that
they couldn't keep paying him. The Oilers acquired three of LA's
first-round selections in that swap, as well as Jimmy Carson and
Martin Gelinas and $15 mililion out of Bruce McNall's wallet . . .
Bob McCammon got knocked around in a limo crash last week, along
with ex-A's hurler Dave Stewart and Darren Flutie, brother of Doug
Flutie. The three passengers were on their way to a charity dinner
in Thunder Bay, Ontario (McCammon's hometown), when the limo was
hit broadside by a car at an intersection. The only one hurt was
McCammon, who suffered minor facial cuts. ``It was frightening
sight to see Dave Stewart coming right at my face,'' said McCammon,
who is No. 2 man in charge at IHL headquarters . . . John Buyck on
the lost art of hip checks: ``No one these days has a big enough
rear end,'' said an amused Hall of Famer. ``I don't know what it
was. It was just my game.'' Bucyk landed a high percentage of his
upending hip checks around the net the Bruins were attacking. As an
opponent was forced behind the net by one of Bucyk's linemates,
attempting to carry out the puck, a charging Chief would sting him
with the powerful body slam as he attempted to curl out from behind
one of the posts. ``That was the key, you've got to get the other
guy to force him around,'' said Bucyk. ``Once he couldn't go back,
that's when you'd get him. Timing's important. You'd have to make
sure you didn't miss him, or you'd look really stupid.'' . . .
Colin Campbell, the NHL's director of discipline, now thinks he was
``too lenient'' when he suspended the Coyotes' Dallas Drake for
four games for the ugly check placed on LA's Doug Bodger Dec. 28.
Bodger missed six games with a sprained neck. ``I'm not perfect;
I'll admit it,'' said Campbell. More appropriate would have been
something upwards of 20 games, mirroring what Dale Hunter got for
his hit on then-Islander Pierre Turgeon . . . Ex-Bruin Glen Murray,
recovering from a wrenched knee, skated Thursday for the first time
since being hurt. He could be back in the Kings lineup in a couple
of weeks, at least a month ahead of schedule . . . Another
ex-Bruin, good guy Garry Galley, played in his 1,000th NHL game
Monday night in Philadelphia. His wife, Terri Lynn, welcomed him
home with no fewer than 1,000 roses. His kids, Shaylynn and Wyatt,
gave him portraits of themselves dressed in LA sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Flame Hakan Loob, now GM of a club in Sweden, wants to return
to North America someday and work in an NHL front office. He has an
18-year-old son, Henrik, eligible for this year's draft (at the
FleetCenter). Loob, at age 28, went home to Sweden after connecting
for 50 goals with the Flames, preferring that his children attend
Swedish schools. Nicklas Lidstrom, Detroit's standout defenseman,
said recently that his NHL days are coming to a close. He, too,
wants his children raised back home . . . It doesn't get much
uglier than the 10-1 pounding the Lightning suffered Wednesday
night at the hands of the Capitals. Washington exploded for seven
goals in seven minutes en route to an eight-goal second period. For
the record: The Sabres hold the mark for most goals (9) in a period
(the second) when they pasted the Leafs, 14-4, at the Aud on March
19, 1981 . . . Ottawa goalie Ron Tugnutt was thrilled to be at the
All-Star Game, making it a point to attend all parties and even
visit the NHL fantasy show. He took his turn at the slapshot
exhibit, and walked away pleased that he nailed an 85 m.p.h.
slapper. ``That's great,'' said Boston captain Ray Bourque, when
Tugnutt told him about his big hit, ``but my 10-year-old just
nailed one at 78 m.p.h.'' . . . Mike Keenan, now off the job in
Vancouver, packed up with his wife and went to watch some games in
Switzerland. Meanwhile, the buzz around Edmonton is that Ron Low
may be at the end of his tenure behind the Oiler bench (his deal
expires this season). ``I don't think he should be fired,'' wrote
one fan in an Edmonton newspaper poll. ``Let the players experience
what it's like to be coached by Mike Keenan for a few games. Then
the players might start appreciating Ron Low a little bit.'' . . .
Mighty Ducks trainer Greg Smith, also the club masseur, underwent
surgery last Sunday to fix the cracked cheekbone he suffered when a
flying puck nailed him the night before at Edmonton. Despite the
obvious pain, Smith finished out his shift. ``And (Paul) Kariya
never missed a massage,'' said one Duck . . . Word around Buffalo
last week was that Matthew Barnaby was about to be dealt. By week's
end, the Sabres' instigator was still under the employ of Niagara
Frontier Hockey (DBA the Sabres). When Barnaby is on his hard-nosed
game (seen rarely since 1996-97), virtually every NHL team would
want him. But his trademark nastiness is all but gone these days,
which makes him little more than a spare part . . . Slava Fetisov,
now an assistant coach in New Jersey, picked up Stanley Cup ring
No. 2 when his ex-Winged Wheels visited the Meadowlands on Monday.
This is Fetisov's first year in tie and jacket and friends say he's
feeling the itch to play again. The chances of that are slim. He'll
be 41 in April and he was used sparingly last year, although he
suited up for 21 playoff games . . . Best Super Bowl chuckle: The
FedEx ad that showed the Stanley Cup mistakenly being delivered
``Somewhere in Bolivia'' while a bunch of irate Red Wings chased a
red-faced, empty-handed NHL executive down ice after clinching the
even-more-elusive silver bowl . . . When Pavel Bure's new deal is
written up in Florida, the $47 million will be paid out over five
years in installments of $8 million, $9 million (two years), $10
million, and $11 million . . . Trevor Linden looked like he was
skating in a fog when the Islanders played here Thursday night. It
was only a year ago Saturday that Linden was dealt from the
Canucks. He can be a much better player, which is the frightening
truth in regards to about two-thirds of that lineup . . .
Unsubstantiated but interesting nonetheless: recent rumors that had
Vancouver's Mark Messier being swapped to Dallas for Joe Nieuwendyk
. . . How much would you be willing to give up for Theo Fleury? The
Bruins have to be asking themselves that a lot these days. The
Rangers, at FleetStreet Sunday afternoon, are expected to make a
heavy pitch for the Flames' little fireball, and it could be a deal
for Fleury that proves the difference between the Bruins or
Blueshirts making the playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
