<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-DAYTONA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYTONA BEGINNING TO HEAT UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Gentlemen, start your engines!''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen NASCAR Winston Cup drivers will kick off SpeedWeeks '99
when they heed that famous command and flip the ignition switches
of their 3,500-pound stock cars for Sunday's Bud Shootout at
Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-lap dash for cash among the 1998 Busch Pole Award winners
_ vying for a total purse of $512,500, with about $108,000
earmarked for the winner _ will serve as a primer for next Sunday's
big race, the Daytona 500, the inaugural event of NASCAR's 51st
season, a grueling campaign that has been expanded to 34 races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows you've got to drive hard and you have to take
some chances,'' said Rusty Wallace, winner of last year's Shootout
who got the pole position in a random drawing Thursday. ``Track
position in NASCAR Winston Cup racing is real important, and
anytime you can start up front it has got to be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon, the three-time Winston Cup champion, earned the
right to start up front next Sunday after qualifying fastest
Saturday in 195.067 miles per hour. Gordon put surprising rookie
Tony Stewart on the outside pole, bettering Stewart's lap of
194.599.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the 43-car field will be determined this week.
Thursday's Twin 125s will set positions 3 through 30. The next six
spots will go to the fastest remaining drivers from the three days
of time trials leading up to the Twin 125s. The remaining seven
spots will be filled with provisional starters who finished in the
Top 40 on last year's points list.
</P>
<P>
   The Bud Shootout field consists of 14 Busch Pole winners and a
15th driver, the winner of a 25-lap qualifying race. Geoff Bodine,
who will pilot a car fielded by Joe Bessey, a Busch Grand National
driver from Scarborough, Maine, drew the pole position for the Bud
Shootout Qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, meanwhile, hopes his No. 2 Miller Lite Ford Taurus will
be every bit as fast in the Shootout as it was during preseason
testing at Daytona, when he posted a fast lap of 193.129 miles per
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was second-fastest during testing in his Chevrolet Monte
Carlo (192.452) with Kyle Petty third in his Pontiac Grand Prix
(192.341).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not predicting more success, but I'll be the first to tell
you that it sure feels good,'' said Wallace, whose fifth-place
finish in last year's Daytona 500 represented his best result this
decade in NASCAR's crown jewel. ``From what all we've experienced
at Daytona down through the years'' _ he has crashed four times in
the last eight races _ ``to have the good runs and good finishes
like we have had is almost a payback. We've had all kinds of weird
stuff happen and sometimes it got pretty wild and ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gordon, ``It's a whole different ballgame when you get to
Daytona for SpeedWeeks. As history has shown, the fastest qualifier
is not always the one who wins. Handling is very important at
Daytona.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Craven, the native of Newburgh, Maine, who last year
parted ways with Hendrick Motorsports, will be in Sunday's Bud
Shootout, behind the wheel of the No. 58 Hollywood Video Ford
Taurus fielded by SB III Motorsports. Craven earned his spot by
winning the pole position in last year's Jiffy Lube 300 at New
Hampshire International Speedway, his first race back after an
extended recuperation from postconcussion syndrome. ``This is
almost like a dress rehearsal for the Daytona 500,'' Craven said.
``The team has literally put in hundreds of hours preparing for
this. I know we are ready. Hollywood Video has signed on for the
big event, but now it's up to us to make sure there's a sequel.'' .
. . Eddie Cheever, winner of the 1998 Indianapolis 500, won the
Indy Racing League opener in Orlando Jan. 24 for the second year in
a row. Last year, Stewart's blown engine vaulted Cheever into the
lead. Minutes later, a downpour forced the stoppage and eventual
cancellation of the race. Cheever was declared the winner without
having led a single green-flag lap. This year, however, Cheever
said he ``had the best team and the best car'' at the end of the
race. He led the final seven laps ahead of runner-up Scott Goodyear
and third-place finisher Jeff Ward . . . Stewart, who left John
Menard's IRL team to embark on a Winston Cup career with Joe Gibbs
Racing, showed up in Orlando as part-owner of an Aurora-powered
Dallara driven by Brazilian Gualter Salles. Stewart teamed up with
Andy Card, and Larry Curry, Team Menard's former manager. Stewart
is contracted with Gibbs to race the full Winston Cup schedule but
will be allowed to drive in the Indy 500 . . . Menard, the
loquacious car owner who was the last to win an IRL race at NHIS,
has pared down his team to a one-car outfit headed by driver Greg
Ray and manager Thomas Knapp. He also has spread his wings to the
FedEx CART Series as a part-owner of Team Gordon, an outfit
co-owned by driver Robby Gordon and Mike Held.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
