<HEADER>
A4734 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBANOTES-PITINO-B     02-06 1840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-PITINO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LOCKOUT DEAL SUITS PITINO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He looks around at his team now and there's a sigh of relief. No
one has to tell Rick Pitino that it easily could have looked quite
different. The old rules were stifling his rebuilding program and
he could only hope for salvation from a new set of rules.
</P>
<P>
   He got it in the form of the new collective bargaining
agreement. And now, with the NBA season two days old, he paused to
look back and talk about how easily all of his efforts could have
come undone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (past) summer, I didn't think there was any way (to
retain the key players),'' he said. ``We looked into all scenarios
and never could get any value for a trade, primarily because the
(other) team said, `We'd be in the same boat as you are, so how can
we sign him?' ''
</P>
<P>
   His owner had said Boston would not follow the salary madness.
Paul Gaston simply said ``no'' to spiraling salaries, and while
that was fiscally sound, it also might have led to the team being
dismantled before it ever had a chance to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way Paul Gaston wants to run the Boston Celtics _ fiscally
_ we could not, under the old rules, do it,'' Pitino said. ``If the
salaries go that high, the Celtics had no chance of making money.
The Knicks last year made $40 million because of Cablevision. We
made $12 million. That's great. But if we do the same things they
do, we'd lose $12 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Was Pitino disappointed that economics was threatening to
unravel everything he was building? He most definitely was.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look back, and one of the biggest things for me as a coach
was having those two draft picks, thinking we might get (Tim)
Duncan and (Keith) Van Horn,'' said Pitino. ``That was an enticing
way to rebuild. Then, when you have your best player (Antoine
Walker) and you might lose him, there are certain handcuffs that
you can't open up.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I never look back and say, `I'm sorry I left.' The Boston
Celtics is one of the best jobs in all of basketball at the
professional level. It gives you what Kentucky gave you at the
collegiate level. I never regretted that. But I wondered how I was
going to build this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The club has taken care of Walker and will get a similar bill
this summer for Ron Mercer's future services. They'll have to start
paying Kenny Anderson's salary as well. Does Pitino feel ownership
will continue to pay out the large sums, even if they are scaled,
to retain their top players?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way we work: He gives me the budget, which is the
salary cap,'' Pitino said. ``Then you have your exceptions above
that. He wants me to stay within that salary cap. Basically, he
lets me do my own thing. `Here's your budget; stay within it.' He
believes in the salary cap. He believes that's what everybody
should live by.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino says his budget projections for the next five years
indicate he is ``close to staying within the framework that Paul
wants.'' Presumably, that does not include contract extensions for
Greg Minor or Pervis Ellison. But it does mean that the eventual
deal produced by all of those days and nights of labor
sabre-rattling were an unadulterated blessing for Pitino and his
team.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC; 
The stolen Nugget
</P>
<P>
   NBC, the former official network of the world-champion Chicago
Bulls, has its cameras Sunday in New York (Miami-Knicks), Detroit
(Indiana-Pistons), and Los Angeles (Utah-Lakers). But the most
interesting game on the docket may be in Phoenix, where the Suns
play host to the Nuggets and ex-Sun Antonio McDyess makes his first
appearance since the bizarre tale that led him to leave for the
Rockies. Suns boss Jerry Colangelo still can't get over it. ``It
was bizarre, beyond comprehension, not even believable,'' Colangelo
said. McDyess turned down more money to sign with Denver, then had
second thoughts at the altar. Some Suns (Jason Kidd, Rex Chapman,
and Danny Manning, according to Colangelo) actually flew to Denver
for one final recruiting pitch. But, Colangelo said, ``They never
got to see him. He had called our players and they thought he
sounded distraught. They were concerned about his well-being. But
when they got there, they didn't see him. They hid him.'' McDyess
signed with the Nuggets the next day. Colangelo said he had a
feeling during the lockout that McDyess was going to slip away.
``The way it played out was a joke, an absolute joke,'' he said. He
inferred that there may even have been some, er, shenanigans going
on with McDyess working out in Houston and some people who looked a
lot like Denver employees close by. ``I've got a lot of stuff,'' he
said. ``What am I going to do with it? Probably nothing. But I have
a very long memory.'' . . . Seven referees who worked last season
will not be working this season. Ed Middleton and Billy Oakes, two
veterans, have retired. Woody Mayfield (knee) and Jo Borgia (back)
had to prematurely retire because of injuries, and Monty
McCutcheon, who was expected back, ruptured an Achilles' tendon
while jogging and is out for the year. Blane Reichelt and Ron
Olesiak have IRS situations and likely will miss six months before
being reinstated . . . Toughest start of this ridiculous season has
to go to the Atlanta Hawks. They broke from the blocks playing
Friday night, Saturday night, and Sunday night. Miami, meanwhile,
has a three-in-three stretch this Sunday afternoon in New York,
Monday night in Charlotte, and Tuesday night in Miami against the
Celtics. One might think the young, frisky Celtics would have a big
edge there, but Boston will be playing its second game in as many
nights and fourth in five days. Meanwhile, three teams opened
Saturday night and two, Portland and Vancouver, do not play their
first game until Sunday night . . . Some of the old-timers are
chuckling over all the wailing about games on consecutive nights.
Rod Thorn, the NBA's director of operations, recalled one season
with Detroit in which the Pistons played on five consecutive nights
in five cities. ``And we won the last one, too, which was against
the Lakers in Pittsburgh. Dick Barnett missed a wide-open jumper at
the buzzer,'' he said. ``Those were the days when men were men,''
he added with a laugh. ``But seriously, you didn't even think about
it. You just did it. That's the way it was.'' . . . Several coaches
were asked if they'd like to have Dennis Rodman on their team. The
Lakers' Del Harris noted that Shaq has endorsed such a move,
adding, ``I wouldn't go against my big fellow.'' He didn't say much
more. New York's Jeff Van Gundy added, ``Do I think he's a very
good player? Absolutely. Do I think he can help a team? Without a
doubt. As of now, I don't think I'm going to worry about that.''
Miami's Pat Riley said he'd had no personal contact with Rodman (in
other words, expect a deal soon), and Sacramento's Rick Adelman
said he'd worry about Rodman's impact on his young players. But the
ever-iconoclastic George Karl of Milwaukee offered this: ``I
personally would like to have him, and I personally had that
conversation with our organization. (Bet Herb Kohl loved hearing
that.) At this time, I think Dennis is more inclined to go to a
contender or a sunshine team, but you never know. In a couple
weeks, he might give us a call. And I would say if he did do that,
I would be fairly optimistic we could talk our people into doing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics get their first look at Ike Austin in Orlando blue
Monday night. Already, the big guy is looking like some old Russian
cooking the history books. He told Miami writers that he never
wanted to leave, which is not what he was saying last year when he
knew the Heat couldn't re-sign him. Riley didn't buy that at all.
``Ike wasn't a mistake,'' he said. ``The mistake was (Brent) Barry.
Period. We basically traded for a guy who, when he got here, didn't
want to be here. That was the mistake.'' Riley said Austin twice
told him last season that he didn't want to be back and insists now
he would never have traded the big guy if he heard anything to the
contrary. As for his new digs, Austin said he thinks the Magic are
a division sleeper. He added that Penny Hardaway, who romanced him
heavily, is better suited for the shooting guard position than the
point. ``For the simple fact that he can do more, score more, and
really focus on his game,'' Austin said. ``At the point, he's got
to run the whole team, and he's got to make sure everyone's in
place, so he's more effective at (shooting guard).'' This comes as
news to Magic coach Chuck Daly, who has Hardaway at the point.
``He's going to play a significant amount of (point guard),'' Daly
said. ``We don't have any (other) point guards.'' . . . Sports
Illustrated profiled a handful of players it feels the NBA should
market to rebuild its image in the post-Jordan era. One was
Milwaukee guard Ray Allen, who is both good and a good guy. ``Ray
is scary at times,'' Karl said. ``I've actually sat there and
watched him play, and he is almost pretty he's so fluid and quick.
A combination of being all those things and a basketball player is
very unusual.'' Allen still hasn't signed an extension _ he has
until mid-March _ and would be a most attractive free agent this
summer. (Chicago may be salivating.) ``I'd be surprised if we
didn't get that done very soon,'' Karl said. ``I know there have
been discussions in that area. Ray is building a house here, so
everything is (moving) in the direction that will get it done very
quickly.'' . . . The Spurs have added perimeter shooting in Steve
Kerr and toughness in Mario Elie, but by far the biggest plus for
them is the return to form of Sean Elliott. The gifted small
forward has basically been missing in action the last two seasons
with injuries. But San Antonio coach Gregg Popovich said this past
week that Elliott has his quick first step back and ``can jump like
he used to jump. Without those skills, Sean is really limited. He's
gone through every practice, through two-a-days, gone through the
whole preseason, and had no pain or swelling. He really is an
X-factor for us. If Sean could come back, it would be like getting
another draft pick. But since coaches always like to worry about
something, now we're just anxious to see how long that will last,
and if his knees hold up.'' . . . New Seattle coach Paul Westphal
isn't expecting much from his first-round pick, Vladimir Stepania.
But, Westy notes, the 7-footer looks a lot like Alvan Adams, one of
his former Phoenix teammates. That may be where the similarity
ends, at least for now.``Right now, he's pretty lost,'' Westphal
said. ``He's a skilled center, a high-post center. But he's totally
and understandably lost concerning NBA rules and defenses. He
doesn't understand what a foul is, or why he can push someone and
get called and not have it happen to someone else. He has a lot of
good fundamentals, but he needs to learn NBA mores. He has to learn
what the league is all about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
