<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-STANFORD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN TOO QUICK FOR STANFORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD _ The gates opened an hour before tipoff and Stanford's
students rushed to the courtside seats. Once there, they quickly
turned their wrath on Connecticut's pudgy point guard, Khalid
El-Amin. They chanted ``Fat Boy,'' they screamed a few obscenities,
and they held a placard that said: ``Khalid, One Word: Slimfast.''
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin smiled at the silliness, then spent the afternoon
helping Connecticut script a two-word response: ``Too Fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether this intersectional matchup is played in Storrs, Conn.,
or Stanford, whether it starts at 9 a.m. or noon, whether the
Huskies have All-American Richard Hamilton or not _ Saturday, they
did not _ the one constant is Connecticut's speed.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies were too fast for Stanford in a 20-point victory
last year, and they were too fast again Saturday _ handing the
Cardinal a rare homecourt loss 70-59 before 7,391 at frenzied
Maples.
</P>
<P>
   ``They forced us out of our game,'' said Stanford coach Mike
Montgomery, whose team shot 35 percent from the field. ``It's very
difficult to simulate how quick they are in practice. We weren't
able to get in the flow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal thrives on brute strength, flawless fundamentals
and precise execution of its half-court offense. But against
well-coached teams that are also improbably fast _ i.e.:
Connecticut and Arizona _ Stanford has no counterpunch.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder it's 0-5 against those teams in the last 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our game plan was to make it fast, make it quick, make it our
game,'' Huskies coach Jim Calhoun said.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin made sure of it.
</P>
<P>
   Without Hamilton, he became Connecticut's first option. Using
his 5-foot-10, 203-pound frame to overpower Stanford's guards, he
took 38 percent of UConn's shots and finished with 23 points, five
assists and five steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pretty much took us apart,'' Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin did most of his damage in the first half, scoring 16
points as the Huskies built an 18-point lead. The Cardinal rallied
late in the half and was within a basket several times in the
second. But it never took the lead, never settled into its comfort
zone. Stanford also missed 12 of 24 free throws and _ after failing
to convert on three crucial possessions in the final minutes _
watched an emotional El-Amin celebrate the Hamilton-less victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't show much class with the things they were yelling
at me,'' El-Amin said. ``Not `fat boy,' you expect that. But
`deadbeat dad.' That's not true. I take care of my kids. (He is
married and has two children.) That got inside my head. I didn't
appreciate that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a crippling loss for Stanford's push for a No.1 seed in
the NCAA Tournament. The Cardinal is the best in the Pac-10, but
with losses to Maryland and Connecticut it may not have the
credentials for a No.1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost to a lot of really good teams, and we haven't
beaten enough of them,'' Stanford center Tim Young said. ``If
you're talking big picture, maybe it doesn't look so good.''
</P>
<P>
   The small picture is a bit murky, as well. The Cardinal lost at
Arizona last weekend, then struggled to beat Cal on Wednesday in a
sloppy, grinding game. Stanford had hoped for a breakout
performance Saturday. Instead, it got a reminder of the need for
speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's discouraging because this was a great opportunity for
us,'' Montgomery said. ``But UConn deserved to win, based on how
hard they played and how efficient they played. We couldn't get
into our offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal gets another chance Thursday against UCLA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
