<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-TYSONKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING HAPPY TO BE OUT OF TROUBLESOME CORNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a stunned Mike Tyson stood in a Rockville, Md., courtroom
Friday and found himself sentenced to a year in jail on what he
thought were two minor assault charges, Don King was not at his
side. No one was happier about that than the sport's leading
purveyor of bombast.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, many have held King responsible for Tyson's many
follies and foibles. Even today, as the former associates in
Palookaville sue each other, King is being blamed by some for Tyson
owing the Internal Revenue Service $14 million in back taxes, as if
Tyson somehow had no idea that a guy making $20 million a fight
owed the government a pound of flesh.
</P>
<P>
   But with King out of the picture for more than a year now, not
even his harshest critics could say that he had led Tyson into
handcuffs this time, just as no one could blame King for the harsh
and often profane words that came out of the former heavyweight
champion's mouth in the days leading up to his return to the ring
last month against Francois Botha.
</P>
<P>
   Those words and Tyson's admission that he had tried to break
Botha's arm during a clinch at the end of the first round of his
first fight since serving more than a year's suspension for twice
biting Evander Holyfield came back to haunt him, but no one could
blame King for that, either, a point reinforced last week by a most
unlikely King defender.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, when it all comes down, a person is gonna say
what he's gonna say,'' Holyfield said of Tyson. ``A person really
can't change his stripes. If you're a zebra, you're a zebra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I said (about the biting incident and that it
should be forgiven by the Nevada State Athletic Commission) I said
from the heart. If you don't forgive, you aren't the person you say
you are. If you give someone a chance and they hang themselves,
it's on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he don't have Don King to blame. His conduct has always
been what it was. It shows you somebody did a great job controlling
him before because a lot of these things didn't get out. Now he's
got no control and things are getting out.''
</P>
<P>
   So there you have it. What Tyson does, Holyfield insisted, is on
Tyson now, which frankly comes as a relief to his former promoter.
With Tyson facing either a year in jail and the possible end of his
boxing career or an appeal that could lead him to a three- to
seven-year sentence and a certain end to his career, King is not
worried about lawyers or bail money this time.
</P>
<P>
   That is now somebody else's problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Tyson was saying (about wishing he'd bitten Holyfield in
the throat and elsewhere, for example) is normal,'' King said.
``Now you know what I was going through. This is a rough guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta work months with that guy to prepare him. Then you
still gotta choke him and say, `Whoa! Hold back!' Shelly Finkel
(Tyson's new manager) is not protecting his investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Finkel is or isn't is a story for another day. The story
for King these days is not Tyson, at least not until they meet in
court _ if they ever do. For the King of Bombast, the story is
Holyfield now, the man who defeated Tyson and became King's
brightest jewel.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most of King's life, his story is a quiet one, a
controlled story, a story he likes to tell these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such a relief,'' King said of promoting Holyfield, who
will fight Lennox Lewis March 13 in a unification title bout that
has sold out Madison Square Garden and is expected to be one of the
all-time highest-grossing pay-per-view fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you say, `Be at the DuPont Plaza at 9 a.m. on Saturday,'
and then go to sleep, he's at the DuPont Plaza at 9. What a relief
this is for me. This is order like I've never known. I only lived
chaos all my life. What Holyfield has done is of redeeming
spiritual value for boxing. It's fun again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Clean brings order and respect into the boxing realm. We
got a new boxing atmosphere where you can enjoy the air. Holyfield
is bringing principles back to the sport. I don't want to talk
about nobody else but my champion. Praise the Lord! Evander is
coming! I've made the great leap of faith! He shocked and amazed
the world when he beat Tyson like David beat Goliath. Certainly it
did me. But I am converted!''
</P>
<P>
   As King roared, Holyfield laughed, a wide smile on his face. But
it was a smile of bemusement more than amusement, for he well knows
what Tyson apparently never did _ that Don King may be your
promoter, but he works for himself.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of most promoters. That does not mean they
don't at times greatly aid their fighters, as King sometimes did
for Tyson. The fact is, in the red light district of sports, it's
every man for himself.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows that better than King, the ultimate survivor in a
sport for whom survival is the bottom line. It is with Holyfield's
help that King has done that once again, when just a year ago many
believed he was finished for the 100th time because he was battling
a federal indictment and watching many of his fighters flee to
other promoters.
</P>
<P>
   They all, including Tyson, struck at the King, yet today King is
within a month of promoting the most talked-about fight since
Holyfield fought Tyson under King's promotional direction.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a difference this time for King _ he doesn't have
to babysit his fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with Holyfield is truly a refreshing breeze,'' said
King. ``You're not reading about him in the tabloids. You're not
asking about law and order. Holyfield has taken the chaos out of
boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the Playboy interview. That's the real Tyson. I kind
of knew it was nuts all along, but where else could I go? You were
there. You had a cash cow. I tried to make him understand the
wayward ways don't work, but a guy from the ghetto outwitted guys
with PhDs, LLDs, and MDs. You gotta give Tyson credit. He's cunning
and shrewd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't that he don't know the difference between good and
bad. He knows. That's why, in the end, I really think they're going
to have to give me credit, because he won't let them do otherwise.
They won't have to lionize me. They'll just have to tell the truth.
I know I made a difference. Look at what's going on. You heard it
from Holyfield's lips.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. And from Tyson's.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield was trying to relax the day before the Super Bowl
knowing his beloved Atlanta Falcons were the underdogs against the
Denver Broncos. Holyfield understood what that meant, having been
in the same position for most of his professional career. The
difference is that Holyfield has generally proved his doubters
wrong while his poor Falcons never got off the ground against the
Broncos. Some might view that as a bad omen, but Holyfield doesn't
believe in omens. He believes in God and himself, feeling that if
he works hard for the one, the other will deliver. His next
opportunity to prove that comes when he tries to unify the
heavyweight title for the first time since he lost it to Riddick
Bowe in 1992. That he is confident was clear from the minute
someone mentioned to him that Lewis went into training for the
fight in the Poconos last week. ``Last week?'' Holyfield said.
``Too late. It's not about who Lennox Lewis fought because we know
on any given night a guy who's been fighting as long as Lennox has
has ability. I haven't seen him do the things I've done, but we'll
all know if he can on that night. If I felt he wasn't no challenge,
I wouldn't fight him. But I don't train for nobody. I train for me.
I concentrate on me being the best. I think about how I could beat
me and figure if I can find a way I'm sure they'll be trying.
Problem is, if a guy don't try to exploit my weaknesses he's in
trouble. But if a guy do try to exploit my weaknesses, he's in
trouble, too. So either way, Lennox is in trouble.'' . . . In case
you tucked yourself in early to get rested up for the Super Bowl,
Michael Grant continued his march through the hinterlands of the
heavyweight division last Saturday night, stopping former sparring
partner Ahmad Adbin (25-2-3, 11 KOs) in the 10th round. Grant
(29-0, 26 KOs) dropped Abdin in the ninth and several times in the
10th before referee Eddie Cotton stopped the bout on the advice of
ringside physicians . . . The third annual Everlast women's
national amateur championships will be held April 20-24 in
Scranton, Pa. Fourteen titles will be at stake in junior and senior
divisions and the finals will be televised by ESPN on tape delay .
. . According to Bob Arum, Oscar De La Hoya will fight the winner
of the Frankie Randall-Oba Carr eliminator match in late spring and
then the winner of the Felix Trinidad-Pernell Whitaker fight in
conjunction with Mexican Independence Day, assuming, of course, De
La Hoya survives Ike Quartey next Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
