<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-RYDERCUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET BUYERS BEWARE OF RYDER DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Ryder Cup at The Country Club in Brookline has created
intense interest, and it should be a great event for the area. But
a happening of this magnitude also creates a cottage industry, and
there seems to be no end to people trying to take advantage.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, sports is big business and the Ryder Cup probably
ranks just below the Olympics and the World Cup on the global
stage. Golf is hot. More important, golf is very hot with the
corporate world.
</P>
<P>
   It has been well-documented that Brookline residents who choose
to rent out their homes will command pretty good money. And that
area golf courses are being taken over for huge sums of cash for
various corporate entities and their pampered guests. But there is
another element lurking, that of the outside hospitality group. For
a while now, people _ most of them from the corporate world _ have
been solicited by telemarketers offering hospitality tent deals at
the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens to us at every event,'' said Mike Gilligan,
director of operations for the PGA of America. ``In a way, we are a
victim of our own success, because if we sell out, (the outside
hospitality groups) become that much stronger in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   People at The Country Club's Ryder Cup office have been fielding
calls from people confused about what these groups are selling. Two
of the more aggressive groups _ The Hospitality Group of America
Inc. and Pall Mall Corporate Hospitality Inc. _ sent out brochures
detailing lavish menus and daily itineraries complete with
champagne receptions and afternoon tea. There are two key points
worth noting about these brochures, however: The tents are not on
the The Country Club's grounds, and tickets to the Ryder Cup are
not included. A brochure from THG reads: ``Tickets are entirely
subject to availability and it is understood that The Hospitality
Group of America, Inc., has no ticketing arrangement with the PGA
or The Country Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe, said Gilligan, but such a disclaimer doesn't
prevent some people from taking the chance.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA isn't alone in its concern about these groups. The US
Open, run by the US Golf Association, is also a favorite target. An
official with the USGA said he could not comment because of ongoing
litigation. A Bellevue, Wash., software company last fall filed
suit against THG over a tent deal at the PGA Championship at
Sahalee CC in Redmond, Wash. The case, said a spokesperson for
Pivotal Software USA Inc., was settled out of court, and under
terms of the agreement they could not comment.
</P>
<P>
   These outside hospitality groups have been noticed by player
agents. Part of THG's package boasts of possible pro-am pairings
with members of the PGA Tour. Bill Glasson is mentioned, but his
agent, David Parker, said, ``That is totally incorrect.'' Rich
Moroscak, who works for the company that represents Gene Sauers and
Brett Ogle, whose names are also mentioned, said he knew of no
plans for those players to be available for outings during the week
of the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Gilligan said there are many groups out there, ``some reputable,
some aren't. We still don't know how many will be out there or
where they will be located.'' A person answering the phone at Pall
Mall confirmed that it had plans to set up tents, but would not say
where. Ed Lawrence, owner of Allandale Farm, which is across the
street from The Country Club, said he has leased space to THG but
it is up to the company to secure the necessary permits. Calls to a
THG office in Chicago were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Sullivan, Brookline's deputy town administrator, said
requests for permits are coming in, but no permits have been issued
yet. He expressed concern that groups such as THG are in
competition with the PGA of America and The Country Club, but said,
``There's nothing we can do to prevent it if they meet all our
codes and rules. But we don't condone it.''
</P>
<P>
   John Cornish is general chair of the Ryder Cup Committee at The
Country Club and together with several members, he has been
involved in the planning since Day 1. He feels ``energized'' as the
event approaches after nearly six years of planning, but he
expressed concern about the outside groups, some of whom are
boasting of their abilities to secure tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know where the tickets are going,'' said Cornish. ``I don't
know where they are getting their tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   The ironic part, said Cornish, is that tables of 10 are still
available and the event is not sold out, as some outside groups
lead people to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Gilligan said it is possible that these outside hospitality
groups will come up with two tickets here, four there, ``but in big
blocks? Believe me, we have ultimate control of tickets, but we're
scratching our heads: Where are they going to get the tickets?''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, they don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I literally have had planners in tears in my office, asking,
`What do I do?' '' said Gilligan. ``I have heard too many stories,
a lot of scams.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ianiro knows about that first-hand. He is a member at
Medinah CC in Chicago, site of the PGA Championship in August, and
in his role as hospitality sales chairman, he has an understanding
of how these outside groups work. In fact, Ianiro said, ``Several
times I have been solicited.''
</P>
<P>
   A logical target since he owns a brokerage firm, Ianiro told of
one call that months later still has him shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is calling me, trying to sell a tent to the PGA
Championship,'' said Ianiro, ``not knowing I was trying to sell
them, too, and at one point he says, `Nobody else knows this, but
Medinah is going to get a Ryder Cup.' I asked him how he knew that
and he said, `I have connections.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ianiro knew that Medinah was in the running for a Ryder Cup (the
club was eventually awarded the 2011 event), but he was curious
about what the caller said. So a few months later, when he found
the guy working at another outside hospitality group, Ianiro
couldn't help but ask about his supposed inside connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Oh, it was just part of the routine. I made lots of
cold calls. It wasn't good.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But the calls and solicitations will continue, said Ianiro,
because, ``They always have something to sell. You name it, they
are going to sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   He sympathizes with the unsuspecting people who get caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of companies are telling the PGA to spend some money to
get these groups off their backs, to get the public more aware,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad commentary,'' said Gilligan. ``But I can't
emphasize enough that it's a serious `buyer beware' situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The International in Bolton earned a victory of sorts last week
when a group that includes longtime general manager Brian Lynch
officially bought the course and adjacent land. Lynch, 38, began
caddying at The International in 1970 after being hired by head pro
Bill Ezinicki. You'd be hard-pressed to find two more loyal
gentlemen than Ezinicki and Lynch, so members should be happy that
things at the course will be pretty much status quo. Lynch is part
of a group _ Arklow LLP, headed by Dan Weadock _ that paid $25
million to Starwood Hotels and Resorts. Weadock retired from
Starwood last December and before that he was the president of ITT,
which owned The International before Starwood. Lynch said plans
will go forward on another 18-hole course on the 750-acre facility,
which also includes a nine-hole layout, Twin Springs . . . Speaking
of new courses, it is hard to believe that the course Jack Nicklaus
is building in Plymouth will be his first in Massachusetts. This is
a man who has 166 in use worldwide . . . More Nicklaus: He was
pampered by the staff at New England Baptist Hospital, he said, to
the point that they made the Golf Channel available. ``But I don't
need golf lessons right now,'' he quipped. The day before he was
released, Nicklaus watched the Phoenix Open and was intrigued by
Tiger Woods's request to have a boulder moved on the grounds that
it was a loose impediment. Nicklaus said he agreed with the ruling
and related it to a story from his design of Shoal Creek in
Alabama. In doing the 17th, a picturesque hole with a waterfall and
lake, Nicklaus was told that plenty of big rocks were available for
aesthetics. ``I said we'd like to get a couple of rocks, just a
little bigger than you can move.'' So heavy trucks came in and
massive rocks were strategically placed. ``They would not have been
ones Tiger could have moved,'' said Nicklaus . . . Ernie Els put up
another disappointing close last Sunday at the Heineken Classic in
Perth. In recent years he has been overtaken in the final round by
the likes of Steve Elkington, Vijay Singh, and Woods _ great
talents, so no embarrassment _ but someone named Jarrod Moseley
supplied the sting this time. Els led by six shots with 12 holes to
play, then began to unravel with a triple bogey. He finished with a
75, in a three-way tie for second. You can't help but wonder why he
struggles with these 54-hole leads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
