<HEADER>
A4739 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-EDWARDS-     02-06 1817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-EDWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS MAY HAVE TO REVERSE THEIR FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Regardless of whether Robert Edwards returns to full strength
before the 1999 season, the Patriots probably will have to shift
gears on their draft plans and take a running back somewhere in the
first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards's knee injury is cause to realize that there isn't a
player on the roster that legitimately could fill the Georgia
rookie's shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Patriots are looking over names such as Edgerrin
James of Miami, Cecil Collins of McNeese State, Sedrick (not
another Sedrick!) Irvin of Michigan State, James Johnson of
Mississipi State, and Kevin Faulk of LSU.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Ricky Williams; they have no shot.
</P>
<P>
   New England, which picks 21st and 28th in the first round,
should have been thinking of taking an offensive lineman, a
defensive lineman, or maybe a receiver with those choices.
</P>
<P>
   Now they may have to use one on another running back _ as
insurance, perhaps, or perhaps as someone who could be as effective
as Edwards. Edwards rushed for 1,115 yards as a rookie, the
15th-best total in the NFL. There were 20 running backs who gained
more than 1,000 yards, from Terrell Davis's 2,008 to Priest
Holmes's 1,008.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have put backup running back Sedrick Shaw on the
expansion draft list, which tells you how impressed they are with
him. Also on the roster are Derrick Cullors and Harold Shaw,
neither of whom instill much confidence in Patriot Nation.
</P>
<P>
   Free agency doesn't offer many options, either.
</P>
<P>
   Karim Abdul-Jabbar is a restricted free agent but the Dolphins
will likely re-sign him to a long-term deal. The Patriots could
pull a Curtis Martin in reverse and offer Jabbar a huge contract
and hope the Dolphins don't match it. That would cost them a first-
and a third-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Unrestricted free agents available include Errict Rhett, Ray
Zellars, Eric Bieniemy, Tyrone Hughes, Sherman Williams, Vaughn
Hebron, Darick Holmes, William Henderson, Keith Elias, Zack
Crockett, Corey Fuller, David Palmer, Aaron Craver, Dave Meggett,
Randy Jordan, Tim Lester, Fred McAfee, Jerry Ellison, and Leshai
Maston.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a stud in that group would be like striking oil in your
backyard.
</P>
<P>
   The time that the Patriots hoped to devote to Edwards's
development this year _ working on things such as strength, speed,
and better open-field running _ now will go toward rehabilitation.
This is a serious setback, one the Patriots certainly didn't need
after a season in which injuries spoiled their chance to move
deeper into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Chris Palmer has been getting his feet wet as the new head coach
of the Cleveland Browns, but on Tuesday, he'll begin to make his
mark when the expansion draft is held in Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer knows he is unlikely to get a star player, though these
selections may have more immediate impact than those from 1995,
when Jacksonville and Carolina were stocking. One hundred and fifty
players are available, and the Browns will chose 32. Palmer
realizes that about half of them will be at the bottom of his
roster.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer had been an assistant with the Jaguars, but not as far
back as '95, when they went through their expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly have a great situation where we're coming into
the league by ourselves and we have the pick of the litter,'' said
Palmer. ``There are some very good players who will be available to
us. We just have to be smart in the players we chose and the
players that the teams pull back. That's the toughest part of the
game, seeing which players the teams pull back once we take one of
their guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, who also was a Patriots assistant, may feel comfortable
selecting Jacksonville and New England players. He coached Vincent
Brisby, one of the more attractive receivers on the expansion list.
He's also familiar with Todd Rucci and Ferric Collons. The Patriots
may leave all three exposed throughout the draft in hopes that the
Browns will take on their big salaries. Also on the Patriots' list
is Shaw and 6-foot-8-inch, 335-pound guard Scott Rehberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Familiarity with players can work both ways,'' said Palmer.
``If you've coached them, you know what they can do and you
certainly know what they can't do. Sometimes you don't want to
coach a particular player again.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer says he hasn't formulated a philosophy for building his
team, whether it be the Jacksonville way with younger players, or
the Carolina way with older ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really follow someone else's blueprint, because the
circumstances are always different with the players available to
you,'' said Palmer. ``We have to do a great job in the college
draft, the expansion draft, and in the free agent market. That much
we know.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in the week he was trying to fill three coaching spot _
linebackers, special teams, and receivers. He had all but given up
on the idea of having an offensive coordinator after Denver
receivers coach Mike Heimerdinger declined to interview. For now,
Palmer will double as head coach and offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Offense is what Palmer knows best. And in an age when offense is
taking over as the biggest aspect of the game, Palmer seems
prepared to piece together a strong one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation is really not unlike what we had with the
Patriots when we were 1-15 and then we had the No. 1 pick in the
draft,'' he said. ``We took Drew Bledsoe and the franchise began to
turn things around for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   As one who has had a hand in developing Bledsoe and Mark
Brunell, Palmer seems to favor quarterbacks, which is why the
speculation is overwhelming that Cleveland will take Kentucky's Tim
Couch with the first selection in April's college draft.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked about it, Palmer laughed and said, ``You know, we
aren't even anywhere close to talking about that. The coaching
staff has taken up most of my time.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Palmer knows that the first selection in the college
draft is one of those monumental picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that long ago that we debated Rick Mirer or Drew
Bledsoe,'' said Palmer. ``After their first year, some thought
Mirer had the better rookie season. Obviously Drew has had the
better career, but it's really a situation where you need a crystal
ball. You have to go with the player your organization feels
strongest about and hope you've made the right pick.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't bet against Palmer making a run at Tom Tupa if the
Patriots haven't re-signed their punter/backup quarterback Friday,
when free agency begins. Palmer was close to Tupa in New England,
and Tupa is a Cleveland native.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   This week's local-boy-makes-good story is Mark Banker, a former
football standout at Plymouth-Carver High School, Class of 1974.
Banker had been on Mike Riley's staff as a secondary coach and
recruiter at Oregon State and was one of three coaches Riley was
able to hire when he was named the Chargers' head man. For a kid
who grew up in America's Hometown, Banker has now spent almost half
his life on the West Coast. After four years and graduate work at
Springfield College, Banker became defensive coordinator and
recruiter at Cal State-Northridge, which went from Division 2 to
Division 1-AA during his 14 years there. He also coached with Riley
at Southern Cal and spent almost two years at the University of
Hawaii before rejoining Riley at Oregon State. ``It's a dream come
true,'' said Banker. ``I've always wanted to end up in the NFL and
I'm fortunate to be with a great coach like Mike Riley. I know the
outside world thought it was surprising he got the job, but when
you've been around him and worked with him, you understand why.
He's a brilliant coach with great ideas. I know that Baltimore,
Chicago, and Carolina all wanted to talk to him about their job. He
has a great reputation in our business.'' . . . Kennard McGuire,
the agent for defensive tackle Mark Wheeler, doesn't believe the
Patriots want his client back . . . The Patriots will go back to
Bryant College for training camp, but only for the short term.
School officials and team brass are working out a new lease. The
Patriots may try to find a Boston site for camp within the next few
years . . . Miami's Jimmy Johnson passed on a chance to acquire
Carl Pickens last week. The Bengals have let the unrestricted free
agent receiver make his own deal with the understanding that
Pickens will have a franchise tag on him. Once he has the tag,
teams must give up a first- and a third-round pick to acquire him
and his $4 million-$5 million salary. Johnson passed. Pickens would
like to play for the Cowboys, who need another receiver to go along
with Michael Irvin . . . Jack Mula, Doug Flutie's agent, flew to
Buffalo Friday to begin contract negotiations. ``We'll find out
whether the Bills want Doug to finish his career in Buffalo,'' said
Mula . . . Williams, the Heisman Trophy winner, made the first big
mistake of his career when he dumped Boston's Woolf Associates as
his representative . . . Back to our favorite subject: offseason
conditioning programs. Before last season, the Chargers had their
best turnout and best program in years. The result: five wins. The
Vikings, who traditionally have a below-average turnout: 15 wins
and 1 point away from the Super Bowl. If you have good players and
they work out, you win a lot of games. Contrary to popular belief,
the Patriots were among the top teams in the league in turnout in
'98, with 46 players attending the program. Not all of them
completed the 40 workouts, but most did . . . Workout bonuses of
$50,000 or more have come into vogue the past three or four years.
Patriots with bonuses of $50,000 or more include: Bledsoe, Terry
Glenn, Rucci, Max Lane, Willie McGinest, Ted Johnson, Chris Slade,
Armstrong, Zefross Moss, Tony Carter, and Ben Coates. The other
players have the more standard $5,000-$7,000 bonus. Who among the
group with big bonuses was skipping out last winter? Only Bruce
Armstrong and Moss were absent for all the workouts, and the
Patriots say they don't worry about Armstrong because he's a
six-time Pro Bowler. Glenn made about 25 workouts. McGinest skipped
a few. Rucci, Lane, Slade, Johnson, Carter, and Coates were all
loyal to the program. Bledsoe made nearly all the workouts . . . It
doesn't look as though Meggett will be re-signed by the Jets, as
Bill Parcells wants Leon Johnson to be his kick returner . . .
Don't be surprised if Coates has his contract renegotiated before
the start of next season . . . Ty Law has been practicing catching
punts in Hawaii, though he won't do it in Sunday's Pro Bowl. Lawyer
Milloy on Law's desire to return punts: ``Over my dead body. Until
we get the right corner spot solid, Ty isn't doing any of that.
He's playing his position. We can't afford to get him hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
