<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-WORLDALPINE-MAIER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAIER STREAKS TO DOWNHILL TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ Over one of the most dangerous downhill courses in
the world _ the Birds of Prey at Beaver Creek _ Hermann Maier,
Austria's all-world ski champion, muscled through the icy track at
80 miles an hour to win the downhill gold medal at the World Alpine
Championships here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Maier beat archrival Lasse Kjus from Norway by .31 of a second,
with another Norwegian champion, Kjetil Andre Aamodt, more than a
half-second back for the bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
   Maier, who electrified the world with his flying, 70-m.p.h.
crash in the Nagano Olympic downhill last year, approached this
race with his customary attitude: ``If you do not take risks, you
cannot win ski races.''
</P>
<P>
   Maier used his size and strength (6 feet 2 inches, 210 pounds)
and was aggressive. Through the difficult series of high-speed
turns and 150-foot jumps, Maier bashed his way between the gate
poles, keeping a line higher than the other racers. He threw his
weight from edge to edge wildly but stayed solid on his skis where
other racers were being tossed around on the icy bumps.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening competition of these championships last Tuesday,
the Super-G, Maier had tied Kjus for the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, waiting at the bottom for Kjus to make his run, Maier
said he was surprised that the Norwegian did not take over the lead
because his run seemd so strong.
</P>
<P>
   The US skiers did not fare well. Daron Rahlves, Casey Puckett,
and Chad Fleischer were victims of a sudden snow squall that
diminished visibility and slowed the track for the late racers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That snow changed the whole race,'' said Tom Kelly, spokesman
for the US Ski and Snowboarding team.
</P>
<P>
   Rahlves, 24, from Truckee, Calif., was thrown off his skis by a
series of bumps that he never saw. After his crash, he was able to
walk off but complained of soreness in one knee. Puckett also
crashed, lost a ski, but finished the race (in 34th place) on one
leg to the delight of a big crowd. Fleischer, a hometown skier from
Vail who is built like Maier, predicted in training that he would
win Saturday's race. But his 23d-place finish was 4.73 seconds off
Maier's winning pace.
</P>
<P>
   The rowdy gathering of 3,000 began picking up the chant from
Maier's fan club from the time the Austrian got into the starting
gate. The roar grew as they watched ``The Herminator'' punch
through turn after turn, courting disaster. When he swept into the
finish area after his trademark run, it was clear that the only
other skier who could beat his time was coming next, Kjus.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian attacked the course with nearly the same ferocity
as Maier. Kjus stayed firm on his skis over the bumpy ice and made
the fallaway turns with precision, yet he fell back by a third of a
second that he never made up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if he was heavier it could have helped him today,'' said
Maier, who cavorted with his jubilant fans after the race, at one
point explaining that a chronically sore back had been soothed by a
new ``groundhog grease'' he was rubbing on it.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining the Austrian team in 1996, Maier has won 17 World
Cup races, an Olympic gold medal, and two golds so far at these
Worlds. After his spectacular crash last year (``Not Lufthansa, but
not bad,'' he joked), he was back in the Super-G race two days
later, with a sore back and several bruises, and won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
