<SLUG> BC-BKW-BOSTONCOLLEGE-RUTGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC PICKED APART BY RUTGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston College women's basketball coach Cathy Inglese tried hard
to be optimistic Saturday when she looked at the stat sheet at
haltime and saw that her team was shooting 22 percent against
Rutgers, and was trailing, 37-20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I said the good news is we can't shoot any worse,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She was right. But even though the shooting got slightly better,
it wasn't enough. Rutgers, No. 12 nationally and No. 2 in the Big
East, improved its record to 20-4, 12-1 in the conference, as it
handed BC a 71-52 loss before 3,243 at Conte Forum. The No. 20
Eagles fell to 17-5 overall, 9-5 in the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers entered ranked second in the country in scoring defense,
having held its opponents to 55.6 points a game. The Knights, who
usually play a zone, switched to a man-to-man to confuse the
Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent the last two days practicing different kinds of zone
and man-to-man defenses, and I really wished we had picked one and
stuck with it,'' said Inglese. ``But I thought they played a
tremendous game and picked us apart.''
</P>
<P>
   That began as soon as the buzzer went off, when Rutgers'
6-foot-4-inch center, Tammy Sutton-Brown, opened with a field goal,
followed by three consecutive 3-pointers by 5-10 senior guard
Tomora Young. Only three minutes into the game, Rutgers had built
an 11-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Inglese called a timeout to get her team to wake up and regroup.
But the damage was only beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Even though point guard Brianne Stepherson _ one of three
freshmen starting for BC _ knocked in a 3-pointer, and the Eagles
made nine trips to the free-throw line to account for 7 points,
forward Alissa Murphy shot 1 for 7 in the first half, while guard
Nicole Conway was 1 for 6.
</P>
<P>
   And as cold as Eagles were, that's how hot the Knights were.
Paced by another 3-pointer by Young, and another by forward
Shawnetta Stewart, Rutgers kept adding to its lead to finish the
half with that 17-point bulge.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the worst we've shot all season, and Rutgers is a very
good defensive team,'' Inglese said.
</P>
<P>
   To open the second half, BC got a steal by Murphy, who was
fouled and made both free throws. That was followed by a jumper by
freshman forward Becky Gottstein, and the Eagles had closed the gap
to 13. But that was the closest they would come, as Rutgers passed
the ball around the perimeter to fire from the outside, and forced
BC into 21 turnovers. Gottstein scored a team-high 12 points,
followed by Whitney Steele's 11, and Murphy's 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably one of the finer games we've played,'' said
Rutgers coach C. Vivian Stringer. ``I was real pleased with our
defense, because we haven't played man-to-man in quite some time.
But everyone knew what their assignment was and held everyone
accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though BC outrebounded Rutgers, 36-35, the Knights shot 48
percent from the field and 41 percent from the 3-point line.
Sutton-Brown scored a game-high 18 points, followed by Young with
16. Tasha Pointer, a 5-6 guard, had 8 points and nine assists.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who gave credit for her four 3-pointers to Pointer among
others, also cited the new black-with-red-trim uniforms the team
broke out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' she said. ``Made all the difference in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   And who can argue with that?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
