<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-STANFORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETERMINED HUSKIES HURT STANFORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ UConn Saturday was facing a hostile crowd.
It was playing a Top 5 team and its best player was on the bench
with an injury. Two other starters were playing hurt, and in the
first half some questionable calls helped an 18-point lead shrink
to 4 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   All of this after one of its worst performances in a decade,
marked by poor play and, quite shockingly, lack of effort.
</P>
<P>
   Sounded pretty grim if you were UConn coach Jim Calhoun and your
No. 1 ranked (at least until Monday) Huskies had traveled to Maples
Pavilion to face No. 3 Stanford, a team with revenge on its mind
after getting spanked by the Huskies last season in Storrs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were people who didn't think we could win this game,''
said Calhoun with a smile after watching his team roll to a 70-59
victory. ``And considering how we played against Syracuse on Monday
night (a 59-42 loss), and with 20 points missing from the lineup
(with the absence of Richard Hamilton, suffering from a thigh
contusion), they might have had reason to feel that way. I never
thought it. And no one on this team thought it.''
</P>
<P>
   A sellout crowd of 7,391 that came to bury the Huskies, not
praise them, certainly didn't expect to see UConn win its 20th game
in 21 tries going away.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a win,'' said Calhoun with a smile, a laugh, and a
shake of his head. ``You're not going to see too many efforts
better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not under the circumstances, which brought the Huskies
into the Bay Area wondering not only how they would play, but who
they would play.
</P>
<P>
   The question marks were center Jake Voskuhl (bruised foot) and
Hamilton. After getting the OK from the doctors in midweek, Voskuhl
was fine and contributned down the stretch when the Huskies
withstood a final Cardinal surge.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was a different matter. The thigh contusion was deep,
making him doubtful. He worked out briefly on Friday and gave it
another shot before the game, but decided not to play.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Monday night, when the Huskies learned Voskuhl and
Hamilton would not play a mere seven hours before tipoff, this time
they had plenty of time to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   Given time, few coaches do a better job of preparing a team than
Calhoun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought Rip (Hamilton) would be available and I don't
think he'll be ready against Boston Collge (on Wednesday),'' said
Calhoun. ``But now, for the first time, I believe we are deep.''
</P>
<P>
   He should. The Huskies trotted out all sorts of heroes. In the
first half, it was Khalid El-Amin, who scored 16 of his 23 points
as the Huskies jumped to an astounding 26-8 lead before the
Cardinal finally got back into it.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was guard Ricky Moore, who again came up with a monster
defensive performance and also scored 12 points, pulled down six
rebounds, and took over the game in the second half when the
Cardinal were matching the Huskies basket for basket.
</P>
<P>
   There was Voskuhl, limited to ony 20 minutes because of his
injury, but who blocked two shots and came up with a couple of key
rebounds in the final two minutes. There also was Kevin Freeman,
who made six of seven field goals and scored 14 points, picking up
the slack for Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing about this team,'' said Voskuhl, who made his
biggest play when he tipped a ball to El-Amin, who then got the
ball to Freeman, who made a jump shot. That turned what had become
a 56-54 lead to 58-54 with 1:34 left. ``We have so many leaders who
can take over. It's what makes this team so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Stanford's not going to argue. The Cardinal (19-4)
never had a lead. ``They took us out early with their defense and
they forced us out of our game,'' said Cardinal coach Mike
Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Big East officiating crew of Ted Valentine, John
Cahill, and Donnee Gray started to take center stage _ Valentine
gave Calhoun a T after he stepped across the line with his constant
haranguing, the game never really got away from the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them to do what they were doing,'' said Calhoun, ``I
told them to continue to play aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we did,'' said El-Amin, who took abuse from the
crowd all game. ``We came out here and took control of the game
from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies did that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
