<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG, BARNES TRADE PLACES FOR UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two months ago, while UCLA guard Ray Young sat on
the bench wondering when his next chance would come, forward Matt
Barnes could do no wrong and had the playing time to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the freshmen have reversed roles. Young is playing heavy
minutes and producing while Barnes struggles, in one minute and out
the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they've traded places,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin
said. ``At the start of the year, Matt was playing well and Ray
couldn't do anything right. They've flip-flopped.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last five games, Young has averaged 22 minutes, scored 37
points and played tenacious defense. Barnes, who lost conditioning
and confidence after spraining his ankle over Christmas, has
averaged 10 minutes and scored 12 points in that span.
</P>
<P>
   Last week at Washington State, Barnes had five points in nine
minutes in the first half, then did not play in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, against Oregon, he played two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really want to get Matt more minutes,'' Lavin said. ``I have
to put him in and let him play through his mistakes. He's had a
couple of good weeks of practice, and he's getting better. Being
yanked in and out probably has hurt his confidence to a certain
degree. . . . I'd like to have him, by (NCAA) Tournament time, in
the rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric update: Freshman center Dan Gadzuric played a
season-low eight minutes against Oregon (one minute in the second
half) because of matchup problems and nagging tendinitis in his
right knee.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins will monitor Gadzuric's minutes. He's lost
conditioning and a bit of confidence because he cannot practice
full-time on the tender knees.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin expects Gadzuric to play today and believes Oregon State
is a better matchup for both Gadzuric and power forward Jerome
Moiso. Whereas Oregon's big men are quick and capable of playing on
the perimeter, Oregon State's front-liners tend to remain in the
low post.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, our quick lineup always works better against
(the Ducks),'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Up against the wall? UCLA played its worst defensive games of
the season against Washington and Oregon, which shot 54.5 and 51.9
percent from the field, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin attributes the trouble to two factors: fatigue and
fundamentals. The Bruins don't fight through screens well, they
gamble for passes, they do not hustle to stop fast breaks and they
yield position in the low post. Fatigue has compounded the
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is when you're fatigued, you're not as alert,
you're not as quick in rotating, not as quick to long rebounds and
loose balls,'' he said. ``And part of it is we have got to continue
to get better in those areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The fatigue factor makes it difficult to correct the problems
using practice, he explained, so the Bruins are watching more
videotape than they have in recent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more mental preparation,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 2018EST &QL; 
