<HEADER>
A4748 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TV-NYT &LR;      02-06 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: THE POWER OF THE EDITED IMAGE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On video, Monica Lewinsky seemed neither the little lost lamb
nor the thong-snapping stalker of some people's imaginations. What
she  &UR; was &LR;  depended on who was choosing the video clips.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Seligman, one of the president's lawyers, played an
18-minute excerpt from Ms. Lewinsky's video deposition Saturday
afternoon. In that lengthy clip, Ms. Lewinsky sighed, she rubbed
her nose, she brushed back her hair, she sipped water from a straw.
Asked how she chose which gifts from the president to produce in
response to a subpoena, she answered, ``Kind of in an obnoxious
way, I guess.'' She offered nervous laughter. After a year of
seeing her mobbed by photographers, of hearing her disembodied
voice sobbing and scheming on the Linda Tripp tapes, we finally saw
her with a sympathetic human face.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Seligman offered the extended excerpt in response to the
flurry of snippets from the same tape played by the House
prosecutors through the morning. She accused them of sleazy
editing, and in fact their presentation had created a far sterner
image. Paring away all small gestures and bits of revealing body
language, they presented a Monica Lewinsky who was businesslike,
confident and surprising only in her familiarity. With her demure
pearls and discreet black suit, she was a woman in full command of
the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the inadvertent tribute to the powers of editing,
Saturday's video testimony offered a fresh phenomenon in the
president's trial: the boomeranging spin, with each side producing
the opposite impression from what they might have liked. For it was
the Republicans who had been howling about how ``young'' and
``vulnerable'' Ms. Lewinsky would seem on tape. And it was the
White House who, by letting the tape roll so Ms. Lewinsky could say
she never discussed affidavits with the president, displayed a
tenderly young woman who thought she had been having an exciting
affair and found herself swept up in a tidal wave of subpoenas and
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The advance billing for this video had always sounded desperate.
(You've seen her! You've heard her talk! But not at the very same
time!) And despite the different approaches, much of what the
public saw yesterday was familiar. In both presentations, Ms.
Lewinsky seemed coiffed and coached to the limits of human
endurance. Her poise was not surprising, given that she has played
the witness in this drama more than 20 times.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides weighed in with what Greta van Sustern, the CNN legal
analyst, had predicted would be ``dueling sound bites.'' And as the
spinning voices of House prosecutors and White House lawyers set up
the clips they wanted viewers to see, they created arguments but
not much of a narrative.
</P>
<P>
   Because the text of the deposition had been released the day
before, everyone knew there would be no slamdunk evidence to change
either side's case. What seemed most disappointing, then, was that
the most gripping moments from Ms. Lewinsky's deposition were not
played.
</P>
<P>
   In the deposition, Ms. Lewinsky mentions several events that
made her sob. She says, ``I was a pest,'' about arranging meetings
with Clinton. She often makes the distinction between ``the
president'' and ``the man.'' In a line quoted endlessly on
television, she says she has ``mixed feelings'' for the president
now. And she asks Rep. Ed Bryant, the Tennessee Republican who
questioned her, not to refer to her first sexual encounter with the
president as ``the first so-called salacious occasion.'' No one
expected Bryant to ask, ``Monica, if you were a tree what kind
would you be?'' but it was astonishing to read such a tone-deaf
reference to ``salacious'' meetings. None of those clips were
played Saturday, and the letdown hints at what the public still
longs for: the human story beneath this political ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident that Ms. Lewinsky's forthcoming book is called
``Monica's Story,'' or that it is written by Andrew Morton, the
author of the best-selling ``Diana: Her True Story,'' which so
effectively spun the sympathetic image of an emotionally wounded
princess. (Not an easy sell when you think about it.) Even Bryant
complained that Ms. Lewinsky ``didn't tell her story'' on the tape
and so should be called as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   The sympathetic tale, the first-person story, is what these
snippets of defensive video testimony can only hint at. However
much it resembled a movie, this was a deposition, with a stationary
camera, off-camera questioner and bad lighting that caused Ms.
Lewinsky's hair to cast shadows on her face. The room was full of
lawyers, but visually Ms. Lewinsky was isolated.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any doubt that Ms Lewinsky's emotional drama is what
matters here, consider how much less intriguing the video clips of
Sidney Blumenthal and even Vernon Jordan were. They are onlookers.
It would have been interesting, though, to see a fuller version of
Jordan talking about how ``alarming'' it was when Ms. Lewinsky
asked if the president would be leaving the first lady after his
term ended. He may have seen yet another Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   We might as well admit that part of the fascination with her is
pure voyeurism. But it is also true that the consequences of this
scandal are weighty, speaking to the country's moral and cultural
divide. The persistence of the story on television comes from its
unbeatable combination of soap opera and news: it is lurid  &UR; and &LR; 
historically important.
</P>
<P>
   And at its heart is Monica Lewinsky's story. For legal as well
as commercial reasons, she seems to be saving the juicy details for
her book and her Barbara Walters interview, and Saturday's video
excerpts were mere promos for them. (Both are on hold until she
gets permission from Kenneth Starr's office.) Strange as it seems,
Ms. Lewinsky has just begun to spin her own story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
