<HEADLINE>
BRYANT'S FAST START ROCKS HARRIS' BOAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The 25 points, the 10 rebounds and the post-game
accolades didn't necessarily guarantee Kobe Bryant an encore
performance as a starter, but he'll get one today anyway.
</P>
<P>
   As the Lakers prepared for their first meeting with Utah since
last May's sweep by the Jazz, coach Del Harris was still working
with a partial roster.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Fox, battling bad shoe insoles and now bone spurs in his
right foot, will sit again today. Robert Horry is due back from
Houston, where his wife gave birth to their second child Friday,
but he will be limited to bench duty.
</P>
<P>
   So it's Bryant and Corie Blount again at the forward slots.
</P>
<P>
   And for Harris, that's a mixed blessing. With Bryant lighting up
Houston's Scottie Pippen on Friday, the questions about Bryant's
role quickly began to irritate the Lakers coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue should not be who starts. If it becomes that,
it's a self-defeating kind of thing,'' Harris said. ``We will work
it out, I promise you. There should be better stories, you know,
like when will the coach be fired.''
</P>
<P>
   With Fox's status uncertain, Bryant could get a couple of more
starts, and if he continues playing the way he did Friday . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Del's gonna have a tough decision coming up, because he looked
pretty good starting,'' Shaquille O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Count Pippen among the impressed. The former Bull struggled to
get any offense going as Bryant blocked his shot twice and picked
him once in the first half. Pippen finished with 10 points and did
little to slow Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a little bit more patient, it seems (this year),'' Pippen
said of Bryant's offense. And as for his defense: ``I didn't think
I shot the ball well. I have to give him credit, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuffling: The lack of Horry and Fox made for some interesting
use of the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Center Elden Campbell, who lost his starting job as power
forward last year, played alongside O'Neal for several stretches
and was fairly effective, with six points and five rebounds in 15
minutes. Seldom-used center Sean Rooks also spent some time on the
floor with O'Neal, logged 10 minutes and helped keep Charles
Barkley in check.
</P>
<P>
   Nerves: Bryant sounded as cool as he played before his big
night, but point guard Derek Fisher, also making his first career
opening-night start, was fighting off some butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't sleep well at all (Thursday) night,'' he said.
``Starting the season is definitely something I've looked forward
to for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The nerves showed a bit. Fisher managed only three points and
three assists in 23 minutes. Veteran Derek Harper played 31 minutes
at both the point and shooting guard, finishing with 16 points and
seven assists.
</P>
<P>
   Boarding school: The Lakers won the rebounding battle Friday
47-44, but the encouraging part to Harris was where the rebounds
came from. Bryant got 10 from the small forward spot and guard
Eddie Jones grabbed eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is really key for us and something that has to be
rewarded when it happens and noticed,'' Harris said, ``because
that's where we've gotta do better. Yes we want to do better
rebounding from the four (power forward), but we have to do it at
the one, two and three spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Fox's sore feet, and delays in getting the proper
shoe insoles, leave him questionable for Monday's game at San
Antonio. Campbell is nursing a sprain in his right hand but will
play today. Jones has a slight contusion in his right thigh but
won't miss any playing time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
