<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SANTANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLOIT EARNS IMPRESSIVE WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ If supper doesn't begin until the hostess lifts her
fork, then the Kentucky Derby prep season doesn't begin until the
future-book favorite makes his 3-year-old debut. Saturday, it was
(begin ital)bon appetite(end ital) for horseplayers.
</P>
<P>
   Exploit was in the starting gate for the $150,000 San Vicente
Stakes, and although it was a short race with only three horses,
the unbeaten colt's presence raised the anticipation at Santa Anita
on a day ostensibly headlined by the $500,000 Strub Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   And Exploit did nothing to discourage his admirers. He put away
a classy sprinter midway through the 7-furlong race, turned back
another rival who had the momentum in the stretch, and won by an
all-out neck under Chris McCarron to run his record to 5 for 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not like to get beat,'' said trainer Bob Baffert, who
will be shooting for an unprecedented third straight Derby victory
if Exploit _ or any of Baffert's string of contenders _ makes it to
Churchill Downs on May 1. ``I like that about him.''
</P>
<P>
   If Exploit can be compared to either of Baffert's Derby winners,
Silver Charm and Real Quiet, the obvious choice would be the
former, the 1997 San Vicente winner. Exploit and Silver Charm have
the same owners, Bob and Beverly Lewis of Newport Beach, and as
Baffert noted, similar spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminds me of Silver Charm in the way that he likes a
fight,'' Baffert said.
</P>
<P>
   Exploit (who paid $3.20) won by a neck over Aristotle as early
leader Yes It's True faded to a distant last. Exploit was timed in
1:22.00 on a track that had just been upgraded from ``good'' to
``fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory margin was the narrowest of Exploit's career, which
left off in November with a 1 }-length score over Vicar in the 1
1/16-mile Kentucky Jockey Club Stakes at Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's (begin ital)other(end ital) stakes, the historic
Strub for 4-year-olds, was won by heavily favored Event of the Year
and jockey Corey Nakatani.
</P>
<P>
   Event of the Year was the Derby favorite for a brief time in '98
_ until he injured a knee in training eight days before the race.
The son of Seattle Slew missed nine months and, before he came
back, he was moved by owners John and Betty Mabee from Jerry
Hollendorfer's barn in the San Francisco Bay Area to Richard
Mandella's barn here.
</P>
<P>
   Mandella said he didn't lose confidence when Event of the Year
finished third to Run Man Run in the Malibu Stakes _ spoiling what
had been a 4-for-4 record _ and second to Dixie Dot Com in the San
Fernando.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very, very good horse,'' Mandella said. ``He just had a
little bit of learning to do.''
</P>
<P>
   With Dixie Dot Com injured and out of the Strub, Event of the
Year ($4) won the 1 [-mile race by 2 } lengths over Dr Fong.
Hanuman Highway was third at 24-1.
</P>
<P>
   Event of the Year strengthens Mandella's hand for the March 6
Santa Anita Handicap, which the trainer won the past two years with
Siphon and Malek. Mandella plans to run Malek.
</P>
<P>
   He indicated Donn Handicap winner Puerto Madero will run in the
Big 'Cap too if it won't interfere with his plans for the March 28
Dubai World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Such mouth-watering anticipation was in the air Saturday.
Baffert's plans for Exploit includes the Feb. 28 San Rafael or the
March 13 San Felipe and then the April 3 Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Eddie Delahoussaye had a second and a third but no
victories at Santa Anita. He'll have seven chances today to ride
No. 6,000.... Run Man Run, sixth in the Strub, pulled up lame....
Bob Baffert-trained Censored and David Flores won the $132,700 Pro
or Con Handicap.... Free House, making his 5-year-old debut, is 7-5
on the morning line for the San Antonio Handicap today. Malek is
2-1. Cavonnier could be scratched if Baffert isn't sold on the
track condition.... Manistique is 3-5 against six fillies in the La
Canada.... Trainer John Shirreffs won his fifth in a row when
Cliquot ($3.40), a photo loser to General Challenge in November,
broke his maiden in 1:09.10.... In Florida, Yagli ($3.20), with
Jerry Bailey, came through on the hedge to win the Gulfstream Park
Breeders' Cup Handicap in his first start since running second in
the Hollywood Turf Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
