u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-1STLEAD     02-06 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-1STLEAD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC HEARS LEWINSKY'S STORY AS VIDEOS ARE PLAYED IN SENATE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to replace earlier Rosenbaum story with same slug)  By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica Lewinsky spoke to the Senate and the world
Saturday, via videotape, about her extramarital affair with
President Clinton, which plunged him and the nation into an
impeachment ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has repeatedly testified that no one ever asked her
to lie under oath about the affair, Ms. Lewinsky said she knew from
the start that if she was subpoenaed to testify in the Paula Jones
case, ``I would deny the relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why, she answered, ``Because it was part of the pattern of
the relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecutors vividly juxtaposed the image of Ms.
Lewinsky, 25, wearing a demure dark suit and a strand of pearls,
raising her small, almost childlike right hand and swearing to tell
the truth, with one of Clinton, 52, wagging his finger at a news
conference in January 1998 and denying having sexual relations with
``that woman, Ms. Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   In a kind of minidocumentary, the prosecutors mixed taped
excerpts of this week's depositions by Ms. Lewinsky with selections
from those of Vernon Jordan, the presidential confidant, and Sidney
Blumenthal, the White House aide, to buttress their case against
Clinton. They also showed selections from the president's sworn
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence, the prosecutors argued, depicted a web of actions
designed to conceal the truth, with Clinton squarely at its center.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey Graham of South Carolina called Clinton's story ``a
fraud and a farce.'' In the prosecution's final words of the day,
which reflected the Republicans' frustration as they watch the
prospect of conviction ebbing, he said: ``The last people in the
United States to straighten it out is the United States Senate. God
bless you in your endeavors.''
</P>
<P>
   In rebuttal, Nicole Seligman, one of Clinton's private lawyers,
said the Republicans had ``cleverly snipped,'' ``distorted'' and
``omitted'' from Ms. Lewinsky's deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Far from strengthening the prosecutors' case against the
president, she said, it ``undermined key elements'' of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shell game,'' said another White House counsel, David
Kendall, ``but there's no shell.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to underline their view that Ms. Lewinsky's and Jordan's
depositions helped their case rather than hurt it, Clinton's
lawyers played back long, unedited passages of their testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and most Senate Democrats had tried earlier this
week to block the public airing of the videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   No riveting new disclosures were made and no fresh arguments
were developed. Much of the long day was a tedious tale, not
twice-told, but a tale some of the weary senators had heard and
read five or six times.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was undeniable drama in the calm, earnest,
occasionally girlish answers of Ms. Lewinsky, who faced her
interrogator squarely, wide-eyed, her face framed by her black
hair. While there was nothing remotely salacious in the questions
or testimony, the Republicans did venture directly into questions
about the extramarital affair itself.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing a conversation with Jordan, Ms. Lewinsky lowered her
eyes and recalled: ``He sort of jokingly said to me, `You know what
your problem is, don't deny it, you are in love with him.' It was
sort of lighthearted in nature.'' And how did she react? ``I
probably blushed or giggled or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Rogan of California worked hard to generate sympathy
for Ms. Lewinsky and to cast Clinton as the villain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica Lewinsky is an intelligent, articulate young woman who
until recently held untarnished hopes for tomorrow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later he added: ``The image of a young woman very much like a
family member or a friend we might know, is an image the president
did not want America to see when his indiscretions with her became
public. When that happened, the president painted Monica Lewinsky
in a very different and callous light.''
</P>
<P>
   Several senators who had seen the videotape of her deposition
earlier had commented on how young Ms. Lewinsky looked. But she
also showed remarkable composure, sticking to the story she had
told the federal grand jury and sounding every bit as well legally
briefed as the practiced Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, some of the lawmakers leaned forward intently to watch
the image of Ms. Lewinsky on large television screens.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   A second element of the strategy adopted by the prosecutors, or
``managers,'' was an effort to separate the affair itself from lies
allegedly told about it and illegal actions allegedly taken to keep
it from becoming public. Such actions, in the form of two articles
charging Clinton with perjury and obstruction of justice, are the
substance of the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan described Clinton as a man whose whole life showed ``a
continuing pattern of indulging all choices and accepting no
consequences.'' But if the president had merely committed adultery
with Ms. Lewinsky, Rogan conceded, ``we would not be here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas, who followed Rogan, sought to
build a circumstantial case against the president through the use
of contrasting tape excerpts and a detailed ``timeline.'' But he
frequently resorted to saying ``he had to know'' and ``he must have
thought'' when he lacked direct evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan flatly denied that there was any link between his efforts
to procure a job for Ms. Lewinsky in New York and the false
affidavit she filed in the Jones case. But Hutchinson played
contrasting excerpts of Jordan and Clinton describing the search to
suggest that Clinton knew of the connection and kept Jordan in the
dark about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was acting on behalf of the president,'' Jordan said, having
been told by both Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky that the two had never
had a sexual relationship. Clinton was vaguer: ``He'd given her
some advice, that's all I know about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall concentrated on Jordan, whose videotaped deposition
showed a man supremely confident and totally in command, repeatedly
fighting Hutchinson to a standstill, sometimes smiling wanly,
sometimes almost menacing in his glare.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan on tape, and Kendall in person, flatly denied that there
was any link or any tie-in between Ms. Lewinsky's affidavit and the
job Jordan sought for her.
</P>
<P>
   Was the private-sector job ``in any way dependent on her doing
anything whatsoever?'' Jordan was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Jordan answered forcefully. ``The job was over here and
the affidavit was over there.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more fascinating bits of Jordan's videotape showed
him telling how, when he graduated from the Howard University Law
School in 1960, with no prospects as a black man of any legal work
in his home town, Atlanta, his high school bandmaster had
interceded with a fraternity brother to help him get a job as a
civil rights lawyer. Ever since, Jordan said, he had done what he
could to help deserving young people like Ms. Lewinsky up the
ladder.
</P>
<P>
   A major element of the cover-up accusations involves Ms.
Lewinsky's suggestion to Clinton that she might hide or perhaps
give to his secretary, Betty Currie, gifts that he had given her.
How had he reacted? Ms. Lewinsky was asked for the umpteenth time.
Once again, she said that the president might have replied that he
would think about it but might have said something else or perhaps
nothing at all. The best Hutchinson could do with that was to
suggest that it was not inconsistent with Ms. Currie's subsequent
pick-up of the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan devoted a surprising amount of time to playing back tapes
of Blumenthal's testimony, which dealt with Clinton's account of
his encounters with Ms. Lewinsky, which included the president's
description of Ms. Lewinsky as ``a stalker'' and other statements
that later proved to be untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he thought the president had lied to him,
Blumenthal, who seemed uncharacteristically subdued on the stand,
answered, ``I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson said that while he had never urged her to lie, the
president had allowed Ms. Lewinsky to conclude she could use the
cover story they had previously used if she was called to testify
in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you believe Monica Lewinsky?'' the congressman asked. ``She
is not trying to hammer the president. She is trying to tell the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson continued: ``He says, continue the same lies even
though you're in a court of law, continue in the same pattern.
Ladies and gentlemen of the Senate, in my book that's illegal. And
I hate to say it, but that is obstruction of justice by the
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Seligman described this as an unjustified inference, based
not upon anything the president or Ms. Lewinsky said in the pivotal
telephone call of Dec. 17, 1997, when he and Ms. Lewinsky described
her possible testimony in the Jones case, but on flimsy supposition
by the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The same was true, Ms. Seligman added, about suggestions that
Clinton pressed Ms. Lewinsky to file a false affidavit in the Jones
case. To back her contention, Ms. Seligman then played a more
complete version of the videotape, in which Ms. Lewinsky said,
among other things, that the president did not urge her to falsify
an affidavit or to lie to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, many of those in the chamber were eager to move as soon
as possible to the final roll-call. Several senators were already
working on speeches explaining their votes.
</P>
<P>
   At midafternoon, the majority leader, Sen. Trent Lott of
Mississippi, asked Chief Justice William Rehnquist, who was
presiding, whether the moment was ripe for a brief recess. ``No,''
the chief justice replied to general laughter from the senators,
``Let's keep going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
