<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PRO-AM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART IS WARMING HIS PRO-AM MITTENS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ The weather changed for the worse
Saturday at Pebble Beach, as did the scores.
</P>
<P>
   Gusts of up to 40 miles an hour, coupled with chilly rain, left
fans shivering and players shaking their heads. What would the AT&AMP;T
Pebble Beach National Pro-Am be without foul weather? In 1996, the
tournament was canceled because of rain. Last year, it took six
months to finish an abbreviated 54-hole tournament, when torrential
rains postponed the final round until August.
</P>
<P>
   Payne Stewart ended the day holding a one-stroke lead over Frank
Lickliter, but with more bad weather predicted for Sunday, nobody
was quite sure when, or how, the tournament would finish. For most
players, Saturday's round was too wet, too cold and too long. Some
players wore mittens, others wore ski caps, and many who missed the
cut were happy to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Those who played at Spyglass Hill and Poppy Hills, two of the
three courses on which the tournament is held, were more fortunate,
because those courses are more inland and not as exposed to the
wind. But those who had the misfortune of playing at Pebble Beach,
where the average score was 79.3, caught the brunt of the winds
howling off the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a one-over-par 73 at Spyglass, and making a crucial
birdie on the 18th hole, Stewart stood at 10 under par for the
tournament (206) and led by one stroke over Lickliter, who shot 71
at Spyglass. Fred Couples and Jay Williamson were tied for third
place at six under par, after Couples shot a 73 at Poppy Hills and
Williamson shot a 71 at Spyglass.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval shot a 76 at Pebble Beach, dropping him to three
under par for the tournament, seven strokes off the lead. Duval
will have a difficult time winning for the 10th time in his last 30
starts.
</P>
<P>
   But players left the course talking about the weather, not the
golf. Stewart, who started the day holding a three-stroke edge, was
happy that he still had the lead, and that he didn't have
pneumonia. ``I'm whipped,'' said Stewart, a two-time major winner
who is looking for his first victory on the PGA Tour since 1995.
``It was a tough day out there. I'm looking forward to a hot shower
and a lot of sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart may get more sleep than he wants. If play is washed out
Sunday, the tournament could be extended to Monday, although if
Monday's forecast is bad, tour officials have the option of ending
the event at 54 holes. With three complete rounds in the books,
enough holes have been completed to make the tournament official.
However, tour officials would prefer to complete 72 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Considering those circumstances, Stewart's birdie on the par-4,
407-yard No. 18 loomed large, because it gave him sole possession
of the lead, and he will be declared the winner if the event is
stopped after three rounds. Stewart hit a terrific second shot at
No.18, a 5-iron that landed a foot from the hole for an easy tap-in
birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of finish you like,'' Stewart said. ``After I
finished and I heard what the weather forecast is, I was real glad
that I was at 10 under par. I've been on the short end of rainouts.
I want to play golf tomorrow, I'm not saying that I'm praying for
rain. But yeah, the lead was important.''
</P>
<P>
   While Stewart was sitting in an enviable position, others were
trying to forget their rounds. How strong was the wind? During a
practice round earlier this week on the par-3, 186-yard No. 5 at
Spyglass, Stewart used a 3-iron. Saturday, with the wind at his
back, he used a 7-iron. And the wind was even stronger at Pebble
Beach, were nobody broke par, and Paul Stankowski (72) was the only
player to shoot even par.
</P>
<P>
   Some who played at Pebble Beach were fortunate just to make the
54-hole cut, which was three over par. Tiger Woods and Mark
O'Meara, playing together, both barely made the cut, finishing at
three over par. Woods shot a 78, his worst round this year, and
needed a birdie at No. 18 to avoid missing the cut.
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lemmon, the actor who has never made the pro-am cut, missed
for the 24th time. The pro-am cut was 17 under par, and Lemmon and
Peter Jacobsen finished at 14 under. Teams that made the cut
included the singer Glenn Frey and Craig Stadler, who were tied for
the lead at 22 under par; and the baseball players Orel Hershiser,
with David Ogrin (20 under par), and Ken Griffey Jr., with Mark
O'Meara (17 under).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
