<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-06 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4917 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TYSON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-06 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Tyson seeks pity, but Payton fights
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson was sentenced to prison. He called it unfair.
</P>
<P>
   His wife said he was a good man caught in a bad circumstance.
His lawyers said he didn't deserve the persecution. His fans _
somehow, this man still has fans _ packed a courtroom in Maryland
and collectively gasped as the sentence was read.
</P>
<P>
   They acted shocked. Some wept. They acted as if there were
racist undertones and spiteful overtones in it all. They acted as
if we should feel sorry for him.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we should.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Tyson will continue to live in his disturbed, twisted
world whether it is behind bars for another year or more, or out in
the real world, where he never has been able to cope. Always, there
will be some sort of cage and some kind of bars trapping this man.
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason to believe Tyson ever will change his
troubled life or do anything for society other than commit crimes
against it, figuratively spitting in its face and then defiantly
declaring he is the victim.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is sentenced to live with himself. And that is something
we should not wish upon anyone.
</P>
<P>
   All of this became remarkably clear last week not just with
Tyson's latest sentence, but with the other sentence handed down on
one of the world's greatest athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Payton, maybe the greatest of Chicago Bears stars, has
done nothing to society other than respect it and entertain it. He
has given us everything he ever had on a football field and then
made a wonderful career for himself in the restaurant and
entertainment fields.
</P>
<P>
   He has done nothing to indicate he ever abused his own body _
drunken binges, raw nights until the wee hours, drugs, rages
against the world.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Payton, 44, was sentenced to what might be death row, the
victim of a rare liver disease that will kill him if a transplant
donor is not found in time.
</P>
<P>
   He looked at us through jaundiced, teary eyes Tuesday. He sat
there, sadly frail and weak, and tried to explain the disease and
how he will try to fight through it like he has fought through
everything else in his life.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't call it an unfair persecution, nor talk about being a
pitiful victim, nor ask us to feel sorry for him. He asked us to
pray with him.
</P>
<P>
   He was brutally honest: ``Hell, yeah, I'm scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we should pray for Payton and hope for him and have faith
in him. He doesn't want our pity, even as he undergoes treatment
and waits for a compatible liver to be found.
</P>
<P>
   The wait could be weeks, months, maybe more than a year. By
then, it might be too late and Payton could be fighting for his
life. Doctors say the disease, primary sclerosing cholangitis, is
incurable and usually proves fatal within two years without a
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Which draws us to the other sad irony of these two sentences
handed down last week.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson has asked for special treatment throughout his criminal
ordeals. He continued to expect special treatment even as he was
sentenced Friday. Part of Tyson's argument against a prison
sentence was his multimillion dollar debt to the Internal Revenue
Service.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't deserve to do time for this crime, Tyson believed,
because there was another crime that he could pay off if he was
free and could fool more fans into more pay-per-view farces. What
sick, twisted logic.
</P>
<P>
   But Payton gets no special treatment. His liver disease doesn't
consider Hall of Fame careers and personal character.
</P>
<P>
   His is just another name on the waiting list. There are other
liver patients in line ahead of him and they, too, have families,
friends and loved ones who are praying their names are called next.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his marvelous career, Payton's talent always gave the
Bears the advantage. Today, Super Bowl rings, All-Pro credentials
and 4.4 speed matter nothing.
</P>
<P>
   It is all so confusing. The temptation is to wonder why such a
thing can happen to a man of dignity and integrity; a man who has
offered the world so much and worked so hard that he should deserve
better than this in return.
</P>
<P>
   We all know that's not how it works. The temptation is to feel
sorry for Payton. The temptation is to pity him.
</P>
<P>
   But we should feel sorry for Tyson. It is Tyson who could live
to be 100, but never escape the cage or have what Payton has known.
</P>
<P>
   Pray for Payton. Hope that he finds the donor and lives to be
100. Have faith that sweetness will win again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do everything I can do with this,'' Payton said.
``I can't lay around and mope around and hope everything is going
to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   He's going to fight. And Tyson will sit in a cage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
