r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BECK-COLUMN-LADN     02-06 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BECK-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE RUMORS WON'T END FOR LAKERS' JONES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Eddie Jones glare. Half disgust, half bewilderment, the
expression is usually reserved for referees, but it's been a more
prominent look for Jones even off the court for the last several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And who can blame him? First, he watched close friend Nick Van
Exel get shipped to Denver in a trade that had ``scapegoat''
written all over it in the wake of the Lakers' playoffs collapse
against Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Then Jones weathered an offseason of trade rumors that him
transplanted to nearly every city in North America. If they were
all true, Jones would have had to expand his closet to accommodate
new jerseys from the Bulls, Timberwolves, Warriors, Kings, Raptors,
Magic and Sixers.
</P>
<P>
   Jones survived the rumor mill long enough to report to Lakers
training camp, where he was dealt back-to-back indignities -- the
(true) rumor of his being offered to Minnesota in the failed Tom
Gugliotta deal and then the possibility (since dismissed) that
Jones would have to share starting time with Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   With each rumor and each Kobe question, Jones' bright demeanor
would devolve into the Glare.
</P>
<P>
   By media day two weeks ago, he'd almost had it. ``I can't let it
go,'' he told the Associated Press, referring to the trade talks.
``I just feel like I can't even feel comfortable. It's ridiculous.
That's what they put me through. I think anybody who's been through
what I've been through would be sick of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, it's not going to end anytime soon. The Lakers
continue to dangle Elden Campbell around the league, often with
Jones as added enticement to take Campbell's $7 million-a-year
salary. That means trade rumors, even specious ones such as the
purported deal with Charlotte for Glenn Rice, will continue to dog
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   (That last one had red herring written all over it, though. The
Lakers' greatest need remains a power forward, not a small forward,
no matter how great a shooter Rice is. And to deal an All-Star and
a valued reserve center for Rice -- who is out six to eight weeks
after elbow surgery -- makes no sense, especially in a 50-game
season.)
</P>
<P>
   But when Bryant performs as he did Friday, it only fuels
speculation that one day soon, there will be room for only one of
them. And the Lakers' $70.9 million deal with Kobe lets you know
he's staying. Jones' contract is up after next season, and he'll
eligible to earn $11 million in the first year of a new deal.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Lakers give Jones that kind of money on top of the $192
million already committed to Bryant and Shaquille O'Neal? It
doesn't seem likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole game is a business,'' Jones said, noting the Van
Exel trade and his own tenuous situation. ``We can't ever forget
that. I will never forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, as popular as he is with the Forum crowd, Jones' days of
basking in the ``Ed-die'' chant are probably numbered, with many
more days of the Glare yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   Menace Rodman: Charles Barkley stopped in Los Angeles long
enough to show off his impressively conditioned physique, taunt
Laker fans relentlessly and issue a critique of Dennis Rodman,
who's toying with joining the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd give them a great rebounder. But I think those days are
over when he can just skip practice and all the other stuff,''
Barkley said. ``The team he goes to, he's gonna have to play,
because he can't hide behind Michael (Jordan) and Scottie (Pippen)
anymore. If he's missing practice and games, it's really gonna
affect the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley also made his pitch to fans to watch the post-Jordan,
lockout-shortened NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting, because you don't know who's going to win the
championship,'' he said. ``You don't know who the best team is. I
don't think you know who the MVP is going to be. From a player's
standpoint and a fan's standpoint, this is gonna be a great
season.''
</P>
<P>
   They're not worthy: You really know it's the end of an era when
the lockers of Jordan and Pippen are now occupied by guys named
Rusty LaRue and Matt Steigenga.
</P>
<P>
   And finally: With any luck, the Lakers-Rodman soap opera will
end soon, with Rodman deciding $610,000 isn't enough to entice him
away from that, ahem, acting career.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the outcome, know this: The Rodman pursuit began
and will end with owner Jerry Buss, who struck up a friendship with
enigmatic ex-Bull because they frequent the same nightclubs. If not
for Buss, the Lakers wouldn't be traveling down this potholed road,
but clearer heads in the organization did not prevail on this
issue.
</P>
<P>
   -- Howard Beck covers the Lakers for the Daily News. E-mail him
at thenext(at)aol.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
