<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-WEST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS IN 4-WAY SHOOTOUT FOR WEST TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A month into the season, the Phoenix Coyotes made a run at the
best-of-the-Western Conference label with a 14-game unbeaten
streak.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, the Stars reeled off their 15-game unbeaten
streak and claimed the role as leader of the Western world.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Colorado Avalanche rides an 11-game winning streak into
today's 2 p.m. game against the Stars at Reunion Arena to make
their stake in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Detroit Red Wings, whose streak is at two _ as
in two consecutive Stanley Cup championships.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the Stars, Coyotes and Avalanche having three of the
league's most impressive streaks this season with the Red Wings'
playoff confidence, and the best-of-the-West clash has become high
profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things started out, you weren't so sure what was going
to happen,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``But coming out of
the break, we've got a heck of a horse race going on here. You've
got some real thoroughbreds and they're starting to find their
stride.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars lead the Western Conference with a 30-9-8 record and
62 points. The Coyotes (26-12-10) have the second-best record, but
as of today would get the fourth-best playoff seed because each
division winner will receive one of the three top playoff seeds.
The Avalanche (28-19-4), meanwhile, has surpassed the Red Wings for
the second seed after starting their recent streak with a sub-.500
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teams that are going to challenge in the playoffs, they
know you really start to get geared up after the All-Star break,''
Hitchcock said. ``Now is the time when teams really start to learn
something about one another.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, the Avalanche might have a better chance at
the Stanley Cup than the Stars. They have overcome inner bickering
that forced the removal of coach Marc Crawford in the off-season
and the trading of the general manager's son, Eric Lacroix, in
November. They have withstood the long holdout of All-Star
defenseman Sandis Ozolinsh and have not lost a game since he
returned to the lineup with a two-year, $6.7 million contract. And
they have overcome an uneven start by goalie Patrick Roy, whose
looming free agency had many wondering whether his days in Colorado
were over.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of letting Roy dangle in trade talks, Avalanche general
manager Pierre Lacroix signed him to a two-year contract extension
for $15 million, and Roy has been Stanley Cup solid since. He was
the NHL's player of the month for January and won his 400th career
game Friday against the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing with a lot of emotion,'' Red Wings associate
coach Dave Lewis said of Colorado. ``They have a lot of great
players, they have character on that team. I'm not surprised they
turned it around.''
</P>
<P>
   It also wouldn't be a surprise to see the Red Wings rip off an
impressive unbeaten streak. Their best run this season is five
consecutive victories, but they're a team that has plenty of
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can talk all we want about what we've done at the start of
the season, but these are teams that have been through the playoff
wars,'' Coyotes coach Jim Schoenfeld said. ``You look at a team
like Detroit, and they have a lot of depth and a lot of experience
in big games. That's bound to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings are struggling with injuries. Free-agent
defenseman Uwe Krupp has played only 22 games because of a
herniated disk and Todd Gill is out a month with a broken forearm.
Mix those problems with slow starts by Sergei Fedorov and Slava
Kozlov and you have a team that has lost 22 games after losing 23
all last season.
</P>
<P>
   But should the Wings add a defenseman via trade, they too could
see the kind of turnaround the Avalanche has enjoyed since getting
Ozolinsh back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chemistry of a hockey club is so fragile,'' Avalanche
coach Bob Hartley said. ``You have to work at it piece by piece.
Now we have lots of depth; slowly but surely every part of our game
fell back into place.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartley has combined center Peter Forsberg and Joe Sakic on the
same line in a somewhat controversial decision. Now, instead of the
one-two punch the Stars and Red Wings have sought with their
all-star centers on separate lines, the Avalanche has a team based
on one line's success.
</P>
<P>
   In 19 games together, Sakic and Forsberg have 20 goals for 35
points and are a plus-29.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes have a similar decision concerning Jeremy Roenick
and Keith Tkachuk. Should Schoenfeld play the two together or keep
them apart? It's one part of the chemistry issues that are puzzling
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of what we're doing now is experimenting and finding
the right chemistry,'' Hitchcock said. ``There are probably 20
things that go on behind the scenes with each team that nobody ever
sees, and all of those things go into winning and losing. Right
now, teams are trying to sort through what those things might be.''
But those things start with each of the West's top four having
great players.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are seeing great chemistry from their top line of Mike
Modano, Brett Hull and Jere Lehtinen, have the deepest defense in
the NHL, are getting a consistent season from goalie Ed Belfour and
have the wild card of a potentially healthy Joe Nieuwendyk for the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are seeking a trade to upgrade the Stars have to
remember that if the team stays healthy, they'll have Hull and
Nieuwendyk in the playoffs this season when they didn't have them
last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche has some of the top skill players in the NHL in
Sakic, Forsberg, Ozolinsh, Valeri Kamensky and Adam Deadmarsh. They
also have a top-flight goalie in Roy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Avalanche is leaning heavily upon unproven youth,
including rookies Chris Drury and Milan Hejduk.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes have stars in Roenick and Tkachuk, a tough veteran
leader in Rick Tocchet, an outstanding goalie in Nikolai Khabibulin
and possibly the second-best defense in the league behind the
Stars'.
</P>
<P>
   However, they also have concerns centering on whether their
five-man defense will burn out and whether their sometimes
combustible lineup will stay cool.
</P>
<P>
   And the Red Wings have enough talent to have won the past two
Stanley Cups. Fedorov, Steve Yzerman, Nicklas Lidstrom, Larry
Murphy, Chris Osgood and Brendan Shanahan are legitimate All-Stars.
The team's greatest strength probably is tough role players like
Martin LaPointe, Darren McCarty and Toma Holmstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Although that group can turn it around at any time, there are
serious concerns about the ability of the Red Wings, the weakening
of the goaltending, the lack of depth on defense and the lack of
scoring from the role players. Which way any one of those four
concerns turns will help determine the Red Wings' fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, that's the same for all four of the West's best. The
Stars, Coyotes and Avalanche each have had down times this season,
and a poorly timed down time in the playoffs can spell the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think guys are jumping up and down yet,'' Avalanche
winger Claude Lemieux said of his team's streak. ``We remember we
had a long period of time when we got pounded and were sucking
wind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
