<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-LEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAFS BEAT DEVILS, 3-2  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In a game marked by spectacular work
from two of the league's best goaltenders, Curtis Joseph and Martin
Brodeur, the Toronto Maple Leafs edged the Devils by 3-2 Saturday
night at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Petr Sykora and Randy McKay scored goals for the Devils before
the game was nine minutes old. But Joseph shut them out the rest of
the way, finishing with 39 saves, a number of them spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs got two goals, including the winner, from Stevie
Sullivan, and one from Sergei Berezin against Brodeur, who had 17
saves. That was fewer than half of Joseph's total, but a number of
Brodeur's saves came at crucial times, such as when the Devils were
two men short for 57 seconds early in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs have become more offense-minded this season
under the direction of Pat Quinn, the 25th coach in the history of
the legendary franchise, one of the league's six original teams.
Quinn returned to the organization where he made his debut as a
player 30 years ago and has taken the Maple Leafs in the right
direction, molding a productive and exciting team.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs (30-18-3) have become the highest-scoring team
in the Northeast Division this season. Their leading scorer is Mats
Sundin, the towering Swede, who centers a line of Fredrik Modin and
Steve Thomas, who was with the Devils last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the Maple Leafs had trouble getting their offense going in
the opening period, going without a shot for the first eight
minutes. Sykora and McKay had scored for the Devils by the time the
Maple Leafs awakened from their lethargy.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora scored his fourth goal in four games, and his 17th of the
season, just 2 minutes 31 seconds into the game, when his wrist
shot from the left circle beat Joseph over the glove. McKay scored
his 13th, at 8:46, on a second effort at Joseph's right door step.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Holik, the leading scorer for the Devils, who has been
taking penalties lately in a sign of frustration for failing to
match his early production, created McKay's goal after skating
around the net from left to right. Holik also created a marvelous
opportunity for Denis Pederson, but Pederson's shot was weak from
close range on the left and Joseph covered up.
</P>
<P>
   One of Joseph's biggest saves came 38 seconds before the first
intermission, when he plunged to his right to deny Patrik Elias
after a marvelous set-up by Sykora on the right.
</P>
<P>
   That came just after Sullivan had cut the lead to 2-1 with his
ninth goal of the season, at 17:53 of the period.
</P>
<P>
   The game was played on equal terms for the entire second period,
but it was the Maple Leafs who managed a goal, Berezin's 18th, just
two minutes into the period, to send the teams into the third
period tied at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had two manpower advantages in the second period, but
failed to capitalize because they were denied by Joseph. First he
stopped Elias in the 10th minute during a penalty to Sullivan, and
then he kicked away Sheldon Souray's shot during a penalty to Tie
Domi.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan redeemed himself for that penalty by scoring the
winning goal with 2:59 left in the game, when, standing to the left
of Brodeur a few feet away, he redirected Sundin's pass from the
other side to the send Devils home disappointed after two victories
on the road.
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Krzyzstof Oliwa, the pugilist for the Devils,
prompted promoters to televise the game in his native Poland and
Oliwa did not disappoint. He was noticed immediately in his first
shift, just under three minutes into the game, when he engaged Tie
Domi, Toronto's policeman, in a fight. Oliwa dominated the early
part of the fight but Domi recovered well. ... Defenseman Kevin
Dean was cleared by the doctors to play after undergoing several
tests for an irregular heartbeat last Monday night, but he did not
play.
</P>
</TEXT>
