<HEADER>
A5003 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TCU-SMU-TEX     02-06 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-SMU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU LOSES FOURTH IN A ROW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ For TCU coach Billy Tubbs, watching his
Horned Frogs lose to SMU last night felt kind of like watching a
stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not the same team that played SMU in Dallas'' on Jan.
11, Tubbs said.
</P>
<P>
   His proof lay before him on a box score _ SMU 94, TCU 92. A
stunned crowd of 7,166 at Daniel-Meyer Coliseum were his witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month ago, TCU went to Dallas and throttled SMU,
92-79. A Top 25 ranking and a certain swagger accompanied Horned
Frogs basketball back then.
</P>
<P>
   Swagger quickly has turned into stagger.
</P>
<P>
   SMU extended TCU's losing streak to four games and a once
pencil-them-in NCAA Tournament berth suddenly looks in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   TCU's usually upbeat and talkative players were at a loss for
answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've lost anything,'' Horned Frogs guard
Shannon Long said. ``I don't know what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs knows.
</P>
<P>
   Adversity has come for TCU, and his players have yet to learn
how to respond to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of adversity come our way, and maybe this will
turn. But we're going to have to go out and make it turn,'' Tubbs
said. ``We just didn't make it happen \Rtonight\S, and time is
starting to run out on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Adversity, once again, included losing preseason All-American
Lee Nailon during crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   He sprained his left ankle while coming down with a rebound. He
hobbled into TCU's locker room with 7:33 remaining and failed to
return. Doctors will examine him this afternoon, but he is listed
as doubtful for Thursday's game against Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Nailon had 22 points, and, maybe more important, 15 rebounds
when he was injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Lee's out, they are a little different,'' Mustangs coach
Mike Dement said. ``Because Lee gets all of the rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Minus Nailon's rebounding presence, SMU had a number of second
chances.
</P>
<P>
   Mustangs guard Stephen Woods took advantage. He scorched TCU,
going 6-of-8 on 3-pointers en route to 24 points. He came in
averaging 11.6 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the real key in the game was when Woods starting
knocking down some deep 3's,'' Tubbs said. ``A lot of those were on
our failure to rebound, and I thought that was a key to the game.
We kept making 2's and he kept making 3's.''
</P>
<P>
   SMU held a 53-46 edge in rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Davis led SMU with 14 rebounds and 25 points while Jeryl
Sasser added another 21 points, only six coming in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Horned Frogs forward Marquise Gainous had a game-high 28, but
his 3-point attempt to tie the game with 6 seconds remaining
bounced off the front of the rim.
</P>
<P>
   Only then were SMU players willing to relax, secure in that a
six-game losing streak against TCU had ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were up by seven to Rice with 57 seconds remaining and we
found a way to lose that one,'' Woods said. ``I think they're
offense kind of slowed up, and we took advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   SMU (9-12, 3-5 WAC) stayed in a zone all game, and TCU's sharp
shooters failed to capitalize. TCU's starting guards combined for
to shoot 9-for-20 for 29 points.
</P>
<P>
   Horned Frogs usual spark plug, Ryan Carroll, had an especially
hard game, going 1-for-6 on 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they were missing some shots,'' Dement said of his
decision to stay in zone instead of going to a man-to-man defense.
``And we were doing a good job getting up on Carroll pretty good in
the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Horned Frogs battled sporadic shooting, rebounded
poorly and lost Nailon during the most important stretch of the
game. No, that wasn't why they lost.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the final 40 seconds, TCU came down the floor with a
chance to make a game of it. Once, with 25 seconds remaining,
Carroll turned the ball over. The other time, Gainous missed a
3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   That was what was so strange for Tubbs. The last-second,
game-winning, killer-instinct swagger isn't there any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can come up with a lot of excuses, but I don't think we
need a lot of excuses,'' Tubbs said. ``We just flat got beat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
