<HEADLINE>
A TEACHER FAILED BY FLUNKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first time you hear what happened to high school teacher
George Alper you find yourself repeating the whole story because
the ending doesn't make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lemme get this straight,'' you say before echoing what you've
just heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alper wanted his students at Desert Vista High School to have
access to the best technology available. So, he somehow finagled a
$20,000 donation of computer software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, he decided to donate $20,000 of his own money to the
upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Word got around. Students found out. Teachers. School
administrators. When the local school figured out what the teacher
had done, it called a public meeting and, in front of the Alper's
colleagues, students and representatives of the local news media _
``suspended'' him?''
</P>
<P>
   It's true.
</P>
<P>
   All over America, concerned parents have been asking why the
nation's education system isn't as good as it could be or as good
as it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, it turns out, is George Alper.
</P>
<P>
   Desert Vista High School is located in what is called the
Ahwatukee Foothills, along the edges of metropolitan Phoenix. It's
the kind of place where the tide of growth washes away desert sand,
exposing row upon row of stucco houses with red tile roofs. &QL; 
REGULATIONS TO FOLLOW
</P>
<P>
   The high school is governed by the Tempe Union School District,
which, in turn, is governed by the state of Arizona, which, in
turn, is governed by boneheads.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, George Alper would have received a medal and a raise
instead of a five-day suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, a school has regulations to follow when it
comes to buying or selling property. It must request bids and get
price quotes and complete enough paperwork to justify the sorry
existence of bureaucrats and politicians who don't give a damn
about the students in Alper's high school journalism class.
</P>
<P>
   I planned to interview Alper, then use his own words to portray
him as a hero and a role model and maybe the best teacher in
America.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to talk to me.
</P>
<P>
   The polite young student who answered the telephone in Alper's
room at Desert Vista told me, ``Mr. Alper said he no longer wants
to comment on what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't need to.
</P>
<P>
   Alper's actions speak loudly enough. So do those of his school
board. &QL; 
FEAR OF SPREADING
</P>
<P>
   Originally, board members wanted to suspend Alper for 20 days
without pay. They wanted to make an example of him. After all, if
his kind of dedication goes unpunished, it might spread.
</P>
<P>
   Better to nip it in the bud, they figured.
</P>
<P>
   Alper demanded, and got, a public hearing.
</P>
<P>
   One indignant board member declared, ``There has been a
conscious decision on Mr. Alper's part as to which rules he'll
follow and which rules he won't.''
</P>
<P>
   This is true.
</P>
<P>
   Rules which interferred with Alper's ability to teach kids were
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never denied that George didn't follow school policy,''
Alper's attorney, Susan Sendrow, told me. ``The administration
could say, with some validity, that they are a public entity and
work with taxpayer dollars and have a responsibility to be sure the
dollars are working correctly.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Alper willingly accepted the five-day
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Just as he willingly used his own money to help his students.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Sendrow if she could tell me where a school teacher got
$20,000 to give away. She didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' she added, ``this is George's second career. He was
involved in promoting and merchandising and working with rock and
roll groups, including some big names, like the Rolling Stones.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Mick Jagger who taught us a lesson about satisfaction,
which is hard to get anywhere, including the public schools. It's
always been that way, and will be, until teachers run the show
instead of flunkies. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
