<SLUG> BC-BKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
AIRING LAUNDRY: BEATING WANNA-bULLS SEEMS EMPTY 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ There were balloons and exploding fireworks,
treats for the home crowd and ear-splitting introductions.
</P>
<P>
   But the expected running of the Bulls never took place here
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Like Geraldo opening the Mafia vault, the Utah Jazz's
long-awaited revenge match with Chicago came up a little empty.
</P>
<P>
   If you're into rooting against laundry, maybe you had a fine
time watching the Jazz hold on to defeat the Chicago Wanna-Bulls,
104-96. Because that's what it was.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Floyd and the Pretenders. Unfamiliar men wearing familiar
vestments.
</P>
<P>
   No Michael Whatsisname. No Scottie Pippen. No Dennis Rodman. No
Steve Kerr. No coach Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times have changed,'' said an understating Bill Wennington,
one of only seven who remain in a Chicago uniform from last year's
NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   It was like the homemade sign, one of many at the Delta Center,
that mocked the dismantled, six-time champs:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Bulls,'' the sign read. ``Forgot something?''
</P>
<P>
   This was sad. This was like going to the opera, and being told
that Pauly Shore was taking the place of Pavarotti. This was like
going to see Ebbets Field, and finding only the wrecking ball. This
was, remember, the same court where Jordan sank his final, dramatic
shot and broke all of Utah's heart.
</P>
<P>
   In the balcony at the Delta Center, Todd Adams of Orem, Utah,
was all dressed up and had no one to boo. ``I hate the Bulls,'' he
said, dressed in full-length Jazz purple and green. ``But there's
nobody left to hate.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not exactly true. Seven players and three assistant
coaches are left from last season's championship outfit. But the
Bulls without Jordan qualify as the NBA's ultimate meatless meal.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen is with the Houston Rockets. Luc Longley is with the
Phoenix Suns. Kerr has taken his shot to the San Antonio Spurs.
Rodman is shopping himself to the highest, most desperate bidder.
</P>
<P>
   The only surviving Bulls are Toni Kukoc, Ron Harper, Wennington,
Randy Brown, Rusty LaRue, Keith Booth and Dickey Simpkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our fans are realistic enough to know what's going
on,'' Floyd said after his NBA coaching debut. ``We are undergoing
a tremendous adjustment. We're probably not going to win very many
games.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Floyd has a free ride for the next 12 or so
months. He can't possibly be judged fairly _ not with this cast.
Plus, there are going to be teams, like Utah, who see the Bulls'
laundry and view it as an invitation to settle a sore old score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we supposed to feel sorry for them or something?'' Utah's
Jeff Hornacek asked. ``Don't be ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   In the season opener, however, the Wanna-Bulls hung tough, as if
determined not to lose by the predicted 30 or 40. When Dickey
Simpkins _ Dickey Simpkins? _ put in a Kukoc miss with 32 seconds
left, the Jazz's lead had been trimmed to only five, 101-96.
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc finished with 32 points, fueling the notion that he had
better be ready to go 40-42 minutes a night. The veteran Harper
will be fine at one guard spot. But newcomer Brent Barry, despite
his moments of scoring ballet, is a veritable turnover machine.
</P>
<P>
   His Airness would never approve.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, Jordan's old nemesis, general manager Jerry
Krause, seemed to almost revel in Michael's absence. As late as 10
minutes before the game, he was parked next to new-guy Floyd on the
Bulls' bench _ a brazen breach of protocol when Jordan was still
around.
</P>
<P>
   But these are, alas, Krause's Bulls. His team. His leftovers.
His new coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Us?'' Floyd repeated. ``I don't know about us, yet. I know
what people are saying we are, though, and that's not so pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   What Floyd meant were the predictions that have the Bulls
finishing somewhere between dead-last in the NBA and no better than
fourth in the Big Ten. Everybody's a comedian when they talk about
the Bulls these days.
</P>
<P>
   Wennington himself said he had to go to the trainer and ask for
a few Advils before the opening game. Just how many, someone asked?
``Twenty-two,'' Wennington answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' said Harper, ``if any of the Utah Jazz wants to see a
real championship ring at least once in their lives, I've got one
right here.''
</P>
<P>
   He was holding his jewelry bag and shaking it.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a hollow boast. As the crowd of 19,911 seemed to say
by its subdued applause, beating the Bulls' laundry wasn't nearly
the fun that it could have been.
</P>
<P>
   And that's sad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
