<HEADLINE>
SATURDAY HOOP DREAMS: PLAYING FOR THE LOVE OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ Driving up Scottsdale Road one Saturday
morning, Dan Welton spotted a couple of guys shooting hoops at
Cactus Park. The next week, he showed up in high tops for a pickup
game.
</P>
<P>
   That was five years ago. The game grew into a weekly ritual for
the 39-year-old Honeywell facilities analyst and about 12 other
guys. They know whatever the weather, come 7:30 on Saturday
mornings, the guys will be there for a game of four-on-four, simply
for the love of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 miles away, in a crowded arena tonight, the Suns will
host the Denver Nuggets in their first home game since the lockout
kept fans away for the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   But on this wet court, tucked away at this north Scottsdale
park, it's not about salary caps or free agents or ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   It's about how the ball feels when Marty Polcari dribbles it. Or
what it's like to squeeze through two guards when Matt Rich makes a
layup. It's how a group of guys who only know each other's first
names come together each week for a game on courts across the
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the love of basketball,'' says Polcari, 49, a mortgage
broker, as he rests, waiting to rotate back into the game. ``It's
the way the ball sounds when you make a basket.''
</P>
<P>
   They are engineers, accountants, salesman and lawyers who range
in age from 25 to 49. They have played high school and college ball
and intramurals. They sprain their fingers, swollen so their
wedding rings stay on dresser tops, and hurt their knees so that
they cut out of weekend games early.
</P>
<P>
   They show up as the light breaks, fueled on Circle K coffee and
bagels, dressed in sweat shirts as the game begins. Their breath
disappears into the morning air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over here, over here,'' Rich, 27, calls. He sinks a
two-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   His beagle, Sydney, comes each week, tied to a nearby tree,
barking when the ball edges too close.
</P>
<P>
   As they warm up, Polcari throws his Fighting Irish sweat shirt
to the side, and the squeak of Air Jordans and Reeboks competes
with breath growing heavier.
</P>
<P>
   They trust each other's calls, arguing, but then letting them
stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too much trash talking here,'' says Rich, an engineer,
working on his MBA at the University of Phoenix. ``I used to come
during the week, but this is a calmer group.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, people arrive to swim laps and run on treadmills at the
Cactus Fitness Center, something most of these guys want to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on the treadmill all week,'' says Duane Novosel, 25, an
Ernst and Young consultant, who played ball for Bowling Green
University. ``So it's great to get out, to exercise, to be
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition, the intensity is good,'' Welton says. ``It's
fun to improve your skills, it's kind of an addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of them watch college ball all season, others follow the
Suns. But what they love most is their own game, here at Cactus
Park.
</P>
<P>
   They admit that as the years pass, the injuries take longer to
heal. The extra ankle supports fit neatly into socks.
</P>
<P>
   And after two hours, they gather their polar fleece, coffee cups
and pagers, and return to their Camrys, their Volvos and 4Runners,
until next Saturday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
