<HEADLINE>
VAN GUNDY DISAPPOINTED BY LACK OF KNICK `URGENCY'  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Larry Johnson had finished his interviews and
walked away when he turned back to the assembled reporters Saturday
and said animatedly: ``Write this: When you play Miami, you want
your big No. 34. When you go to war, you want that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be no No. 34 in uniform for the Knicks on Sunday when
they face the Miami Heat in their home opener at Madison Square
Garden, and the absence of Charles Oakley was on their minds as
they finished Saturday's practice session at Purchase College.
Oakley, traded in the off season to Toronto, could be counted on to
push and shove with Alonzo Mourning or P.J. Brown and to greet Tim
Hardaway or Jamal Mashburn with a forearm shiver as they skittered
into the lane.
</P>
<P>
   If the players wondered how they would fare on Sunday without
the forward who had watched their backs, Jeff Van Gundy was already
missing the Oakley who contributed as much on the practice floor as
he did at game time. With a disappointing opening-night loss to the
Orlando Magic behind the Knicks and the rival Heat on the horizon,
Van Gundy was confounded to see his team go through a lackluster
practice Saturday. He kept them long, stretching the session to
nearly three and a half hours, but he was still unimpressed with
the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I wasn't the only one having to be upset,'' Van Gundy
said. ``It's all right for them to be upset, too. I just didn't
like the sense of urgency. There just didn't seem to be any sense
of urgency or energy, and we're only two weeks into it. So how we
couldn't have energy, and coming off a loss like we did, how we
couldn't have urgency is sort of surprising to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy added: ``They thought last night was heated and hot.
They haven't seen anything when it comes to competitive from trying
to win a game against Miami. Everything is contested hard. There's
body blows. There's physical contact. It's that way for 48 minutes,
so if you want to win that type of game you've got to be able to
sustain it for 48 minutes. Hopefully, we'll be more ready tomorrow
than today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are well aware that they need someone to fill
Oakley's role. Right now it does not appear to be the man they
traded Oakley for, Marcus Camby, who saw just 19 seconds of action
on Friday night in the loss at Orlando. On Sunday, Patrick Ewing
will draw Mourning at the start of the game with Johnson covering
Brown, but the Knicks know they will miss Oakley's muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would help, definitely it would,'' Allan Houston said.
``But Oak's gone. We all miss him. It's going to definitely be one
of those games where it sticks out, a game where Oakley would be
important. We have to use what we have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-06-99 2319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
