r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MAVS-NOWITZKI-TEX     02-06 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-NOWITZKI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOWITZKI FAILS FIRST TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Mavericks rookie Dirk Nowitzki failed his
first NBA test.
</P>
<P>
   In 16 minutes of playing time in the Mavericks' season opener
Friday night against the Seattle SuperSonics, Nowitzki produced no
rebounds, two points, four assists and was 0-of-5 from the field
and 2-of-2 from the charity stripe. That's not exactly the grade
the 20-year-old talent from Germany expected in his NBA
examination.
</P>
<P>
   But give Nowitzki credit. He made no excuses and did not blame
others for his failures.
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki glanced at the scoring line next to his name and saw
statistics he'd never seen next to his name. It was as if he were
watching a horror flick.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much to say, other than I have to play much more
aggressive on both ends and get more rebounds,'' he said. ``For a
6-11 guy to get no rebounds in 16 minutes is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki gets a chance to redeem himself when the Mavericks play
the Golden State Warriors at 8 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson wasn't thrilled with
the performance of the player he thinks so highly of. The no-show
by Nowitzki forced Nelson into playing backup small forward Cedric
Ceballos 37 minutes in the 92-86 overtime loss to the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't feel that \RNowitzki\S was playing very well,''
Nelson said. ``He got no rebounds in 16 minutes, and that's a
priority for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went with Ced, and I thought Ced was playing great. We'll
play it game-to-game with Nowitzki, but he needs to rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he was not trying to send a message to Nowitzki by
playing him only 16 minutes _ barely enough time to crack a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no message here,'' Nelson said. ``He's 20 years old,
and we'll deal with each game at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a gradual learning process. But if anybody who
doesn't rebound on the frontline, they really can't play very long,
because that's the weakness that we have.''
</P>
<P>
   During Nowitzki's whirlwind trip to Dallas last summer after the
NBA draft _ when Nelson was trying to convince Nowitzki to come to
the NBA immediately _ Nowitzki kept telling everyone who would
listen that he didn't think he was ready for basketball at this
level. His words were never more true than against the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the game I wasn't really nervous,'' Nowitzki said.
``But when I stepped on the court for the starting five and shook
everybody's hands, I realized where I was, and that was a little
bit of a strange feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as soon as the game started, you're into the game, and the
nervousness went away.''
</P>
<P>
   SuperSonics forward Detlef Schrempf, who is the only other
native of Germany playing in the NBA, said he would rather reserve
judgment on Nowitzki's NBA debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I've ever seen him play, so it's hard
to say,'' Schrempf said. ``He's a big body, he can handle the ball,
and it looks like he's comfortable shooting the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to wait and see and watch him a few more games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle game was shown on live TV in Germany, starting at 4
a.m. German time. And Nowitzki's parents, girlfriend and other
relatives were watching.
</P>
<P>
   However, they probably won't be rushing to hit the rewind button
on the VCR to watch reruns of Nowitzki's first NBA game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the game, I talked to my parents, and they said they
were going to watch it live,'' Nowitzki said. ``Before the game,
you think of that, and about how they're doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as soon as the game started, you're so focused that don't
think about it any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite's Friday's subpar performance, Nowitzki's presence in
the NBA, Schrempf said, is a shot in the arm for foreign players
who aspire to play in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty excited about having him here playing,'' Schrempf
said. ``I think it's great for international basketball, European
basketball and especially German basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'm looking forward to him having a long career here. I'm
almost done, and he's got many years ahead of him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
