<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-IMPEACH-SKETCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SCENE: A SHOW OF U.S. SENATORS HEARING LEWINSKY TAPE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to change coding)   By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was understandable that Sen. Larry Craig got
down to business with his set of multicolored markers Saturday and
doodled his way through much of Monica Lewinsky's appearance by
video snippets at President Clinton's impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Like others in the trial court, Craig, a Republican from Idaho,
had studied the Lewinsky videotape earlier this past week, but he
still appeared to be keeping an ear out as he doodled. It was as if
Ms. Lewinsky's voice were a soothing bit of soft rock and her face
playing on the Senate television screens a national icon to be
safely taken for granted by now.
</P>
<P>
   Most other senators had no such make-work to get them through a
long and odd day that provided, after all, a certain kind of
spectacle: the sight not so much of Ms. Lewinsky as of themselves
having to watch Ms. Lewinsky talk.
</P>
<P>
   The yearlong ordeal had come to this, the government's highest
deliberative body on display as the court finally tasked with
parsing out witness testimony on behalf of a nation surfeited with
the oft-told tale of the President's misbehavior with the former
White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's listen,'' the senators were told time and again as they
turned to the screens like Orwellian serfs to watch excerpts of Ms.
Lewinsky and two other witnesses presented in selected cameos to
attack or defend the president.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Democrats, John D. Rockefeller IV of West Virginia
offered an elaborate, Job-like shrug, hands upraised, as the first
Lewinsky riff played in the chamber _ the prosecutors' excerpt of
her totally wholesome testimony about her college education. Next
to him, Tom Harkin of Iowa grinned and shrugged in sympathy, as if
to suggest the sheer wonderment of the Senate having to sit still
for this.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses in the chamber could see wary Democrats seem to slouch
like couch potatoes as the prosecutors artfully wove tape and
oratory to once more argue their case to banish the president. Some
Republicans nodded and smiled openly at points they found salient,
although one, John Chafee of Rhode Island, often consulted his
wristwatch and sometimes closed his eyes as if in some deeper level
of pondering the meaning of Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all heard about the light at the end of the tunnel,''
Chafee said later during a welcome break in the trial. ``We see it
now and are anxious to arrive there.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William Rehnquist had a small television hidden
under his desk that seemed aquarium-like when glimpsed from the
gallery as the pink and black image of Ms. Lewinsky floated on the
screen, her mouth ever moving through the day, her eyes blinking,
her voice rebounding about the Senate chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The judge kept his hand firmly on the tiller, leaving Sen. Trent
Lott, the majority leader, wincing when his routine proposal for a
brief recess was suddenly overruled.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, let's just keep going,'' Rehnquist said with all
deliberate speed, drawing laughs and a few claps of approval from
senators obviously aching to be done with the task sooner rather
than later.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the novelty of the tape excerpts, the day was mainly a
dress rehearsal for the next trial session on Monday, when closing
arguments are expected. The House Republican prosecutors already
seemed knife-sharp for this task.
</P>
<P>
   In the chamber, they denounced the president as a sexual
predator and a legal cheat. Beyond the chamber, they mounted an
eleventh-hour attempt to reopen the evidence docket with fresh
accusations about the veracity of Sidney Blumenthal, the
president's communications strategist whose videotaped testimony
was also shown Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Blumenthal's excerpts appeared to have a more gripping
effect in the chamber than did the Lewinsky snippets. Hillary
Rodham Clinton called him when the scandal allegations emerged,
Blumenthal testified electronically; instantly the clip garnered
attention. The first lady, he continued, said ``the president had
helped troubled persons in the past'' as a compassionate man of
religion and this was the case with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   At this, Republican senators betrayed tight smiles and angry
nods to each other, knowing that the White House ultimately dropped
this defense when the president was finally forced to acknowledge
sexual misbehavior with the intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your president obstructed justice in a mean way,'' Rep.
Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., scathingly told the Senate at the end of
the day, contending that a predawn phone call to Ms. Lewinsky by
the president presented undeniable evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Graham drew the biggest laugh of the day, saying: ``Where I come
from, you call somebody at 2:30 in the morning, you're up to no
good.''
</P>
<P>
   The senators were finally free to go after a seven-hour day. In
the parting bustle, Craig emerged from the chamber with a look of
considerable satisfaction. He clutched his sketch pad.
</P>
<P>
   ``What doodle?'' the senator asked in response to a question.
``This was a  &UR; three &LR; -doodle day,'' he announced, patting his pad.
``I call this my `Impeachment Series.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
