<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFE AT HOME, PEPPERDINE GETS REVENGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU _ It's an event reserved for a splendid fall afternoon on
most campuses, when the alumni come home and create a buzz of
excitement that fills a football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Pick any day to visit Pepperdine's campus and you'll get the
majestic afternoon, but since the Waves have no football program,
homecoming is reserved for another time.
</P>
<P>
   Like Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Which is when the rejuvenated Waves made amends for a loss at
Loyola Marymount earlier in the week with a 97-83 beating of the
Lions in front of a sellout crowd of 3,315, the largest crowd at
Firestone Fieldhouse in six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Waves senior forward Marc McDowell, sporting a self-inflicted
crew cut, scored a career-high 24 points and had seven rebounds in
25 minutes. And it helped ease the bad memories of Wednesday's
13-point loss at LMU, when the Lions danced on the court and jumped
atop tables afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were acting like they won a national championship, like
they weren't expecting to beat us, and they probably shouldn't
have,'' McDowell said. ``You get mad because you know it probably
shouldn't have happened, but you can't be mad at anyone but
yourself. I'm glad we got a chance quickly to play them again.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine said much of its energy came from homecoming weekend,
but West Coast Conference leader Gonzaga's loss to San Diego on
Thursday added a little spice. It moved Pepperdine (17-8, 8-2 WCC)
back within a game of Gonzaga for the league lead and, again, sets
up a showdown for first place Feb. 19 in Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys are pretty resilient so they just came to work, but
I'm not going to take away from the fact that I was excited,''
Pepperdine coach Lorenzo Romar said. ``We were pumped up to know
that we had a chance to win the conference again. They were charged
up. They got a second life.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last meeting, Pepperdine was coerced into a run-and-gun
style that better suited the Lions. Though the Waves reached a
season-high in points in the rematch, it wasn't done through
helter-skelter play.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Waves moved the ball well and had easy shots. Led
by McDowell and David Lalazarian (16 points), Pepperdine's bench
produced 50 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was expected from the beginning of the year, for me to
shoot like this, and it hasn't been there,'' said Lalazarian, who
was 3 for 3 from 3-point range. ``To finally get a game like this
under my belt, hopefully it will help my confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Waves point guard Jelani Gardner scored 22 points and had eight
rebounds, but his most significant contribution came less than four
minutes into the game. After picking up his second foul, which is
usually followed by a seat on the bench, Gardner talked Romar into
allowing him to stay on the court.
</P>
<P>
   During the next eight minutes, the Waves went on a 22-10 run to
take a 29-14 lead. LMU (10-12, 5-5) didn't get closer than eight
points again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Let me play. Let me play, coach,' '' Gardner said.
``I was feeling real good. I had a good energy going and I wanted
him to let me to continue to play. I told him I'd be smart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
