<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, Feb. 14.) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending Jan. 30, at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE STREET LAWYER, by John Grisham. (Island/Dell,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A young lawyer comes to terms with himself
</P>
<P>
   after discovering his prestigious firm's dirty secret.
</P>
<P>
   2. MESSAGE IN A BOTTLE, by Nicholas Sparks. (Warner
</P>
<P>
   Vision, $6.99.) After finding a seaborne bottle
</P>
<P>
   containing an enigmatic letter, a divorced woman
</P>
<P>
   encounters love.
</P>
<P>
   3. MEMOIRS OF A GEISHA, by Arthur Golden. (Vintage, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   The life of a young woman growing up in Kyoto who has
</P>
<P>
   to reinvent herself after World War II begins.
</P>
<P>
   4. WHERE THE HEART IS, by Billie Letts. (Warner, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A pregnant teen-ager, left stranded in a small
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma town, finds help and caring from its
</P>
<P>
   inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   5.(x) JEWEL, by Bret Lott. (Washington Square/Pocket, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   The life of a poor Mississippi woman is strained
</P>
<P>
   and enriched by her daughter, who has Down syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   6. TOM CLANCY'S NET FORCE, created by Tom Clancy and
</P>
<P>
   Steve Pieczenik. (Berkeley, $7.99.) In 2010, federal
</P>
<P>
   agents combat terrorist sabotage of defense and
</P>
<P>
   intelligence computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   7. CHARMING BILLY, by Alice McDermott. (Delta,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95.) At a party to celebrate a man's
</P>
<P>
   memory, many secrets of the past come to life.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE MACGREGORS: Alan _ Grant, by Nora Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   (Silhouette, $6.99.) Two romantic stories about
</P>
<P>
   the members of a clan.
</P>
<P>
   9. OLIVIA, by V.C. Andrews. (Pocket, $7.99.) The fifth
</P>
<P>
   volume in a series about the Logan family.
</P>
<P>
   10. TOXIN, by Robin Cook. (Berkley, $7.99)
</P>
<P>
   When his daughter becomes seriously ill
</P>
<P>
   after eating fast food, a physician takes
</P>
<P>
   on a hospital and the meat industry.
</P>
<P>
   11. DIVINE SECRETS OF THE YA-YA SISTERHOOD,
</P>
<P>
   by Rebecca Wells. (Harper Perennial, $13.50.) Three
</P>
<P>
   generations of Southern women.
</P>
<P>
   12. MAD JACK, by Catherine Coulter. (Jove, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   Romance, mystery and family problems in Georgian
</P>
<P>
   London.
</P>
<P>
   13. MIRACLE CURE, by Michael Palmer. (Bantam, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   A cardiologist, investigating a miracle drug, uncovers
</P>
<P>
   a huge, deadly conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   14. MIDWIVES, by Chris Bohjalian. (Vintage, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   Trouble, legal and moral, haunts a midwife who may have
</P>
<P>
   killed a woman while trying to save the baby's life.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE NOTEBOOK, by Nicholas Sparks. (Warner Vision, $5.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A World War II veteran meets an old flame who is about
</P>
<P>
   to be married.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. A CIVIL ACTION, by Jonathan Harr. (Vintage, $14)
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit brought by Massachusetts householders
</P>
<P>
   against industrial polluters. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav.
</P>
<P>
   (Fireside/S&AMP;S, $12.) How daily activities can
</P>
<P>
   be enhanced by feelings of meaning and purpose.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Paperbacks, $6.99.) The story of the
</P>
<P>
   nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a crew of
</P>
<P>
   fishermen from Gloucester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   4. INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor/Doubleday, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ascending Mount Everest in 1996, the deadliest season in
</P>
<P>
   history.
</P>
<P>
   5. A CHILD CALLED ``IT,'' by Dave Pelzer.
</P>
<P>
   (Health Communications, $9.95.) The autobiography
</P>
<P>
   of a man who survived his mother's abuse. (b)
</P>
<P>
   6. UNDER THE TUSCAN SUN, by Frances Mayes.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $13.) A celebration of life in the
</P>
<P>
   Italian countryside.
</P>
<P>
   7.(x) ADVENTURES OF A PSYCHIC, by Sylvia Browne and
</P>
<P>
   Antoinette May. (Hay House, $12.95.) A psychic
</P>
<P>
   tells her life story.
</P>
<P>
   8.(x) THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   9. 'N SYNC: The Official Book, by 'N Sync with
</P>
<P>
   K.M. Squires. (Dell, $9.95.) A profusely
</P>
<P>
   illustrated account of the pop group.
</P>
<P>
   10. INTO THE WILD, by Jon Krakauer.
</P>
<P>
   (Anchor/Doubleday, $12.95.) How a young man's
</P>
<P>
   obsession with the wilderness had a tragic end
</P>
<P>
   in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE MAN WHO LISTENS TO HORSES, by Monty Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   (Ballantine, $7.99.) The memoirs of a professional
</P>
<P>
   horse trainer.
</P>
<P>
   12. THE END OF THE DREAM, by Ann Rule. (Pocket, $7.99)
</P>
<P>
   Four true crime cases in which people's dreams were
</P>
<P>
   destroyed by acts of violence.
</P>
<P>
   13. SLAVES IN THE FAMILY, by Edward Ball.
</P>
<P>
   (Ballantine, $15.95.) A family chronicle by a
</P>
<P>
   journalist whose forebears owned thousands of slaves. (b)
</P>
<P>
   14. THE COLOR OF WATER, by James McBride.
</P>
<P>
   (Riverhead, $12.) A black writer remembers growing
</P>
<P>
   up with his white mother in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) ARE YOU SOMEBODY? by Nuala O'Faolain.
</P>
<P>
   (Owl/Holt, $11.95.) The memoir of a Dublin journalist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by
</P>
<P>
   Robert C. Atkins. (Avon, $14 and $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ways to lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. WOMEN'S BODIES, WOMEN'S WISDOM, by Christiane
</P>
<P>
   Northrup. (Bantam, $17.95.) How to create physical
</P>
<P>
   and emotional well-being. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. PROTEIN POWER, by Michael R. Eades and Mary
</P>
<P>
   Dan Eades. (Bantam, $6.50.) A protein-rich,
</P>
<P>
   low-carbohydrate plan for losing weight.
</P>
<P>
   4. CHICKEN SOUP FOR THE COUPLE'S SOUL, compiled by Jack
</P>
<P>
   Canfield, Mark Victor Hansen et al. (Health Communications,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95.) Inspirational stories about love and relationships. (b)
</P>
