</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Feb. 14)  
(lb) 
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; MEMOIRS OF A GEISHA &LR;  By Arthur Golden. Vintage Contemporaries,
$14. This first novel is an audacious ventriloquist act, assuming
the voice of a Japanese woman born in the 1920s who recalls her
metamorphosis from ugly duckling to luminous geisha and kept
mistress. In 1997 the New York Times reviewer John David Morley
found the heroine flatly drawn but said the period details and
``colorful nuggets of information ... serve to enrich'' the book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; M.F.K. FISHER. A LIFE IN LETTERS: CORRESPONDENCE, 1929-1991 &LR; 
Selected and compiled by Norah K. Barr, Marsha Moran and Patrick
Moran. Counterpoint, $21. The celebrated food writer had a lifelong
addiction to correspondence and is said to have treated letter
writing as a warm-up exercise each morning. This sampling displays
her finely controlled siren voice and reveals the continuing
struggle between the woman and the writer, while artfully
concealing the intimate details of her life. ``It is a special
pleasure to open a book of nearly 500 pages and hear on each one of
them the distinctive, quirky, personable, contradictory and
altogether artful Fisher voice,'' Betty Fussell wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MAGICIAN'S WIFE &LR;  By Brian Moore. Plume, $12.95. When a
famous French illusionist is sent by Napoleon III on a political
mission to work his magic in North Africa, his wife goes native,
shedding her bourgeois inhibitions and taking up the Muslim cause.
The novelist, who died last month at the age of 77, pulls off ``one
of his neatest tricks yet,'' Thomas Mallon wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SLAVE TRADE: THE STORY OF THE ATLANTIC SLAVE TRADE,
1440-1870 &LR;  By Hugh Thomas. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $20.
Sidestepping the moral outrage that characterizes so many other
books on the topic, the author explores the development of the
slave trade as a business and the many (often complex) characters
involved in the commerce until its demise in the 19th century. In
1997, John Thornton called this ``a fine narrative history, long on
detail and striking anecdote.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFRICA IN CHAOS &LR;  By George B.N. Ayittey. St. Martin's Griffin,
$18.95. This book focuses on the continent in the postcolonial
years, finding fault with those African and Western liberals who
blame imperialist legacies alone for problems often rooted in
incompetent leadership and home-grown corruption. The result is a
``robust, provocative'' book, Jeremy Harding wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTO THE HOUSE OF THE ANCESTORS: INSIDE THE NEW AFRICA &LR;  By Karl
Maier. Wiley, $14.95. This is a more optimistic look at
contemporary Africa and its diverse peoples, who the author
maintains are bound together by their struggle to build a workable
future. ``He introduces the reader to his subject through a rich
variety of Africans, from computer scientists and doctors to
guerrilla fighters and traditional healers,'' Howard W. French said
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NOBODY'S GIRL &LR;  By Antonya Nelson. Scribner, $12. After the
death of her mother, this novel's 30-ish heroine sends herself into
exile in rural New Mexico, where she falls for a 17-year-old
student in one of her high school classes. Last year the reviewer
Suzanne Ruta said the author ``wraps her tart, surprising sentences
around a slew of trends and shibboleths.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERDIDO &LR;  By Rick Collignon. Bard/Avon, $10. This takes place in
another dusty corner of New Mexico, where an Anglo construction
worker in the village of Guadalupe finds his sense of belonging
threatened when he starts asking questions about the mysterious
hanging death of a girl. In 1998 Denise Gess called this ``a novel
that captivates and surprises all the way to its chilling end.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRIDE &LR;  By Lorene Cary. Anchor/Doubleday, $12.95. This story of
the enduring friendship of four middle-class black women is both a
morality tale about the dangers of compromise and a strong argument
that women are just as likely as men to suffer midlife crises. Last
year the reviewer Michael Rovner praised the novel's ``subtle,
idiosyncratic characters.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; W.B. YEATS: A LIFE VOLUME 1: THE APPRENTICE MAGE, 1865-1914 &LR;  By
R.F. Foster. Oxford University, $26.50. The first of two planned
volumes follows William Butler Yeats through his ``Celtic
Twilight'' years to his emergence as a fully formed modern poet.
``The biographer is himself a fine writer, bearing with grace his
knowledge of Irish history, and writing with wit, authority and ...
eloquence,'' Thomas Flanagan wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MY SISTER LIFE: THE STORY OF MY SISTER'S DISAPPEARANCE &LR;  By
Maria Flook. Broadway, $13. The author was 12 when her teen-age
sister, Karen, a ``problem'' child with a history of truancy, drug
abuse and promiscuity, ran away from their home in suburban
Delaware for two years. This memoir ``traces the trajectory of
Karen's disappearance and the fallout of her actions on Maria,''
Courtney Weaver wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNDER THE SNOW &LR;  By Kerstin Ekman. Picador USA, $12. This
Swedish mystery, originally published in 1961, revolves around an
eccentric artist and a policeman who team up to solve the murder of
a teacher in a remote village. ``The novel's plot is nicely
convoluted ... with plenty of satisfying revelations and a deft
solution,'' Margot Livesey wrote last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
